(1, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 1:2: &ldquo;Abraham was the father of Isaac. Isaac was the father of Jacob, and Jacob the father of Judah and his brothers.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is Judah, the youngest among the sons of Leah, included in Jesus\' genealogy?</em></p>', 1, 2, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Leah, the wife Jacob disliked, bore him four sons: Reuben, Simeon, Levi, and Judah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Judah was the youngest of the four.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These four sons along with Rachel\'s sons became the foundational tribes of Israel.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus belonged to the tribe of Judah (Luke 3:33), which is why Judah is included in Jesus\' genealogy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This highlights how God often chooses the least to be part of His divine plan.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-06-15 08:35:40', '2024-12-27 05:59:14'),
(8, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Matthew 1: 3, </span>&ldquo;Judah was the father of Perez and Zerah, whose mother was Tamar. Perez was the father of Hezron, and Hezron, the father of Aram.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was special about the women in Jesus\' genealogy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 2, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The women mentioned in Jesus\' genealogy are remarkable:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Tamar &ndash; A Canaanite who bore children from her father-in-law Judah (Genesis 38:1-3).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Rahab &ndash; A Canaanite harlot (1 Chronicles 2:11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Ruth &ndash; A Moabite who became Boaz\'s wife through Levirate marriage (Ruth 3).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bathsheba &ndash; The wife of Uriah, the Hittite and the mother of Solomon.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These women didn&rsquo;t become a part of Jesus&rsquo; ancestral lineage by following a righteous path. Therefore, God chose to wait for the perfect woman, Mary, to complete the plan of his Salvation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-18 17:04:58', '2024-12-27 06:00:52'),
(9, '<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">Matthew 1:6: &ldquo;Boaz was the father of Obed, whose mother was Ruth, Obed the father of Jesse, and Jesse the father of King David. David was the father of Solomon, whose mother had been Uriah&rsquo;s wife.&rdquo; </span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><em style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">Should Jesus have been born in the line of David?</span></em></p>', 1, 2, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, Jesus\' birth in David\'s line fulfils God\'s covenant with David.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">2 Samuel 7:16 states, \"Your house and your kingdom will endure forever before me; your throne will be established forever.\" Jesus\' eternal kingship fulfils this promise.<br><br></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 05:27:53', '2024-12-27 06:00:12'),
(10, '<p><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-fareast-font-family: Arial; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-NZ; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\">Matthew 1:12: And after the deportation to Babylon: Jechoniah was the father of Salathiel, and Salathiel the father of Zerubbabel,</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><em style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">Were all the descendants of Jesus kings after King David?</span></em></p>', 1, 2, '<p dir=\"ltr\">No, after the Babylonian exile, none of David\'s descendants became kings.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hasmoneans (Maccabees) ruled from 143 to 63 B.C, but they were not descendants of David.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Herod was crowned king (63 B.C.&ndash;A.D. 6) and was of Idumean descent.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Then, Jesus in the lineage of King David, becomes the Eternal Priest.<strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-e32ced76-7fff-3ecd-af48-28667f35dd53\"><br></strong></p>', 1, '2024-12-19 05:33:07', '2024-12-19 18:49:40'),
(11, '<p><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-fareast-font-family: Arial; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-NZ; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\">Matthew 1:15-16:&nbsp;<span id=\"en-NRSVUE-23159\" class=\"text Matt-1-14\">Achim the father of Eliud, </span><span id=\"en-NRSVUE-23160\" class=\"text Matt-1-15\"><sup class=\"versenum\">&nbsp;</sup>and Eliud the father of Eleazar, and Eleazar the father of Matthan, and Matthan the father of Jacob,&nbsp;</span><span class=\"text Matt-1-16\">and Jacob the father of Joseph, the husband of Mary, who bore Jesus, who is called the Messiah </span></span></strong></p>\r\n<p><em style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">Why is Joseph\'s father\'s name changed in the Gospels of Matthew and Luke?</span></em></p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-fareast-font-family: Arial; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-NZ; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\"><span id=\"en-NRSVUE-23161\" class=\"text Matt-1-16\"></span></span></strong></p>', 1, 2, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Matthew\'s Gospel Joseph\'s father is named Jacob, while in Luke\'s Gospel his father is referred to as Eli. This discrepancy arises from the distinct genealogical approaches each Gospel takes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew presents the genealogy as \"Ancestors according to Nature,\" tracing Joseph&rsquo;s line through biological descent, indicating that Jacob is Joseph\'s biological father.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;In contrast, Luke\'s genealogy is framed as \"Ancestors according to Law,\" focusing on legal succession and the possession of hereditary property.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Joseph\'s grandfather was Mathan; he married a woman named Esa and Jacob the biological father of Joseph was born out of wedlock.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;After Mathan&rsquo;s death Esa married Mathat and Levi, born to them, is considered Joseph\'s father by law, representing the legal claim to Joseph\'s ancestry. Thus we see the differentiation in the lineages based on biological versus legal ancestry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jacob - Joseph&rsquo;s Father by Nature.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Levi - Joseph&rsquo;s Father by Law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: 150%; margin: 12.0pt 0cm 12.0pt 36.0pt;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 06:35:53', '2024-12-19 18:50:17'),
(12, '<p><strong><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-fareast-font-family: Arial; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-NZ; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\">Matthew 1:17: \"</span></strong>So all the generations from Abraham to David are fourteen generations; and from David to the deportation to Babylon, fourteen generations; and from the deportation to Babylon to the Messiah, fourteen generations.\" </strong></p>\r\n<p><em style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">Shouldn\'t there be 42 names in Jesus\' genealogy?</span></em></p>', 1, 2, '<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The genealogy of Jesus has 41 names. However, according to Matthew 1:17, 42 names are to be found (14 + 14 + 14 = 42). </span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">This is because the Jaconia mentioned in Matthew 1:11 and Matthew 1:12 are father and son.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&ldquo;Josiah was the father of Jaconiah and his brothers, born during the Babylonian exile. Jaconiah was the father of Salathiel, and Salathiel the father of Zerubbabel, who was born after the Babylonian exile\" (Matthew 1:11-12).</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The reason why there are 41 names is that the evangelist mistook these two as one name.</span></p>', 1, '2024-12-19 06:38:21', '2024-12-27 06:04:15'),
(13, '<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><span><em style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">Why do the parallel gospels lack the genealogy of Jesus only in Mark\'s Gospel?</span></em></span></p>', 1, 2, '<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Mark\'s Gospel does not include Jesus\' genealogy as it is primarily aimed at Gentile Christians in Rome. </span></p>\r\n<p><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\">1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Mark presents Jesus as a servant, and no one is interested in a slave&rsquo;s genealogy.</span></p>\r\n<p><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\">2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><!--[endif]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Mark emphasises the works and mission of Christ rather than His family history. </span></p>\r\n<p><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang=\"EN-GB\">3. &nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Gentile audiences were generally less familiar with Jewish customs and traditions,&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Thus Mark would have found it unnecessary to include a genealogy, which wouldn&rsquo;t have resonated with his readers.&nbsp;</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><br></span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break;\"></span></p>', 1, '2024-12-19 06:39:46', '2024-12-27 06:03:08'),
(14, '<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><em><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Why </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">does Matthew tell the genealogy of Jesus through 14 generations?</span></em></p>', 1, 2, '<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Gematria is a technique that existed in Greek literature.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">According to Gematria, a person is assigned a number. For example, 666 refers to the emperor Nero (Revelation 13:18).</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">This number is calculated according to the value of the letters of each person\'s name.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">In Gematria, the number given to King David in Hebrew is 14.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Based on this technique, there are 14 generations of genealogy from Jesu</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">s to David, which indicates that he is the king.</span></p>', 1, '2024-12-19 06:42:35', '2024-12-27 06:03:53'),
(15, '<p><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-fareast-font-family: Arial; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-NZ; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\">Matthew 1:19: \"Her husband Joseph, being a righteous man and unwilling to expose her to public disgrace, planned to divorce her quietly.\"</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><em style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">What does it mean to leave a spouse in secret?</span></em></p>', 1, 2, '<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">According to Jewish law, if a husband became suspicious of his wife, he could send her away with a divorce decree (Deuteronomy 24:1-3).</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">The divorce decree to be presented was called &ldquo;Ervat Debar&rdquo;.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">\"It is written, \'If a man finds any fault in his wife after he is married, and he no longer likes her, he shall give her a divorce and send her home\'\" (Deuteronomy 24:1-3).</span></p>\r\n<p>Joseph decides to leave Mary secretly because he did not wish to portray Mary as an adulteress by presenting&nbsp; Ervat Debar.</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 06:44:40', '2024-12-27 06:05:42'),
(16, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What other options did Joseph have?</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 2, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the law, a woman who made a promise of marriage had two potential circumstances under which she could become pregnant:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Consensual pregnancy from another man (Deuteronomy 22:20-24).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Subdued without her consent, leading to conception (Deuteronomy 22:25-27).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the first case, the penalty was stoning to death. In the second case, Mary would have to prove her innocence legally.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In both situations, Mary will be disgraced in front of the society. That is why Joseph decided to secretly leave her.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: 150%; margin: 12.0pt 0cm 12.0pt 36.0pt;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:20:29', '2024-12-19 18:57:55'),
(17, '<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><em><span lang=\"EN-GB\">What </span><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">was the Jewish divorce like?</span></em></p>', 1, 2, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It must be assumed that two procedures existed at that time regarding a husband&rsquo;s suspicions about his wife.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The husband must bring his wife before the jury and initiate legal proceedings (Deuteronomy 22:22-27).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">It is sufficient for the husband to issue a divorce bill (Erwat Debar) as long as two witnesses sign the bill (Deuteronomy 24:1-4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:21:34', '2024-12-27 06:04:55'),
(18, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Are there prophecies about Saint Joseph in the Old Testament?</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 2, '<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">One citation from the book of the prophet Isaiah states, &ldquo;From the stump of Jesse will sprout a branch; from his roots, a bud will bear fruit&rdquo; (Isaiah 11:1).</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">&nbsp;This imagery is often connected to Saint Joseph, symbolising him being the root from which the most excellent fruit, Jesus, came.</span></p>\r\n<p><span lang=\"EN-GB\">Saint Joseph is shown holding a spangled staff in various depictions, representing his connection to this prophetic fulfilment.</span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><br></span><span lang=\"EN-GB\"><br style=\"mso-special-character: line-break;\"></span></p>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:24:02', '2024-12-27 06:05:25'),
(19, '<p><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-fareast-font-family: Arial; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-NZ; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\">Matthew 1:23: <span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-fareast-font-family: Arial; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-NZ; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\"><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span>&ldquo;All this happened to fulfil what the Lord had said through the prophet: &lsquo;The virgin will conceive and give birth to a son, and they will call him Immanuel,&rsquo; which means &lsquo;God with us.&rsquo;&rdquo; </span></span></strong></p>\r\n<p><em style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">What is the background to Isaiah\'s Immanuel prophecy?</span></em></p>', 1, 2, '<p dir=\"ltr\">King Ahaz ruled Judea from 735 B.C.&nbsp; to 720 B.C.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In 725 B.C., the Assyrian king Tiglath-Pileser prepared to attack Israel and Syria.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">King Pekah of Israel sought the help of King Ahaz of Judah to stop the Assyrian invasion but Ahaz refused. Consequently, Israel and Syria joined forces to attack Judah.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Isaiah tells King Ahaz that God has taken over the protection of the kingdom of Judah. When Ahaz asked the prophet Isaiah for a sign of the Lord&rsquo;s protection of Judah, the Immanuel prophecy was given to him as a sign (Isaiah 7:14-16).</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: 150%; margin: 12.0pt 0cm 12.0pt 36.0pt;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:26:18', '2024-12-19 19:05:56'),
(20, '<p><strong>Matthew 2:1: \"In the time of King Herod, after Jesus was born in Bethlehem of Judea, magi from the east came to Jerusalem.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p><em style=\"mso-bidi-font-style: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%;\">How many Herods are mentioned in the New Testament?</span></em></p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There are references to six Herods in the New Testament:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Herod the Great (37 B.C. - 4 B.C.)<br>He was the ruler of Judea at the time of Jesus\' birth.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Herod Archelaus (23 B.C. - 18 A.D.)<br>He was a cruel ruler and governed Judea and Samaria. He ruled for three years and was eventually replaced by a Roman governor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Herod Antipas (4 B.C. - 39 A.D.)<br>He was the ruler of Galilee and Perea during the time of Jesus\' ministry and was involved in the events leading to Jesus\' crucifixion.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Herod Agrippa I (12 B.C. - 44 A.D.)<br>He beheaded James the Apostle (Acts 12).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Herod Agrippa II (27 A.D. - 100 A.D.)<br>He was the ruler when the Jerusalem Temple was destroyed.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Herod Philip (26 B.C. - 34 A.D.)<br>He ruled over the regions of Iturea, Trachonitis, Gaulanitis and parts of Batanea and Panias&mdash;territories located to the northeast of the Sea of Galilee.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:36:43', '2024-12-27 05:02:21'),
(21, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Where did the wise men who visited Jesus come from?</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The wise men came from the East. There are two traditions about their place of origin:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Arabia:<br>Saints Justin and Tertullian assert that they came from Arabia because the gifts they brought were considered valuable in Arabian culture.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Persia:<br>Fathers Cyril of Alexandria and Climatus of Alexandria claim they came from Persia. The reasons for this belief include:</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The sages were part of the monarchy in Persia.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">All the old paintings depict them wearing Persian clothing, leading to a general belief that they originated from Persia.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:37:49', '2024-12-27 05:03:45'),
(22, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Were the wise men astrologers from the East?</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Astrology is an evil thing God hates\" (Isaiah 47:13).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These wise men were likely well-versed in the Old Testament texts available to them.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From passages such as Daniel 9:24-27, they learned about the birth of the coming King of Judah.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the term \"wise men\" is more appropriate for them than \"astrologers.\"</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:39:57', '2024-12-27 05:05:32'),
(23, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Were the wise men from the East kings?</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Traditionally, the wise men are often referred to as kings, though they were likely rulers of smaller kingdoms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As the Persian Empire expanded, it absorbed these smaller kingdoms; thus, these wise men may have been former kings who held significant status.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This belief is supported by the nature of the gifts they presented that were fitting for royalty.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:45:52', '2024-12-27 05:05:11'),
(24, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:2 &ldquo;Where is the one who has been born king of the Jews? We saw his star when it rose and have come to worship him.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Israelites come to be known as Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Following the Babylonian exile in 586 BC, Aramaic became the spoken language of the Israelites.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Babylonians referred to Judah as the \"Province of Yehuda,\" and its inhabitants, living in this province, came to be known as Jews.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:48:14', '2024-12-27 05:06:50'),
(25, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Which is &lsquo;His star&rsquo; that the worshipers referred to?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Balaam prophesied about the Saviour, saying, &ldquo;A star shall rise out of Jacob&rdquo; (Numbers 24:17).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This star is referred to as \"derek kokav me\'iakob.\" Orientals considered this star a sign and waited ages for it.</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:51:33', '2024-12-27 05:07:30'),
(26, '<p class=\"chapter-1\"><strong><span class=\"text Matt-2-5\">&nbsp;</span></strong><strong>Matthew 2:6 &ldquo;Bethlehem in Judea, for this is what the prophet has written: &lsquo;But you, Bethlehem, in the land of Judah, are by no means least among the rulers of Judah; for out of you will come a ruler who will shepherd my people Israel.&rsquo;&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which prophet predicted that Jesus would be born in Bethlehem?</em></p>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-1\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Allusions to Bethlehem are found in the prophet Micah\'s prophecy:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Bethlehem Ephrathah, though you are small among the houses of Judah, out of you shall come forth for me one who shall rule over Israel; he is of old, before the ages\" (Micah 5:2).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Christ becomes Israel\'s King through the fulfilment of this prophecy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"chapter-1\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 07:59:27', '2024-12-27 06:06:13'),
(27, '<p><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span lang=\"EN-GB\" style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-fareast-font-family: Arial; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-NZ; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;\">Matthew 2:11: On entering the house, they saw the child with Mary his mother, and they knelt down and paid him homage. Then, opening their treasure chests, they offered him gifts of gold, frankincense, and myrrh.&nbsp;</span></strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the symbolic significance of the myrrh offered by the wise men?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Myrrh mixed with wine was given to Jesus on the cross.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"And they gave him the wine mingled with myrrh, and he did not drink it\" (Mark 15:23).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hence, the myrrh given to Jesus by the Magi alludes to His death.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:01:54', '2024-12-27 05:09:29'),
(28, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was myrrh a valuable commodity?</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Myrrh appears as a trade item of merchants from Gilead (Genesis 37:25).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was one of Joseph\'s gifts to his father, Jacob (Genesis 43:11).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Myrrh was also included in the gifts the kings sent to Solomon (1 Kings 10:25).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Additionally, myrrh was added to the anointing oil used to anoint kings and priests (Exodus 30:22-31).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:12:55', '2024-12-27 05:10:27'),
(29, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>&ldquo;Was frankincense available at that time?&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, frankincense was available at that time. It is commercially obtained from two species of trees, Boswellia carterii and Boswellia frereana.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These trees were mainly found in Southern Arabia and Northern Somaliland.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>From these regions, frankincense was exported to many locations, as noted by (Pliny the Elder (Natural History, XII. xxx. 52).</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:15:27', '2024-12-27 05:11:27'),
(30, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>&ldquo;Why not name the baby here?&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew wrote the Gospel primarily for Jewish Christians, who revered the name of God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews only uttered the name YHWH once a year, specifically at three o\'clock in the evening on the Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur) when the high priest would say the name YHWH (Yahweh) and pray.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice highlights the sacredness of God&rsquo;s name and the significance of His presence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:16:20', '2024-12-27 05:12:31'),
(31, '<p><em>What is Myrrh?</em></p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Myrrh is a resin obtained from the Balsamodendron myrrh tree. It was dried and used for various purposes.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Uses of Myrrh:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">1. Myrrh was used for incense in temples.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">2. The Jews used myrrh in anointing oil (Exodus 30:23).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">3. It was used as a perfume (Psalm 3:6).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">4. Myrrh was used as medicine, e.g., as a pain reliever (Mark 15:23).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">5. It was used to prepare dead bodies (John 19:39-40).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:17:25', '2024-12-27 05:26:46'),
(32, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:12: \"And having been warned in a dream not to return to Herod, they departed by another way.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which way did the wise men choose for their return from Bethlehem?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p>The wise men were to take the eastern route to Syria via Jerusalem, but they must have gone north along the road to Damascus via Gaza.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent: -18pt; line-height: 150%; margin: 12pt 0cm 12pt 39.3pt; text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:18:21', '2024-12-27 05:26:13'),
(33, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:13: &ldquo;When they had gone, an angel of the Lord appeared to them in a dream. And said unto Joseph, Arise, and take the child and his mother, and flee to Egypt.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Holy Family dare to go to Egypt?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There is evidence of a community of Jews in Egypt in the first century, and the Old Testament hints at one.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">1. \"At that time, some of the Edomites, the servants of Hadad\'s father, fled to Egypt. Hadad was a little boy that day&rdquo; (1 Kings 11:17).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">2. \"King Jehoiakim, the soldiers, and the princes heard it, and the king tried to kill him. But Uriah heard this and fled to Egypt in fear\" (Jeremiah 26:21).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:19:32', '2024-12-27 05:16:28'),
(34, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:14: &ldquo;Glory to God in the highest! Peace be upon those who have received God\'s grace on earth&rdquo;!&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why do angels speak of peace on Christmas Day?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Augustus Caesar erected an altar in Rome in 9 B.C. called the Ara Pacis Augustae.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On his birthday, September 23, he was hailed as the \"Saviour of the Whole World\" in anticipation of the Pax Augustae.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the angels proclaimed that it would be Jesus, not Caesar, who would bring true peace.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:24:17', '2024-12-27 05:27:50'),
(35, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:15: &ldquo;He stayed there until the death of Herod. This was to fulfil what the Lord had said through the prophet, \'Out of Egypt I have called my Son.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which prophet said he called my son out of Egypt?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This prophecy is from the prophet Hosea: \"When Israel was a child, I loved him; out of Egypt I called my son\" (Hosea 11:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites fled to Egypt when they were in trouble (1 Kings 11:40).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Calling out of Egypt signifies good times for Israel&mdash;there is no need to stay in the land of exile anymore.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:29:03', '2024-12-27 05:32:03'),
(36, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Were dreams important to the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">They did not have a psychological approach to dreams (not the work of Sigmund Freud). They understood five types of dreams:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">1. Enigmatic Dream</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">2. Prophetic Vision</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">3. Oracular Dream</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">4. Nightmare</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">5. Apparition</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed that God could speak to them through dreams.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:30:36', '2024-12-27 05:32:55'),
(37, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:16: &ldquo;When Herod realised that the wise men had deceived him, he was furious. According to the time he learned from them, he sent and killed all the boys in Bethlehem and the surrounding area who were two years old and under&rdquo;.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is it possible that Herod killed the babies?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod killed two of his sons, Alexander and Aristobulus, in 7 BC, as they posed a threat to his throne.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On his deathbed, he entrusted his sister with the task of executing palace officials. His sister, Salome, later released them. <br>Additionally, other kings, such as Antiochus Epiphanes, also ordered the killing of infants.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Their family members and the circumcised were put to death. Infants were hanged around the necks of their mothers\" (1 Maccabees 1:61).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, it is plausible that Herod ordered the killing of the infants.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:32:29', '2024-12-27 05:34:02'),
(38, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:18: \"In Ramah a voice of great weeping and wailing. Rachel weeps for her children and it is impossible to comfort her, for she is bereft of children.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is significant about Ramah?&nbsp;&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In this verse, Matthew is quoting from Jeremiah 31:15.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In 587 B.C., Nebuchadnezzar gathered the Israelites at Ramah to take them to Babylon. The slaying of the children was followed by a bitter lamentation similar to that of the Babylonian exile.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was also in this region that Jacob\'s wife, Rachel, gave birth and died. (Genesis 35:16-20).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:33:57', '2024-12-27 05:34:55'),
(39, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did Rachel weep for her children?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p>In the Old Testament, Rachel had two sons, Benjamin and Joseph.</p>\r\n<p>Although the text does not explicitly mention Rachel weeping over them, her weeping can be interpreted as a metaphor, especially in the context of the Babylonian exile, when Israel profoundly experienced the sorrow of losing their children.</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:35:17', '2024-12-27 05:36:04'),
(40, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:22: \"When Joseph heard that Archelaus, the son, was ruling Judea in place of his father Herod, he was afraid to go there, and they went to the region of Galilee.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Joseph hesitate to return from Egypt?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">After Herod\'s death, the kingdom of Israel was divided among his successors:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Archelaus: He received Judea, Samaria and Idumaea and had coins minted in his name.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Philip: He ruled over the territories of Iturea, Trachonitis and Batanaea.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Antipas: He became the ruler of Galilee and Perea.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Archelaus ruled for only nine years (4 B.C.- 6 A.D.). During his reign, he replaced the priests of the Jerusalem temple and killed many who opposed his actions. He even stopped the water supply to Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In 5 A.D., a group of Jews went to Augustus Caesar to complain about his harsh rule. As a result, Caesar exiled Archelaus, and the region subsequently came under direct Roman governance.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Joseph hesitated to return to Judea upon learning that the cruel Archelaus was in power.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:36:23', '2024-12-27 05:37:11'),
(41, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How many children did Herod have?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">We can summarise Herod\'s family as follows:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Father: Antipater the Idumaean</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mother: Cyprus</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">First Wife: Doris (son: Antipater)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Second Wife: Mariamne I (sons: Herod II, Philip, Aristobulus IV; daughter: Salampsio)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Third Wife: Malthace (sons: Archelaus, Antipas; daughter: Olympias)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Fourth Wife: Cleopatra of Jerusalem (son: Philip the Tetrarch)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Fifth Wife: Pallas (no children)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sixth Wife: Phaedra (no children)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Seventh Wife: Elpis (no children)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:40:45', '2024-12-27 05:38:52'),
(42, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:23: \"And he went and dwelt in a city called Nazareth, that it might be fulfilled which was spoken by the prophet, that he should be called a Nazarene.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where is the prophecy \"He shall be called a Nazarene\" found?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The prophecy about Jesus in the Book of Isaiah is as follows:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"A branch shall spring from the stump of Jesse; a branch shall spring from his root\" (Isaiah 11:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hebrew word for sprout is \'Netzer,\' so it was rumoured that the coming Messiah would be called \'Nazarene.\'&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew uses this prophecy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;<em>Matthew 2:23: \"He went and lived in a town called Nazareth, so that what had been spoken through the prophets might be fulfilled, \'He will be called a Nazarene.\'\"</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To ensure the courtiers were killed at the time of his death, Herod entrusted the task to his sister, Salome. However, Salome later released them.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">History also records instances of other kings killing infants, such as Antiochus Epiphanes.<br>\"Their family members and the circumcised were put to death. Infants were hanged around the necks of their mothers\" (1 Maccabees 1:61).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, it is plausible that Herod could have ordered the killing of infants.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:41:38', '2024-12-27 05:41:39'),
(44, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 3:4: &ldquo;John was clothed in a garment of camel\'s hair and had a leather girdle around his waist. His food was locusts and wild honey.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John wear camel\'s hair?</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It is believed that the clothing of the prophets of Israel included a fur coat.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Every prophet who prophesies on that day will be ashamed of his vision. Therefore they shall not put on fur coats to deceive\" (Zechariah 13:4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This might explain why John wore camel\'s hair and skin.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:51:34', '2024-12-27 05:42:45'),
(45, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 3:7: \"John saw many Pharisees and Sadducees coming to be baptised, and said to them: Who warned you, brood of vipers, to flee from the coming wrath?&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John the Baptist call the Pharisees and Sadducees vipers?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This refers to the concept of vipers in Palestine. The male viper snake is killed during mating. In revenge, the babies are born by killing the mother.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, the Pharisees and Sadducees, who claimed to be sons of the prophets, killed their fathers, which is why John the Baptist referred to them as the offspring of vipers.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 08:52:49', '2024-12-27 05:43:35'),
(46, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 3:7 \"But when he saw many Pharisees and Sadducees coming for baptism, he said to them, &lsquo;You brood of vipers! Who warned you to flee from the wrath to come?&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where did John get the term \'brood of vipers\'?</em></p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John the Baptist may have been connected with the Qumran Community, a sect of desert sages of Jewish religion who held apocalyptic beliefs.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In their writings, specifically the Thanksgiving Scroll (1QH a XI, 12), they describe the end times in which a woman gives birth to many viper-like offspring.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John may have adopted this term from the Qumran Community, which could have influenced him to use the phrase \"brood of vipers.\"</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: 12.0pt; margin-bottom: 12.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 17:29:36', '2024-12-27 05:45:22'),
(47, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 3:9.Do not presume to say to yourselves, &lsquo;We have Abraham as our ancestor&rsquo;; for I tell you, God is able from these stones to raise up children to Abraham\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the significance of the stones from which God can raise up children for Abraham?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John baptised at al-maghtas, near Bethany, a location believed to be the crossing point of the Jordan River where the Israelites, led by Joshua, entered the Promised Land.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is thought that the twelve stones Joshua set up to commemorate this event were still there.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Joshua set up twelve stones in the middle of the Jordan, in the place where the feet of the priests bearing the ark of the covenant had stood; and they are there to this day\" (Joshua 4:9).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John indicates that a new nation will arise from these stones.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 17:35:03', '2024-12-27 05:46:33'),
(48, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 3:10: \"Even now the axe is lying at the root of the trees; every tree therefore that does not bear good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the axe that John is referring to?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek term Axine refers to a two-edged axe.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This tool had a dual purpose: one side was designed to scrap underground tubers and roots, while the other was used to cut down trees and plants.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John uses this metaphor to indicate the coming judgement, suggesting that any tree (person or group) not bearing good fruit (righteous deeds) will be cut down and cast away.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 17:36:43', '2024-12-27 05:47:33'),
(49, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What did the Jews consider to be their roots?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">For the Jews, two things were seen as the roots of their existence:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">the Torah and&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">the Temple of Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If any of these are destroyed, their survival is at risk. They knew this well, so they were scattered to many places when the Temple in Jerusalem was destroyed in AD 70.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 18:10:46', '2024-12-27 05:52:17'),
(50, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Were the unfruitful trees cut down?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews thought that trees that did not naturally bear fruit were wasting the land.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Moreover, they believed that unfruitful trees would defile the soil.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">That is why such trees were cut down.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 18:11:41', '2024-12-27 05:53:03'),
(51, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 3:11-12 \"I baptise you with water; but one who is more powerful than I is coming; I am not worthy to untie the thong of his sandals. He will baptise you with the Holy Spirit and fire. His winnowing fork is in his hand to clear his threshing floor and to gather the wheat into his granary, but the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was John trying to convey?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Two tools were used in Palestine when gathering wheat:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Winnowing Shovel (3:12): Used for gathering and storing wheat.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Winnowing Fork (3:17): Used to separate the husk and straw from the wheat, using the wind aid in the process.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The gathering of wheat and the burning of the chaff represent the separation of the righteous from the unrighteous.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 18:19:50', '2024-12-27 05:53:46'),
(52, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 4:1: \"Then Jesus was led by the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews not find it unusual when they said that Jesus was tempted?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Among the Jews, there existed many stories about Adam. One of them is the Apocalyptic Book of Adam.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was believed that Adam, who was expelled from Paradise, atoned for his sins.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After doing so, he started fasting to enter the garden of Eden. But the Devil came to tempt him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Adam was tempted by the Devil and could not complete the fast. Thus, the Devil prevents Adam from returning to paradise.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">But Jesus, the second Adam, triumphed over the Devil and entered Paradise. The story of Adam helped the Jews to understand and accept the biblical account of Christ\'s temptation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 19:42:26', '2025-01-20 05:43:14'),
(53, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Why did Jesus go to the desert after the baptism in Jordan?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">On the Jewish Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur), there was the ritual of the priest placing his hands on the head of the scapegoat.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">With this laying on of hands, God would impute the sins of all the Israelites that year on the head of this lamb. Then, they would drive this lamb into the wilderness.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since Jesus knows that he is the lamb of God who will be&nbsp; sacrificed for the sins of the world, He goes to the wilderness after His baptism.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 19:43:18', '2024-12-19 19:43:18'),
(54, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 4:3: \"The tempter came to him and said, \'If you are the Son of God, tell these stones to become bread.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the tempter ask Jesus to turn the stones into bread?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Limestone was found everywhere in the Judean desert. Such smooth stones had the appearance and feel of bread; they looked like bread at first glance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Were the stone and the bread related?</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"May your bread turn to stone\" was a curse in those days. Thus, the Devil made this remark.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 19:45:27', '2024-12-19 19:45:27'),
(55, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 4:5: &ldquo;On the other side of the Jordan, in the region of Zebulun and Naphtali, Galilee of the Gentiles.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is meant by the territories of Zebulun and Naphtali being Gentile lands?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the war with Assyria around 734-732 B.C., Israel was conquered (2 Kings 15:29). Many Jews were deported from Israel to Assyria, and in turn, the Assyrians brought Gentiles into these territories, resulting in a mixed population.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the regions of Zebulun and Naphtali became regions with non-Jewish residents.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 19:46:31', '2024-12-19 19:46:31'),
(56, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 4:6 &ldquo;If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down; for it is written, &lsquo;He will command his angels concerning you,&rsquo; and &lsquo;On their hands they will bear you up, so that you will not dash your foot against a stone.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Devil ask Jesus to jump down from the top of the temple?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus&rsquo; time, the concept of the coming Messiah had evolved.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many believed that the Messiah would one day suddenly descend from heaven into the courtyard of the Jerusalem temple (Daniel 7).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The tempter sought to exploit this emerging Messianic expectation among the Jews.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 19:48:32', '2024-12-19 19:48:32');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(57, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 4:9: &ldquo;All these I will give you if you will fall down and worship me.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Devil tell Jesus he would be given all these places if He worshipped him?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sibylline Oracles were a popular text among Jews in Jesus&rsquo; time. According to oracles, when the time was fulfilled, God would send a king from the sun who would defeat all the enemies of the Israelites.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was believed that, following this victory, the Israelites would be granted a permanent place to live around the temple of Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The tempter aimed to manipulate this understanding of God&rsquo;s promise.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 19:51:07', '2024-12-19 19:51:07'),
(58, '<p><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-520f03c2-7fff-4b6c-63a6-f3d320e6804f\">Did the Devil say that he would give the whole world?</strong></p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Caesar claimed to be the emperor of the whole world, issuing coins that bore the title \"Emperor of the World.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The devil&rsquo;s offer may reflect this authority associated with the Roman emperor.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 20:27:05', '2024-12-19 20:27:05'),
(59, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 4:12: &ldquo;When Jesus heard that John had been arrested, he withdrew to Galilee.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What caused many Jews to come to Galilee?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p>During the Maccabean period, when the Jews established their government, many Jews went to Galilee. As the native population began to leave, a significant number of Jews settled in the region during this time.</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 20:29:01', '2024-12-19 20:29:01'),
(60, '<p><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-af0f3c36-7fff-3aa3-e442-a03e0a152985\">Mathew 4:13 &ldquo;Leaving Nazareth, he made his home in Capernaum by the sea, in the territory of Zebulun and Naphtali.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus stay in Nazareth for 30 years before His public life?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The scriptures and historians do not provide a clear indication of this. Jesus was born and raised in Nazareth but began his public ministry in Capernaum. The term \'Capernaum\' appears 50 times in the Gospel, while \'Nazareth\' is mentioned only 6 times.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 20:30:29', '2024-12-19 20:30:29'),
(61, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus leave Nazareth and begin His mission in Capernaum?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus spent the first period of his public life centred around Capernaum. There were only about a thousand families in Nazareth, while Capernaum had a population of approximately 10,000 to 12,000 families.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Capernaum had trade relations with other towns around the Sea of Galilee, which facilitated the quick spread of the Gospel of Jesus to the people.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Moreover, Jesus was not accepted in Galilee (Matthew 13:54-57). For these reasons, Jesus started his public life in Capernaum.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 20:32:10', '2024-12-19 20:32:10'),
(62, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 4:16: &ldquo;The people who sat in darkness have seen a great light, and for those who sat in the region and shadow of death, light has dawned.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the darkness Matthew is referring to?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The verse Matthew is referring to here is Isaiah 9:1-2.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the book of Isaiah, \'night\' also refers to \'the time when God works.\' They believed that God was actively working for them at night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, God\'s messenger killed 185,000 Assyrians in one night (Isaiah 37:36).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Additionally, the shepherds received the Christmas message at night. Therefore, the night of God symbolises the time when God is active.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 22:22:33', '2024-12-19 22:22:33'),
(63, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 4:23 &ldquo;And he went about all Galilee, teaching in their synagogues, and preaching the gospel of the kingdom, and healing every disease and every sickness among the people.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When did Jews start building synagogues?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Babylonian exile was the catalyst for the establishment of synagogues in Israel.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jerusalem temple was destroyed by the Babylonians in 586 B.C., leading to the exile of the Jews to Babylon, where they could no longer worship at the temple in Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Babylon, the leading men of Israel occasionally gathered to seek God\'s will (Ezekiel 14:1, 20:1). Synagogues were developed as a means for them to worship God and learn the Torah during this time.</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 22:24:50', '2024-12-19 22:24:50'),
(64, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 4:25 \"Great crowds followed him from Galilee, the Decapolis, Jerusalem, Judea, and beyond the Jordan.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was Decapolis?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 9, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Decapolis comprised the regions of Bashan and Gilead. Decapolis means \"Power of a League of 10 cities.\". This area came under Greek influence when Emperor Alexander conquered Syria. Later, the Seleucids and Ptolemies ruled the region alternately. He will choose the least of these to be his disciples.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 22:25:43', '2024-12-19 22:25:43'),
(65, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:9: &ldquo;Blessed are the peacemakers, for they will be called children of God.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who were known as peacemakers at that time?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Roman Emperor Augustus Caesar and his followers referred to themselves as \'peacemakers\' and \'sons of God.\'</p>\r\n<p>This was in light of the Pax Romana principle issued by the Roman Emperor, as they called themselves \'Peacemakers and Sons of Divinity.\' However, the evangelist informs us that those who follow the gospel of Jesus will establish true peace.</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 22:31:36', '2024-12-19 22:31:36'),
(66, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:13 &ldquo;If you are the salt of the earth, how will the salt lose its taste? It is no longer good for anything but to be thrown out and trampled underfoot.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was salt important in Jewish worship?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Salt was an important ingredient in Jewish worship.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Jews used to rub salt on the meat before the burnt offering, believing that salt helps to brown the meat.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In Old Testament times, when kings made a covenant with each other, they would sprinkle salt on the ground.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jews believed that salt cleansed water and other things that are to be used for the temple (2 Kings 2:19-22&mdash;Elijah cleanses a spring with salt).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 22:32:38', '2024-12-19 22:32:38'),
(67, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 5:14 &ldquo;You are the light of the world. A city built on a hill cannot be hidden.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was there a city built on a hill?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman city was believed to be built on seven hills. Perhaps the Roman town had the name \"City Built on a Hill.\" Moreover, this city was believed to be the centre of knowledge and industry in the world.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 22:39:39', '2024-12-19 22:39:39'),
(68, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Matthew 5:18 &ldquo;For truly I tell you, until heaven and earth pass away, not one letter, not one stroke of a letter, will pass from the law until all is accomplished.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">What is the unchangeable \'yod\' of the law?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A traditional story existed among the Jews. \'Yod\' was the smallest letter in the Hebrew language. <br><br>When God called \"Sarai\" as \"Sarah,\" one letter \'Yod\' was removed. The story goes that when God chose Joshua, he returned the letter \'Yod&rsquo;, which He removed from Sarai. \"Moses named your son Hosea \'Joshua\'\" (Numbers 13:16).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 22:40:22', '2024-12-19 22:40:22'),
(69, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was the law greater than heaven and earth?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Jewish belief, God created seven things before creating the heavens and the earth (b. Zebah, 116 a):</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Torah</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Abode of God</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The throne of glory</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Gehenna</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Temple</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Name of the Messiah</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Messengers of God</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Looking at it this way, the law (Torah) was created before the heavens and the earth. Therefore, the law was more important to them than heaven and earth.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 22:41:02', '2024-12-19 22:41:02'),
(70, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What is one stroke of a letter in the law?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Some Hebrew letters have a small extension, similar to a horn, that distinguishes otherwise identical letters (e.g., n and n).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This small extension is called an \"apex\" or a \"fine point\"&mdash;a single iota or one tiny stroke&mdash;known as a \"tittle.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It refers to the smallest, most minute detail or stroke in written language.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 22:41:42', '2024-12-27 06:06:58'),
(71, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:20 &ldquo;For I tell you, unless your righteousness exceeds that of the scribes and Pharisees, you will never enter the kingdom of heaven.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were all Pharisees the same?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Talmud speaks of seven types of Pharisees:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Shikmi Pharisee - One who performs the action of Shechem (i.e., the one who carried his deeds on his shoulder for everyone to see).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Nikpi Pharisee - One who knocks his feet together (i.e., finds excuses to delay and not to do good deeds).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Kizai Pharisee - One who makes his blood flow against walls (i.e., walks into the wall to avoid looking at/ making contact with a woman).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The \'Pestle\' Pharisee - One who bows his head like a pestle in a mortar (i.e., displays humility constantly).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Pharisee who constantly exclaims, \"What is my duty that I may perform it? What further duty is for me that I may perform it?\" (constantly reckoning good deeds vs. bad ones).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Pharisee from love (serves God out of love).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Pharisee from fear (serves God out of fear of punishment).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:08:02', '2024-12-19 23:08:02'),
(72, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 5:22 &ldquo;But I say to you that if you are angry with a brother or sister, you will be liable to judgment; and if you insult a brother or sister, you will be liable to the council; and if you say, &lsquo;You fool,&rsquo; you will be liable to hell of fire.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who is a fool/Raca?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus said that he who calls his brother fool/Raca will be punished. The root word Raca means \'worthless/empty handed.\'&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Perhaps Jesus meant that no one should be called \'worthless.\'</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:08:59', '2024-12-19 23:08:59'),
(73, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Does anger equal murder?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Enmity leading to murder would have been easily relatable to people in ancient times. When the citizens of a small country are divided and fight among themselves, it becomes easy for an enemy to conquer them.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, strife among people leads to bloodshed and the eventual downfall of a nation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:10:12', '2024-12-19 23:10:12'),
(74, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:25 &ldquo;Come to terms quickly with your accuser while you are on the way to court with him, or your accuser may hand you over to the judge, and the judge to the guard, and you will be thrown into prison.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the imprisonment described here?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Imprisonment of the debtor was the Roman method of punishment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Roman prisons were dark, poorly ventilated and filthy. Prisoners relied on family members or friends to bring them food; otherwise, they would face starvation for days.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:11:07', '2024-12-19 23:11:07'),
(75, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was there a way to resolve the issue?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Those days, there was a system of settling matters outside of court.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some debts were sometimes settled out of court when they were overdue.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So the Jews believed that it was wise to be gentle and talk things out. Because they believed if they&nbsp; proceeded to court, they may face consequences that could have been avoided.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:12:52', '2024-12-19 23:12:52'),
(76, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:29 &ldquo;If your right eye causes you to sin, tear it out and throw it away; for it is better to lose one of your members than to have your whole body thrown into hell.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus ask us to lose our eyes, hands and feet?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the beliefs of that time, sinful impulses were often thought to originate in the eyes, hands, and feet.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some people even walked with their eyes closed to avoid sin. This cultural context explains why Jesus used such strong imagery, urging us to \"remove\" these parts to emphasise cutting off anything that leads us into sin.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:13:56', '2024-12-19 23:13:56'),
(77, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:30 &ldquo;And if your right hand causes you to sin, cut it off and throw it away; for it is better to lose one of your members than to have your whole body go into hell.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the Jews understand by the concept of hell?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews used three words to describe hell:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Gehenna: Gehenna was a place where the dead were buried in the Kedron Valley. Gehenna is the place where sinful men are physically tormented after death (Jeremiah 7:29-34).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Hades: This is where the sinner and the righteous wait for eternal judgement after death (Revelation 1:18).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Abyss: This is the place of darkness where the angels who sinned fell (Revelation 11:7).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:14:58', '2024-12-19 23:14:58'),
(78, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:32&ldquo;But I say to you: whoever divorces his wife, except for fornication, makes her an adulteress; and he who marries a woman who has been divorced commits adultery.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was divorce like among the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Among the Jews, a man could initiate a divorce by issuing a decree known as Erwat Debar. The reasons for divorce differed between various Jewish schools of thought:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Shammai Judaism: This school maintained that fornication was the only valid ground for divorce.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Hillel Judaism: In contrast, this school permitted divorce for almost any reason.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Women had limited rights regarding divorce and could initiate it only in specific cases, such as when their husbands suffered from terminal illnesses like leprosy.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:16:09', '2024-12-19 23:16:09'),
(79, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:33 &ldquo;Do not swear falsely; you have heard that the ancestors were commanded to fulfill the oath they made to the Lord.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was this oath meant to be upheld?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish society, oaths held significant importance, and breaking an oath was seen as a grave matter.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Oaths were taken in God\'s name, as stated in Deuteronomy 6:13: \"You shall fear the Lord your God; you shall serve him, and you shall swear by his name.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The Essenes, a Jewish sect, even forbade swearing in public.</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:17:21', '2024-12-19 23:17:21'),
(80, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:39 &ldquo;But I say to you: Do not resist the evil one. But if anyone strikes you on the right cheek, turn to him the other also.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was hitting on face a crime?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In ancient times, striking someone on the cheek (referred to as hitting face) was considered an insult and was punishable under both Jewish and Roman law. The typical punishment for such an act was public whipping.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:18:44', '2024-12-19 23:18:44'),
(81, '<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Matthew 5:40 \"And if anyone would sue you and take your coat, let him have your cloak as well.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which robe was Jesus referring to?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish men typically wore two types of clothing:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Talit (Robe): This is a full-body garment made of wool. Jews usually wore a Talit (cloak) on top.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Haluk (Garment): This is a garment made of linen that reaches below the knee.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Usually, men would wear a Talit over their Haluk. Jesus&rsquo; instruction was to give a Talit when one&rsquo;s Haluk is taken, emphasising generosity and selflessness.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:19:43', '2024-12-19 23:19:43'),
(82, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 5:43 \"You have heard that it was said, \'You shall love your neighbor and hate your enemy.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were the Jews not supposed to love their enemies?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 10, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish understanding of love was largely derived from Leviticus 19:17-18: &ldquo;You shall not hate your brother in your heart; you shall reason with your neighbor, lest you incur sin because of him. You shall not take vengeance or bear a grudge against the sons of your own people, but you shall love your neighbor as yourself; I am the Lord.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Despite this command, many Jews harbored animosity towards Gentiles and rival sects, such as the Pharisees, Sadducees and Essenes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus&rsquo; teaching called for unconditional love, even towards enemies.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-19 23:21:01', '2024-12-19 23:21:01'),
(83, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:1\"Beware of practicing your piety before others in order to be seen by them; for then you will have no reward from your Father in heaven.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were considered good deeds by the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish tradition emphasised three primary good deeds:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Almsgiving</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Prayer</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Fasting</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus advised against performing these acts solely for the sake of being seen by others, stressing the importance of sincere devotion.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:42:40', '2024-12-20 08:42:40'),
(84, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:2 \"Thus, when you give alms, do not sound a trumpet before you, as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and in the streets, that they may be praised by men. Truly, I say to you, they have received their reward.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jews blow a trumpet while giving alms?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The custom of sounding a trumpet to announce almsgiving was not a common practice among Jews.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">But, almsgiving was typically done in synagogues and public spaces, where treasury boxes known as Shopharot were provided for donations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The sound produced while depositing money was likened to that of a trumpet, reinforcing Jesus&rsquo; point against ostentatious displays of piety.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:43:42', '2024-12-20 08:43:42'),
(85, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:6 \"But when you pray, go into your room and shut the door and pray to your Father who is in secret; and your Father who sees in secret will reward you.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which room is best suited for prayer?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Here, the word Tamcion is used for \"room.\" In Palestine, a room was built next to the field to store grain, and this room had no windows. Perhaps this room was the first thing that came to their mind.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:45:05', '2024-12-20 08:45:05'),
(86, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:7 &ldquo;When you pray, do not be like the heathen; for they think that they will be heard for their many words.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were the important prayers of the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews had two main prayers:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Shema: \"Hear, O Israel,\" (Deuteronomy 6:4-9). The Shema was their creed. It should be prayed twice a day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Amidah (Shemoneh Esreh or The Eighteen Benedictions). The Amidah was a collection of 18 prayers. All these prayers end with the Benediction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Rabbis emphasised daily recitation of these prayers, which served as the cornerstone of Jewish worship.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:46:33', '2024-12-20 08:46:33'),
(87, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:9 \"Pray then like this: \'Our Father who art in heaven, hallowed be thy name.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews address God as their \'Father\' (ABBA)?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews did refer to God as \"Our Father\" in prayers, as they invoke in the Shemonen Esreh, which starts with \"-Lord, God of our Fathers, The Holy God, Our Father.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, personalising this to \"My Father\" was uncommon. Sincere love for God often led individuals to express their relationship with Him in more intimate terms.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:47:31', '2024-12-20 08:47:31'),
(88, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the Jews address God in prayer?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">God\'s name YHWH was only used by the high priest in the Holy of Holies on the Day of Atonement. Generally, they used names associated with various attributes of God.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, when they prayed for healing, they would refer to God as Adonai Ruphe (\"God heals,\" as noted in Exodus 15:26).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:48:24', '2024-12-27 06:07:22'),
(89, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:12 \"And forgive us our debts, as we also have forgiven our debtors.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the Jews understand when Jesus prayed for forgiveness of debts?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish communities often found themselves in debt due to Roman taxation and crop failures.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;According to Mosaic Law, all debts were to be forgiven in the sabbatical year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To circumvent financial loss during this year, Jews invented a document called Prosbul, which allowed debts to persist beyond the sabbatical year.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many believed that the Messiah would eventually erase these prosbul debts. Jesus&rsquo; request for forgiveness of debts resonated with the hope of divine mercy and restoration.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:49:31', '2024-12-20 08:49:31'),
(90, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:16 \"And when you fast, do not look dismal, like the hypocrites, for they disfigure their faces that their fasting may be seen by men. Truly, I say to you, they have received their reward.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did all Jews pretend to be depressed while fasting?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish society, there were different groups, each with their own approach to religious observance:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Talmid Hakham: Scholars dedicated to studying and practicing the law.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Zaddik: Individuals known for pious actions.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Hasid: Devout followers engaged in extreme devotional practices.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some individuals would express discontent to gain recognition during fasting, highlighting the pitfalls of seeking approval over genuine piety.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:51:00', '2024-12-20 08:51:00'),
(91, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why do some people walk around pretending to be depressed while fasting?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">They wanted others to know that they were fasting.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">They pretended to be depressed so that others would not ask for help.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:51:59', '2024-12-27 06:11:55'),
(92, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:20 \"But lay up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor rust consumes and where thieves do not break in and steal.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the Jews mean by gathering treasures in heaven?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews believed that aiding the poor was tantamount to serving God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in Proverbs 19:17, \"Whoever is generous to the poor lends to the Lord, and he will repay him for his deed.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This perspective reinforced the notion that acts of kindness towards the needy would yield divine rewards.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:57:16', '2024-12-20 08:57:16'),
(93, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:26\"While they were eating, Jesus took bread, blessed it, broke it, and gave it to the disciples, saying: \'Take and eat; this is my body.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was it unleavened bread that Jesus cut and served?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The bread that Jesus blessed and broke is referred to in the Gospels as Artos. Traditionally, it is believed to have been unleavened bread (Azume), as it was unlikely during the Feast of Unleavened Bread to use leavened bread.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 08:58:43', '2024-12-20 08:58:43'),
(94, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:28 \"And why do you worry about clothing? Consider the lilies of the field, how they grow; they neither toil nor spin.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which is the \'lily of the field\' that Jesus praised?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The \"lily of the field\" that Jesus praised is most likely the Madonna Lily (Lilium candidum).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Known as Krina in Greek and Shoshanah in Hebrew, this flower was common in many parts of Galilee and the foothills of Mount Hermon.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The lilies typically bloom in May, providing a sweet fragrance both during the day and night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus used them as an example to show how God provides for even the smallest things in nature, encouraging His followers not to worry about material things.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:00:05', '2024-12-20 09:00:05'),
(95, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 6:9 \"Pray then in this way: Our Father in heaven, hallowed be your name.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>By what names did the Jews address God?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 11, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews often addressed God by names that were associated with His attributes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Elohim (Creator God) - Genesis 1:1</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">El Roi (God who sees me) - Psalm 139:12</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">El Shaddai (Lord God Almighty) - Psalm 84:8</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Yahweh Rophe (The LORD heals) - Exodus 15:26</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Yahweh Yireh (The LORD will provide) - Genesis 22:14</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Yahweh Shammah (The LORD is there) - Ezekiel 48:35</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Yahweh Nissi (The LORD is my banner) - Exodus 17:15-16</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Yahweh Raah (The LORD is my shepherd) - Psalm 23:1</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Yahweh Shalom (The LORD is peace) - Judges 6:24</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:01:08', '2024-12-20 09:01:08'),
(96, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 7:9-10 \"Is there anyone among you who, if your child asks for bread, will give a stone? Or if the child asks for a fish, will give a snake?\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say that the Father will provide bread and fish?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 12, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Bread and fish were common foods among the Jews in daily life. Meat was normally reserved for special occasions or festivals.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus used these examples to show that the Father provides for the basic needs of His children.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:05:47', '2024-12-20 09:05:47'),
(97, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 7:10 \"Or if the child asks for a fish, will give a snake?\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the relationship between the fish and the snake?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 12, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The snake mentioned here could refer to the harmless water snake, Tripodonotus tesselatus, which was commonly found around the Sea of Galilee.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sometimes, this snake was used as fish bait, as seen in Matthew 17:27, where Jesus catches a&nbsp; fish with a coin in its mouth. Jesus contrasts the image of a harmless snake with the nourishment of a fish, illustrating the absurdity of offering something deceptive for the sake of sustenance.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:07:35', '2024-12-20 09:07:35'),
(98, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 7:16 \"You will know them by their fruits. Are grapes gathered from thorns, or figs from thistles?\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Do some thorn trees bear grapes?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 12, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Some thorn bushes, such as the blackberry, bear fruit that resemble grapes from a distance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, the flowers of the saffron tree can look like figs when viewed from afar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus used this parable to highlight the importance of discerning the true nature of people, contrasting outward appearances with genuine character.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The optical illusion of seeing fruit on thorny plants shows how deceptive outward appearances can be, much like a tree that only looks good from a distance but lacks true substance.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:09:05', '2024-12-20 09:09:05'),
(99, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Are the effects of thistles and thorns bad?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 12, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The word \"Akantha\" refers to a type of thorn, likely from the Syrian Acanthus genus (Acanthus syriacus).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This plant grows about two feet tall and has small white flowers, producing fruit that is not edible.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Similarly, the thistle which is known as the Maltese Cross (Tribulus terrestris) produces fruits that are also inedible. These plants symbolise efforts or actions that appear fruitful but are useless.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:10:03', '2024-12-20 09:10:03'),
(100, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 7:21 \"Not everyone who says to me, \'Lord, Lord,\' will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only the one who does the will of my Father in heaven.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does Matthew use the phrase \"kingdom of heaven\" a lot?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 12, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew uses the phrase \"Kingdom of heaven\" 33 times, while other Evangelists preferred using the phrase \"kingdom of God\". This is because Matthew wrote his Gospel primarily for Jewish Christians.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews were not permitted to use the name of God (YHWH) directly, following what is called the Circumlocution Theory. Instead, they used the term \"Heaven\" as a respectful substitute for God&rsquo;s name. This practice is also seen in Daniel 2:44 , where \"the God of heaven\" is mentioned.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, Matthew consistently uses \"Kingdom of Heaven\" to express the Jewish reverence for the divine name.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:11:17', '2024-12-20 09:11:17'),
(101, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 7:22 \"On that day many will say to me, &lsquo;Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name, and cast out demons in your name, and do many deeds of power in your name?&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Can miracles take place without God?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 12, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Magic was practised in Palestine during the time of Christ.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;For example, in Acts 8:9 , it is mentioned: \"Now a certain man named Simon had previously practised magic in the city.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;These individuals performed wonders and miracles through magical means, claiming to have divine power. Jesus\' prophecy serves as a warning against these practices.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:12:20', '2024-12-20 09:12:20'),
(102, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 7:24 \"Everyone then who hears these words of mine and acts on them will be like a wise man who built his house on rock\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were all the houses of the Israelites the same?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 12, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites built different types of houses during that time, depending on their social status and location:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Tent: Primarily used by shepherds, these were temporary dwellings suitable for nomadic lifestyles.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mud and Straw Houses: These were built on flat land, mostly in rural areas, and were more common among the lower classes.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Stone Houses: Constructed along the hillsides, these homes were sturdier and offered better protection, particularly for those living in more permanent and developed areas.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These varying types of houses reflect the diverse ways in which Israelites adapted to their environment.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:13:41', '2024-12-20 09:13:41'),
(103, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 7:26 \"And everyone who hears these words of mine and does not act on them will be like a foolish man who built his house on sand.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is it possible to build a house on sand?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 12, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus told this parable in the Bayda region, near the Sea of Galilee. The soil in this area is alluvial, meaning it has good stability during the dry summer months. However, when the rainy season arrives, the soil becomes loose and unstable, like sand.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although houses can be built on this soil during summer, they are easily destroyed during the rains.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus uses this analogy to illustrate the instability of ignoring His teachings.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:14:45', '2024-12-20 09:14:45'),
(104, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 7:28 \"Now when Jesus had finished saying these things, the crowds were astounded at his teaching.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What made them think that Jesus was teaching like someone with authority and not like their scribes?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 12, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish rabbis commonly taught by asking questions, encouraging heated debates and exchanging dialogues with their listeners.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their sermons often involved extensive arguments and discussions.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, when Jesus spoke, there was no room for debate or contradiction. His words carried an undeniable clarity and authority that left the crowd astonished.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They recognised that He taught with authority, unlike their scribes, whose teaching often relied on interpretations and debates.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:15:57', '2024-12-20 09:15:57'),
(105, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 8:5-6 \"When he entered Capernaum, a centurion came to him, appealing to him and saying, &lsquo;Lord, my servant is lying at home paralyzed, in terrible distress.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the centurion love his servant so much?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 13, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the early days of joining the Roman army, soldiers were often forbidden to marry, especially those in higher positions like centurions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Due to the demands of their role, centurions frequently had to travel and had little opportunity to build a family. In such cases, household affairs were entrusted to slaves, who often became like family.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;This centurion, lacking a traditional family, may have developed a deep bond with his servant, who likely took care of his home.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:26:40', '2024-12-20 09:26:40'),
(106, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 8:12&nbsp; \"While the heirs of the kingdom will be thrown into the outer darkness, where there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Jesus mean by outer darkness?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 13, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus\' reference to \"outer darkness\" and \"weeping and gnashing of teeth\" in Matthew would have resonated with the Jewish audience familiar with apocalyptic literature, particularly the Book of Enoch, written in the second century B.C.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this book, it is said that certain angels, led by Azazel, took human women as wives before the flood during Noah\'s time. Because of their transgression, God cast them out of paradise. God commanded the Archangel Raphael to imprison them in a pit in the desert, where they were condemned to live in utter darkness (1 Enoch 10:4-6).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This imagery of darkness, judgment and separation from God likely came to mind for Jesus&rsquo; listeners when they heard the concept of being cast into a place of eternal suffering.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:27:35', '2024-12-20 09:27:35'),
(107, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 8:22 \"But Jesus said to him, &lsquo;Follow me, and let the dead bury their own dead.&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does it mean for the dead to bury the dead?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 13, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish customs, the dead were traditionally buried in rock-hewn caves.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After a year, the bones of the deceased were collected and transferred to ossuaries, small stone containers used to store the bones of the dead.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice allowed families to honour their ancestors, as it was believed that the deceased would \"join their kinsmen\" in death.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus\' statement about letting the dead bury their own dead highlights the urgency of following Him, suggesting that one should prioritise spiritual matters over temporal obligations.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:28:50', '2024-12-20 09:28:50'),
(108, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 8:24 \"And suddenly a great storm arose on the sea, so that the boat was being swamped by the waves; but he was asleep.\" </strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Were the unexpected waves on the Sea of Galilee a natural phenomenon?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 13, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sea of Galilee lies 6 to 13 feet below sea level and is surrounded by hills.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Golan Heights to the east rise to about two thousand feet. As cool air descends from these elevated heights and meets the warm air over the lake, it can create sudden and unexpected waves.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This phenomenon often leads to unpredictable turbulence on the lake, driven by the cold air currents coming from the east.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:30:19', '2024-12-20 09:30:19'),
(109, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 8:26 \"He said to them, &lsquo;Why are you afraid, you of little faith?&rsquo; Then he got up and rebuked the winds and the sea; and there was a great calm.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was it windy and rainy that day on the lake?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 13, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Cold air typically comes from the Golan Heights, which can cause waves to rise in the Sea of Galilee due to shifting currents.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the presence of rain is not necessarily related to this phenomenon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since the Gospel does not mention rain, it can be assumed that the storm was caused solely by the wind.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:31:20', '2024-12-20 09:31:20'),
(110, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 8:33 \"The whole herd of pigs rushed down the steep bank into the sea and perished in the water. The swineherds ran off, and on going into the town, they told the news about what had happened to the demoniacs.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were the pigs released into the sea?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 13, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Places mentioned in the Bible carry significant attributes of God, not necessarily limited to their physical characteristics.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">1.Mountain:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Old Testament: The place where God chooses Israel\'s leaders<br>New Testament: The place where Jesus chooses His disciples.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">2.Sea:<br>Old Testament: The place where God displays His power in creation.<br>New Testament:The place where we see the manifestation of Jesus\' dominion over evil.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">3. Desert:<br>Old Testament: The place where God feeds His children.<br>New Testament: The place where Jesus interprets the Word.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, sending the pigs into the sea serves as a powerful demonstration of Jesus\' divine authority.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:32:46', '2024-12-20 09:32:46'),
(111, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 9:3 \"Then some of the scribes said to themselves, &lsquo;This man is blaspheming.&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the Jews consider to be blasphemy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 14, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Rabbinic Law, two things were considered blasphemy:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Pronouncing the name Jehovah (YHWH).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Worshiping other gods and leading others to worship false gods.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish understanding, blasphemy was a serious offense, as it was believed that God\'s glory should not be diminished by human words or actions.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:36:26', '2024-12-27 06:12:05'),
(112, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 9:08 \"Therefore, pray to the Lord of the harvest to send out laborers into his harvest.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the Jewish harvest time like?</em></p>', 1, 14, '<p>The Jewish harvest season begins with the offering of the firstfruits to the Lord (Leviticus 23:9-14).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This marks the start of a seven-week period known as the harvest time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The harvest concludes on the day of the Feast of Weeks, which occurs on the fiftieth day after the seven weeks. On this day, bread made from fresh flour is offered to God (Leviticus 23:15-22,).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, other gifts, known as freewill gifts, are presented to God (Deuteronomy 16:9-12)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:37:46', '2024-12-20 09:37:46');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(113, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 9:9: \"As Jesus went on his way, he saw a man named Matthew sitting at the tax booth.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was Roman tax collection like?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 14, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Romans imposed two types of taxes:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Direct Tax: These taxes were paid directly to Rome and collected by Roman law enforcers. There were two types of direct taxes:</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Poll Tax: A tax payable by all adults.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Property Tax: A tax of 12.5% of the yield payable on property.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Indirect Tax: These included taxes on goods and services. For example, there was a tax on the carriage of goods, the rights for which were auctioned to private individuals.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Levi, also known as Matthew, was one assigned to collect&nbsp; this indirect tax.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:38:54', '2024-12-20 09:38:54'),
(114, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 9:20: \"A woman who had suffered from bleeding for twelve years came up behind him and touched the hem of his garment.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the hem of Jesus\' garment like?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 14, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus wore the typical clothing of an ordinary Jewish man. Jewish men often had fringes, known as tzitzit, with blue cords on their robes.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;As commanded in Numbers 15:38, \"Speak to the people of Israel, and tell them to make tassels on the corners of their garments throughout their generations, and to put a blue cord on the tassels at each corner.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These fringes served as a reminder of their identity as God\'s chosen people.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:40:11', '2024-12-20 09:40:11'),
(115, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 9:36 &ldquo;When he saw the crowds, he had compassion for them, because they were harassed and helpless, like sheep without a shepherd&rdquo; .</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the reason why Matthew mentions that Jesus felt compassion?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 14, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, Moses experienced deep sorrow upon seeing the people of Israel without leaders after his time. He prayed,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;May the Lord, the God of all life, appoint someone over the community to lead them in all things, lest the people become like sheep without a shepherd!&rdquo; (Numbers 27:16-17).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Matthew\'s Gospel, Jesus embodies the role of Moses in the New Testament. This is why Matthew highlights Jesus\' compassion when He sees the crowd; He recognises their need for guidance and leadership.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 09:41:16', '2024-12-20 09:41:16'),
(116, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:2 \"These are the names of the twelve apostles: first, Simon, also known as Peter, his brother Andrew; James son of Zebedee, and his brother John.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Peter hold a prominent role among Jesus\' disciples?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Peter was the first disciple Jesus called (Matthew 4:18).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew refers to him as \"the first\" as an epithet, emphasising his significance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Frequently, it is Peter who speaks on behalf of the disciples, indicating his leadership role among them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, Peter has been regarded as the foremost disciple (Primus Inter Pares) from that time onward.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:23:08', '2024-12-20 18:23:08'),
(117, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:3 \"Philip, Bartholomew, Thomas, Matthew the tax collector, James the son of Alphaeus, Thaddeus.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Bartholomew a Hebrew name?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p>His name in Hebrew was likely Bar Tholmai, meaning \"son of Thomas.\" When the Gospel was later written in Greek, it was recorded as Bartholomew (&Beta;&alpha;&rho;&theta;&omicron;&lambda;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;ῖ&omicron;&sigmaf;).</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:24:25', '2024-12-20 18:24:25'),
(118, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:4 \"Simeon the Canaanite, and Judas Iscariot, the one who betrayed him.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is Simeon the Canaanite the same as Simeon the Terrorist?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p>In Aramaic, \"Qanaim\" is the equivalent term for \"Zealot.\" Therefore, Simeon was likely referred to as \"Qanaan Simon\" in Aramaic. The name \"Simeon the Canaanite\" derives from this term and does not imply that he was from Cana. Thus, Simeon the Canaanite and Simeon the Terrorist refer to the same individual.</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:25:38', '2024-12-20 18:25:38'),
(119, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:5 \"These twelve Jesus sent out, instructing them, &lsquo;Go nowhere among the Gentiles and enter no town of the Samaritans&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What caused the separation of Jews and Samaritans?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">When the Israelites returned after the Babylonian exile, the Samaritans were not recognised as Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews regarded the Samaritans as defiled due to their intermarriage with people of other religions. However, the Samaritans considered themselves to be the true, undefiled Jews and referred to themselves as the \"Holy Seed&rdquo; (Zera Haqodesh).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This perception of purity and defilement is the reason for the longstanding conflict and separation between Jews and Samaritans.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:26:48', '2024-12-20 18:26:48'),
(120, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:5 \"These twelve Jesus sent out, charging them, &lsquo;Go nowhere among the Gentiles and enter no town of the Samaritans&rsquo;\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus send his disciples only for the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The gospel was initially preached to the Jews before being extended to the Gentiles. This is why Matthew\'s Gospel begins with a focus on the Jewish audience.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, it concludes with a directive for universal evangelism, stating, \"Go therefore and make disciples of all nations\" (Matthew 28:19).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This progression reflects the early church\'s mission to spread the Gospel beyond Israel.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:27:42', '2024-12-20 18:27:42'),
(121, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:6 \"Go rather to the lost sheep of the house of Israel.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who were the lost sheep of Israel?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">When the Israelites first settled in the land of Canaan, they were divided into 12 tribes.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, due to multiple exiles, 10 tribes &mdash; Asher, Dan, Ephraim, Gad, Issachar, Manasseh, Naphtali, Reuben, Simeon and Zebulun&mdash;could not be clearly distinguished.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These tribes had mingled with non-Israelites, which lead to their designation as the Ten Lost Tribes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There was a belief that when the Messiah came, they would be gathered together again.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:28:35', '2024-12-20 18:28:35'),
(122, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:7 \"Beware of men; for they will hand you over to councils, and they will flog you in their synagogues.\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the persecution of the Jews like?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A person could be punished with a maximum of 40 lashes (Acts 25:3).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The customary practice involved 13 lashes on the chest, followed by 26 lashes on the back, often stopping at 39 lashes to avoid accidentally exceeding the limit of 40.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;The blood, tears and sweat endured during these punishments held significant meaning and value for those who suffered.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:29:28', '2024-12-20 18:29:28'),
(123, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:10 \"Take no bag for your journey, or two tunics, or sandals, or a staff; for laborers deserve their food.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Shouldn\'t the disciple of Christ take a stick for the journey?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Among the Jews of that time, the devout Hasidim ( Hasidenes) firmly believed in God\'s providence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their law (Halachah) stated that even if a poisonous snake wrapped around one\'s leg, one should not interrupt their prayer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They refrained from using sticks on the road, trusting in God\'s protection. It is possible that Jesus was referring to this example when He instructed His disciples to not take a staff.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:30:24', '2024-12-20 18:30:24'),
(124, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:11 &ldquo;Of him it is written, &lsquo;See, I am sending my messenger ahead of you, who will prepare your way before you.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus call John \'the one who is to come&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Old Testament concludes with the prophecy of Malachi who is regarded as the last prophet before the arrival of the Saviour.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;After Malachi, it was believed that God would no longer send any prophets to Israel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Malachi had foretold that God would send Elijah before the coming of the Lord: &ldquo;Lo, I will send you the prophet Elijah before the great and terrible day of the Lord comes&rdquo; (Malachi 4:5).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, John the Baptist is identified as the Elijah who fulfills this prophecy by heralding the Saviour\'s arrival.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:31:18', '2024-12-20 18:31:18'),
(125, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:16 &ldquo;See, I am sending you out like sheep into the midst of wolves&rdquo;.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What makes wolves dangerous?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There is a folktale among the Israelites about a wolf that infiltrated a flock of sheep. The wolf said to the goats, \"Anyway, I will sacrifice you, but it is better for you to become food for me. So, each of you should come to me every day and serve as my meal.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This story reflects the biblical sentiment expressed in Ecclesiastes 13:17 : &ldquo;What is a wolf to a lamb? And what is a sinner to a godly person?&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Wolves symbolise the practical threats that sought to hinder early Christians from living their faith during times of persecution.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:32:13', '2024-12-20 18:32:13'),
(126, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:21 \"Brother will betray brother to death, and a father his child, and children will rise against parents and have them put to death.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does the brother oppose the brother?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">When the Jerusalem temple was destroyed in 70 CE, the synagogue became the primary place of prayer for both Jews and Judeo-Christians.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This transition led to frequent disputes between the two groups regarding the management of the synagogue and the manner of prayer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As noted in Matthew 10:17, \"They will hand you over to councils; and they will flog you in their synagogues.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This conflict is depicted in Matthew as a family quarrel within Judaism. Such divisions ultimately benefit outsiders, who take advantage of the rifts among the children of the Church.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:33:03', '2024-12-20 18:33:03'),
(127, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:29 \"Are not two sparrows sold for a coin? Not one of them will fall to the ground without your Father&rsquo;s knowledge.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How much did a sparrow cost?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The coin mentioned here is a copper coin called the Assarion, which was worth one-sixth of a denarius (the wage for one hour\'s work). A sparrow typically costs about half an Assarion.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:33:58', '2024-12-20 18:33:58'),
(128, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:32 \"Everyone therefore who acknowledges me before others, I also will acknowledge before my Father in heaven.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews call God the Father?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It was only after the Babylonian captivity that the Jews began to refer to God as Father, as seen in Isaiah 63:16.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, they mostly used the term \"Our Father.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Jehovah became the Father of the Jews by \'adoption rather than by creation.\'</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, Jesus referred to God as \'My Father\'.&nbsp; &pi;&alpha;&tau;έ&rho;&alpha;&sigmaf; &mu;&omicron;&upsilon;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He used the most affectionate term, \'Abba,\' which signifies a deep, personal relationship.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:34:54', '2024-12-20 18:34:54'),
(129, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:34 \"Do not think that I have come to bring peace to the earth; I have not come to bring peace, but a sword.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say that He brought a sword?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Greek thought, the sword was a symbol of justice. In many texts written within this framework, God is referred to as the \"Bellator&rdquo; (Latin for warrior of light).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">God is depicted as wielding a sword to signify divine justice.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:35:54', '2024-12-20 18:35:54'),
(130, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:40 \"Whoever receives you, receives me, and whoever receives me receives him who sent me.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How does accepting disciples equate to accepting Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">To the Jews, receiving someone as a guest was equivalent to accepting their principles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in the Jewish tradition, \"A man\'s deputy is like the man himself\" (Berachot 5:5).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, when Saul persecuted the church, it was as though he were persecuting Jesus Himself (Acts 9:4). Therefore, accepting Jesus\' disciples is akin to accepting Jesus Himself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:36:54', '2024-12-20 18:36:54'),
(131, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:41 \"Whoever welcomes a prophet in the name of a prophet will receive a prophet&rsquo;s reward; and whoever welcomes a righteous person in the name of a righteous person will receive the reward of the righteous.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Should a prophet be accepted as a prophet?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The people of Israel regarded their greatest sin as grumbling against Moses, as noted in Exodus 16:8.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Then Moses said, \'It is the Lord who gives you meat to eat in the evening and your fill of bread in the morning; because the Lord has heard the complaining that you utter against him.\'\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Their murmuring was not merely directed at Moses but ultimately against God Himself. In this context, there was a prevailing understanding among the Israelites that accepting a prophet as a prophet was essential.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:37:49', '2024-12-20 18:37:49'),
(132, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What is the prophet\'s reward that Jesus mentioned?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, it was considered a great honor to receive a teacher or a prophet into one&rsquo;s home and to host them with a feast.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When a rabbi or guru entered a house, he would say \"Shalom,\" which means peace.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is supported by Luke 10:5: \"Whatever house you enter, first greet it with peace.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews believed that by offering this greeting of peace, they would receive significant blessings from God. For example, in 2 Kings 4:8-15, God blessed the Shunammite woman who welcomed the prophet Elisha into her home by granting her a son.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the concept of \"Shalom\" (peace) represents the greatest blessings a family can receive.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:38:44', '2024-12-20 18:38:44'),
(133, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 10:42 \"Truly I tell you, none of these little ones will lose their reward if they give even a cup of cold water to one of these little ones, because they are disciples.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How much is a pot of water worth?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, the Greek root refers specifically to cold water.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A portion of Mount Hermon received snow several times a year (Psalm 133:3).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;\"As the dew of Hermon, which falls on the mountains of Zion, for there the Lord ordained his blessing, life forevermore (Psalm 133:3).&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The question is posed, \"Will the snow of Lebanon cease to flow from the crags of Sirion (Jeremiah 18:14)?&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In hotter regions, some people fill earthen pots with cold water and sell it to travelers and those working in the fields.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Icy, cold water was especially appreciated by those working in the fields, as it was seen as a reward for their hard labour.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;\"Like a snow-cooled drink at harvest time is a trustworthy messenger to the one who sends him; he refreshes the spirit of his master (Proverbs 25:13)&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Offering cold water freely to poor travellers was regarded as a pious act.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:39:35', '2024-12-20 18:39:35'),
(134, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was pouring water for guests considered a big deal?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It was a part of Jewish hospitality for the host to pour water into the cup for the guest.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This act was a sign of honour, as certain cups could not be placed on the ground.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, pouring water into the cups for guests was a significant gesture.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:40:20', '2024-12-27 06:12:13'),
(135, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Who are the little ones Jesus spoke of?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 15, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The \'little ones\' are primarily interpreted as the disciples set apart for Jesus (Epiphanius, Origen).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During that time, there were disciples who endured many hardships for His sake.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As Paul wrote in 1 Corinthians 4:11, \'To the present hour we are hungry and thirsty, we are poorly clothed, beaten, and homeless.\'&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is likely that these disciples are referred to as the least of His followers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus acknowledges their struggles and has given them grace to endure for His sake.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:41:00', '2024-12-27 06:12:21'),
(136, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 11:7 \"As they went away, Jesus began to speak to the crowds about John: &lsquo;What did you go out into the wilderness to see? A reed shaken by the wind?&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which reed did Jesus mean?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 16, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The most common reed in Israel is Phragmites australis. This plant, resembling bamboo, has a hollow stem and leaves that grow along its length. These reeds were often used to decorate the tabernacles during the Feast of Tabernacles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:43:32', '2024-12-20 18:43:32'),
(137, '<p><em>Why John the Baptist connected to a reed?</em></p>', 1, 16, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod Antipas, the ruler of Galilee, was often symbolized by a reed.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Antipas minted coins, they featured engravings of reeds.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He also yielded to his wife, Herodias, by appointing her brother, Agrippa Tiberius, as overseer of the market.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Antipas was widely regarded as a reed by the people, particularly when criticized by John the Baptist.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:44:26', '2024-12-20 18:44:26'),
(138, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 11:8 &ldquo;Or what then did you go out to see? A man in soft robes? Look, those who wear soft robes are in royal palaces&rdquo;.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who is the man in soft clothes?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 16, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, Rebekah dresses Jacob in Esau\'s expensive clothes (Genesis 27:15,).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The Idumeans are descendants of Esau, and King Herod\'s family belonged to the Idumean clan. Therefore, the man in soft clothes refers to Herod Antipas.</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:46:14', '2024-12-20 18:46:14'),
(139, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Were those wearing soft clothes in the royal palace?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 16, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews were primarily sheep breeders, so they mainly used wool as clothing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cotton, silk and linen garments were rarely available and were considered luxurious. Israel did not have sufficient land to grow cotton.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Only the rich could afford such luxurious clothing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:47:00', '2024-12-20 18:47:00'),
(140, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 11:11 \"Truly I tell you, among those born of women no one has arisen greater than John the Baptist; yet the least in the kingdom of heaven is greater than he.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the name \'the Baptist\' unique to John?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 16, '<p>Before one was admitted to Judaism as a proselyte, immersion was required. <br>This baptism needed a witness, known as a Matbil (Immerser). <br>John might have been one of the many Matbil/Immersers.\"</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:47:57', '2024-12-20 18:47:57'),
(141, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 11:14 \"If you are willing to accept it, he is the Elijah who is to come.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews expect Elijah to come?</em>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 16, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The prophet Elijah was a man from the tribe of Benjamin (1 Chronicles 8:27, 40).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While only Levites were permitted to make sacrifices, Elijah, despite being from the tribe of Benjamin, performed sacrifices (1 Kings 19:21).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Furthermore, the expectation of Elijah\'s return was rooted in the prophecy that all nations would gather for sacrifice when the Saviour arrives (Malachi 1:10-12).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This anticipation contributed to the Jews\' expectation of Elijah\'s return.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:48:56', '2024-12-20 18:48:56'),
(142, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 11:16 \"But to what will I compare this generation?\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus ever doubt?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 16, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The phrase \'To what shall I be likened?\' is a common expression used by rabbis to introduce stories and parables.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus did not use this expression out of doubt. He employed it because of His profound intelligence and insight. This rhetorical question invites listeners to reflect on their understanding and responses.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:49:49', '2024-12-20 18:49:49'),
(143, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 11:17: &ldquo;We played the flute for you, and you did not dance; we wailed, and you did not mourn.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>On what occasions did the Jews play the pipe?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 16, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews played the pipe primarily during three occasions:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">During the anointing with water on Sukkot.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">For bridal processions.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">During funeral processions.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Each of these occasions had distinct tunes.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:51:52', '2024-12-20 18:51:52'),
(144, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the children sing a dirge?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 16, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Babylonian Talmud states that children sometimes imitated funeral rites (b. Yev. 121 b).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The children would mimic certain rituals of Jewish funerals by picking up the bodies of dead insects.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This context may be the reason why Jesus told this parable.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:52:38', '2024-12-27 06:12:28'),
(145, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 11:21 \"Woe to you, Chorazin! Woe to you, Bethsaida! For if the miracles done in you had been done in Tyre and Sidon, they would have repented long ago in sackcloth and ashes!\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were the three places that Jesus cursed cities?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 16, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew mentions Chorazin, Bethsaida, and Capernaum as the locations cursed by Jesus.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Chorazin and Capernaum were not likely cities in the conventional sense.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is probable that the Hebrew word \"Yir\" (meaning \"village\") was translated by Matthew as \"Polis\" (meaning \"city\"). Therefore, it must be assumed that all three places cursed by Jesus were small villages.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-20 18:53:31', '2024-12-20 18:53:31'),
(146, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:1 &ldquo;At that time Jesus went through the grainfields on the Sabbath; his disciples were hungry, and they began to pluck heads of grain and to eat.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews travel on the Sabbath?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The distance the Pharisees could travel on the Sabbath was limited. There was an expression known as \"a Sabbath day\'s journey,\" which was approximately 2000 cubits or about 4100 meters.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This fact is supported by Acts 1:12 , which states: \"Then they returned to Jerusalem from the mount called Olivet, which is near Jerusalem, a Sabbath\'s journey away.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While the Pharisees adhered to these restrictions, the Sadducees were opposed to traveling on the Sabbath altogether</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:34:49', '2024-12-21 03:34:49'),
(147, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:5 \"Or have you not read in the law that on the Sabbath the priests in the temple break the Sabbath and yet are guiltless?\" (Matthew 12:5)</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say that the priests were breaking the Sabbath?</em></p>', 1, 17, '<p>According to Jewish law, there are six valid reasons for a Jew to break the Sabbath:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">If the eighth day of circumcision falls on the Sabbath, circumcision may be performed on that day, even if it violates the Sabbath.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sometimes, the Sabbath was relaxed to allow preparation for the Passover.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">If there is a fire on the Sabbath day, one is permitted to extinguish it if it threatens the Book of the Law.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">One can defend oneself on the Sabbath to save their life.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Necessary actions to save the life of an animal may be taken on the Sabbath.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The priests were permitted to perform prayers in the Temple of Jerusalem on the Sabbath..</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus may have pointed out this sixth reason.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:37:01', '2024-12-21 03:37:01'),
(148, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:6 \"But I say to you, something greater than the temple is here.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say that He is greater than the temple?</em></p>', 1, 17, '<p>At that time, there were debates among the Jews regarding whether the temple laws or Sabbath laws were more significant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the rabbis of that era, temple laws were considered more important than Sabbath laws (Tosefta, Shab 15:16).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, David ate the consecrated bread in the temple, which indicated that he even broke temple laws; thus, the Sabbath law could not be considered superior.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is within this context that Jesus proclaimed that He is greater than the temple.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:39:23', '2024-12-21 03:39:23'),
(149, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:8 \"For the Son of Man is lord of the sabbath.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the Jewish view of the Sabbath?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish Sabbath was observed for three key reasons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Rest: God rested on the seventh day after creation.<br>\"And on the seventh day God finished the work that he had done, and he rested on the seventh day from all the work that he had done.\" (Genesis 2:2)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Messianic Peace: The Sabbath was seen as a foretaste of the perfect peace that would be restored when the Messiah came.<br>\"The wolf shall live with the lamb, the leopard shall lie down with the kid, the calf and the lion and the fatling together, and a little child shall lead them.\" (Isaiah 11:6)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Commemoration of Deliverance from Egypt: The Sabbath also served as a remembrance of God&rsquo;s deliverance of the Israelites from slavery in Egypt.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:40:23', '2024-12-21 03:40:23'),
(150, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:11 \"He said to them, \'Suppose one of you has only one sheep and it falls into a pit on the sabbath; will you not lay hold of it and lift it out?\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>\"What are the pits that Jesus refers to here?\"</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Small pits were often dug to protect goats and sheep from wolves and other wild animals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These pits served as a form of defense, but occasionally, sheep or goats themselves would fall into these traps.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus may have been referring to rescuing such an animal from one of these pits, even on the Sabbath.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:42:31', '2024-12-21 03:42:31'),
(151, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Could the animal be taken out of the pit on the Sabbath?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The law does not explicitly address this situation for the Sabbath.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Exodus 23:5 says, \"f you see the donkey of someone who hates you fallen down under its load, do not leave it there; be sure you help them with it.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For the Essene monks, this practice was forbidden on the Sabbath (CD 11.13-14).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some Rabbis allowed it if the animal was meant for sacrifice at a feast (m. Bet. 3.4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Others permitted actions necessary to keep animals alive (Dt. Shab. 14.3).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:44:25', '2024-12-21 03:44:25'),
(152, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:26 \"If Satan casts out Satan, he is divided against himself; how then will his kingdom stand?\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus speak of division among demons?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Beelzebub is regarded as the chief of demons, and Jesus also reminds us that Satan desires to establish a kingdom.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Jesus spoke of the division among demons to illustrate that they work together, under a unified leadership, to destroy souls within the Devil\'s kingdom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:46:58', '2024-12-21 03:46:58'),
(153, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:31 \"Therefore I tell you, people will be forgiven for every sin and blasphemy, but blasphemy against the Spirit will not be forgiven.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews sin against the Spirit of God.?</em></p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Jewish understanding, God worked through the Spirit in their prophets.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The greatest of these prophets was Moses.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, murmuring against Moses at the waters of Meribah was considered a sin against the Spirit of God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Likewise, creating the golden calf in opposition to Moses was viewed as a grave offense against the Spirit. Failing to heed the Spirit of God is thus a profound sin.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:48:10', '2024-12-27 06:12:37'),
(154, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:38 \"Then some of the scribes and Pharisees said to him, \'Teacher, we wish to see a sign from you.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews ask for a sign?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time, many people claimed to be prophets, arguing that they could save the people from Roman rule.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They attempted to prove their authority by performing signs and miracles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, \"For some time ago Theudas rose up, claiming to be somebody, and a number of men, about four hundred, joined him; but he was killed, and all who followed him were dispersed and disappeared.\" (Acts 5:36, Josephus Ant. 20:97-98).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews, having witnessed such claims, asked Jesus for a similar sign to prove His authority.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:49:13', '2024-12-21 03:49:13'),
(155, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:42: \"The queen of the South will rise at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, because she came from the ends of the earth to listen to the wisdom of Solomon, and see, something greater than Solomon is here!\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was the queen who visited Solomon?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Old Testament tells us that the Queen of Sheba came to visit Solomon (1 Kings 10:1-13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sabeans were a people who lived in what is now modern-day Yemen, in the southwest corner of Arabia. It is believed that the Queen of Sheba came from this community of Sabeans, hence the reference to her as the \"Queen of the South.\"</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:54:01', '2024-12-21 03:54:01'),
(156, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:41 \"The men of Nineveh will stand up at the judgment with this generation and condemn it; for they repented at the preaching of Jonah, and now something greater than Jonah is here.!\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say He was greater than Solomon?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish belief, Solomon was regarded as the greatest exorcist (Exorcist - Josephus, Ant. 8.46-47).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His wisdom surpassed that of the wise men of the East and Egypt, as stated in 1 Kings 4:30 : \"Solomon\'s wisdom excelled the wisdom of all the people of the east, and all the wisdom of Egypt.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many attempted to exorcise demons by invoking Solomon\'s name.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:57:31', '2024-12-21 03:57:31'),
(157, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus say that the Queen of Sheba would come from the south?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Queen of Sheba is known to have come from the country of Yemen to visit King Solomon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Hebrew, the word \"Yemen\" means \"right hand.\" When facing the sun, the right hand naturally points to the South.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This geographical association is why Jesus said the Queen of Sheba came from the South.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:58:51', '2024-12-21 03:58:51'),
(158, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:45 : \"Then it goes and brings along seven other spirits more evil than itself, and they enter and live there; and the last state of that person is worse than the first. So will it be with this evil generation.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Can one evil spirit bring forth 7 evil spirits?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Jewish tradition, the number 7 is considered a symbol of completeness or perfection.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Jesus refers to seven devils, it emphasizes the full extent of wickedness.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, in Genesis 4:15 , God says, &ldquo;Not so! Whoever kills Cain will suffer a sevenfold vengeance,&rdquo; indicating the fullness of the punishment.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The statement suggests that once sin or evil takes hold, the situation can worsen dramatically&mdash;much like how once a fruit begins to rot, it spoils entirely.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 03:59:48', '2024-12-21 03:59:48'),
(159, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 12:47 \"Someone told him, &lsquo;Look, your mother and your brothers are standing outside, wanting to speak to you.&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus have brothers?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 17, '<p>The Greek word for \"brothers\" is \'Adelphos\'.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This term can mean brother, cousin, kinsman, fellow believer or fellow countryman.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, Lot is referred to as \"the son of Abraham\'s brother Haran\" (Genesis 11:27), but in many contexts, Lot is depicted as Abraham\'s brother (Genesis 13:8; 11:14-16).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Therefore, it is likely that those referred to as Jesus\' brothers were actually cousins</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 04:01:14', '2024-12-21 04:01:14'),
(160, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:3 \"He told them many things in parables, saying: &lsquo;Listen! A sower went out to sow.&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were the common methods used to sow seeds?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The seeds were primarily sown in the field in two ways.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some seeds were scattered by hand, while others were placed in a perforated sack tied to the animals, allowing the seeds to be distributed as the animals moved through the field.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These two methods were commonly used for sowing seeds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 05:23:49', '2024-12-21 05:23:49'),
(161, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:4 \"And as he sowed, some seeds fell on the path, and the birds came and ate them up.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the farmer sow the seed carelessly?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus&rsquo; time, a farmer had to pay three types of taxes:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Roman tribute</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Taxation to the King</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Contributions for the temple</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Due to these heavy taxes, many had to abandon their good lands. Consequently, the farmer was left with stony and thorny fields.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus told the story of a poor farmer who lost his good fields, highlighting the struggles of those who faced such burdens.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 05:24:51', '2024-12-21 05:24:51'),
(162, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:8 &ldquo;Other seeds fell on good soil and brought forth grain, some a hundredfold, some sixty, some thirty.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the hundred percent yield?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"hundredfold yield\" refers to the success achieved from a year\'s farming.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Specifically, it means that a yield of 30 yield equates to 30 seeds produced from the sowing of one seed, while a hundred yield represents approximately 100 seeds from the same single seed sown.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This concept of yield is rooted in agricultural practices, as seen in Genesis 26:12, where it is stated, &ldquo;Isaac sowed seed in that land, and in the same year reaped a hundredfold.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The yield can vary based on the quality of the soil.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 05:25:54', '2024-12-21 05:25:54'),
(163, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:14 \"For the kingdom of heaven is like treasure hidden in a field, which someone found and hid; then in his joy he goes and sells all that he has and buys that field.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Jesus mean by the treasure in the field?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During the time of besieging forts to conquer kingdoms, sieges could last for years.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was common for people to bury their savings in the ground before surrendering.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Stories about such hidden treasures also existed, such as those found in the Qumran Copper Scroll.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 05:26:46', '2024-12-21 05:26:46'),
(164, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:20 \"As for what was sown on rocky ground, this is the one who hears the word and immediately receives it with joy; yet such a person has no root, but endures only for a while, and when trouble or persecution arises on account of the word, that person immediately falls away\" (Matthew 13:20).</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is the Devil likened to a bird?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish philosophy, the Devil is often depicted as a winged creature.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Apocalypse of Abraham suggests that Azalel, a figure representing evil, tests Abraham in the form of a bird (Apoc. Abr: 13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, Revelation 18:2 refers to \"Babylon\" as the \"nest of the unclean bird,\" while Ephesians 2:2 describes the Devil as \"the ruler of the invisible forces of the air.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This imagery reinforces the notion that the Devil is a creature with wings, which is why he is likened to a bird.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 05:27:41', '2024-12-21 05:27:41'),
(165, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:24 \"He put before them another parable: &lsquo;The kingdom of heaven may be compared to someone who sowed good seed in his field.&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When did Israelites sow seeds?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In 1908, the Agricultural Calendar tablet was discovered at Gezer, Israel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to this tablet, the Israelites sowed wheat seed after the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkot).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This sowing typically took place during the months of November and December.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 05:28:29', '2024-12-21 05:28:29'),
(166, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:25 \"But while everybody was asleep, an enemy came and sowed weeds among the wheat, and then went away.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What are the weeds sown by the enemy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">Matthew uses the term \"Zizanion\" to refer to the weeds, specifically tares, scientifically known as Lolium temulentum, a plant traditionally found in the Middle East. This weed is notable for several reasons:</span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><span style=\"color: #e67e23;\">It bears a striking resemblance to the wheat plant, making it difficult to distinguish between the two.</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><span style=\"color: #e67e23;\">Its roots grow entwined with the roots of the wheat, complicating the harvesting process.</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><span style=\"color: #e67e23;\">The grain of this plant is poisonous if consumed in large quantities.</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Palaeobotanical evidence has revealed that a thousand-year-old grain of this type was found in Egypt.</p>', 1, '2024-12-21 05:29:31', '2024-12-23 09:56:37'),
(167, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>Matthew 13:25 \"But while everybody was asleep, an enemy came and sowed weeds among the wheat, and then went away.\"&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What are the weeds sown by the enemy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew uses the term \"Zizanion\" to refer to the weeds, specifically tares, scientifically known as Lolium temulentum, a plant traditionally found in the Middle East. This weed is notable for several reasons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">It bears a striking resemblance to the wheat plant, making it difficult to distinguish between the two.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.5;\" role=\"presentation\">Its roots grow entwined with the roots of the wheat, complicating the harvesting process.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The grain of this plant is poisonous if consumed in large quantities.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Palaeobotanical evidence has revealed that a thousand-year-old grain of this type was found in Egypt.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 03:42:16', '2025-01-20 05:44:40'),
(168, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:26 \"So when the plants came up and bore grain, then the weeds appeared as well\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were weeds harmful?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Wheat fields were often plagued by a weed known as Zizanion (&zeta;&iota;&zeta;ά&nu;&iota;&omicron;&nu;)(This weed can cause fainting, as noted by Pliny the Younger.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, it significantly reduces the yield of wheat.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:28:10', '2024-12-27 06:13:02'),
(169, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:30 &ldquo;Let both of them grow together until the harvest; and at harvest time I will tell the reapers, &lsquo;Collect the weeds first and bind them in bundles to be burned, but gather the wheat into my barn&rsquo;&rdquo;.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were these weeds easy to identify during harvest?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The weed referred to as tares (Lolium temulentum) grew in such a way that when fully matured, it was shorter than a wheat plant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, their ears were very different from those of wheat. Therefore, it was possible to identify and remove them before harvesting.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:29:48', '2024-12-27 06:13:11');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(170, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:31 \"He put before them another parable: &lsquo;The kingdom of heaven is like a mustard seed that someone took and sowed in his field.&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is mustard the smallest seed?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mustard (Brassica nigra) was the smallest seed (10-30 mm) cultivated by the Jews at that time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was primarily grown as food for camels rather than as a grain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some mustard plants growing near the lakes could reach up to 10 feet in height.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:30:58', '2024-12-27 04:30:58'),
(171, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:33 \"He told them another parable: &lsquo;The kingdom of heaven is like yeast that a woman took and mixed in with three measures of flour until all of it was leavened.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How much is three measures of flour?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word used here is &sigma;&alpha;&tau;&omicron;&nu; , which refers to approximately 12 litres (or about 1.5 bushels).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This amount of flour is sufficient for a dough that a woman can knead alone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is important to understand that when one begins the process, God will take care of the rest.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:40:13', '2024-12-27 04:40:13'),
(172, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:44 \"The kingdom of heaven is like treasure hidden in a field; which a man found and hid; then in his joy he goes and sells all that he has and buys that field.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the hidden treasure?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In biblical times, pearls were considered one of the most precious items, symbolising glory and value.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, in Matthew 7:6 , it is said: \"Do not throw your pearls before swine, or they will trample them underfoot and turn and maul you.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This reflects the idea that God\'s word and wisdom must be sought and obtained at a significant cost, emphasising the immense value of the kingdom of heaven.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:43:31', '2024-12-27 04:43:31'),
(173, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:45 &ldquo;Again, the kingdom of heaven is like a merchant in search of fine pearls.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is gemstone the most valuable stone?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p>Before the discovery of diamonds in the 19th century, gemstones and corals were considered the most valuable materials. These gems and corals were found along the shores of the Red Sea, as noted by Pliny the Younger.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:44:36', '2024-12-27 04:44:36'),
(174, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:47 \"Again, the kingdom of heaven is like a net that was thrown into the sea and caught fish of every kind\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What kind of net was cast to catch fish of every kind?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The net referred to here is a dragnet or seine (Greek: &sigma;&alpha;&gamma;ή&nu;&eta; - sagēnē).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These types of nets were typically 250 to 300 meters long and around 8 meters high.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Corks were attached to the upper side of the net to keep it afloat. A group of about 16 people were usually involved in casting and hauling the net.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is important to note that such nets had to be continuously hauled without stopping.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:53:21', '2024-12-27 04:53:21'),
(175, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 13:48: \"When it was full, they drew it ashore, sat down, and put the good into baskets but threw out the bad\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What type of net was used to catch fish?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The net referred to here is a Dragnet.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This large net is equipped with heavy objects (sinkers) at the bottom to keep it submerged, while floats are sewn onto the top to keep it afloat. Dragnets were typically used with two boats to effectively catch fish.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:54:13', '2024-12-27 04:54:13'),
(176, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Were some fish considered bad to eat?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 18, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews were not permitted to eat all types of fish. They were only allowed to eat fish from the sea that had both fins and scales.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"For anything in the seas or the streams that does not have fins and scales, of the swarming creatures in the waters and among all the other living creatures that are in the waters&mdash;they are detestable to you\" (Leviticus 11:12).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:54:46', '2024-12-27 06:13:22'),
(177, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 14:1 \"At that time Herod the ruler heard reports about Jesus\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Herod called Tetrarch?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 19, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"Tetrarch\" means \"ruler of a quarter of a kingdom.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After the death of Herod the Great, his kingdom was divided into four parts: Archelaus, Antipas, Philip, and Salome.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod Antipas was called Tetrarch because he ruled over one-quarter of the kingdom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:55:47', '2024-12-27 04:56:08'),
(178, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 14:3 \"For Herod had arrested John, bound him, and put him in prison on account of Herodias, his brother Philip&rsquo;s wife.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Herodias have two husbands who were brothers?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 19, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, Herodias\' two husbands were half-brothers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Herodias first married Herod Philip, her half-uncle, and then Herod Antipas, Philip&rsquo;s half-brother.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Despite this familial bond, Herodias\' second marriage violated moral and religious laws, which led to John the Baptist\'s condemnation of their union.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:57:02', '2024-12-27 04:57:02'),
(179, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 14:6 \"But when Herod&rsquo;s birthday came, the daughter of Herodias danced before the company, and she pleased Herod.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Salome also Herod\'s daughter?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 19, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the writings of the historian Flavius Josephus, Herod did not have any children with Herodias.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Salome was Herodias\' daughter from a previous marriage, specifically with Herod Philip, Herod\'s half-brother.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:57:48', '2024-12-27 04:57:48'),
(180, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 14:25 \"And early in the morning he came walking toward them on the sea.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the fourth watch of the night?</em></p>', 1, 19, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews traditionally divided the night into three watches:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">6:00 p.m. to 10:00 p.m.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">10:00 p.m. to 2:00 a.m.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">2:00 a.m. to 6:00 a.m.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the Romans divided the night into four watches:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">6:00 p.m. to 9:00 p.m.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">9:00 p.m. to 12:00 midnight</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">12:00 midnight to 3:00 a.m.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">3:00 a.m. to 6:00 a.m.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the \"fourth watch\" refers to the time between 3:00 a.m. and 6:00 a.m.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 04:58:46', '2024-12-27 06:13:32'),
(181, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 2:14: \"And he awoke, and took the child and his mother, and went that night into Egypt.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the Holy Family\'s journey to Egypt difficult?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time, the territory of Egypt was under Roman rule, extending as near as Gaza, which was approximately 250 miles from Bethlehem.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The journey to Alexandria, where many Jews lived in Egypt, was approximately 350 miles, requiring travel through a large stretch of desert.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 05:31:05', '2024-12-27 05:31:05'),
(182, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 3:12: \"His winnowing fork is in his hand, and he will clear his threshing floor and gather his wheat into the granary; but the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Jews separate the chaff from the wheat?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">After threshing, the wheat was thrown into the air, allowing the wind to separate the wheat from the chaff. It was customary to burn the chaff in the field itself. This practice serves as a metaphor for purification.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 05:54:22', '2024-12-27 05:54:22'),
(183, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mathew 3:13: \"Then Jesus came from Galilee to John at the Jordan, to be baptised by him.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was John\'s baptism mandatory for all Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews primarily used water for purification, and they had three types of purification rituals involving water:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sprinkling: This method involves sprinkling water for purification purposes.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Washing: This involved washing specific parts of the body or utensils.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Immersion: This was a complete immersion in water, which John practised as a baptism of repentance.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews could choose any of these methods for sanctification, but the usual act of purification was washing the body with water. Therefore, John\'s baptism of repentance (immersion) was not mandatory for the Jews. It represented a significant call to repentance rather than a required ritual.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 05:54:59', '2024-12-27 05:54:59'),
(184, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why was Jesus baptised without sin?</em></p>', 1, 8, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mosaic Law: Jesus adhered to all the rituals required of a Jewish person, including:</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Circumcision: Performed on the eighth day after birth.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Dedication: Took place on the fortieth day after birth.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Redemption: Observed at the age of twelve.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Baptism: Required at the age of thirty.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Beginning of Ministry: A Jewish priest began his ministry at the age of thirty, marking a significant transition in responsibility and leadership.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Baptism of Repentance: Jesus\' baptism was viewed as a baptism of repentance, which preceded the Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur). This act symbolised a commitment to spiritual renewal and preparation for His ministry.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Theological Significance: Jesus\' baptism held deep theological meaning. <br>It symbolised the Israelites\' entry into the Kingdom of Heaven when they crossed the Jordan River into the land of Canaan. This act foreshadowed the transformative journey He would lead His followers toward salvation and reconciliation with God.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 05:56:12', '2024-12-27 05:56:12'),
(185, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 3:15 \"But Jesus answered him, \'Let it be so now; for it is proper for us in this way to fulfil all righteousness.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>According to Matthew, what was fulfilled in Jesus\' baptism?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">On the tenth day (Tishri 10) of the seventh month, the Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur) was observed. For this day, two goats and a bull were chosen with one of the goats designated as the scapegoat.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The high priest placed all the sins of the people of Israel on the head of the scapegoat, symbolically transferring the sins through the act of laying both hands on it.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This act involved reciting prayers as the sins were laid upon the goat. The atoning lamb was then driven into the wilderness, symbolising the removal of sin from the community.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the first Day of Atonement, it was Aaron who placed his hand on the lamb\'s head to atone for the sins of the people, as described in Leviticus 16:21: \"Aaron shall lay both his hands on the head of the live goat, and confess over it all the iniquities of the people of Israel, and all their transgressions, all their sins, putting them on the head of the goat, and sending it away into the wilderness by the man designated for the task.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke 1:5: \"In the days of King Herod of Judea, there was a priest named Zechariah, who belonged to the priestly order of Abijah. His wife was a descendant of Aaron, and her name was Elizabeth.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Here, John the Baptist, a priest of the Aaron clan, baptises Jesus. Thus, Matthew is portraying Jesus as the atoning lamb of the New Testament.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Here Jesus fulfills the Old Testament Day of Atonement.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 05:57:23', '2024-12-27 05:57:23'),
(186, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 3:17 &ldquo;This is my beloved Son; with whom I am well pleased.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who heard the voice from heaven?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 8, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John the Baptist baptised two kinds of people.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Those who stayed at home after being baptised by John the Baptist.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Those who became John\'s disciples after being baptised.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Those who became John\'s disciples were always with John (John 1:35).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John taught them to lead a life of fasting (Mark 2:18), and prayer (Luke 11:2). So that they become witnesses of Jesus&rsquo;s baptism</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 05:57:59', '2024-12-27 05:57:59'),
(187, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 15:7-8 :&ldquo;You hypocrites! Isaiah prophesied rightly about you when he said: &lsquo;This people honours me with their lips, but their hearts are far from me.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who does Matthew call hypocrites?</em></p>', 1, 20, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Those who do good with evil intentions:<br>\"So whenever you give alms, do not sound a trumpet before you, as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and in the streets, so that they may be praised by others.\" (Matthew 6:2,)<br>\"And whenever you pray, do not be like the hypocrites; for they love to stand and pray in the synagogues and at the street corners, so that they may be seen by others.\" (Matthew 6:5,)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Those who are overly concerned about minor matters while neglecting important ones:<br>\"Or how can you say to your neighbour, &lsquo;Let me take the speck out of your eye,&rsquo; while the log is in your own eye?\" (Matthew 7:4-5)<br>\"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you tithe mint, dill and cumin, and have neglected the weightier matters of the law: justice and mercy and faith.\" (Matthew 23:23)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Those who worship with their lips but not with their hearts:<br>\"You hypocrites! Isaiah prophesied rightly about you when he said: &lsquo;This people honors me with their lips, but their hearts are far from me.&rsquo;\" (Matthew 15:7-8)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:15:01', '2024-12-27 06:15:01'),
(188, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 15:22: \"Just then a Canaanite woman from that region came out and started shouting, \'Have mercy on me, Lord, Son of David; my daughter is tormented by a demon.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does Matthew call this Syro-Phoenician woman a Canaanite?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 20, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the 10th century B.C., the Canaanites, who originally inhabited Palestine, became fragmented into small city-states along the Mediterranean Sea.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These city-states, which fell under control of Egypt, Israel and Phoenicia, included Biruta, Byblos, Hazor, Tyre, Sarepta and Sidon. In 738 B.C., the Assyrians conquered these Phoenician kingdoms, followed by the Babylonians in 573 B.C., the Persians in 539 B.C., and later, the Greeks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Despite these conquests, many Canaanites did not migrate and continued to be known as Canaanites.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:15:59', '2024-12-27 06:15:59'),
(189, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the Canaanite woman call Jesus the son of David?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 20, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Canaanite woman referred to Jesus as the \"Son of David\" to acknowledge Him as the expected Messiah. According to Jewish belief, Solomon was regarded as an exceptional exorcist, or the \"Exorcist par excellence\" (Kings 4:20-34).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They expected that the Messiah would surpass Solomon in power, particularly in driving out demons.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By calling Jesus the \"Son of David,\" the woman recognised Him as the Messiah with authority over evil.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:16:46', '2024-12-27 06:16:46'),
(190, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 15:26 \"He said, \'It is not proper to take the bread of the children and throw it to the dogs.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Would the bread be given to the dogs?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 20, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time, wealthy people in Israel used bread to wipe their hands between meals. The discarded bread, which had been used to clean off leftovers, was often thrown away, attracting many dogs that came to eat it. Dogs scrambling for food in front of a house was considered a sign of richness .</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:19:51', '2024-12-27 06:19:51'),
(191, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the Jews not value dogs?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 20, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In some instances in the Old Testament, dogs are portrayed as good creatures. For example:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The dog follows Tobias (Tobit 11:4).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Dogs were used to protect livestock: \"Now those younger than me mock me; I was a servant to their fathers. I was not even to be counted among the dogs of my flock\" (Job 30:1).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, for the most part, dogs are depicted negatively in the Old Testament. Reasons why Israelites generally disliked dogs include:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">They lick and drink blood (Psalm 68:24).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">They eat dead bodies (1 Kings 14:11-13).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Dogs were sacred in some pagan temples.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Being called a dog was considered an insult.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, in Deuteronomy 14:8, dogs are not listed among unclean animals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:20:40', '2024-12-27 06:20:40'),
(192, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 16:6 \"And Jesus said, &lsquo;Watch out, and beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Jesus mean by the leaven of the Pharisees?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews traditionally set aside leaven to ferment the dough.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, leaven also symbolises \'false influence.\'&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is emphasised by the instruction given to the Israelites not to take leaven when they departed from Egypt (Exodus 12:15).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:21:30', '2024-12-27 06:21:30'),
(193, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 16:13 \"When Jesus came to the region of Caesarea Philippi, he asked his disciples, &lsquo;Who do people say that the Son of Man is?&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was special about the area of Caesarea Philippi?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Caesarea Philippi was notable for its worship of the Canaanite god Baal.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Later, it became a significant site of worship for the Greek God Pan. Subsequently, during Roman rule, the region was governed by Herod and then by his son Philip.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Philip named Caesarea Philippi to honour Caesar and appease his benevolence .</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:22:13', '2024-12-27 06:22:13'),
(194, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 16:16 \"Simon Peter replied, &lsquo;You are the Messiah, the Son of the living God.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Christ\'s disciple Simeon get the name Peter?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus addressed Peter in Aramaic, saying, &ldquo;You are a rock&rdquo; (Matthew 16:18).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Greek language, in which the Gospel was written, the word for rock is \"Petra.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From the word \"Petra\" Simeon received the name Peter.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:24:23', '2024-12-27 06:24:23'),
(195, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 16:17 \"And Jesus answered him, &lsquo;Blessed are you, Simon son of Jonah! For flesh and blood has not revealed this to you, but my Father in heaven.&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the name of Peter&rsquo;s father?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Matthew\'s Gospel, Peter\'s father is referred to as \"Jonah\" (Matthew 16:17).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in the Gospel of John (John 1:42), it is mentioned as \"John.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name Jonah is rendered as \"Yovanus\" in Greek culture, and the name Yehochanan may have derived from this, as both names are considered interchangeable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, Jonah and John can be viewed as one.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:25:07', '2024-12-27 06:25:07'),
(196, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 16:18 \"And I tell you, you are Peter, and on this rock I will build my church, and the gates of Hades will not prevail against it.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews believe there was a gate to hell?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, the word \"Hades\" is used for hell, referring to a place of the dead.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Furthermore, the Jewish court was situated at the city gate, where they believed judgment and the separation of souls to heaven and hell occurred.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This belief contributed to the notion that hell has a gate.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:26:00', '2024-12-27 06:26:00'),
(197, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the term \"Hades\" come to be associated with hell?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Hades is the term used for hell in the Bible.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The word originates from Greek mythology, from Hades the brother of Zeus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After overthrowing their father, Kronos, the brothers divided the universe into two realms. Zeus chose to rule the upper part, while Hades reigned the lower part.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, Hades became the ruler of the lost souls, which is how the name Hades came to be associated with hell.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:26:42', '2024-12-27 06:26:42'),
(198, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What did the gates symbolise?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">All the old towns were protected by forts, each with a main gate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This gate served as a hub for important trade and activities within the town.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Courts, significant trade dealings, discussions and decisions were held near this entrance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"gate of hell\" signifies not only the door to hell but also the place where the devil\'s schemes are devised.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:27:32', '2024-12-27 06:27:32'),
(199, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus call the Church \'My Church\'?</em></p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In the Old Testament, God the Father referred to the people of Israel as \"My own people.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in Deuteronomy 7:6 , \"For you are a people holy to the Lord your God; the Lord your God has chosen you out of all the peoples on earth to be his people, his treasured possession.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, in the New Testament, Jesus refers to the Church as \"My Church,\" signifying that the Church belongs to Christ.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:28:16', '2024-12-27 06:28:16'),
(200, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why does Matthew use the word church?</em></p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Matthew is writing his Gospel to Jewish Christians, who possess considerable knowledge of the Old Testament.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;The term \"Ecclesia\" is used 106 times in the Septuagint (LXX: the Old Testament written in Greek).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Septuagint, Matthew employs this term because of the audience\'s familiarity with it.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:28:58', '2024-12-27 06:28:58'),
(201, '<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Matthew 16:19 &ldquo;I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven; and whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be lost in heaven.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the key symbolise?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Often, the keys were much larger than it appears today and it was a symbol of authority.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The master would entrust the key of his house to his most important servant. This serves as a metaphor for the key to God\'s kingdom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:39:24', '2024-12-27 06:39:24'),
(202, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 16:19 &ldquo;I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven; and whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven.&rdquo;</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was locking and unlocking with a key important to the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Since the establishment of the Temple in Jerusalem, it was the Levites who were responsible for opening and closing it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in 1 Chronicles 9:26 : \"The four chief gatekeepers were of the Korahites, and were responsible for the chambers and the treasures of the house of God.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the time of Jesus, closing the doors of the temple was a ritual conducted by the priest.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After the priest\'s blessing, the act of sending people away and closing the gate was known as Neliah.</p>\r\n<p>Thus, the Jews were familiar with Neliah and the concept of locking and unlocking doors with keys.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:51:17', '2024-12-27 06:51:17'),
(203, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was it important to hand over the keys to the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">As noted in 1 Chronicles 9:27 , \"They would spend the night around the house of God, for they had the responsibility for guarding it; and the opening of it every morning belonged to them.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The priests who held the keys (Mapteah) of the temple were responsible for opening and closing the temple daily. The transfer of this right from one priesthood to the next was a ritual.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the day of the key exchange, the two groups would count and exchange the keys and the holy vessels in the temple courtyard at noon (Josephus, Against Apion 2.108).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Mishna, the priest who kept the keys of the temple was not allowed to put them down, even while sleeping, to ensure that one would always be aware of heaven.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:54:19', '2024-12-27 06:54:19'),
(204, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did thieves steal from open houses?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The houses during the time of Matthew were designed with courtyards, and all the doors of the house would open towards this central area.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The back walls of these homes typically had no doors or windows, making them vulnerable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since there were usually more people gathered at the front of the house, thieves used to break in through the back wall.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:54:59', '2024-12-27 06:54:59'),
(205, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What did the key symbolise?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Isaiah 22:22, God grants Eliakim the key to the house of David: \"I will place on his shoulder the key of the house of David; he shall open, and no one shall shut; he shall shut, and no one shall open.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This passage is a divine warning against Shebna, the steward in Israel\'s palace, whom God replaces with Eliakim, the son of Hilkiah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The key symbolises authority and judgment, a privilege of the court council (soken)</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:55:35', '2024-12-27 06:55:35'),
(206, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the Jews lose the keys to the Temple of Jerusalem?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Before the Babylonian exile, the priests kept the keys of the temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A tale arose among them about what happened when the temple was destroyed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to this tale, the prophet Jeremiah threw the keys of the temple into the air, after which they disappeared (Bar. 4:4-5; 2 bar. 10:18; Lev. Rab. 19.6; Abbot R. Nat. A. 4:5).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The keys were no longer held physically, but symbolically, reflecting God\'s ultimate authority over the temple.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:56:19', '2024-12-27 06:56:19'),
(207, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Can other bishops exercise the authority given to Peter?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes. In the Gospels, Jesus first gives authority to Peter (Matthew 16:19) and later extends it to the other disciples (Matthew 18:18).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus says: \"Truly I tell you, whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven\" (Matthew 18:18).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This authority of binding and loosing, initially granted to Peter, is shared with other bishops through their communion with Peter (in union with Peter).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bishops exercise this same authority but only in union with Peter\'s unique role.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:56:57', '2024-12-27 06:56:57'),
(208, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 16:23 &ldquo;But he turned and said to Peter, &lsquo;Get behind me, Satan! You are a stumbling block to me, for you are setting your mind not on divine things but on human things.&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus ask Peter to go away from him?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 21, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus rebukes Peter with the words \"Get behind me, Satan\" as they were on their way to Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word hupage (\"be off\") indicates dismissal. Peter, whose name means \'rock,\' was becoming a \'stumbling block\' to Jesus\' mission, especially as He was preparing for His suffering and death.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus pushes away anything or anyone that obstructs His path to fulfilling God\'s will.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 06:57:33', '2024-12-27 06:57:33'),
(209, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 17:1 \"Six days later, Jesus took with him Peter and James and his brother John and led them up a high mountain, by themselves.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus take the disciples to the mountain after six days?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The reference to six days is significant because it echoes the experience of Moses on Mount Sinai.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As recorded in Exodus 24:16: \"The glory of the Lord settled on Mount Sinai, and the cloud covered it for six days; on the seventh day he called to Moses out of the cloud.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus\' transfiguration on the mountain parallels this event. Just as Moses waited, everyone experiences a period of waiting for the Lord\'s glory to be revealed.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:00:45', '2024-12-27 08:03:36'),
(210, '<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Matthew 17:3 \"And suddenly there appeared to them Moses and Elijah, talking with him\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Moses and Elijah speak to Jesus?</em></p>', 1, 22, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">God took both men into heaven. Elijah was taken up in a whirlwind: \"Now when the Lord was about to take Elijah up to heaven by a whirlwind\" (2 Kings 2:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Regarding Moses, it is believed that God Himself buried him in a hidden location: \"He was buried in a valley in the land of Moab, opposite Beth-peor, but no one knows his burial place to this day\" (Deuteronomy 34:6,).</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Both Moses and Elijah had significant encounters with God on Mount Horeb (Exodus 24:15-16; 1 Kings 19:8).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why Moses and Elijah spoke to Jesus.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:01:36', '2024-12-27 08:03:14'),
(211, '<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Matthew 17:4 \"Then Peter said to Jesus, \'Lord, it is good for us to be here; if you wish, I will make three dwellings here, one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah\'\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Peter experienced in tent-making? Did Peter have experience making tents?</em></p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, the Jews celebrated the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkot) annually, during which they lived in temporary shelters to commemorate their ancestors\' journey through the wilderness.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Peter, like other Jews, would have built these tents for the festival.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:02:47', '2024-12-27 08:02:47'),
(212, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Peter offer to make three tents?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Transfiguration of Jesus took place during the Feast of Tabernacles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This feast commemorated the Israelites\' 40 years in the desert during their journey to the Promised Land of Canaan. Peter, being familiar with the customs of the Feast of Tabernacles, offered to build tents for Jesus, Moses and Elijah as a way of honouring this event and seeking the Lord\'s presence. His offer expresses his deep desire for the Lord to dwell with him.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:04:37', '2024-12-27 08:04:37'),
(213, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 17:11 \"He replied, \'Elijah is indeed coming and will restore all things.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was Elijah supposed to restore?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish scholarly community believed that some religious practices of the time had deviated from the laws given by Moses.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, Moses&rsquo; law prescribed that worship should occur only in Jerusalem, but Diaspora Jews worshiped in other places (John 4:20).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish tradition, Elijah was expected to return and resolve such religious disputes (Malachi 4:5).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During Passover, they would leave their doors open and empty a seat to symbolise the return of Elijah.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:05:23', '2024-12-27 08:05:23'),
(214, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the Jews believe Elijah will return?</em></p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews believed that after death, individuals passed through the gates of Sheol (hell), and once they passed through, there was no return.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Elijah did not pass through this door since he was taken up into heaven (2 Kings 2:11). Therefore, it was believed that Elijah would return before the coming of the Messiah, as he had not experienced death.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Once someone goes through the door of death, there is no returning.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:06:07', '2024-12-27 08:06:07'),
(215, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 17:20 \"He said to them, \'For truly I tell you, if you have faith the size of a mustard seed, you will say to this mountain, \"Move from here to there,\" and it will move; and nothing will be impossible for you.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is faith supposed to be as small as a mustard seed?</em></p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Traditionally, Jesus&rsquo; reference to faith \"the size of a mustard seed\" has been interpreted as \"minuscule faith.\" However, another interpretation is possible, based on the Israelites\' understanding of the mustard seed\'s unique properties:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Rigorosity: &nbsp;Mustard plants are highly prolific. They grow in clusters in a small area, this analogy was used to symbolise how even the smallest amount of faith can grow abundantly.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Zero Wastage: The Israelites believed that every mustard seed that falls to the ground will sprout, representing the surety and fruitfulness of genuine faith.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sharp Taste: Mustard has a sharp, pungent taste, which can be seen as a metaphor for the intensity and vigor of faith.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Therefore, faith \"the size of a mustard seed\" also signifies rigorous, fruitful and intense faith.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:07:02', '2024-12-27 08:07:02'),
(216, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 17:24 \"When they came to Capernaum, the collectors of the temple tax came to Peter and said, \'Does your teacher not pay the temple tax?\'\"</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the temple tax?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">All Jewish men over the age of 20 were required to pay the temple tax.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The tax was half a shekel per year, as specified in Exodus 30:13 \"Each one who is registered shall give half a shekel according to the sanctuary shekel.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was a mandatory contribution for the maintenance of the temple.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:08:03', '2024-12-27 08:08:03'),
(217, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did they question whether Jesus paid taxes?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Though all Jewish men over 20 were required to pay the temple tax, certain groups, such as beggars or temple workers who depended on charity, were exempt.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There is no indication that Jesus is exempt from taxation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:08:42', '2024-12-27 08:08:42'),
(218, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What was the temple tax?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">All Jews over the age of 20 were required to pay the temple tax.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was a yearly contribution of half a shekel. As stated in Exodus 30:13 , \"This is what each one who is registered shall give: half a shekel according to the shekel of the sanctuary.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was their share to contribute, symbolising their dedication through their hard work.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:09:39', '2024-12-27 08:09:39'),
(219, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What was the temple tax?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">All Jews over the age of 20 were required to pay the temple tax.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was a yearly contribution of half a shekel. As stated in Exodus 30:13 , \"This is what each one who is registered shall give: half a shekel according to the shekel of the sanctuary.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was their share to contribute, symbolising their dedication through their hard work.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:09:39', '2024-12-27 08:09:39'),
(220, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why was the temple tax paid?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The temple tax covered the cost of the sacrifices offered on behalf of the individual at the temple.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In addition, it helped provide for the public sacrifices made for all the people of Israel, including food sacrifices, drink offerings and grain offerings.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The temple was sustained by the contributions of their forefathers, a reflection of the community&rsquo;s shared efforts.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:10:22', '2024-12-27 08:10:22'),
(221, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How much was the amount to be paid as temple tax?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Law of Moses, the temple tax was half a shekel (Exodus 30:13).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">1/2 Shekel = 2 Drachmas (and 3 Denarii = 1 Shekel).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, after the Babylonian exile, the contribution was reduced to one-third of a shekel (Nehemiah 10:32-34).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:10:58', '2024-12-27 08:10:58'),
(222, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why was the temple tax paid in shekels?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The temple tax had to be paid in Tyrian Shekels.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They are known as the \"Tyrian Shekel,\" because they were minted in Tyre.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These coins were known for their high silver content, ensuring a pure and valuable contribution.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:11:37', '2024-12-27 08:11:37'),
(223, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 17:25 : &ldquo;He said, &lsquo;Yes.&rsquo; And when he came home, Jesus spoke of it first, saying, &lsquo;What do you think, Simon? From whom do kings of the earth take toll or tribute? From their children or from others?&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were there two types of taxes?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, there were two distinct types of levies.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word for \"tax\" is teleos (meaning toll), while the word for \"tribute\" is kenos.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Historically, teleos referred to the general taxes collected in Greek times. However, under Roman rule, the term kenos was more commonly used for taxes paid to the emperor.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:12:19', '2024-12-27 08:12:19'),
(224, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 17:27: \"However, so that we do not give offense to them, go to the sea and cast a hook; take the first fish that comes up, and when you open its mouth, you will find a coin; take that and give it to them for you and me.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What coin did Peter get out of the fish\'s mouth?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Peter found a silver coin known as a stater.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The value of the coin was equivalent to four drachmas, which was a significant sum in Roman currency, sufficient to pay the temple tax for both Jesus and Peter for a few years.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:13:15', '2024-12-27 08:13:15'),
(225, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 17:26: \"When Peter said, \'From others,\' Jesus said to him, \'Then the children are free.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Jesus mean when He said the children are free?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">St. Augustine explains that in no kingdom were the children of the king required to pay taxes; they were exempt from taxation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, the children of God, the King of all kings, are free.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This illustrates the freedom and grace bestowed upon the followers of Christ, the true heirs of the kingdom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:13:56', '2024-12-27 08:13:56'),
(226, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 17:27: \"However, so that we do not offend them, go to the sea and cast a hook; take the first fish that comes up, and when you open its mouth, you will find a coin.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were the fishing methods employed by the Jews to fish from the Sea of Galilee?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 22, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There were three types of fishing methods used in the Sea of Galilee:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Dragnet Spread Fishing: This involved spreading the net between two boats.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Cast Net Fishing: Sitting in a boat and casting a small net to catch fish (as seen in Matthew 4:18).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Metal Hook Fishing: Baiting a hook, as described in Matthew 17:27.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:14:41', '2024-12-27 08:14:41'),
(227, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:3: \"Truly I tell you, unless you change and become like children, you will never enter the kingdom of heaven.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why repent and become like little children?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The verb used for \"repent\" is strepho.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Combined with the idea of \"being like a child,\" it suggests innocently acknowledging and accepting God as our Father.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:20:32', '2024-12-27 08:20:32'),
(228, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:6:\"If any of you put a stumbling block before one of these little ones who believe in me, it would be better for you if a great millstone were fastened around your neck and you were drowned in the depth of the sea.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were men tied to stones and lowered into the sea?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, this was a form of Roman punishment for certain crimes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The guilty person would be tied in a sack and thrown into the sea, with a large stone attached to ensure that they would not resurface.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:21:19', '2024-12-27 08:21:19');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(229, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:10:\"Take care that you do not despise one of these little ones; for I tell you, in heaven their angels continually see the face of my Father in heaven.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews believe in guardian angels?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">While the specific term \"guardian angel\" developed much later, the concept of good angels were present in Jewish tradition.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, in Tobit 5:22 , it is written: \"The good angel will accompany him; his journey will be successful.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Other Jewish texts, such as (Tosefta Shabat 17:2-3, Sifre Numbers 40.1.5) &nbsp;also state instances of angels walking with individuals.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:22:00', '2024-12-27 08:22:00'),
(230, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:12 &ldquo;What do you think? If a man has a hundred sheep and one of them goes astray, does he not leave the ninety-nine on the mountains and go in search of the one that went astray?&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus count the 100 sheep?&nbsp;</em></p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Palestine, a shepherd was usually given about 100 sheep to look after (as noted in the Hibeh Papyri 33.16, which mentions 80).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This detail illustrates the story of a common shepherd, emphasising Jesus\' familiarity with their lives and duties.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:22:43', '2024-12-27 08:22:43'),
(231, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:12 &ldquo;But the children of the kingdom will be thrown into the outer darkness, where there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Jesus mean that there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth in outer darkness?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Wailing and gnashing of teeth is an expression found in Semitic languages, indicating overwhelming disappointment and regret over lost opportunities.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:23:46', '2024-12-27 08:23:46'),
(232, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:15 &ldquo;If your brother sins against you, go and tell him his fault between you and him alone.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>If I make a mistake, should I correct it privately?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish social life was regulated by the rabbis, who emphasised the importance of maintaining one&rsquo;s dignity and avoiding public shame (b. Sanh 101 a).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jethro correcting Moses is one such example(Exodus 18:14-16).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:24:26', '2024-12-27 08:24:26'),
(233, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:19 &ldquo;Again, truly I tell you, if two of you agree on earth about anything you ask, it will be done for you by my Father in heaven.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How can two people agree to ask for one thing?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word \"Sumphoneo\" is used here, meaning to ask together. This word is akin to \"symphony,\" which describes harmony in music.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even though two musical instruments emit different tones, they create an enjoyable sound when harmoniously played together.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, although two people may differ, they should unite in spirit and intention while asking for something.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:25:06', '2024-12-27 08:25:06'),
(234, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:20: \"For where two or three are gathered in my name, I am there among them.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Should two people pray together?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish belief, for a prayer to be considered sacrificial, at least ten men must pray together, a practice known as corporate worship.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Jesus emphasises that even when two people pray together, it constitutes corporate worship.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:25:51', '2024-12-27 08:25:51'),
(235, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:22: \"Jesus said to him, \'Not seven times, but, I tell you, seventy-seven times.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Should we forgive 490 (seventy-seven) times?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, the number seven is often associated with atonement.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Vengeance of God: \"And the Lord said, \'Whoever kills Cain will suffer a sevenfold vengeance.\'\" (Genesis 4:15, .).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Expiation: \"He shall sprinkle the blood of the sin offering on the altar seven times.\" (Leviticus 16:14, .).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Forgiveness: \"God waits seven times for one who repents.\" (Proverbs 24:16).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, forgiving seventy-seven times signifies an attitude of infinite forgiveness.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">10. Should we forgive seven and seventy times?</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Lamech, a descendant of Cain, expressed a vengeful spirit, declaring, \"If Cain is avenged sevenfold, truly Lamech seventy-sevenfold!\" (Genesis 4:24).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus encourages His disciples to embody greater patience and willingness to forgive.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:26:39', '2024-12-27 08:26:39'),
(236, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 18:24 \"When he began the reckoning, one who owed him ten thousand talents was brought to him.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Will the king lend ten thousand talents?</em></p>', 1, 23, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Ten thousand talents is equivalent to 100 million denarii.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For perspective, the price of a slave at that time was only between 500 and 2,000 denarii.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Lending such a vast amount was highly unlikely. Matthew used this extreme figure as a shock tactic, emphasising the impossibility of repaying such a debt.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The parable\'s point illustrates that humanity cannot repay their debt to God.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:27:17', '2024-12-27 08:27:17'),
(237, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 19:6: \"So they are no longer two, but one flesh. Therefore, what God has joined together, let no one separate.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jewish tradition hold that husbands and wives were one body?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 24, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Genesis 2:23, when God created Eve, Adam declared, \"This at last is bone of my bones and flesh of my flesh.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\" The expression \"bone of my bones and flesh of my flesh\" describes one&rsquo;s own body, as also seen in Job 2:5: \"Stretch out your hand now, and touch his bone and his flesh, and he will curse you to your face.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To the Jews, husband and wife were indeed regarded as one body.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:28:00', '2024-12-27 08:28:00'),
(238, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 19:12 \"For there are eunuchs who have been so from birth, and there are eunuchs who have been made eunuchs by others, and there are eunuchs who have made themselves eunuchs for the sake of the kingdom of heaven. Let anyone accept this who can.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were there people who were castrated by humans?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 24, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, in some pagan cultures, men were castrated for roles in royal courts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, this practice was forbidden for the Jews, as it is written in Deuteronomy 23:1: \"No one whose testicles are crushed or whose penis is cut off shall be admitted to the assembly of the Lord.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:28:41', '2024-12-27 08:28:41'),
(239, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 19:16 \"Then someone came to him and said, &lsquo;Teacher, what good deed must I do to have eternal life?&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the young man approach Jesus to ask about eternal life?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 24, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In that era, it was common for Jewish youth to explore different religious sects to pursue a deeper spiritual life. Among these groups were:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Essenes,&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Zealots</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The disciples of John</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The young man likely approached Jesus out of curiosity, possibly having observed other groups and wanting to understand how Jesus\' teachings differed from theirs.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:29:24', '2024-12-27 08:29:24'),
(240, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 19:24: \"Again I tell you, it is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for someone who is rich to enter the kingdom of God.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the camel considered to be a monstrous creature?</em><br><br></p>', 1, 24, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The \"eye of a needle\" referred to the smallest possible opening known at that time, while the camel was the largest land animal known in the region.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The comparison between the largest and smallest things in their experience was used as a hyperbolic metaphor to highlight the difficulty of the rich entering the kingdom of heaven.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:30:35', '2024-12-27 08:30:35'),
(241, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 19:27 \"Then Peter said in reply, &lsquo;Look, we have left everything and followed you. What then will we have?&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Peter give up everything to become a disciple?</em><br><br></p>', 1, 24, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, in those days, if a king wished to join an alliance with another king, he had to break all ties with previous allegiances.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, after Mark Antony\'s death, King Herod abandoned his alliance with Antony and became a friend of Augustus Caesar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, in following Jesus, Peter and the disciples had to renounce previous ties and commit to the new alliance with Jesus.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:31:15', '2024-12-27 08:31:15'),
(242, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 19:28 \"Jesus said to them, \'Truly I tell you, at the renewal of all things, when the Son of Man is seated on the throne of his glory, you who have followed me will also sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Will the 12 tribes of Israel be reunited?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 24, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Israel\'s golden age, there were twelve tribes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, after the Assyrian invasion in 721 B.C., ten tribes were dispersed and assimilated into other nations, leaving only the tribes of Judah and Benjamin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews believed that when the Saviour comes, the ten lost tribes would be restored to Israel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:31:53', '2024-12-27 08:31:53'),
(243, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 19:29 \"And everyone who has left houses or brothers or sisters or father or mother or children or fields, for my name&rsquo;s sake, will receive a hundredfold, and will inherit eternal life.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus ask us to give up everything?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 24, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Essenes, a monastic Jewish community, abandoned all their possessions and lived together in the desert, dedicated to a life of purity and spirituality.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Similarly, the Gospel of Matthew was written within a community setting (Mathean Community), reflecting the practices of groups like the Essenes and the Qumran community. This is why Matthew emphasises the call to renounce everything for the sake of the Kingdom of God.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:32:34', '2024-12-27 08:32:34'),
(244, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 20:2 \"After agreeing with the labourers for the usual daily wage, he sent them into his vineyard\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When should a day\'s work end?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Grape ripening typically begins in the first weeks of September.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The day&rsquo;s work was expected to end when the first star appeared in the sky, a common marker for labourers.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:33:29', '2024-12-27 08:33:29'),
(245, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 20:3 \"When he went out about nine o&rsquo;clock, he saw others standing idle in the marketplace\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What time is the third hour for the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish day starts the evening before, but they count hours from six o\'clock in the morning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the \"third hour\" is between 8:00 AM and 9:00 AM.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The \"eleventh hour\" refers to the time between 4:00 PM and 5:00 PM.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:40:57', '2024-12-27 08:40:57'),
(246, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 20:4 \"He said to them, &lsquo;You also go into the vineyard, and I will pay you whatever is right.&rsquo; So they went\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is \'wages\' an important word in the Gospel?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Gospel emphasises that man always serves a master.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As Matthew 6:24&nbsp; says, \"No one can serve two masters; for a slave will either hate the one and love the other, or be devoted to the one and despise the other.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;You cannot serve God and wealth.\" If you serve God, you will receive the kingdom of God as your reward. If you serve evil, the wages will be punishment.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:41:32', '2024-12-27 08:41:32'),
(247, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 20:6 \"And about five o&rsquo;clock he went out and found others standing around; and he said to them, &lsquo;Why are you standing here idle all day?&rsquo;\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were the workers who were not called to work lazy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In those times, employers would hire workers from the marketplace when they needed help.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These workers who didn&rsquo;t get called first were not necessarily lazy. <br>They were simply not called earlier.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:42:11', '2024-12-27 08:42:11'),
(248, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What was the eleventh hour when the last crew was called?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p>For the Jews, the first hour of the day was at six o\'clock in the morning. Therefore, the eleventh hour, when the last workers were called, was at 5 PM.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:42:45', '2024-12-27 08:42:45'),
(249, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 20:8 \"When evening came, the owner of the vineyard said to his manager, \'Call the labourers and give them their pay, beginning with the last and then going to the first.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews pay the wages of the workers on the same day?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews were careful to pay their workers on the same day, as it was commanded by God:<br>\"You shall pay them their wages daily before sunset because they are poor and their livelihood depends on them; otherwise they might cry to the Lord against you, and you would incur guilt\" (Deuteronomy 24:15).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"You shall not defraud your neighbour; you shall not steal; and you shall not keep for yourself the wages of a labourer until morning\" (Leviticus 19:13).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Non-payment of wages to a worker was seen as a serious offence, equated with murder in the Old Testament: \"To deprive an employee of wages is to shed blood\" (Sirach 34:26-27).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the Mishnah later interpreted that if the worker does not request payment and it was not given on the same day, it was permissible under certain circumstances (Mishnah 9:12, The Mishnah, London: Oxford University Press, 1993). Despite this, the Jews were generally diligent in paying workers on the same day.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:43:28', '2024-12-27 08:43:28'),
(250, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 20:9 \"When those hired about five o&rsquo;clock came, each of them received the usual daily wage\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was a denarius a day\'s wages?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The denarius was a Roman silver coin that represented a day\'s wage for a soldier.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;However, Jewish laborers were not necessarily required to receive a denarius as their wage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Often, wages were negotiated based on the nature of the work, and employers might call workers multiple times during the day depending on the job\'s needs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The payment amount was typically determined through negotiation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:44:12', '2024-12-27 08:44:12'),
(251, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the workers have to work 12 hours?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A 12-hour workday was not common in those times, but during the harvest, when there was a risk of fruit spoiling, 12-hour shifts were sometimes required.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In such emergency situations, the workers might labour for extended hours to ensure the harvest is protected.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:44:43', '2024-12-27 08:44:43'),
(252, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 20:13 \"But he replied to one of them, &lsquo;Friend, I am doing you no wrong; did you not agree with me for the usual daily wage?&rsquo;.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does the master call the worker \"friend\"?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This is a literary technique used by Matthew in his narrative. \"Friend\" is used here to show.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Generosity of the speaker&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To shame the person addressed.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Another example:<br>\"Immediately he came up to Jesus and said, &lsquo;Greetings, Rabbi!&rsquo; and kissed him. Jesus said to him, &lsquo;Friend, do what you are here to do.&rsquo; Then they came and laid hands on Jesus and arrested him\" (Matthew 26:49-50).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The master here uses \"friend\" to highlight his fairness and generosity in contrast to the worker&rsquo;s envious attitude.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:45:32', '2024-12-27 08:45:32'),
(253, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 20:27 \"Whoever wishes to be great among you must be your servant, and whoever wishes to be first among you must be your slave\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Are the minister and the servant the same?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Greek context, a minister is referred to as Diakonos and a servant is referred to as Doulos. There is a distinction between the two:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Diakonos refers to a paid servant or a subordinate slave who is owned by the master. The term is the root of the word Deacon (derived from Diakonos, meaning \"through the dust\").</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Doulos, on the other hand, refers to someone who is appointed to perform any kind of task in the master\'s household.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The word \"Deacon\" comes from diakonos (dio = through, konis = dust).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The wages for a Diakonos are typically monetary, while a Doulos\'s service may be seen as more integral to the master\'s household.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:46:11', '2024-12-27 08:46:11'),
(254, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 20:28 \"Just as the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life a ransom for many.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is meant by \"ransom\"?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 25, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The word used for ransom here is Lutron, a term commonly used in the marketplace for the price paid to free prisoners of war.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In ancient times, a person captured in battle could be redeemed for a certain sum of money. This payment, called ransom, secured the person&rsquo;s freedom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:46:45', '2024-12-27 08:46:45'),
(255, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:1 \"When they had approached Jerusalem and had come to Bethphage, at the Mount of Olives, Jesus sent two disciples, saying to them...\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus choose the Mount of Olives to commence His royal entry?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Zechariah\'s prophecy concludes with a description of the Day of the Lord, stating that He will arrive in Jerusalem as a warrior from the Mount of Olives.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in Zechariah 14:3-4, \"Then the Lord will go forth and fight against those nations as when he fights on a day of battle. On that day his feet shall stand on the Mount of Olives, which lies before Jerusalem on the east.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is the reason Jesus selected the Mount of Olives as the starting point for His royal entry.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:53:48', '2024-12-27 08:53:48'),
(256, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why is Bethphage, where Jesus began His royal accession, named as such?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Bethphage was a village located on the slopes of the Mount of Olives.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name \"Bethphage\" translates to \"House of Unripe Figs.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is where Jesus commenced His royal entry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:54:21', '2024-12-27 08:54:21'),
(257, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:5 \"Tell the daughter of Zion, &lsquo;Look, your king is coming to you, humble, and mounted on a donkey, and on a colt, the foal of a donkey.&rsquo;\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus have two donkeys for His auspicious procession?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark and Luke mention only one donkey (Polos) but Matthew mentions two (a donkey and its colt).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the evangelists (Mark 11:2, Luke 19:30), no one had ridden this donkey until that moment, as stated in Mark 11:2&nbsp; \"Go into the village ahead of you, and immediately you will find a donkey tied, and a colt with her; untie them and bring them to me.\"</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The donkey that had never been ridden must have been quite young, which suggests that the presence of its mother cannot be dismissed.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Among the apostles, Matthew is the only one who observed this detail.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The mention of one donkey in Mark and Luke does not negate the possibility of another being present. The existence of one young donkey does not imply there weren\'t two, as prophesied in Zechariah 9:9.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:55:03', '2024-12-27 08:55:03'),
(258, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:7 \"They brought the donkey and the colt and put their cloaks on them, and he sat on them.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Does this imply that Jesus rode on two donkeys for His royal entrance?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The phrase indicates that Jesus is seated on two donkeys, which does not seem plausible.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The text states that they spread their cloaks over them, meaning that Jesus sat on the cloaks placed on the donkey\'s back, rather than riding on two separate animals simultaneously.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, it does not imply that Jesus rode on two donkeys.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:55:40', '2024-12-27 08:55:40'),
(259, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus ask to bring the donkey and the colt?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The prophet Zechariah foretold the royal accession of Jesus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To fulfill this prophecy, Jesus required a donkey and a colt. Zechariah proclaimed: \"Rejoice greatly, O daughter of Zion! Shout aloud, O daughter of Jerusalem! Lo, your king comes to you; triumphant and victorious is he, humble and riding on a donkey, on a colt, the foal of a donkey\" (Zechariah 9:9).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:56:13', '2024-12-27 08:56:13'),
(260, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:9: &ldquo;The crowds that went ahead of him and that followed were shouting, &lsquo;Hosanna to the Son of David! Blessed is the one who comes in the name of the Lord! Hosanna in the highest heaven!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews shout, \'Hosanna\'?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"Hosanna\" was utilised by the Israelites during the Feast of Tabernacles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Hoshana Rabbah, the final day of this feast, involved the priest sounding a trumpet while the people fervently prayed aloud, &ldquo;Save us, we beseech you&rdquo; (Hoshia Na).</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:56:53', '2024-12-27 08:56:53'),
(261, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What does the word \'hosanna\' mean?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The word \"Hosanna\" appears in the Greek New Testament as \"Osanna,\" derived from the Hebrew \"Hoshay/na,\" meaning \"please save.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hebrew root \"Hoshay\" translates to \"save\" and &ldquo;na\" translates to \"please.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This expression is found in Psalm 118:25 and was part of the Great Hillel sung by the Jews as they journeyed to Jerusalem for Passover.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:57:26', '2024-12-27 08:57:26'),
(262, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:10: \"When he entered Jerusalem, the whole city was in turmoil, asking, &lsquo;Who is this?&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jerusalem army not interfere with Jesus\' entry into Jerusalem?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Approximately 3,000 Roman soldiers were stationed in Jerusalem to maintain order during Passover.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During a previous Passover under Archelaus (B.C. 4 - A.D. 6), the Jewish people revolted, resulting in the deaths of over 3,000 Jews and many Roman soldiers.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This rebellion contributed significantly to Archelaus\' loss of power.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, the Romans aimed to prevent riots during the Passover, so they did not intervene during Jesus\' royal entry.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:57:59', '2024-12-27 08:57:59'),
(263, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What happened to the Ark of the Covenant in the Temple in Jerusalem?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The whereabouts of the Ark of the Covenant in the Temple of Jerusalem remain an enduring mystery. Neither Pharaoh Sheshan\'s attack on the Temple (1 Kings 14:25-26), King Jehoash\'s actions in Israel (2 Kings 14:13-14), nor the Assyrian King Nebuchadnezzar\'s conquest resulted in the Ark\'s destruction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Queen Athaliah\'s attempts to eradicate the Davidic line (2 Chronicles 24:7) did not succeed in destroying the Ark either.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish tradition, Jeremiah hid the Ark of the Covenant on Mount Nebo before the Babylonian invasion (2 Maccabees 2:48).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:58:29', '2024-12-27 08:58:29'),
(264, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:12: &ldquo;Then Jesus entered the temple and drove out all who were selling and buying in the temple, and he overturned the tables of the money changers and the seats of those who sold doves.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus drive out all the merchants from the temple premises?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The prophet Zechariah foretold that no merchant would be found in the Jerusalem temple when the Saviour came.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;\"And there shall no longer be traders in the house of the Lord of hosts on that day\" (Zechariah 14:2).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus expelled all the merchants from the temple to fulfil this prophecy.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:59:02', '2024-12-27 08:59:02'),
(265, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:14: &ldquo;The blind and the lame came to him in the temple, and he healed them.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Could the blind and lame enter the Jerusalem temple?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Leviticus 21:17, &ldquo;Persons with disabilities were not to be priests.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, legally, the blind and lame were not barred from entering the temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The guards often brought them to the temple, although some were not admitted (Acts 3:3).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 08:59:39', '2024-12-27 08:59:39'),
(266, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:15: &ldquo;And when the chief priests saw the wonderful works that he had done, and the children shouting in the temple, &lsquo;Hosanna to the Son of David,&rsquo; they were indignant.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Jewish women enter the temple?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus\' time, women could only access the temple through the &lsquo;Court of Women&rsquo; on the east side.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;This area was not exclusive to women; Jewish men could enter as well but Gentiles were forbidden.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Behind the &lsquo;Court of Women&rsquo;, there was the &lsquo;Court of Israel&rsquo;, which was forbidden to women.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:00:16', '2024-12-27 09:00:16'),
(267, '<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Matthew 21:16: &ldquo;They said to him, &lsquo;Do you not hear what these are saying?&rsquo; Jesus answered, &lsquo;Yes; have you never read, &ldquo;Out of the mouths of infants and nursing babies you have prepared praise&rdquo;?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is there a connection between Jesus\' entry into Jerusalem and the Passover lamb?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The month of Nisan marks the time when the lamb to be sacrificed for Passover is selected.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is brought home before the 10th day and kept there until the Passover. This procedure ensures the lamb is examined for flaws or blemishes (Exodus 12:3-6).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Just as the lamb is scrutinised before the Passover, so too was Jesus, the Passover Lamb, scrutinised by the Jewish leaders upon his entry into Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:00:51', '2024-12-27 09:00:51'),
(268, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:17: &ldquo;Then he left them and went out of the city to Bethany and stayed there.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where did Jesus spend his last three days?</em></p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Gospel of Matthew, Jesus spent these days in Bethany.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Luke, Jesus lived on the Mount of Olives, &ldquo;Every day he taught in the temple, but at night he went out of the city and stayed on the Mount of Olives&rdquo; (21:37).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Both Matthew and Luke convey this detail, noting Bethany\'s proximity to the Mount of Olives.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:01:31', '2024-12-27 09:01:31'),
(269, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:20: &ldquo;When you see the army encamped around Jerusalem, know its destruction is near.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Roman army surround Jerusalem?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 67, General Vespasian surrounded Jerusalem, imposing a blockade.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By A.D. 70, Vespasian handed the siege over to his son Titus, who led an army into the temple in Jerusalem and ultimately destroyed it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:02:09', '2024-12-27 09:02:09'),
(270, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:20 &ldquo;Know that its destruction is near.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the army encamped around Jerusalem later?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Here, the word Stratopedon is used to refer to the army.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This term denotes a legion of 6,000 soldiers of the Roman army encamped in one place. Therefore, this army signifies the siege of Jerusalem by the Roman army in AD 70.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:02:46', '2024-12-27 09:02:46'),
(271, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:25: &ldquo;Whence was the baptism of John? From heaven or men?&rdquo; They consulted one another, saying, &ldquo;If we say, From heaven, then he will ask, &lsquo;Why did you not believe him?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the baptism given by John the Baptist?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The baptism administered by John the Baptist is referred to as the Mikvah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This act of immersion (Tevilah) in running water was customary among the Jews before significant events, such as the Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur) and weddings.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:03:31', '2024-12-27 09:03:31'),
(272, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:31: \"The tax collectors and the harlots will enter the kingdom of heaven before you.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews believe that publicans and harlots would not enter the kingdom of heaven?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews categorised sins into two types:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sins against God, including:</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Violation of the Sabbath</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Taking tolls</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Prostitution</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Not tithing</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sins against men, including:</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Murder</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Harassment</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Exploitation</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Bearing false witness</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over time, the perception of sins against God evolved, and the Jews came to view tax collecting and prostitution as grievous sins, leading them to believe that those engaged in such activities would not enter heaven.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:04:21', '2024-12-27 09:04:21'),
(273, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:31 &ldquo;Which of these two did the will of the Father?&rdquo; They said, &ldquo;The second.&rdquo; Jesus replied, &ldquo;I tell you the truth, tax collectors and harlots will enter the kingdom of heaven before you.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews say Amen?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Amen (אמן) was the customary response of the people to every Jewish blessing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Ezra praised the Lord God Most High, and the people lifted up their hands and cried, &lsquo;Amen, Amen!&rsquo; They fell on their faces and worshipped the Lord&rdquo; (Nehemiah 8:6).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Later the Greeks picked up the term from the Jews, and retained its meaning and significance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Amen served as a reminder for the Jews of their covenant with God.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:05:08', '2024-12-27 09:05:08'),
(274, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:33: &ldquo;Listen to another parable: A householder planted a vineyard. He built a fence around it, placed a grapevine in it, and erected a tower. Then he handed it over to the cultivators and left.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the master give the vineyard to the cultivators?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus&rsquo; time, landowners typically possessed agricultural land in various locations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The owners resided in towns and entrusted their plantations to stewards.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The stewards were responsible for calling in labourers to manage the work on the plantations. In this parable, Jesus refers to this common practice of land stewardship.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:07:04', '2024-12-27 09:07:04'),
(275, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:34: &ldquo;When the harvest time came, he sent his servants to the tenants to collect his produce.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How was the fruit of the vine shared?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Collecting the fruit takes about four years after the vines are planted. Up to 25% of the yield is paid as wages to the workers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Once these wages are settled, the master sends his servants to collect his share.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:07:36', '2024-12-27 09:07:36'),
(276, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:35: &ldquo;But the tenants seized his servants; they beat one, killed another, and stoned another.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Does the parable of the tenants in the vineyard refer to the Jerusalem temple?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, this parable has connections to the Jerusalem temple. Jesus shared it while He was in the temple, which would have brought to mind the resemblance between the vineyard and the temple for His listeners.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From A.D. 3, the Roman Emperor took over the appointment of key positions in the Jerusalem Church, and many of its officials accepted Roman rule.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The servants who despised their master in the parable represent the officials of the Jerusalem temple who accepted Roman supremacy.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:10:02', '2024-12-27 09:10:02'),
(277, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the period in which the gospel was written influence the parable of the tenants in the vineyard?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The gospel was written during a time of persecution of Christians.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some Jews in Palestine exposed Christians to Roman soldiers, leading to further oppression.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew likely chose this parable to warn those who betrayed Christians for their comfort.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:10:33', '2024-12-27 09:10:33'),
(278, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 21:42: &ldquo;Jesus said to them, &lsquo;The stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone; this was the Lord&rsquo;s doing, and it is amazing in our eyes.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the stone left by the builders?</em><br><br></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 26, '<p>In ancient times, builders cut and brought several cornerstones to the construction site to choose the best one. Once the most suitable stone was selected, the others were left behind, discarded, or set aside for future use. This is the \'stone\' that the builders rejected&mdash;a symbol of something cast aside in favour of the new. As time passes and choices are made, what is overlooked or deemed unnecessary can later prove essential. Jesus is indicating that, though rejected by men, He is the cornerstone of God\'s plan.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:11:06', '2024-12-27 09:11:06'),
(279, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 22:9: &ldquo;Go therefore into the main streets, and invite everyone you find to the wedding banquet.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were strangers invited to the feast?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews typically did not invite people outside their community to weddings. This was due to their awareness of issues related to ritual uncleanliness and the potential dangers of associating with those outside their circles.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To invite a stranger to a feast meant to receive them as one of their own, fully accepting them into their midst.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:11:44', '2024-12-27 09:13:33'),
(280, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 22:11: &ldquo;But when the king came in to see the guests, he noticed a man there who was not wearing a wedding robe.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the guests need wedding garments?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In some royal weddings, guests were provided with special clothes (Genesis 45:22; Esther 6:8-9). Although ordinary weddings likely didn&rsquo;t provide these garments, it was seen as dishonourable to attend the King&rsquo;s wedding in ragged clothing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Clothing symbolised one\'s dignity and respect for the host.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:12:17', '2024-12-27 09:13:19'),
(281, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Would the king have given wedding clothes to the guests?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, if invited to a royal wedding, the king would provide wedding garments for the guests.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This ensured that those who accepted the invitation, including those from lower social classes, would appear in appropriate attire, symbolising their acceptance and inclusion in the royal celebration.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It also allowed the king to showcase his kingdom\'s wealth and prosperity to other guests.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attending the wedding feast without proper attire, especially without the provided wedding garment, was considered an insult to the king.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:13:56', '2024-12-27 09:13:56'),
(282, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 22:21 \"Then he said to them, \'Give therefore to the emperor the things that are the emperor&rsquo;s, and to God the things that are God&rsquo;s.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Caesar require as payment?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 6, Caesar introduced a new tax, the census tax, which all Roman subjects were required to pay.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 17, Judas the Galilean led a revolt in Jerusalem to protest against this tax.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman Empire quickly quashed the rebellion, and Judas and his two sons were executed.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A common slogan during this revolt was, \"We are not slaves to render unto Caesar.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This passage refers to the obligation of paying taxes to Caesar.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:14:40', '2024-12-27 09:14:40'),
(283, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 22:16 \"So they sent their disciples to him, along with the Herodians, saying, \'Teacher, we know that you are sincere, and teach the way of God in accordance with truth, and show deference to no one; for you do not regard people with partiality.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Pharisees and Herodians unite against Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees and the Herodians were at odds with one another.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Herodians supported Herod\'s ruling dynasty, while the Pharisees believed that Herod, being of Idumean descent, was not a legitimate king of the Jews.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, they united against Jesus because both groups saw him as a threat to&nbsp; their positions of authority.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:15:55', '2024-12-27 09:15:55'),
(284, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 22:20: \"Then he said to them, \'Whose head is this, and whose title?\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Whose images and inscriptions were engraved on the coin?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The coin shown to Jesus was a denarius issued by Herod Antipas.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On one side of the coin, Caesar\'s image was displayed, and the Latin inscription \"Tiberius Caesar, Son of Divine Augustus\" was engraved on the other side.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the other side was the image of the Roman goddess of justice, along with the Latin title \"High Priest.\"</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:16:34', '2024-12-27 09:16:34'),
(285, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 22:44 \"The Lord said to my Lord, \'Sit at my right hand, until I put your enemies under your feet.\'\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is there a mention of two Lords here?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">When David wrote this psalm, he used the Hebrew name YHWH (Yahweh) for God in one part and ADONAI (Adonai, meaning \'Lord\') in another.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the Jews, out of reverence, did not pronounce the name YHWH, so they read both as \"Adonai.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the New Testament, both names were written as \"Kurios\" (Lord in Greek).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:17:27', '2024-12-27 09:17:27'),
(286, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the Jews address God?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews refrained from pronouncing God\'s name YHWH out of deep respect. Instead, they commonly used two titles when referring to God:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Adonai &ndash; meaning \"Lord.\"</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">HaShem &ndash; meaning \"The Name.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:18:10', '2024-12-27 09:18:10'),
(287, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 22:35-36: \"And one of them, a lawyer, asked him a question to test him. \'Teacher, which commandment in the law is the greatest?\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the lawyer ask which commandment was the most important?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Law of Moses contained 613 commandments.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">David later summarised them into 11 (see Psalm 15), and Isaiah reduced them further to six (Isaiah 33:15).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The task of condensing the commandments became a point of discussion among Jewish scholars.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Rabbi Hillel famously summarised the law as: \"What is hateful to you, do not do to your neighbor; that is the whole Torah, the rest is commentary. Go and learn\"&nbsp; (b. Sbabbatb 31 a).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The lawyer\'s question aimed to test Jesus\' knowledge as a Jewish rabbi. In response, Jesus affirmed that love is the most important and central commandment.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:18:56', '2024-12-27 09:18:56');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(288, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 22:44: \"&lsquo;The Lord said to my Lord, &ldquo;Sit at my right hand, until I put your enemies under your feet.&rdquo;&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why are there two \'Lords\' here?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In this passage, it can be assumed that the first \"Lord\" is Jehovah (God). Since this is a royal psalm, the second \"Lord\" mentioned must be a ruler or someone in a high position. There are several possibilities for the identity of the second \"Lord\":</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">King David himself (if the psalm was written by someone else).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Solomon.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Joshua, son of Josedech.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Any king or priest-king of the Hasmonean Dynasty.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many believe that the second \"Lord\" refers to King Solomon, and that this psalm was written in connection with Solomon&rsquo;s ascension to the throne.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:19:33', '2024-12-27 09:19:33'),
(289, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 22:45: \"If David thus calls him Lord, how can he be his son?\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the term \"Son of God\" familiar to the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 27, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, Roman emperors often referred to themselves as the \"Son of God.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In 26 B.C., Augustus Caesar&rsquo;s seal was found with an inscription describing him as the \"Son of God.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, coins were found bearing Mark Antony\'s description as \"Son of God.\" Augustus even erected a statue of himself in Judea resembling the god Jupiter.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">King Herod built three temples dedicated to Roman emperors, and after Vespasian\'s death, his children referred to him as the \"Son of God.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the term was indeed familiar to the Jews, especially in connection with Roman emperors.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:20:07', '2024-12-27 09:20:07'),
(290, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 23:2 \"The scribes and the Pharisees sit on Moses&rsquo; seat.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the \"seat of Moses\"?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 28, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The law was taught in the synagogue from a special seat, referred to as \'Moses\' sea.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The seat represented Moses\'s authority to teach and interpret the law. Legal experts and scribes would instruct the people from this seat.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The seat of Moses was a reminder of divine authority passed down through the law.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:21:01', '2024-12-27 09:21:01'),
(291, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 23:5 \"They do all their deeds to be seen by others; for they make their phylacteries broad and their fringes long\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What do Jews wear on their forehead during prayer?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 28, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews wear a small box called Tefillin around their foreheads during prayer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Inside this box are parchments inscribed with God&rsquo;s words.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice is a literal obedience to God&rsquo;s commandment in Deuteronomy 6:7-8:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"Recite them to your children, and talk about them when you are at home and when you are away, when you lie down and when you rise. Bind them as a sign on your hand, fix them as an emblem on your forehead\" .</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:22:10', '2024-12-27 09:22:10'),
(292, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 23:8 \"But you are not to be called rabbi, for you have one teacher, and you are all students\" .</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When does one become a rabbi?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 28, '<p dir=\"ltr\">To become a rabbi, a person must progress through several levels of study:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Talmid (Disciple)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Talmid Watiq (Distinguished Student)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Talmid Ḥabbar (Disciple Associate)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Talmid Hakham (Disciple of the Wise)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Rabbi (Master)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Only after passing these stages does one become a rabbi, capable of accepting disciples and teaching them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:23:36', '2024-12-27 09:23:36'),
(293, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 23:24 \"You blind guides! You strain out a gnat but swallow a camel!\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were gnats strained out?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 28, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews were prohibited from eating certain winged creatures. <br><br>Leviticus 11:23 states, \"But all other winged insects that have four feet are detestable to you.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To avoid consuming unclean creatures unknowingly, many Jews would strain wine and other drinks. This ensured no insects like gnats were accidentally consumed, a meticulous practice that reflects their attention to detail in obeying the law.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:24:20', '2024-12-27 09:24:20'),
(294, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 23:29 \"Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees, hypocrites! For you build the tombs of the prophets and decorate the graves of the righteous\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews build tombs for the prophets?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 28, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Around the Jerusalem temple were the tombs of kings, prophets and other significant figures.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An example is the tomb of John Hyrcanus, located just outside the Second Wall of Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During Passover, Jerusalem was crowded, and some people unknowingly touched these graves, which made them ritually unclean and prohibited from entering the temple for seven days (Leviticus 19:11-21).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 30, tombs of kings and prophets were sealed, and the rest of the city was ordered to evacuate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These tombs were whitewashed to prevent accidental contact, a practice&nbsp; used to maintain ritual purity during religious festivals.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:25:01', '2024-12-27 09:25:01'),
(295, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 23:35 \"So that upon you may come all the righteous blood shed on earth, from the blood of righteous Abel to the blood of Zechariah son of Barachiah, whom you murdered between the sanctuary and the altar\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was this Zechariah who was killed?</em></p>', 1, 28, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This likely refers to the priest Zechariah, whom King Joash had stoned to death in 2 Chronicles 24:20-22: \"They conspired against him and by command of the king they stoned him to death in the court of the house of the Lord.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Zechariah\'s father\'s name in 2 Chronicles was Jehoiada, not Barachiah. The Zechariah mentioned by Jesus may be a later figure from the same family, thus explaining the reference to Barachiah.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Some scholars suggest this refers to a later Zechariah who was killed in the Jerusalem Temple in AD 67.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:26:43', '2024-12-27 09:26:43'),
(296, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 23:35: \"So that upon you may come all the righteous blood shed on earth, from the blood of innocent Abel to the blood of Zechariah son of Barachiah, whom you murdered between the sanctuary and the altar.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Zechariah&rsquo;s blood fall upon them?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 28, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jehoash, king of Judah, forgot God and turned to pagan idols, offering sacrifices to them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Zechariah, the priest, objected to this, he was killed by the king&rsquo;s order. As he died, Zechariah prayed for God to seek justice for his blood.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many believed that God responded by sending the king of Damascus to invade Judah as retribution for Zechariah&rsquo;s blood (2 Chronicles 24:17-23).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:27:31', '2024-12-27 09:27:31'),
(297, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:15: &ldquo;So when you see the desolating sacrilege standing in the holy place, as was spoken of by the prophet Daniel (let the reader understand)...&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the unholy sign of destruction prophesied by the prophet Daniel?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This prophecy is found in Daniel 11:31:<br>&ldquo;His forces shall occupy and profane the temple and fortress. They shall abolish the regular burnt offering and set up the abomination that makes desolate&rdquo; (Daniel 11:31).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Antiochus Epiphanes IV, the Seleucid king who ruled Israel in 167 B.C., abolished Jewish practices such as circumcision, Sabbath observance, and dietary laws.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In December 167 B.C., a statue of Zeus was placed on the main altar of the temple, where it remained for three years. In Jewish understanding, this statue is referred to as the \"abomination of desolation,\" a sign of unholy destruction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:28:19', '2024-12-27 09:28:19'),
(298, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:2: &ldquo;Then he asked them, &lsquo;You see all these, do you not? Truly I tell you, not one stone will be left here upon another; all will be thrown down.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>After the destruction of the Jerusalem Temple in A.D. 70, was there an attempt to rebuild it?</em></p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 362, Roman Emperor Julian the Apostate (361-363 A.D.) permitted the rebuilding of the Jerusalem Temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, before the renovation could begin, an earthquake struck, delaying the project.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Emperor Julian died in 363 A.D., and the rebuilding was abandoned.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:29:00', '2024-12-27 09:29:00'),
(299, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:2: &ldquo;Let the one who is on the housetop not go down to take what is in the house.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews use the upper part of the house?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During that time, houses were built with flat roofs, and access to these roofs was often by external stairs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The upper space was used for storing items and other general purposes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was even the setting for observing the Passover (t.pes. 6:11). Nothing stored below could easily be carried to the rooftop.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:29:33', '2024-12-27 09:29:33'),
(300, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:2: &ldquo;Truly I tell you, not one stone will be left here upon another; all will be thrown down.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say that everything will be broken down, leaving no stone unturned?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew wrote his Gospel after the destruction of the Jerusalem Temple by the Roman army in A.D. 70.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When the Roman general Titus attacked Jerusalem, the Jewish people fiercely resisted.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Women and children clung to the temple walls, preferring death to the destruction of their holy site.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman soldiers set fire to the temple to drive them out. They entered the holy place and desecrated it with offerings.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As a result, the temple was utterly destroyed, leaving not one stone upon another.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:30:08', '2024-12-27 09:30:08'),
(301, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:15-16: &ldquo;...then those in Judea must flee to the mountains when you see the desolating sacrilege standing in the holy place.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why flee to the mountains?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 70, the Roman army intended to install a statue of the Roman Emperor in the Jerusalem Temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In defiance, the Jews formed a human barrier around the temple. The Romans slaughtered them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the Christian leaders in Judea advised their followers to flee to Perea, which is the escape referred to here.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:30:46', '2024-12-27 09:30:46'),
(302, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:18: \"The one in the field must not turn back to get a coat.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did you need a cloak for the trip?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews commonly used cloaks for travelling. It was only in moments of extreme urgency that one would abandon their cloak.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;The cloak also doubled as a blanket at night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:31:18', '2024-12-27 09:31:18'),
(303, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:20: \"Pray that your flight may not be in winter or on a Sabbath.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was travelling difficult in the winter?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Israel is dotted with many wadis, which are dry riverbeds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, when it rains even slightly, these wadis become dangerous swamps.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even today, many accidents occur in these swamp-like wadis after rains.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, travel during the winter was quite difficult, while in the summer, these areas become solid, stable ground.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:31:55', '2024-12-27 09:31:55'),
(304, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:28: \"Wherever the corpse is, there the vultures will gather.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which eagles did Jesus refer to?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This verse reflects a scene from Genesis, where \"the birds of prey came down on the carcasses\" (Genesis 15:11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Genesis, these birds symbolize the people of Egypt, who would later enslave Abraham&rsquo;s descendants.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus, however, may be referring to the Roman Empire, which would bring about the destruction of Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The eagle was also the emblem of the Roman legions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:32:32', '2024-12-27 09:32:32'),
(305, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:20: \"Pray that your flight may not be in winter or on a Sabbath.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say the destruction of Jerusalem should not be on the Sabbath?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish law restricted how far one could travel on the Sabbath, allowing only about two thousand cubits (approximately 1 kilometre).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some Jews strictly adhered to this rule, and such limitations would hinder their ability to flee.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus expressed concern that the destruction should not occur on the Sabbath.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:33:08', '2024-12-27 09:33:08'),
(306, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:31: \"And he will send out his angels with a loud trumpet call, and they will gather his elect from the four winds, from one end of heaven to the other.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Does this trumpet have an Old Testament background?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, the trumpet is rooted in Old Testament tradition.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish New Year, known as the Feast of Trumpets, is described in Numbers 29:1: &ldquo;On the first day of the seventh month, you shall have a holy convocation; you shall not work at your occupations. It is a day for you to blow the trumpets.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The sound of the trumpet was a reminder of the coming of God\'s kingdom (Zechariah 14:1-4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When the trumpet was blown, it was a signal to remember God&rsquo;s proximity.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:33:45', '2024-12-27 09:33:45'),
(307, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the Jews blow the trumpets?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The instrument used for the trumpet was the shofar, and it had several purposes:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To mark the beginning of the sabbath (Sukkah 4:11-12).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To give instructions to the army (1 Corinthians 14:8).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To terrify enemies (Joshua 6:5).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">During the anointing of a king (1 Kings 1:34).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">For important ceremonies in the temple (Leviticus 10:10).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">When God was near to His people (Exodus 19:16).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:34:22', '2024-12-27 09:34:22'),
(308, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the trumpet sound?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The shofar was the trumpet used by the Jews, typically made from a ram\'s horn.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was blown before kings entered as a herald of their arrival.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Isaiah 27:13, the Jews believed this trumpet would also be sounded to gather all people together in the last days as a sign of God\'s final call.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:34:59', '2024-12-27 09:34:59'),
(309, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:32: &ldquo;From the fig tree learn its lesson: as soon as its branch becomes tender and puts forth its leaves, you know that summer is near.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Does the fig tree bloom in summer?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The fig tree sheds all its leaves in winter.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Before summer, new buds appear.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The tree blooms and bears fruit in summer, and people eagerly anticipate this flowering and fruiting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:35:36', '2024-12-27 09:35:36'),
(310, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:41: &ldquo;Two women will be grinding meal together; one will be taken, and one will be left.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where did the Jews grind grain?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Many Jewish households shared a common courtyard.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Activities such as grinding grain and baking bread often took place here.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The grains were sometimes ground together, and bread was made for the entire household. Hence, the mention of two women grinding grain together.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:36:13', '2024-12-27 09:36:13'),
(311, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 24:43: &ldquo;But understand this: if the owner of the house had known in what part of the night the thief was coming, he would have stayed awake and would not have let his house be broken into.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was theft a problem at night?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 29, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Palestine, houses were built close to one another, and the homes of the wealthy often had rooms surrounding a courtyard.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The windows and doors of these houses opened to the courtyard, making theft during the day difficult due to the many people present. Consequently, thieves often targeted homes at night.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:36:46', '2024-12-27 09:36:46'),
(312, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:4: &ldquo;But the wise took flasks of oil with their lamps.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the lamps need a lot of oil?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Two Greek words are used in the Bible for lamps:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Lynchos: Small lamps kept burning indoors (Matthew 5:15).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Lampada: Larger, torch-like lamps for outdoor use.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since the word lampada is used here, it refers to a large outdoor lamp that requires a substantial amount of oil.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Oil symbolising readiness and preparation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:37:38', '2024-12-27 09:37:38'),
(313, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:6: &ldquo;At midnight there was a shout, &lsquo;Look! Here is the bridegroom! Come out to meet him.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the bridegroom received at night?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Marriage customs varied from place to place, but typically, the process began with the groom arriving at the bride\'s house accompanied by his friends.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Afterward, they proceeded to the groom&rsquo;s house for a seven-day celebration where the marriage covenant and the seven blessings were established.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;In many cases, wedding celebrations took place at night (Matthew 22:13; 25:6).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:38:17', '2024-12-27 09:38:17'),
(314, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:15: &ldquo;To one he gave five talents, to another two, to another one, to each according to his ability.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How much is a talent?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, a talent (kikkar) was a unit of weight.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, &ldquo;One talent of pure gold is to be used for the lampstand and all its accessories&rdquo; (Exodus 25:39).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By the New Testament period, a talent had come to represent a large sum of money, approximately 3,000 shekels.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:38:53', '2024-12-27 09:38:53'),
(315, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:24: &ldquo;Then the one who had received the one talent also came forward, saying, &lsquo;Master, I knew that you were a harsh man, reaping where you did not sow, and gathering where you did not scatter seed.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does it mean to reap where you did not sow?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Palestine, farmers were required to pay a significant portion of their harvest as taxes. If they couldn&rsquo;t meet these obligations, they had to take out loans from landowners.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During the next year&rsquo;s harvest, landowners would seize part of the yield to cover the debt.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The master in this parable represents a landowner who benefits from others&rsquo; labour&mdash;reaping where he did not sow.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:39:28', '2024-12-27 09:39:28'),
(316, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:25: &ldquo;&lsquo;So I was afraid, and I went and hid your talent in the ground. Here you have what is yours.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the third servant bury the talent in the ground?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p>In those days, the safest way to store money was by burying it in the ground to protect it from thieves. This is why the third servant buried his talent&mdash;he feared losing it.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:40:02', '2024-12-27 09:40:02'),
(317, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:27: &ldquo;Then you ought to have invested my money with the bankers, and on my return I would have received what was my own with interest.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Would the moneylenders have paid interest?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Although Jewish law forbade charging interest, some individuals still engaged in this practice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Money changers accepted small amounts as deposits and gave a portion of the profits to the depositor. Small interest could be earned through these money changers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:40:35', '2024-12-27 09:40:35'),
(318, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:33: &ldquo;He will put the sheep at his right hand and the goats at the left.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did shepherds separate sheep and goats?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p>In Palestine, sheep and goats grazed together during the day, but they were often separated before nightfall. Goats required warmth, so they were kept in indoor sheds, while sheep remained outside. This separation represents the division of the righteous and the unrighteous at the final judgment.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:41:17', '2024-12-27 09:41:17'),
(319, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the money earn interest?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During that time, moneylenders played a significant role in society. There were two main types of moneylenders:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Money Lenders: These individuals would exchange money within the temple, often borrowing from others. They would pay a portion of the profit to those who lent them the money.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Temple Deposits: Money could also be stored in the Jerusalem Temple.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:41:54', '2024-12-27 09:41:54'),
(320, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:33 \"He will put the sheep at his right hand and the goats at the left.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Would the shepherd have separated the sheep and the goats?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p>In Palestine, it was common for sheep and goats to graze together during the day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, at least in some regions, they were separated before being put into enclosures at night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The reason for this separation is practical: goats required warmth during the night, so they were kept in indoor sheds, while sheep, more resilient to cooler temperatures, remained in open sheds.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the separation was based on necessity, with each animal being placed where they could best thrive.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:42:32', '2024-12-27 09:42:32'),
(321, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:34: &ldquo;Then the king will say to those at his right hand, &lsquo;Come, you that are blessed by my Father, inherit the kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the right side significant?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In ancient times, the right side was of great importance. Kings would place the most trusted or honored person on their right.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, Josephus records that King Saul placed Jonathan, his son, on his right hand and Abner, his general, on his left (Josephus, Antiquities 6.11.9.&pound;235).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Being on the right hand was considered a place of honor, while the left was seen as of lesser importance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:43:10', '2024-12-27 09:43:10'),
(322, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 25:38: &ldquo;And when was it that we saw you a stranger and welcomed you, or naked and gave you clothing?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was clothing a valuable item?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 30, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Nudity was considered a form of suffering in those days.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As it says in Romans 8:35, \"Who will separate us from the love of Christ? Will hardship, or distress, or persecution, or famine, or nakedness, or peril, or sword?\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Clothing was seen as a luxury item, especially in times of hardship.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:43:50', '2024-12-27 09:43:50'),
(323, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:2: &ldquo;You know that after two days the Passover is coming, and the Son of Man will be handed over to be crucified.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say the Passover would be in two days?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish rabbis would hold a feast for their disciples when they completed a significant part of their study.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This feast was called Se\'udat Mitzvah (Banquet of Completion).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It often took place on the 14th of Nisan, the same day as Passover.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Jesus mentioned that the Passover was in two days, He meant that He had only two more days to teach about the Kingdom of Heaven, after which His disciples were to continue His mission.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:44:42', '2024-12-27 09:44:42'),
(324, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:3-4: &ldquo;Then the chief priests and the elders of the people gathered in the palace of the high priest, who was called Caiaphas, and they conspired to arrest Jesus by stealth and kill him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was Caiaphas?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time, there were four significant priestly families: Boethus, Annas, Phabi and Kamith.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Annas was the high priest until A.D. 15. When the Roman government deposed Annas, his son-in-law Caiaphas (A.D. 18-36) was appointed as high priest.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The historian Josephus referred to him as \"Joseph, who was called Caiaphas,\" indicating that Caiaphas might have been his family name.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 36, Caiaphas was excommunicated by the Roman government after he obstructed a Samaritan pilgrimage to Mount Gerizim.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:45:22', '2024-12-27 09:45:22'),
(325, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:7: &ldquo;A woman came to him with an alabaster jar of very costly ointment, and she poured it on his head as he sat at the table.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was special about the jar of ointment?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This jar, known as an alabaster jar, was made of alabaster stone and was used to store expensive oils.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These jars had long necks that had to be broken to access the contents, meaning the jar could only be used once.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Such vessels were often reserved for the anointing of kings. This woman&rsquo;s act of anointing Jesus with costly oil symbolised offering the greatest wealth of life to Him.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:47:37', '2024-12-27 09:47:37'),
(326, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:14: &ldquo;Then one of the twelve, who was called Judas Iscariot, went to the chief priests.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was there anything special about Judas?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">He was known as Judas Iscariot. The name \"Iscariot\" likely comes from Qirya, possibly indicating that he was from the town of Kerioth.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The term Iscariot (Ish-Qerioth) means \"Man of Kerioth\". There were two places named Kerioth (or Qirya), one in Judea in Moab and another in Southern Judea.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This suggests that Judas may have been the only apostle who was not from Galilee, making him distinct in that sense among the Twelve.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:48:11', '2024-12-27 09:48:11'),
(327, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:14: &ldquo;Then one of the twelve, who was called Judas Iscariot, went to the chief priests.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was there anything special about Judas?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">He was known as Judas Iscariot. The name \"Iscariot\" likely comes from Qirya, possibly indicating that he was from the town of Kerioth.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The term Iscariot (Ish-Qerioth) means \"Man of Kerioth\". There were two places named Kerioth (or Qirya), one in Judea in Moab and another in Southern Judea.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This suggests that Judas may have been the only apostle who was not from Galilee, making him distinct in that sense among the Twelve.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:49:20', '2024-12-27 09:49:20'),
(328, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:15: &ldquo;What will you give me if I betray him to you?&rdquo; They paid him thirty pieces of silver.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the value of Judas\' thirty pieces of silver?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p>The silver coin Judas received was a stater, typically used for paying the temple tax. One silver coin was worth about four shekels, meaning Judas\' thirty pieces were equivalent to four months\' wages.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:49:52', '2024-12-27 09:49:52'),
(329, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What is the significance of thirty silver coins?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish currency at the time consisted of silver shekels, which did not bear the images of pagan gods.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The price of a male slave in Israel was thirty silver coins (shekels), as noted in Exodus 21:32.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Likewise, in Hosea 3:2, the prophet Hosea buys back his wife for \"fifteen shekels of silver and a homer and a lethech of barley.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Judas&rsquo; act reminds us that there are many things in life&mdash;like loyalty to God&mdash;that cannot be bought with money .</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:50:31', '2024-12-27 09:50:31'),
(330, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:17: &ldquo;On the first day of Unleavened Bread, the disciples came to Jesus, saying, &lsquo;Where do you want us to make the preparations for you to eat the Passover?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the disciples search for a place to eat the Passover?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews were required to eat the Passover within the walls of Jerusalem, which meant that many of the houses in the city were filled to capacity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, the disciples needed to find a suitable place for them to celebrate the Passover.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bethany, where Jesus lived at that time, was located outside the city of Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:52:03', '2024-12-27 09:52:03'),
(331, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>On what day was the Jewish Passover observed?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Passover lamb was chosen on the tenth day of the first Jewish month, Nisan (March-April).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The lamb was sacrificed on the fourteenth day of Nisan, typically between 3 PM and 5 PM (though this time was later adjusted to accommodate larger crowds). Passover was then eaten after dusk on the fifteenth of Nisan.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This observance coincided with the seven-day Feast of Unleavened Bread.</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:52:37', '2024-12-27 09:52:37'),
(332, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:18: &ldquo;He said, &lsquo;Go into the city to a certain man, and say to him, The Teacher says, My time is near; I will keep the Passover at your house with my disciples.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where did Jesus keep the Passover?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus celebrated the Passover in a location known as the Upper Room as mentioned in Luke 14:14-15. (It is also referred to as Avaylov in some traditions.)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This place is believed to have also served as the house of Zion, where the disciples gathered with the Holy Mother after Jesus&rsquo; resurrection (Acts 1:13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Cenaculum on Mount Zion in Jerusalem is recognised today as the site of the Last Supper, and there are indications that it was used for worship since A.D. 70.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:53:15', '2024-12-27 09:53:15'),
(333, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:2-3: &ldquo;You know that after two days the Passover is coming, and the Son of Man will be handed over to be crucified.&rdquo; Then the chief priests and the elders gathered in the palace of the high priest, who was called Caiaphas.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the plan to kill Jesus begin two days before Passover?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Passover was celebrated on the fourteenth day of the month of Nisan.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The two days leading up to Passover were a time of preparation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many people observed fasting during this period, and the most significant act during these days was selecting the Passover lamb.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The decision to kill Jesus coincided with the selection of the sacrificial lamb, foreshadowing His role as the ultimate sacrifice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:53:53', '2024-12-27 09:53:53'),
(334, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:23: &ldquo;He replied, &lsquo;The one who has dipped his hand into the bowl with me will betray me.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>In which vessel did Jesus and Judas dip their hands?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During the Passover meal, the Jews ate bitter herbs, which were dipped in a mixture and consumed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This common bowl, known as the bowl of Haroset, is a blend of dried fruits, ginger and wine.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Both Jesus and Judas ate from this bowl.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:54:27', '2024-12-27 09:54:27'),
(335, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:26: &ldquo;While they were eating, Jesus took bread, and after blessing it, he broke it and gave it to the disciples and said, &lsquo;Take, eat; this is my body.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did He take the bread and break it?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At the Passover meal, the Jews would cut the Passover bread in half, wrapping one portion in a cloth and hiding it under a pillow.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This wrapped half-bread, known as the Afikoman, symbolises participation in the great feast at the coming of the Messiah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Its concealment signifies that deliverance is not yet complete and that it will be fulfilled with the arrival of the Messiah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus gave this piece of bread to His disciples, establishing His identity as the heir.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The imagery of the body of Jesus, wrapped in linen and placed in the tomb, resonates with this piece of bread. As stated in John 19:40, &ldquo;They took the body of Jesus and wrapped it with the spices, as is the burial custom of the Jews.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:55:05', '2024-12-27 09:55:05'),
(336, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:36: &ldquo;Then Jesus went with them to a place called Gethsemane; and he said to his disciples, &lsquo;Sit here while I go over there and pray.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the reason for the name Gethsemane?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term Gethsemane means \'olive press\' in Aramaic (gat&scaron;emen = \'an oil press\').</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This location, situated on the west side of the Mount of Olives beyond the Kidron Valley, likely received its name due to the abundance of olive trees and groves in the area.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:55:39', '2024-12-27 09:55:39'),
(337, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:48: &ldquo;Now the betrayer had given them a sign, saying, &lsquo;The one I kiss is the man; arrest him.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did those who beat Jesus ask him to prophesy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed that the coming Messiah would be the greatest prophet.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in Deuteronomy 18:15, &ldquo;The Lord your God will raise up for you a prophet like me from among your own people; you shall heed such a prophet.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This belief led those who beat Jesus to ask Him to prophesy if He truly was the Messiah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:56:42', '2024-12-27 09:56:42'),
(338, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:48: &ldquo;The one who betrayed him had given them a sign, saying, &lsquo;The one I kiss is the man; seize him.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the kiss a customary greeting for the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, a kiss was a traditional Jewish greeting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Subordinates would often kiss the hands of the elder.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, friends or those of equal status in society would greet each other with a kiss on the cheek. This gesture, rooted in respect, was significant as it conveyed both familiarity and reverence.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:57:18', '2024-12-27 09:57:18'),
(339, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:49: &ldquo;He came up to Jesus at once and said, &lsquo;Greetings, Rabbi!&rsquo; and kissed him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Judas said when he kissed Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It was common for disciples to kiss their teacher as a sign of respect.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The customary greeting was often accompanied by the word \'Shalom\' (peace).</p>\r\n<p>In the Greek translation of the Gospel, the greeting is rendered as \"Chaire\" (Hail).</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 09:59:44', '2024-12-27 09:59:44'),
(340, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Judas kiss Jesus?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus&rsquo; time, friends often greeted one another with a kiss upon meeting (Luke 7:45; Romans 16:16; 1 Corinthians 16:20; 1 Peter 5:14).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Judas may have chosen the kiss as a way to conceal his true intentions, ensuring that he did not raise suspicion when approaching Jesus to betray Him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:00:41', '2024-12-27 10:00:41'),
(341, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:53: &ldquo;Do you think that I cannot appeal to my Father, and he will at once send me more than twelve legions of angels?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How many angels are in twelve legions?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A legion typically consists of about 6,000 soldiers, which means twelve legions would total approximately 72,000 angels.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, we see the power of a single angel who killed 185,000 Assyrians (2 Kings 19:35; Isaiah 37:36).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:01:16', '2024-12-27 10:01:16'),
(342, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Matthew emphasise the number of more than twelve legions of angels?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p>The Devil boasted of having a legion of demons to demonstrate his power (Mark 5:1-20). Matthew mentions twelve legions to signify that the power of heaven is exponentially greater</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:01:47', '2024-12-27 10:01:47'),
(343, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:57: &ldquo;Those who had arrested Jesus took him to Caiaphas the high priest, where the scribes and the elders had gathered.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the house of the high priest the court of the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sanhedrin was the principal judicial body of the Jews, typically convened in proximity to the Jerusalem Temple, specifically in the Chamber of Hewn Stone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in times of emergency, the Sanhedrin would meet in the high priest\'s house without prior agendas.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:02:26', '2024-12-27 10:02:26'),
(344, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:59: &ldquo;Now the chief priests and the whole council were looking for false testimony against Jesus so that they might put him to death.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How many votes were needed to sentence someone to death?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish Sanhedrin consisted of 71 members.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, a quorum of just one-third was sufficient for a death sentence to be pronounced. This practice allowed for a legal determination even with a reduced assembly, thereby maintaining a semblance of justice. If the council met this threshold, it was considered as a noble settlement among the Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:03:29', '2024-12-27 10:03:29'),
(345, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:65: &ldquo;Then the high priest tore his robe and said, &lsquo;He has blasphemed! Why do we still need witnesses? You have now heard his blasphemy!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Jesus commit \'blasphemy\'?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Two actions were deemed blasphemous:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Speaking against God: Jesus claimed to be the son of God.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Speaking against the temple and its services: Against what is noted in Exodus 22:28, Jesus proclaimed that He would destroy the temple.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:04:02', '2024-12-27 10:04:02'),
(346, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why was the garment torn?</em></p>', 1, 31, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Tearing garments was a traditional expression of mourning (Genesis 37:29; Joshua 7:6).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A garment could also be torn to signify disassociation with someone else\'s words (Numbers 14:6; 2 Kings 19:1). Ultimately, it is our heart that should be torn, not&nbsp; clothes.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Judges tore their garments upon hearing blasphemy in court (M. Sanh 7.5).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:05:03', '2024-12-27 10:05:03'),
(347, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the high priest tear his clothes?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the law of Moses, the high priest was not permitted to tear his garments.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;The high priest shall not bare his head, nor tear his clothes&rdquo; (Leviticus 21:10).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The high priest&rsquo;s action symbolised the end of the Old Testament priesthood, as Christ initiated a new sacrifice and priesthood.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This change is echoed in the verse, &ldquo;Therefore, they said to one another, &lsquo;Let us not tear it&rsquo;&rdquo; (John 19:24).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:05:37', '2024-12-27 10:05:37'),
(348, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:67: &ldquo;Then they spat in his face and struck him; and some slapped him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were criminals spat upon?</em></p>', 1, 31, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Spitting on someone was considered one of the greatest insults (Numbers 12:14).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Additionally, it was believed that spitting on blasphemers was a divine act.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:06:11', '2024-12-27 10:06:11');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(349, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:69: &ldquo;Now Peter was sitting outside in the courtyard. A servant girl came to him and said, &lsquo;You also were with Jesus the Galilean.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Peter deny Jesus three times at the same place?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, with each denial, Peter distanced himself further.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The first denial occurred in the courtyard outside the high priest&rsquo;s house: &ldquo;A servant girl came to him and said, &lsquo;You also were with Jesus the Galilean&rsquo;&rdquo; (Matthew 26:69).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The second denial happened at the outer gate when another maid approached him: &ldquo;And she said to those standing there, &lsquo;This man was with Jesus of Nazareth&rsquo;&rdquo; (Matthew 26:71).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The third denial likely took place near the exit, illustrating that the farther Peter moved from Jesus, the stronger his denials became.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:07:02', '2024-12-27 10:07:02'),
(350, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 26:73: &ldquo;After a while, the bystanders came up and said to Peter, &lsquo;Certainly you are also one of them, for your accent betrays you.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How was Peter\'s language different?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 31, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Aramaic spoken by Peter, living in Galilee, exhibited slight differences from the Aramaic used in Jerusalem. Notably, the letters \"het\" (ח) and \"ayin\" (ע) were pronounced differently by Galileans. Additionally, Jerusalemites had their own distinct pronunciation.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Galileans often omitted the letters \"aleph\" (א) and \"hey\" (ה), which contributed to the unique characteristics of their dialect. These linguistic variations highlight the cultural and regional differences among the Jewish people of the time.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:07:43', '2024-12-27 10:07:43'),
(351, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:2: \"They bound him, led him away, and handed him over to Pilate the governor.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Jesus brought before Pilate?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The power to impose the death penalty had been stripped from the Jews by Caesar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, Pilate\'s permission was required to execute Jesus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish authorities brought Jesus before Pilate with the explicit intention of having him put to death.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:08:15', '2024-12-27 10:08:15'),
(352, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:6: \"The chief priests took the silver coins and said, \'It is not lawful to put them into the treasury since it is blood money.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did they refer to the money that Judas returned as the price of blood?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews believed that the cost of a scapegoat lamb, which had been purchased for slaughter, should not be recovered once it was sacrificed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They held that worshipping such an offering would bring upon themselves the pain endured by the atoning lamb and unite it with the temple.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This belief is why they referred to Judas&rsquo; money as \'blood price\';&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:08:52', '2024-12-27 10:08:52'),
(353, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:10: \"They gave them for the potter\'s field, as the Lord commanded me.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the field bought by Judas with 30 pieces of silver come to be called Akeldama?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Since it was not permissible to deposit blood money in the temple treasury, the chief priests used it to purchase a potter\'s field for burying foreigners.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This location became known as the Field of Blood, or \'Haqel dema\' in Aramaic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Situated on the southern side of the Hinnom Valley, it is still referred to as Hak el-damm today.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:09:39', '2024-12-27 10:09:39'),
(354, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:15: \"Now at the festival the governor was accustomed to release a prisoner for the crowd, anyone whom they wanted.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the release of a prisoner customary during Passover?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Some assert that the Romans instituted this practice to appease the Jews, as had been commented upon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, new findings indicate that it began during the Maccabean period (Hasmonean Period).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Initially, only political prisoners benefited from this custom, but over time it evolved into a right for the Jews under Roman rule.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:10:14', '2024-12-27 10:10:14'),
(355, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:19: \"While he was sitting on the judgement seat, his wife sent word to him, \'Have nothing to do with that innocent man, for today I have suffered a great deal because of a dream about him.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where did Pilate pass judgement?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilate sat on a throne known as the Bema &Beta;&eta;&mu;&alpha;&tau;&omicron;&sigmaf;&nbsp; , were Roman judges delivered their verdicts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod Agrippa used a similar seat when he addressed the people of Tyre and Sidon (Acts 19:13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The greatest regrets are often felt in the moments leading up to judgement.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:12:17', '2024-12-27 10:12:17'),
(356, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:19: &ldquo;Moreover, while he was sitting on the judgement seat, his wife sent word to him, &lsquo;Have nothing to do with that righteous man, for today I have suffered a great deal because of a dream about him.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Pilate\'s wife know Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilate\'s wife was named Claudia (Claudia Procula) (Ref: The Gospel of Nicodemus).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is likely that she was part of Pilate\'s advisory committee regarding Jewish affairs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Her involvement in the trial of Jesus indicates that she had some influence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In historical context, Empress Livia admonished her husband, Augustus Caesar, in administrative matters; thus, it is reasonable to assume that Claudia knew prominent figures in Israel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Claudia may have been familiar with Jesus, one of Israel\'s most significant rabbis.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:12:55', '2024-12-27 10:12:55'),
(357, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:24: &ldquo;So when Pilate saw that he could do nothing, but rather that a riot was beginning, he took water and washed his hands before the crowd, saying, &lsquo;I am innocent of this man&rsquo;s blood; see to it yourselves.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Pilate wash his hands?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews had a concept of &ldquo;blood revenge&rdquo; (Dorash Dam), which meant that if a person\'s death was unjust, God would demand accountability for that blood (see 2 Chronicles 24:22).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, God demanded the blood of Zechariah the priest by sending the Arameans into battle as a form of divine retribution.The practice underscores the seriousness with which the Jews viewed the shedding of blood and the need for justice.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Pilate, wishing to avoid the repercussions of Jesus\' death, washed his hands to symbolically absolve himself of responsibility for the consequences of this act.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:14:00', '2024-12-27 10:14:00'),
(358, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:32: &ldquo;As they went out, they came upon a man from Cyrene named Simon; they compelled this man to carry his cross.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Simon of Cyrene carry Jesus\' cross?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Roman law, a soldier could compel a citizen to carry their burden for a mile.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why Jesus taught, &ldquo;If anyone forces you to go one mile, go also the second mile&rdquo; (Matthew 5:41).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;In this instance, soldiers forced Simon to carry Jesus\'s cross.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:15:48', '2024-12-27 10:15:48'),
(359, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:35: &ldquo;When they had crucified him, they divided his clothes among them by casting lots.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Romans invent crucifixion?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Crucifixion was not originally a Roman invention; the Old Testament prescribed stoning as a method of execution, although it was common for bodies to be hung on trees as a warning (Deuteronomy 21:22-23).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Phoenicians and Carthaginians were among those who practised crucifixion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Romans adopted this method for executions after conquering various cities.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:16:24', '2024-12-27 10:16:24'),
(360, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:37: &ldquo;Over his head, they put the charge against him, which read, &lsquo;This is Jesus, the King of the Jews.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is INRI?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman government mandated that individuals sentenced to death carry a small tablet known as the Titulus. This tablet served two purposes:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Charge Against Him (Titulus): This outlined the specific crime for which the individual was being executed.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Causa Poenae: This indicated the reason for imposing the death penalty.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the case of Jesus, the inscription read \"Iesus Nazarenus Rex Iudaeorum\" (This is Jesus of Nazareth, King of the Jews). The charge against Him and the rationale for His death sentence were identical: He claimed to be the King of the Jews.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:17:00', '2024-12-27 10:17:00'),
(361, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:46-47: &ldquo;About the ninth hour Jesus cried with a loud voice, &lsquo;Eli, Eli, lama sabachthani?&rsquo; that is, &lsquo;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&rsquo; When some of the bystanders heard it, they said, &lsquo;This man is calling for Elijah.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did they not understand Jesus\' cry on the cross?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus cried out, &ldquo;Eli, Eli, lama sabachthani?&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;lama sabachthani&rdquo; is in the Aramaic language that Jesus spoke.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Eli&rdquo; is a shortened form of &ldquo;Eliyahu,&rdquo; the Hebrew name for God. God was not called Eli in Aramaic.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The people did not comprehend Jesus\' cry because they were interpreting the Hebrew words &ldquo;Eli&rdquo; and &ldquo;lama sabachthani&rdquo; without understanding their significance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:17:34', '2024-12-27 10:17:34'),
(362, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:46: &ldquo;About the ninth hour Jesus cried with a loud voice, &lsquo;Eli, Eli, lama sabachthani?&rsquo; That is, &lsquo;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the ninth hour when Jesus died?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish ninth hour corresponds to around 3 p.m.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was the time when the Passover lamb was traditionally sacrificed in the temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:18:10', '2024-12-27 10:18:10'),
(363, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus recite a passage from Psalm 22 while being crucified?</em></p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Eli, Eli, lama sabachthani?&rdquo; is the opening verse of Psalm 22: &ldquo;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This psalm is regarded as a Messianic Psalm in Jewish tradition, and many of its verses are fulfilled in the experiences of Jesus.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, Psalm 22:18 states, &ldquo;They divide my clothes among themselves, and for my clothing they cast lots.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In uttering these words, Jesus was declaring His identity as the Messiah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:18:45', '2024-12-27 10:18:45'),
(364, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:47: &ldquo;When some of the bystanders heard it, they said, &lsquo;This man is calling for Elijah.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus call for Elijah to the bystanders?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p>The Jews held the belief that Elijah would come to aid God\'s people in times of suffering, which is why they mistook Jesus\' cry to God as a call for Elijah</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:19:31', '2024-12-27 10:19:31'),
(365, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:50: &ldquo;Then Jesus cried again with a loud voice and breathed his last.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus die crying?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, Matthew uses the word krazo, which means to scream. However, when combined with the verb aphiemi (to leave), it also conveys a sense of triumph.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, His cry can be understood as a victorious shout.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:20:05', '2024-12-27 10:20:05'),
(366, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:54: &ldquo;Now when the centurion and those with him, who were guarding Jesus, saw the earthquake and what took place, they were terrified and said, &lsquo;Truly this man was God&rsquo;s Son!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was the centurion standing under the cross?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A Roman legion typically consisted of 6,000 soldiers, divided into 10 cohorts, each containing approximately 600 soldiers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Each cohort was further divided into 6 centuries, making a centurion the commander of 100 soldiers.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Additionally, the centurion was a person who swore allegiance to Caesar, recognizing him as Kurios (Lord) of all things.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:21:19', '2024-12-27 10:21:19'),
(367, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:57: &ldquo;When it was evening, there came a rich man from Arimathea, named Joseph, who was also a disciple of Jesus.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was Joseph of Arimathea?</em></p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Arimathea was a town located about 20 kilometers northwest of Jerusalem, where Joseph likely settled.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This proximity is why he built a tomb for himself in Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Its best to prepare the grave where we would eventually rest.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:21:53', '2024-12-27 10:21:53'),
(368, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:58: &ldquo;He went to Pilate and asked for the body of Jesus. Then Pilate ordered it to be released to him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Joseph of Arimathea ask for and buy the body of Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Roman law, the bodies of those executed by crucifixion were typically released to their relatives.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the bodies of individuals who caused disturbances against Rome were often denied to their families, left instead to be preyed upon by vultures and birds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, Joseph of Arimathea purchased the body of Jesus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Let us grow in hope of the resurrection of the body.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:22:27', '2024-12-27 10:22:27'),
(369, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:61: &ldquo;Mary Magdalene and the other Mary were there, sitting opposite the tomb.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who is the other Mary mentioned in the Bible?</em></p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the four Gospels, we encounter four women named Mary:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary, the mother of Jesus</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary Magdalene</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The other Mary</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary, the mother of Cleophas</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is reasonable to assume that the other Mary refers to Mary, the mother of Cleophas, who is identified as the mother of James and Joseph in Matthew 27:56. &ldquo;Among them were Mary Magdalene, and Mary the mother of James and Joseph, and the mother of the sons of Zebedee.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:23:02', '2024-12-27 10:23:02'),
(370, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Is there anything special about Mary Magdalene sitting facing the cross?</em><br><br></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the biblical context, sitting is often seen as a sign of mourning.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, &ldquo;By the rivers of Babylon, there we sat down and there we wept when we remembered Zion&rdquo; (Psalm 137:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, &ldquo;Job sat in the ashes and rubbed his body with a piece of broken pottery&rdquo; (Job 2:8).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mary Magdalene\'s act of sitting facing the cross can be interpreted symbolically as an expression of grief and deep sorrow.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:23:37', '2024-12-27 10:23:37'),
(371, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:62: &ldquo;The next day, that is, after the day of Preparation, the chief priests and the Pharisees gathered before Pilate.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews call the day Jesus died the Day of Preparation?</em></p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">On the day Jesus died, the Jews needed to make two types of preparations:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">It was a preparation day for the Sabbath, as it is every week.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Additionally, the festival of Unleavened Bread began on the 15th of Nissan, lasting for seven days.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;For these two reasons, the day Jesus died is referred to as the Day of Preparation.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:24:18', '2024-12-27 10:24:18'),
(372, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 27:66: &ldquo;So they went with the guard and made the tomb secure by sealing the stone.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the tomb sealed?</em></p>', 1, 32, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Sealing the tomb (Sphragidzo) was a Roman practice, indicating that a Roman guard was assigned to secure the tomb of Jesus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A typical Roman guard consisted of 16 soldiers, who were required to stand watch for three hours at a time.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If one fell asleep during this duty, the punishment was imposed on all others, ensuring a strict enforcement of vigilance.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:24:50', '2024-12-27 10:24:50'),
(373, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 28:1: &ldquo;After the Sabbath, as the first day of the week was dawning, Mary Magdalene and the other Mary went to see the tomb.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus rise from the dead on the third day?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 33, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews had a unique method of counting days. Even a part of a day was considered a full day. For instance, in Esther 4:16-5:1, a part of a day was counted as a day, allowing Esther to approach the king after three days of fasting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why it is stated that Jesus rose on the third day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:25:25', '2024-12-27 10:25:25'),
(374, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 28:11: &ldquo;While they were going, some of the guards went into the city and told the chief priests everything that had happened.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the guards announce Jesus\' resurrection to the chief priests?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 33, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The chief priests likely took responsibility for guarding the tomb. In that context, the temple servants would also have been guarding the temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This explains why the guards reported the resurrection to the chief priests.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is also important to acknowledge that the message of resurrection has two aspects:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mary Magdalene brings a message of joy, while the soldiers represent a message of fear.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:26:03', '2024-12-27 10:26:03'),
(375, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 28:16: &ldquo;Now the eleven disciples went to Galilee, to the mountain to which Jesus had directed them.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus finally gather the disciples on the mountain?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 33, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Gospel of Matthew, Jesus is portrayed as the new Moses. Two mountains are pivotal in Moses\' journey:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mount Sinai: The place where God gave the commandments.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mount Nebo (Deuteronomy 34:1): Where Moses gazed upon the Promised Land.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, Jesus establishes&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&Alpha; new commandment on a mountain (Matthew 5-7) and&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Stands on another mountain to commission His disciples to preach the Gospel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:26:39', '2024-12-27 10:26:39'),
(376, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 28:19: &ldquo;Go therefore and make disciples of all nations.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who spread the Gospel to the entire world?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 33, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew wrote his Gospel after the destruction of the Jerusalem temple in A.D. 70, during a time when the Christian community was gradually evolving from Jewish traditions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This evolution allowed the Gospel to reach broader audiences.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Much like the Jews, Judeo-Christians migrated extensively, facilitating the spread of the Gospel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:27:12', '2024-12-27 10:27:12'),
(377, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Matthew 28:20: &ldquo;Baptising them in the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit, teaching them to obey everything that I have commanded you. And remember, I am with you always, to the end of the age.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus command to baptise or to teach first?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 33, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During the time of the apostles, believers were baptised (Acts 8:36; 16:33).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Belief in the Triune God formed the foundation of baptism.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The practice of pre-baptismal faith instruction developed later.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:27:45', '2024-12-27 10:27:45'),
(378, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why is it significant to baptise in the name of the Son and the Holy Spirit?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 33, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John&rsquo;s baptism can be understood in relation to Christian baptism.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>To highlight the difference between the two, Christian baptism is to be performed in the name of the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>This also reinforces the concept of the Holy Trinity as one God</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2024-12-27 10:28:55', '2024-12-27 10:28:55'),
(379, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:3: &ldquo;The voice of one crying out in the wilderness: &lsquo;Prepare the way of the Lord, make his paths straight,&rsquo; as it is written in the book of the prophet Isaiah.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why is the Old Testament referred to as \"the book\"?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews were prohibited from pronouncing the name YHWH. Instead of directly attributing the words to God, they would say \"as written in this book\" to maintain reverence for the divine name. This practice helped preserve the sanctity of God\'s name.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:18:18', '2025-01-03 00:18:18'),
(380, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:4: &ldquo;John the Baptist appeared in the wilderness, proclaiming a baptism of repentance for the forgiveness of sins.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John go to the wilderness?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In 1946, some manuscripts, known as the Qumran Scrolls, were discovered in the Qumran canyon of the Judean desert.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These scrolls reveal that there were Jewish monastic communities during Jesus\' time, identified as the Essenes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their settlement was situated in the Jordan desert near the Dead Sea, where they diligently obeyed the Jewish Law. It&rsquo;s likely that John lived as a hermit, emulating the lifestyle of the Essene community in the wilderness.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:19:04', '2025-01-03 00:19:04'),
(381, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:5: &ldquo;And people from the whole Judean countryside and all the people of Jerusalem were going out to him, and were baptised by him in the Jordan River, confessing their sins.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John baptise in the Jordan River?</em></p>', 2, 3, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Jordan River was believed to be perennial, never drying up.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Jews entered the Promised Land by crossing the Jordan River (Joshua 3).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Additionally, Naaman was healed after immersing himself in the Jordan River (2 Kings 5:10-14).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These reasons highlight the Jordan River\'s importance to the Jewish people. It serves as a symbol of faith and a site of divine intervention.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:19:45', '2025-01-03 00:19:45'),
(382, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:6: &ldquo;John was clothed with camel&rsquo;s hair, with a leather belt around his waist, and he ate locusts and wild honey.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John wear a garment made of camel&rsquo;s hair and a leather belt?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The prophet Elijah is described in the Old Testament as wearing similar attire:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;They answered him, &lsquo;He wore a garment of hair, with a leather belt around his waist.&rsquo; So he said, &lsquo;It is Elijah the Tishbite&rsquo;&rdquo; (2 Kings 1:8).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John wore camel\'s hair and a leather belt to signify that he was the Elijah who would precede the Saviour.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:20:23', '2025-01-03 00:20:23'),
(383, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:7: &ldquo;He proclaimed, &lsquo;The one who is more powerful than I is coming after me; I am not worthy to stoop down and untie the thong of his sandals.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does John the Baptist call Jesus \'mighty\'?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John introduces Jesus to the world by referencing Isaiah 40:3: &ldquo;A voice cries out: &lsquo;In the wilderness prepare the way of the Lord, make straight in the desert a highway for our God&rsquo;&rdquo; (Isaiah 40:3).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Isaiah 40:10, God is described as &ldquo;coming with might&rdquo;: &ldquo;See, the Lord God comes with might, and his arm rules for him&rdquo; (Isaiah 40:10).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why John the Baptist called Jesus \'the Mighty One.\'</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:20:58', '2025-01-03 00:20:58'),
(384, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:9: &ldquo;In those days Jesus came from Nazareth of Galilee and was baptised by John in Jordan.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Nazareth a famous place?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Nazareth is not mentioned in the Old Testament or other Jewish texts, except in the New Testament.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The earliest known inscription related to Nazareth was discovered in 1962 and is believed to be from the third century.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It speaks of a priestly family residing in Nazareth. So it is likely that Nazareth was a relatively obscure settlement during Jesus\'s time.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:22:23', '2025-01-03 00:22:23'),
(385, '<p><em>Should John have immersed Jesus?</em></p>', 2, 3, '<p>Ritual immersion does not require a witness unless it is for adding someone to the Israeli community. <br><br>Proselyte immersion, however, does require a witness (Mathil - Immerser), who approves the baptism. <br><br>There is no stipulation that an individual receiving this witnessed baptism must be immersed in water.</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:48:40', '2025-01-03 00:48:40'),
(386, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:11: &ldquo;And a voice came from heaven, &lsquo;You are my Son, the Beloved; with you I am well pleased.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does Mark specifically say that the voice came from heaven?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews believed that God ceased to speak directly following the establishment of the Jerusalem Temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They anticipated that God would speak directly only upon the arrival of the Messiah. By stating that the voice came from heaven, Mark emphasises that Jesus is the long awaited Messiah.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:49:35', '2025-01-03 00:49:35'),
(387, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:13: &ldquo;After being tempted by Satan, he was in the wilderness for forty days; he was with the wild beasts, and the angels waited on him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Mark say that Jesus was with the wild beasts?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Isaiah prophesied that the coming of the Saviour would restore the harmony between humanity and the animal kingdom that existed in Paradise.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;As stated in Isaiah 11:6-7, &ldquo;The wolf shall live with the lamb, the leopard shall lie down with the kid, the calf and the lion will feed together, and a little child shall lead them. The cow and the bear shall graze; their young shall lie down together, and the lion shall eat straw like the ox.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark indicates that Jesus was with the wild animals for forty days to fulfil this prophecy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:50:14', '2025-01-03 00:50:14'),
(388, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:13: &ldquo;After being tempted by Satan, he was in the wilderness for forty days; he was with the wild beasts, and the angels waited on him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus choose to fast in the desert for forty days?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites wandered in the desert for forty years before entering the Promised Land, a time of preparation for their future.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus Jesus chose to fast in the desert for forty days to prepare for his public ministry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:50:49', '2025-01-03 00:50:49'),
(389, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:13: &ldquo;After being tempted by Satan, he was in the wilderness for forty days; he was with the wild beasts, and the angels waited on him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were the wild animals of the desert?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \'theria\' is used to refer to these wild animals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some beings possessing demonic powers were also referred to as \'theria.\'&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The wilderness and wild animals represent Jesus\' trials.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:51:34', '2025-01-03 00:51:34'),
(390, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:15: &ldquo;He said, &lsquo;The time is fulfilled, and the kingdom of God has come near; repent, and believe in the good news.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did he say &ldquo;the time is fulfilled?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish understanding of time differs slightly from contemporary views.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;In Jewish thought, time can be likened to a stack of bricks: each year adds another layer, one on top of the other.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;If a person lives for seventy years, by the time they reach that age, no more \'bricks\' can be added.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Once their allotted time is up, they must bid farewell to this world. This is why the Jews proclaimed that \'the time is fulfilled</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 00:54:48', '2025-01-03 00:54:48'),
(391, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:17: &ldquo;Jesus said to them, &lsquo;Follow me, and I will make you fish for people.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is there anything special about Jesus calling his disciples?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition it was ordinary for disciples to seek out rabbis, as the norm was for disciples to pursue their teachers.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Jesus calls those He desires to follow Him.</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:00:13', '2025-01-03 01:00:13'),
(392, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:18: \"Immediately they left their nets and followed him.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the disciples follow Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish education progressed through three stages:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Bet Sefer &ndash; From ages 5 to 10, students studied the Law in the synagogue.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Bet Talmud &ndash; Between the ages of 10 and 12, they learned the interpretations of the Torah.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Bet Midrash &ndash; After turning 12, students could become disciples of any rabbi to attain proficiency in law and interpretation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A jurist was only recognised after successfully completing their studies at the Bet Midrash. The disciples likely followed Jesus as part of their education with a rabbi.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:01:00', '2025-01-03 01:01:00'),
(393, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:21: \"And they came to Capernaum; and on the Sabbath he entered the synagogue and taught.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus teach primarily in Capernaum?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Capernaum flourished with a robust fishing industry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The road leading to Iturea and Trachonitis, governed by King Philip, also passed through Capernaum.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This geographical significance explains why Jesus chose to teach in Capernaum <br>over the sparsely populated Nazareth.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:01:32', '2025-01-03 01:01:32'),
(394, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:24: \"He shouted, &lsquo;What have you to do with us, Jesus of Nazareth? Have you come to destroy us? I know who you are, the Holy One of God.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the demoniac call Jesus \'the Holy One of God\'?</em></p>', 2, 3, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In the Old Testament kings were anointed with holy oil and were referred to as the \'Holy One of God.\' For instance, David is called the Holy One of God: \"The Lord is our shield; the Holy One of Israel is our King\" (Psalm 89:18).&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus the title &lsquo;Holy One of God&rsquo; signifies Jesus as the Messiah from David\'s line.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In addition to God, the high priest in the Old Testament, such as Aaron, is also referred to as \'the holy one\' (2 Kings 4:9; Psalm 106:16; Numbers 16:35).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Only the high priest was allowed to perform acts of atonement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Here the evangelist underscores the holiness required in the ministry of casting out demons, highlighting that great holiness is necessary to resist the devil.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:03:35', '2025-01-03 01:03:35'),
(395, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:25: \"Jesus rebuked him, saying, &lsquo;Be silent, and come out of him!&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Jesus cast out demons?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus rebuked the demons (Mark 9:25), rendered them inactive (Mark 1:25) and expelled them (Mark 5:8). He also trained his disciples to cast out demons.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His disciples can employ all three methods of casting out demons in His name.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The power of the name of Jesus ultimately vanquishes demonic activities.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:04:13', '2025-01-03 01:04:13'),
(396, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:30: \"Now Simon\'s mother-in-law was in bed with a fever, and they told him about her at once.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is Simon\'s mother-in-law unnamed?</em></p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus\' time, Jewish women were often defined by their relationships with men.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, they were called:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Wife of Kuza&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The mother of the sons of Zebat&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Simeon\'s mother-in-law&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why Peter\'s mother-in-law is not mentioned by name in the Gospel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:04:48', '2025-01-03 01:04:48'),
(397, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:31: &ldquo;He came and took her by the hand and lifted her up. Then the fever left her, and she began to serve them.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is it recorded that Simon\'s mother-in-law ministered to them after she was healed?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Isaiah\'s prophecy, when the Messiah arrives and vanquishes evil, there will be profound joy and happiness in the world, often referred to as the Messianic Banquet.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Say to those who are of a fearful heart, &lsquo;Be strong, do not fear! Here is your God. He will come with vengeance; with terrible recompense He will come and save you.&rsquo; Then the eyes of the blind shall be opened, and the ears of the deaf unstopped; then the lame shall leap like a deer, and the tongue of the speechless sing for joy. For waters shall break forth in the wilderness, and streams in the desert&rdquo; (Isaiah 35:4-6).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is against this Old Testament backdrop that Mark records the ministry of Simon\'s mother-in-law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:05:24', '2025-01-03 01:05:24'),
(398, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:34: &ldquo;He healed many who were sick with various diseases, and cast out many demons; and he would not permit the demons to speak, because they knew him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were all possessed by the Devil?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The harm inflicted by the Devil can be understood in two primary ways:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Spiritual Possession: This form of possession obstructs one&rsquo;s ability to know or love Christ.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Physical Possession: This occurs when the Devil uses a person&rsquo;s body to fulfil his desires.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:05:58', '2025-01-03 01:05:58'),
(399, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:41: &ldquo;Moved with compassion, Jesus stretched out his hand and touched him, and said to him, &lsquo;I am willing; be made clean!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is it significant to note that Jesus felt compassion and reached out to heal the leper?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The people of Israel experienced God\'s profound mercy during their deliverance from Egypt.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Book of Exodus, they read that God liberated the Israelites from bondage with an outstretched hand.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;When I stretch out my hand against Egypt and bring the Israelites out from among them, the Egyptians shall know that I am the Lord&rdquo; (Exodus 7:5).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To signify that a second exodus had begun through Jesus, the new Moses, Jesus felt compassion and extended His hand to heal.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:06:32', '2025-01-03 01:06:32'),
(400, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 1:44: &ldquo;He said to him, &lsquo;See that you say nothing to anyone; but go, show yourself to the priest, and offer for your cleansing what Moses commanded, as a testimony to them.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus instruct those He healed not to speak of Him?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 3, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Messianic Secret is a distinctive feature of Mark\'s Gospel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to this concept, Jesus is publicly declared to be the Son of God only at His crucifixion.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;When the centurion, who stood facing him, saw that in this way he breathed his last, he said, &lsquo;Truly this man was God&rsquo;s Son!&rsquo;&rdquo; (Mark 15:39).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To maintain this Messianic Secret, Jesus instructs those who have been healed not to speak of Him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:07:02', '2025-01-03 01:07:02'),
(401, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:4: &ldquo;And when they could not bring him to Jesus because of the crowd, they removed the roof above him; and after having dug through it, they let down the mat on which the paralytic lay.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was it easy to unroof the house?</em></p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Palestine, many homes were constructed with an external staircase leading to the roof.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This space was often used to dry various items. The roofs were commonly made by mixing soil to create tiles, which were then stacked.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Removing sections of the roof required considerable effort.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:07:49', '2025-01-03 01:07:49'),
(402, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:7: &ldquo;Why does this man speak like this? He is blaspheming. Who can forgive sins but God alone?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Jesus\' forgiveness of sins lead to accusations of blasphemy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish people had only one day a year, Yom Kippur, to atone for their sins.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On that day the high priest would symbolically place the sins of the children of Israel onto a scapegoat.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He would then proclaim, acting as God&rsquo;s representative, &ldquo;Your sins are forgiven.&rdquo; So when Jesus uttered similar words they were perceived as blasphemous because only God can forgive sins.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:08:31', '2025-01-03 01:08:31'),
(403, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:10: &ldquo;But so that you may know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins, he said to the paralytic,&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the Jews understand about authority?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">For the Jews all authority originates from God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed that such powers were bestowed upon them through the Torah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They used this Torah to question Jesus&rsquo; authority, as seen in Mark 2:23-36.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:09:10', '2025-01-03 01:09:10'),
(404, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:14: &ldquo;As he passed by, he saw Levi, son of Alphaeus, sitting at the tax booth, and he said to him, &lsquo;Follow me.&rsquo; And he got up and followed him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the nature of the tax office where Matthew was seated?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Palestine, two primary types of taxes were collected for Rome.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The first was the Head Tax, a levy imposed on each individual,&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">while the second was the Sales Tax, applicable to transporting goods for sale.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Toll booths were established along roads and bridges to collect sales tax, and Matthew may have been seated at one of these booths.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:10:51', '2025-01-03 01:10:51'),
(405, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:16: &ldquo;When the scribes of the Pharisees saw that he was eating with sinners and tax collectors, they said to his disciples, &lsquo;Why does he eat with tax collectors and sinners?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is deemed inappropriate about dining with publicans?</em></p>', 2, 4, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Publicans are tax collectors for Gentile authorities, and thus, they are considered sinners.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jews typically shared meals from the same bowl and reclined together, making it especially egregious to eat from the vessel of a sinner.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:12:10', '2025-01-03 01:12:10'),
(406, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the Jews harbour such animosity towards tax collectors?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Idolatry: Tax collectors acknowledged Caesar as a god, which was offensive to the Jewish faith.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Slavery: By collecting taxes, publicans positioned themselves as slaves to the Romans.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This explains the deep-seated hatred the Jews held for tax collectors.</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:14:08', '2025-01-03 01:14:08');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(407, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:18: &ldquo;Now John\'s disciples and the Pharisees were fasting; and people came and said to him, &lsquo;Why are John\'s disciples and the disciples of the Pharisees fasting, but your disciples are not fasting?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How many days did the Jews traditionally fast?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Book of the Law specifies only one day&mdash;the Day of Atonement&mdash;as a day for fasting:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;It is a day of atonement for you to be cleansed from all sins. It is a holy Sabbath of rest for you; you must fast&rdquo; (Leviticus 16:30-31).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Later, four additional days were designated as fast days (Zechariah 8:19): &ldquo;Thus says the Lord of hosts: The fast of the fourth, fifth, seventh and tenth months shall be joy and gladness to the house of Judah. Therefore, love truth and peace.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, zealous Pharisees chose to fast twice a week (Luke 18:12).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:14:50', '2025-01-03 01:14:50'),
(408, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:19: &ldquo;Jesus said to them, &lsquo;The wedding guests cannot fast while the bridegroom is with them, can they? As long as they have the bridegroom with them, they cannot fast.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus call Himself the bridegroom?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, the people of Israel considered themselves God\'s bride (Hosea 2:20-25).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This relationship was based on the covenant that God made with Israel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed God would maintain this bond if they remained faithful (Hesed) to the covenant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By calling Himself the bridegroom, Jesus reminds us of this intimate relationship with God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:15:33', '2025-01-03 01:15:33'),
(409, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:19: &ldquo;Jesus said to them, &lsquo;The wedding guests cannot fast while the bridegroom is with them, can they? As long as they have the bridegroom with them, they cannot fast.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the bridegroom&rsquo;s fast?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Some Pharisees fasted specifically in anticipation of the coming of the Saviour. However, they continued this practice even in Jesus\' time, despite His presence. This is the \"bridegroom\'s fast\" that Jesus was referring to. Fasting for the coming of the Saviour was no longer necessary since He was already among them.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:16:22', '2025-01-03 01:16:22'),
(410, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:21: &ldquo;No one sews a piece of unshrunk cloth on an old cloak; otherwise, the patch pulls away from it, the new from the old, and a worse tear is made.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is a new piece of clothing attached to an old garment?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Here, the new, unprocessed cloth is attached to the old garment. After weaving, the cloth undergoes several processes, such as:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Cleaning</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Combing</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Removal of hair and gum</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Bleaching</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These steps are essential before the raw material is ready for stitching.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:16:56', '2025-01-03 01:16:56'),
(411, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:22: &ldquo;And no one puts new wine into old wineskins; otherwise, the wine will burst the skins, and the wine is lost, and so are the skins; but one puts new wine into fresh wineskins.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Are old leather skins prone to tearing?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Some skins are initially flexible and easy to work with, but over time, they become stiff and prone to tearing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is especially true when storing drinks like wine, which can accelerate skin deterioration. <br>Without proper care, both the skin and the wine can be ruined.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:17:29', '2025-01-03 01:17:29'),
(412, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:24: &ldquo;The Pharisees said to him, &lsquo;Look, why are they doing what is not lawful on the sabbath?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Pharisees take Sabbath-breaking so seriously?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees meticulously observed the written laws, particularly regarding the Sabbath.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed that the Babylonian Exile in 597 B.C. resulted from failing to keep the Sabbath holy (Jeremiah 17:21-27).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So they placed great importance on strict Sabbath observance. To them, the key to preventing another disaster was in their hands, through strict adherence to the law</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:19:01', '2025-01-03 01:19:01'),
(413, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 2:26: \"But when he entered the house of God, in the time of Abiathar the high priest, and ate the bread of the Presence, which it is not lawful for any but the priests to eat, and he gave some to his companions?\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jeuss make a factual error when He said David ate the bread of the Presence when Abiathar was high priest?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 4, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus stated that David ate the bread of the Presence when Abiathar was high priest.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, 1 Samuel 21:1-6 records that Ahimelech was the high priest then. Jesus did not make an error here.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The phrase \"in the days of Abiathar\" refers to a period during which Abiathar was prominent.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Shortly after the event, Abiathar succeeded Ahimelech as high priest (1 Samuel 22:20-23). Thus the Jews later referred to that time as the era of Abiathar, which is why Jesus used that name.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:20:06', '2025-01-03 01:20:06'),
(414, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 3:1: \"Again he entered the synagogue, and a man who had a withered hand was there.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the Jewish concept of a withered hand?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 34, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Jews, a withered hand was associated with evil actions.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed that the act of raising one&rsquo;s hand to commit evil would bring about decay.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, Psalms 137:5 is written, &ldquo;If I forget you, O Jerusalem, let my right hand wither!&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Zechariah 11:17 condemns a wicked shepherd with the words, &ldquo;May his arm be completely withered, his right eye utterly blinded!&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, in 1 Kings 13:4-6 King Jeroboam&rsquo;s hand withered due to his defiance against the Lord.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews believed that hands raised for evil purposes would wither while hands raised for good would prosper.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:21:31', '2025-01-03 01:21:31'),
(415, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 3:6: \"The Pharisees went out and immediately conspired with the Herodians against him, how to destroy him.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Mark connects the conspiracy of the Pharisees to which Old Testament event?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 34, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark narrates the Pharisees&rsquo; conspiracy against Jesus following the mention of David in Mark 2:26.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This parallels the Old Testament story of Doeg, who conspired with King Saul against David (1 Samuel 21:7; 22:22).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Doeg reported David&rsquo;s encounter with the high priest Ahimelech to Saul, leading to the massacre of the priests at Nob (1 Samuel 22:9-10).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, the Pharisees, like Doeg, conspired with King Herod&rsquo;s supporters to plot against Jesus, who is the Mediator of the New Covenant. Just as David prevailed, so too would Jesus.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:22:09', '2025-01-03 01:22:09'),
(416, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What caused Herod\'s supporters to rise?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 34, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod&rsquo;s followers, the Herodians, expected a saviour from Herod&rsquo;s royal lineage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many desired Herod Agrippa I, the grandson of Herod the Great, to be their ruler.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They even attempted to honour Herod by placing his tomb above David&rsquo;s, as the historian Josephus noted (Josephus A. J. Halics 16.182).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They compared Herod the Great&rsquo;s construction works to Solomon\'s, hoping for a stable reign under his dynasty alongside Roman support.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their loyalty to the Herodian dynasty was motivated by a desire for stability and continuity in Roman-backed governance.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:22:38', '2025-01-03 01:22:38'),
(417, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What caused the Pharisees and the Herodians to come together?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 34, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees, who focused on legal matters and the Herodians, who were politically inclined, had different priorities.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However both groups found it necessary to eliminate Jesus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since the Sadducees, a priestly class, were mostly concentrated in Jerusalem, it was the Pharisees who held greater influence in regions like Capernaum, where Jesus performed many of His healings.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore the Herodians allied with the Pharisees in their opposition to Jesus, seeing Him as a threat to both their political and religious positions.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:23:07', '2025-01-03 01:23:07'),
(418, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 3:17: \"James son of Zebedee and John the brother of James (to whom he gave the name Boanerges, that is, Sons of Thunder).\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus call James and John \"Boanerges\"?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 34, '<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Boanerges\" is a Greek name.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Jesus likely spoke to them in Hebrew, calling them \"Bene Roges,\" which translates to \"sons of thunder\" (bene = sons, rogen = thunder).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This title likely reflects their fiery, passionate nature. Jesus gave them a name that resonated with their inner spirit and potential.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:24:43', '2025-01-20 05:46:25'),
(419, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 3:22: \"And the scribes who came down from Jerusalem said, &lsquo;He has Beelzebul and by the ruler of the demons he casts out demons.&rsquo;\" </strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What were the scribes trying to achieve by saying Jesus had Beelzebul?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 34, '<p dir=\"ltr\">All forms of demonic activity were forbidden to the Israelites. &ldquo;Do not permit a sorceress to live&rdquo; (Exodus 22:18).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;There shall not be found among you anyone who practices divination or is a soothsayer, or an augur, or a sorcerer&rdquo; (Deuteronomy 18:10-11).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Sacrificed his son in the fire, practised soothsaying and augury, and dealt with mediums and wizards. He did much evil in the sight of the Lord, provoking him to anger&rdquo; (2 Kings 21:6).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If they could prove that Jesus had Beelzebul, they would have grounds to condemn Him.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:25:31', '2025-01-03 01:25:31'),
(420, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:3: &ldquo;Listen! A sower went out to sow.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When did the Jews sow seeds?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Sukkot, the Feast of Tabernacles, takes place on the 15th day of Tishrei (September/October).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Corn seeds were often sown alongside other grains. These grains would be ripe for harvest around the time of the Pentecost festival (Shavuot, 50 days after Passover, in May/June).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish festival of Sukkoth, occurring on the 15th day of Tishrei (September/October), was traditionally when corn seeds were sown. These crops would ripen around the Feast of Pentecost (Shavuot), celebrated 50 days after Passover (May/June). Barley, however, ripened earlier, being ready for harvest around Passover (Nissan 15, March/April).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:31:34', '2025-01-03 01:31:34'),
(421, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:8: \"Other seeds fell into good soil and brought forth grain, growing up and increasing and yielding thirty and sixty and a hundredfold.\"&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were there hundredfold harvests in Palestine?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A hundredfold yield means a yield of a hundred seeds from one seed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Such yields were uncommon in the soil of Palestine but it was believed that if God blessed the land, it could indeed produce a hundredfold.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Genesis 26:12, God blessed Isaac with a hundredfold harvest.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:32:14', '2025-01-03 01:32:14'),
(422, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:11: &ldquo;And he said to them, &lsquo;To you has been given the secret of the kingdom of God, but for those outside, everything comes in parables.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were there secrets exclusive to the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Some Jewish communities believed that God revealed certain mysteries only to the Jews, such as the Testaments of the Twelve Patriarchs (e.g., Test Lv 2:10; Judah 16:4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">God had also revealed to them how He created the earth (e.g., Deuteronomy 29:29; 1 Enoch 4:1-3).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;These secrets were hidden from other nations (Wisdom 2:22; 4 Ezra 14:45-47).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Christ is the greatest mystery revealed to us.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:32:50', '2025-01-03 01:32:50'),
(423, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What was referred to as \'the secrets\'?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews used the word &lsquo;raz&rsquo; for secret. They considered certain truths to be mysteries and that they can be understood only with divine help.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An example is Daniel 2:4-7:28 where Daniel, filled with God&rsquo;s Spirit, revealed the secret (raz) of King Nebuchadnezzar&rsquo;s dream.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;As Daniel came in, who was named Belteshazzar after the name of my god, and in whom is the spirit of the holy gods, I told him the dream...&rdquo; (Daniel 4:8).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:33:20', '2025-01-03 01:33:20'),
(424, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:12: &ldquo;...in order that &lsquo;they may indeed look, but not perceive, and may indeed listen, but not understand; so that they may not turn again and be forgiven.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why couldn&rsquo;t the people of Israel see during Isaiah&rsquo;s time?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus quoted Isaiah 6:9-10 when speaking to His disciples, referencing the spiritual condition of Israel before the Babylonian exile.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Make the heart of this people calloused; make their ears dull and close their eyes, lest they see with their eyes, hear with their ears, and understand with their hearts, and turn and be healed\" (Isaiah 6:10).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This blindness occurred before the punishment of the exile, showing how some might regret disregarding God\'s word later.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:33:53', '2025-01-03 01:33:53'),
(425, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:21: &ldquo;He said to them, &lsquo;Is a lamp brought in to be put under the bushel basket, or under the bed, and not on the lampstand?&rsquo;&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the hidden lamp?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The lamp was sometimes hidden under a bushel called a \"modios,\" a measuring basket for grain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This basket measured about 8.75 litres (1 peck).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:34:31', '2025-01-03 01:34:31'),
(426, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:25: &ldquo;For to those who have, more will be given; and from those who have nothing, even what they have will be taken away.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why take from one who has nothing?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There was a common saying among the Jews: \"The Jews have little to lose, and the Romans much.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\'\'We Jewish people have nothing else to lose and the bigger a Roman soldier is the further he has to fall.\'\'</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus presents a divine logic here, contrary to human reasoning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:35:16', '2025-01-03 01:35:16'),
(427, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:27: &ldquo;...and would sleep and rise night and day, and the seed would sprout and grow, he does not know how.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Do you wake up first or go to sleep first?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition the day begins at 6 p.m. \"And there was evening, and there was morning, the second day\" (Genesis 1:8).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus sleeping first and then waking follows the natural order of creation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:35:58', '2025-01-03 01:35:58'),
(428, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:27: &ldquo;...and the seed would sprout and grow, he does not know how.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is it enough for the farmer to stand idle?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The phrase \"sleep and rise\" in Hebrew signifies waiting patiently.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After sowing the seed the farmer waits for the growth, trusting in God\'s timing and blessings.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:36:32', '2025-01-03 01:36:32'),
(429, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:38: &ldquo;But he was in the stern, asleep on the cushion; and they woke him up and said to him, &lsquo;Teacher, do you not care that we are perishing?&rsquo;&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the cushion Jesus used?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In 1986 a first-century boat was discovered at Qibbuz Kinnosar near the Sea of Galilee.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This boat was 26 feet long and 8 feet wide, with a large stern where nets and other items were stored.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sandbags were sometimes used as anchors, and it is possible they served as a cushion for Jesus to rest on.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:37:04', '2025-01-03 01:37:04'),
(430, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 4:38: &ldquo;But he was in the stern, asleep on the cushion; and they woke him up and said to him, &lsquo;Teacher, do you not care that we are perishing?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the disciples call Jesus \"Teacher\" when the boat was sinking?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 35, '<p dir=\"ltr\">When the boat began to sink, the disciples called Jesus \"Episthala.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The word Episthala translates to \'Commander\' or \'Chief.\'&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was commonly used to refer to the helmsman of a boat.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By calling Jesus Episthala (teacher), they were pleading with Him to take control of the boat.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:37:35', '2025-01-03 01:37:35'),
(431, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 5:6: &ldquo;When he saw Jesus from a distance, he ran and bowed down before him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How is Jesus\' act of casting out demons generally described?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 36, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There are six key events that occur in the miracles where Jesus casts out demons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The demon-possessed person encounters Jesus.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The miserable condition of the possessed is described.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The demon-possessed recognises Jesus\' power.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jesus rebukes the demon.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The demon departs from the person.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Onlookers marvel at the event.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 01:38:56', '2025-01-03 01:38:56'),
(440, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 5:7: &ldquo;And he shouted at the top of his voice, &lsquo;What have you to do with me, Jesus, Son of the Most High God? I adjure you by God, do not torment me.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the demons swear in God\'s name and plead with Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 36, '<p dir=\"ltr\">All demonic powers become powerless in the presence of Jesus.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">That is why the demons, when they encounter Jesus, resort to swearing by God and begging Him for mercy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 23:44:04', '2025-01-03 23:44:04'),
(441, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 5:8: &ldquo;For he had said to him, &lsquo;Come out of the man, you unclean spirit!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the unclean spirit leave at the command of Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 36, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, by the word of Jesus the unclean spirit was expelled.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus also trained His disciples to cast out demons using His name.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By instructing them to say, \"Come out, you unclean spirit,\" they learned that demons would obey in the name of Jesus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The disciples later exercised this authority in their ministries (Acts 16:18, 9:40, 32, 35, 3:6).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 23:45:19', '2025-01-03 23:45:19'),
(442, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 5:9: &ldquo;Then Jesus asked him, &lsquo;What is your name?&rsquo; He replied, &lsquo;My name is Legion, for we are many.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the demon-possessed individual called \"legion\"?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 36, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A legion refers to a unit of 6,000 Roman soldiers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This demon-possessed man was a Gentile from the region of Gadara, a land where the people maintained favourable relations with Roman authority.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Instead of giving his name the possessed man identified with a familiar group&mdash;the Roman legion.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 23:46:50', '2025-01-03 23:46:50'),
(443, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 5:12: &ldquo;And the unclean spirits begged him, &lsquo;Send us into the swine; let us enter them.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were the demons sent into the herd of swine?</em></p>', 2, 36, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Pigs were sacrificial animals for the Greek gods Zeus, Athena and Dionysius.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The symbol of a legion (a unit of 6,000 Roman soldiers) was also a wild boar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This act demonstrated Christ&rsquo;s superiority over pagan kings and gods.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">It also fulfilled the prophecy of Isaiah 65:1-7:&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;They sit in tombs, and spend the night in secret places; they eat swine\'s flesh, with the broth of abominable things in their vessels&rdquo; (Isaiah 65:4).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 23:50:57', '2025-01-03 23:50:57'),
(444, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 5:13: &ldquo;He gave them permission. And the unclean spirits came out and entered the swine; and the herd, numbering about two thousand, rushed down the steep bank into the sea and were drowned in the sea.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did demons enter the pigs?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 36, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus used this incident as an example of exorcism.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Demons desire to inhabit any physical body, which is why they begged Jesus to allow them to enter the pigs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 23:52:06', '2025-01-03 23:52:06'),
(445, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 5:25: &ldquo;Now there was a woman who had been suffering from haemorrhages for twelve years.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were people with bleeding disorders shunned from society?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 36, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Leviticus 15:25 bleeding was considered an impurity called \"Zab&ocirc;t.\" Anyone who touched blood was deemed defiled because blood symbolised life and contact with it was seen as impure.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There was also a belief that the affliction of bleeding in women was tied to Eve\'s sin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 23:53:22', '2025-01-03 23:53:22'),
(446, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 5:38: &ldquo;When they came to the house of the synagogue\'s leader, he saw a commotion, people weeping and wailing loudly.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How many days of mourning were there for the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 36, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Typically Jewish mourning lasted seven days (1 Samuel 31:13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, for certain individuals, it could extend longer&mdash;30 days for Moses (Numbers 20:29), 77 days for Jacob in Egypt (Genesis 50:3, 10) and even three years for Amnon.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 23:54:24', '2025-01-03 23:54:24'),
(447, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 5:41: &ldquo;He took her by the hand and said to her, &lsquo;Talitha cum,&rsquo; which means, &lsquo;Little girl, get up!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the Aramaic phrase &lsquo;Talitha Cum&rsquo; added?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 36, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus often spoke in Aramaic, a language that was common in His time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some of the words He used became popular in Greek-speaking regions, and His words carried a unique power.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Aramaic phrases used by Jesus in the Gospel were preserved because they evoke a sense of authority.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 23:57:25', '2025-01-03 23:57:25'),
(448, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the Jews begin to speak Aramaic?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 36, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Aramaic, a Semitic language, developed between the 11th and 8th centuries B.C.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By the 6th century B.C. it became the official language of Assyria and Babylonia, and later Persia.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews adopted Aramaic during the Babylonian exile.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, books like Daniel and Ezra, written after the exile, were composed in Aramaic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus&rsquo; time the common language mixed Aramaic and Hebrew.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-03 23:58:21', '2025-01-03 23:58:21'),
(449, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:3: &ldquo;Is not this the carpenter, the son of Mary and brother of James and Joses and Judas and Simon, and are not his sisters here with us?&rdquo; And they took offence at him.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the carpenter\'s work only woodwork?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus was referred to as the \"son of Tekton,\" which translates to carpenter.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While Joseph, His earthly father, was likely a carpenter, the role of a \"Tekton\" also involved other aspects of construction.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:00:06', '2025-01-04 00:00:06'),
(450, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:7: \"He called the twelve and began to send them out two by two and gave them authority over the unclean spirits.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus send out the disciples two by two?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">We don&rsquo;t see teachers sending out pairs like this in the Old Testament.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in Jewish courts a testimony was only considered valid if it was supported by two witnesses (Deuteronomy 17:6).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, when official representatives were sent to foreign nations they were often sent in pairs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus may have adopted this method to ensure His disciples would not grow weary while spreading the gospel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:05:35', '2025-01-04 00:05:35'),
(451, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:9: \"He told them to wear sandals and not to put on two tunics.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were the sandals of the Jews like?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The sandals, known as &sigma;&alpha;&nu;&delta;&alpha;&lambda;&iota;&alpha;, were commonly worn by the average person.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These simple sandals had thick leather soles and were secured to the feet with straps (thongs).<br><br>Although more expensive sandals that covered the tops of the feet existed, simplicity was a key characteristic of Jesus\' disciples.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:06:28', '2025-01-04 00:06:28'),
(452, '<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Mark 6:11: \"If any place will not welcome you, and they refuse to hear you, as you leave, shake off the dust that is on your feet as a testimony against them.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews practise shaking off the dust?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, when Jews returned from Gentile lands they would shake the dust off their feet as a testimony against those lands.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Any dust clinging to their feet from the Gentile regions had to be brushed away to symbolise a break from those places.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:07:22', '2025-01-04 00:07:22'),
(453, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:17: \"For Herod himself had sent men who arrested John, bound him, and put him in prison on account of Herodias, his brother Philip&rsquo;s wife, because Herod had married her.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Was Herodias Herod\'s sister-in-law?</em></p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This union caused controversy especially because John the Baptist openly condemned Herod for marrying his brother&rsquo;s wife.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, Herodias was originally the wife of Herod&rsquo;s half-brother Philip.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod the Great ruled during Jesus\' birth and had four wives:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mariamne I, 2. Mariamne II, 3. Malthace, and 4. Cleopatra.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Philip was the son of Herod the Great and Mariamne I. Later, Herod Antipas the son of Malthace married Herodias, who had previously been married to his half-brother Philip.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXeiv7ZcE2SdkofJ6qEQgCblb4pbcD4jOvR0-MRf-UL3n8nQUWmgOW9wzKRNPQTj2QEYt3Wqh1dMtZXo75Hc5ZNWDEarTSaH4zEDojpKg88mnck6vPBRRmJMD1sh71DUUNzg9bm4xvZigBZ2wN-M0gD6QCjO?key=EGYgbpsCnlKmfZ1GTETMNQ\" width=\"570\" height=\"281\"></p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:09:15', '2025-01-04 00:09:15'),
(454, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:18: \"For John had been telling Herod, &lsquo;It is not lawful for you to have your brother&rsquo;s wife.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Herod Antipas married before Herodias?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, Herod Antipas was previously married to the daughter of Aretas IV, the Nabataean king.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He later divorced her to marry Herodias, the wife of his half-brother Philip, which led to John\'s public rebuke.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:10:07', '2025-01-04 00:10:07'),
(455, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:45: &ldquo;Immediately he made his disciples get into the boat and go on ahead to Bethsaida, while he dismissed the crowd.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What made Bethsaida an important city?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Bethsaida was located where the Jordan River meets the Sea of Galilee.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was a significant settlement area with many homes and businesses on both sides of the river.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The town&rsquo;s strategic location made it an important hub at that time as it had a thriving fishing industry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:11:11', '2025-01-04 00:11:11'),
(456, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:45: &ldquo;Immediately he made his disciples get into the boat and go on ahead to Bethsaida, to the other side, while he dismissed the crowd.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Bethsaida a city?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, from the Gospel we know that Peter, Andrew and Philip were from Bethsaida (John 1:44, 12:21).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The city of Bethsaida was built by King Philip Herod who renamed it Julias after the daughter of Augustus Caesar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name &lsquo;Bethsaida&rsquo; means &lsquo;house of fishing&rsquo; in Hebrew, indicating that it was primarily a fishing town.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:12:24', '2025-01-04 00:12:24'),
(457, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:48: &ldquo;When he saw that they were straining at the oars against an adverse wind, he came towards them early in the morning, walking on the sea. He intended to pass them by.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was it a miracle that Jesus calmed the sea?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition both Moses and Joshua parted the sea by the power of God (Exodus 14:16, 27; Joshua 3:14-19).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Only God was believed to have control over the sea.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, a false messiah named Theudas claimed he could control the sea but failed (Josephus, Antiquities 20.97).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus calming the sea was seen as a manifestation of His divine authority, affirming His identity as God incarnate.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:14:04', '2025-01-04 00:14:04'),
(458, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:48: &ldquo;When he saw that they were straining at the oars against an adverse wind, he came towards them early in the morning, walking on the sea. He intended to pass them by.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is it mentioned that Jesus intended to pass by His disciples?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, when God descended to earth, a Theophany (a divine manifestation) often involved the passing of God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, God said, &ldquo;I will make all my goodness pass before you&rdquo; (Exodus 33:19), and in 1 Kings 19:11, &ldquo;The Lord passed by.&rdquo; <br><br>Jesus walking on the sea and appearing to pass by His disciples echoes this divine motif, affirming His divinity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:16:48', '2025-01-04 00:16:48'),
(459, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:50: &ldquo;For they all saw him and were terrified. But immediately he spoke to them and said, &lsquo;Take heart, it is I; do not be afraid.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus tell His disciples to \'fear not\' at the sea?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, before God revealed His power, the people were often told not to fear (Exodus 14:13; 20:20; Zephaniah 3:16; Genesis 15:1; Joshua 8:1).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, before the parting of the Red Sea, God told the Israelites through Moses, \"Do not be afraid.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;These words were a precursor to divine manifestation (Theophany). Jesus likewise comforts His disciples with the same message, assuring them of His divine presence and control over every fear in life.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:18:11', '2025-01-04 00:18:11'),
(460, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:53: \"When they had crossed over, they came to land at Gennesaret and moored the boat.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did it get the name Gennesaret?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The name Gennesaret in Hebrew is \"Kinneret,\" derived from the word \"Kinnor,\" meaning harp. The lake was named this because of its harp-like shape.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:21:12', '2025-01-04 00:21:12'),
(461, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 6:53: \"When they had crossed over, they came to land at Gennesaret and moored the boat.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does the evangelist mean by \'crossing the sea\'?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 37, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The western side of the Sea of Galilee was Gentile territory, while the eastern side included Jewish lands, such as Galilee.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">West - Jews, East-Gentiles</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"crossing the sea\" refers to travelling between these two regions. The evangelist uses \"crossing\" as a metaphor for spiritual journey.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:22:08', '2025-01-04 00:22:08'),
(462, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:1: \"Now when the Pharisees and some of the scribes who had come from Jerusalem gathered around him.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Pharisees become dominant among the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">After John Hyrcanus, Alexander Jannaeus became the ruler of the Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He established Himself as king and high priest, but this was met with opposition.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many Jews disapproved because he was not a descendant of David and had married a foreign woman, Salome Alexandra, which was forbidden for priests (Leviticus 21:13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees, a group zealous for the Law (Hasidim), led the resistance against Jannaeus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Historical accounts suggest that Jannaeus killed about 800 Pharisees, which only intensified their influence over time.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:28:18', '2025-01-04 00:28:18'),
(463, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:2: \"They noticed that some of his disciples were eating with defiled hands, that is, without washing them.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did all Jews traditionally wash their hands before eating?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Old Testament contains laws about ritual cleanliness, but it is unclear whether hand washing before meals was a long-standing Jewish practice.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Evidence of stone vessels used for washing before meals has not been found before the 1st century BC, suggesting that this custom might have been relatively new.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is likely that the Pharisees strictly enforced this rule during Jesus\' time, even though it may not have had deep historical roots.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The law of handwashing before meals was more of a Pharisaic custom than a long-held tradition.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:30:56', '2025-01-04 00:30:56'),
(464, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:3: \"For the Pharisees, and all the Jews, do not eat unless they thoroughly wash their hands, thus observing the tradition of the elders.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Mark reject Jewish tradition?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Gospel of Mark was written around AD 65-70, during a time when both Jewish and Gentile Christians were present in the church.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A debate arose about whether Jewish purity laws (Leviticus 11) applied to Gentile Christians.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jerusalem Council of AD 48 had already ruled that these laws did not apply to Gentiles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark, writing after this decision, sought to refute Jewish tradition, particularly the strict adherence to these laws, in order to make it clear that they no longer bound Gentile believers.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark rejected these traditions to affirm the Council\'s ruling.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:32:51', '2025-01-04 00:32:51'),
(465, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why was handwashing associated with eating?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews considered eating a divine act, closely connected to prayer. Since food was part of worship it was important to maintain ritual purity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Washing one\'s hands before eating was thought to prevent the meal from being defiled and make it acceptable to God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why the Jews insisted on handwashing before eating&mdash;it was a matter of maintaining holiness, not just a superficial act of cleanliness.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:34:00', '2025-01-04 00:34:00'),
(466, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Does the Old Testament say to wash your hands before eating?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This is what the Old Testament teaches about cleansing through washing the hands:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"The priests shall wash their hands before entering the temple\" (Exodus 30:17-21).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"If you touch anything unclean, wash your hands\" (Leviticus 15:11).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"All the elders of the city nearest to the place where the dead body was found shall wash their hands (Deuteronomy 21:6)&rdquo;.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However the Old Testament does not directly command the washing of hands before every meal. This seems to have been a later tradition among the Israelites.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:34:46', '2025-01-04 00:34:46'),
(467, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:4: &ldquo;And they do not eat anything from the market unless they wash it; and there are also many other traditions that they observe, such as the washing of cups, pots, and bronze kettles.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Would the vessels have been defiled?</em></p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, these vessels would be considered impure if any unclean creature had touched them. The vessels would remain unclean until the evening, after which they could only be used again following immersion in water.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"If anything falls upon any object&mdash;whether it be a wooden vessel, garment, sack, or any other utensil&mdash;it shall be put into water, and it will remain unclean until evening. Then it shall be clean\" (Leviticus 11:32).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:36:46', '2025-01-04 00:36:46'),
(468, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:5: &ldquo;So the Pharisees and the scribes asked him, &lsquo;Why do your disciples not live according to the tradition of the elders, but eat with defiled hands?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Pharisees pay attention to Jesus\' disciples when they ate?</em></p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees, strict adherents to the Torah and its literal interpretation, carefully observed how people followed the traditions of cleanliness.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;They were teachers of the law, demonstrating these traditions publicly, which is why they took notice when Jesus\' disciples ate with unclean hands.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:39:47', '2025-01-04 00:39:47'),
(469, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the Pharisees have the right to criticise the disciples for how they ate?</em></p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Pharisees often held communion meals, known as \"Haburah,\" where they instructed others on how to purify themselves before eating.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;As such, they believed they had the right to demand others follow the same practices.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:41:45', '2025-01-04 00:41:45'),
(470, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:7: &ldquo;In vain do they worship me, teaching human precepts as doctrines.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where were the Jews taught the laws?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;</p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees were responsible for upholding and teaching the law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They strictly followed the rules and referred to themselves as \'am ha-aretz\' (People of the Land).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They were adept at learning existing rules and creating new ones.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There was even an organisation called Haberim, which later developed into two major centres of learning</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Beth Hillel, which took a more lenient approach.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Beth Shammai, which adhered to stricter interpretations.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:45:07', '2025-01-04 00:45:07'),
(471, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:11 \"But you say that it is sufficient for a man to say to his father or mother that what you will receive from me is a korban i.e. an offering\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is it sufficient to provide a \'korban\' instead of protecting parents?</em></p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"&Kappa;orban\" means \"a gift dedicated to God.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Jews used it to signify that they had dedicated their possessions to God, even to the extent that they could no longer use them to support their parents.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus criticised this practice as it allowed people to avoid their duty to care for their parents.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"The first commandment with a promise is to honour your father and your mother, so that your days may be long in the land that the Lord your God is giving you\" (Exodus 20:12).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:49:20', '2025-01-04 00:49:20'),
(472, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:26: &ldquo;Now the woman was a Gentile, of Syrophoenician origin. She begged him to cast the demon out of her daughter.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the Greek woman called Syrophoenician?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Romans had conquered Syria and made it a province where people from Phoenicia frequently traded.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"Syrophoenician\" refers to those who were the offspring of intermarriages between Phoenicians and Syrians.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:50:54', '2025-01-04 00:50:54'),
(473, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:31: &ldquo;Then he returned from the region of Tyre, and went by way of Sidon towards the Sea of Galilee, in the region of the Decapolis.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How were Jewish and Gentile lands separated in Galilee?</em></p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the region around the Sea of Galilee, Jewish lands were primarily on the western side, while Gentile lands extended along the eastern side.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sea of Galilee served as a natural boundary between these two regions.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:52:59', '2025-01-04 00:52:59');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(474, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:33: &ldquo;He took him aside in private, away from the crowd, and put his fingers into his ears, and he spat and touched his tongue.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus touch the deaf man\'s tongue with spit?</em></p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Here, Jesus is demonstrating an act of healing through an exorcism.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His touching of the man&rsquo;s tongue with spit symbolises the loosening of the tongue, enabling speech.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As the scripture says, &ldquo;And immediately his ears were opened, his tongue was released, and he spoke plainly&rdquo; (Mark 7:35).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This miracle represents not just physical healing but the spiritual act of freeing the man from what binds him. Jesus, filled with the Holy Spirit, uses spit as a sign of casting out the devil.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:54:46', '2025-01-04 00:54:46'),
(475, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the evangelist write that Jesus put his finger in the deaf man\'s ear?</em></p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Throughout the Gospel of Mark, Jesus physically touches individuals. He often heals by physically touching the person in need of healing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The evangelist highlights these gestures to show the intimate closeness between Jesus and the one He heals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, in Mark 8:23, Jesus spits in the eyes of a blind man, and in Mark 5:41, He takes the hand of a girl and raises her up.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These actions emphasise that there is no need for fear when one is near Jesus.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:57:04', '2025-01-04 00:57:04'),
(476, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 7:34: \"Then looking up to heaven, he sighed and said to him, \'Ephphatha,\' that is, \'Be opened.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is the word \"Ephphatha\" mentioned in the Gospel?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 38, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Although the Gospels were written in Greek, the evangelists chose to retain certain Aramaic words spoken by Jesus due to their impact.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Ephphatha\" is one of these powerful words. It was retained as it had a deep meaning.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 00:58:26', '2025-01-04 00:58:26'),
(477, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 8:8: \"They ate and were filled; and they took up the broken pieces left over, seven baskets full.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is 7 a perfect number for the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The number 7 symbolised completeness and divine perfection for the Jewish people. Moses, for example, waited on Mount Sinai for six days, and on the seventh day, God gave him the Ten Commandments.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"The glory of the Lord settled on Mount Sinai, and the cloud covered it for six days; on the seventh day, he called to Moses out of the cloud\" (Exodus 24:16).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is how the number seven came to represent the fullness of God\'s gift to the Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:00:09', '2025-01-04 01:00:09'),
(478, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>In what kind of baskets were the remaining pieces of bread collected?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The pieces of bread were gathered in a type of basket called \"Spuris,\" which is made from cane.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These baskets were used for carrying provisions from the market.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:01:46', '2025-01-04 01:01:46'),
(479, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 8:10: \"And immediately he got into the boat with his disciples and went to the district of Dalmanutha.\"</strong><br><em>Which region is known as Dalmanutha</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Dalmanutha is a region on the western side of the Sea of Galilee., mentioned&nbsp; with Jesus\' travels.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Dalmanutha\" translates to \"adjacent to place,\"&nbsp; (d&icirc; (which) + l&ecirc; (belonging to)+ m&eacute;natah (territory)). It is close to the region of Magdala.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:05:13', '2025-01-04 01:05:13'),
(480, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 8:11: \"The Pharisees came and began to argue with him, asking him for a sign from heaven, to test him.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Pharisees ask for a sign to test Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Deuteronomy outlined how to discern whether a prophet was truly from God (Deuteronomy 18:18-22).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to this law, if a prophet\'s words did not come true, the prophet was not speaking for the Lord and could be disregarded, even punished.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"If a prophet speaks in the name of the Lord but the thing does not take place or prove true, it is a word that the Lord has not spoken; the prophet has spoken it presumptuously\" (Deuteronomy 18:22).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A false prophet was subject to death (Deuteronomy 18:20).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Without a sign Jesus could be easily labelled as a false prophet and condemned. This is why the Pharisees demanded a sign from Him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:07:08', '2025-01-04 01:07:08'),
(481, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 8:15: \"And he cautioned them, saying, \'Watch out&mdash;beware of the yeast of the Pharisees and the yeast of Herod.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the leaven used in the bread?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time people did not know about the microorganisms (zyme) that comprise yeast.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Instead, sourdough was traditionally prepared each week, except during the Feast of Unleavened Bread when all leavened bread was removed from homes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The \"yeast\" Jesus mentioned refers to a harmful influence that should be avoided, much like certain types of leaven that can spread and cause lasting harm.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:08:06', '2025-01-04 01:08:06'),
(482, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 8:15 &ldquo;He cautioned them, saying, &lsquo;Watch out&mdash;beware of the yeast of the Pharisees and the yeast of Herod.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the &ldquo;yeast of the Pharisees&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In those days, &ldquo;yeast&rdquo; had several spiritual meanings:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Unbelief (R.A. Guelich)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Pride and Arrogance (Hans Bayer)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">False hope that they could overcome Roman rule by their own means (H.W. Hoehner),&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Failure to see that Jesus was the Messiah (James R. Edwards)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The false teachings of the Pharisees</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">All of these can be considered the leaven of the Pharisees.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These are what Jesus called the &ldquo;yeast of the Pharisees&rdquo; because, like yeast, they grow and spread in the hearts of those affected.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:09:05', '2025-01-04 01:09:05'),
(483, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 8:23 &ldquo;He took the blind man by the hand and led him out of the village; and when he had put saliva on his eyes and laid his hands on him, he asked him, &lsquo;Can you see anything?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does Mark mention that Jesus used mud to heal the blind man?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Following Emperor Nero&rsquo;s death, Rome experienced political upheaval, as short-lived rulers like Galba, Otho and Vitellius briefly held power before Vespasian, once a general in Egypt, became Emperor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Vespasian claimed divine status as the &ldquo;son of God&rdquo; and asserted he could heal, even using mud to treat a blind man.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark contrasts Jesus&rsquo; healing of the blind man with earthly rulers who claimed divinity and healing powers, emphasising that Jesus alone has the true power to heal.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:10:16', '2025-01-04 01:10:16'),
(484, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 8:24 &ldquo;And the man looked up and said, &lsquo;I can see people, but they look like trees, walking.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the blind man see people as trees?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish understanding, blindness had two levels:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Optical Blindness: Blindness caused by damage to the eyes.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Cognitive Blindness: The inability to interpret or understand what one sees.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When the blind man was partially healed, he could see people but without clear perception they appeared as indistinct shapes such as trees. Christ fully restored his sight, healing both optical and cognitive blindness</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:11:23', '2025-01-04 01:11:23'),
(485, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 8:31 &ldquo;Then he began to teach them that the Son of Man must undergo great suffering, and be rejected by the elders, the chief priests, and the scribes, and be killed, and after three days rise again.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus foretell His suffering?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Roman culture held that a man&rsquo;s death reflected his life:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Socrates died courageously.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Nero, in disgrace, took his own life.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Augustus Caesar died peacefully.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus foreshadowed His own suffering and death, defying this cultural misconception. He wanted His followers to understand that suffering can have a divine purpose and can unite believers to Him.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:12:19', '2025-01-04 01:12:19'),
(486, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was crucifixion a Jewish form of punishment?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish Hasmonean King Alexander Janneus reportedly crucified 800 Pharisees in 60 B.C. (Josephus, Antiquities 13-380,3). But his successor, King Herod did not follow this method.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, crucifixion was a common punishment throughout all the Roman provinces.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:13:41', '2025-01-04 01:13:41'),
(487, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 8:33 &ldquo;But turning and looking at his disciples, he rebuked Peter and said, &lsquo;Get behind me, Satan! For you are setting your mind not on divine things but on human things.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus call Peter a stumbling block?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 2, 39, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus had named Peter &ldquo;Cephas&rdquo; (meaning &ldquo;rock&rdquo;), a word that also implies a &ldquo;stone of stumbling.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Here, Jesus highlighted that Peter&rsquo;s thinking was a barrier to divine purpose.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 01:19:08', '2025-01-04 01:19:08'),
(488, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:2: &ldquo;Six days later, Jesus took with him Peter and James and John, and led them up a high mountain apart, by themselves. And he was transfigured before them.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is it said that Jesus transfigured on Mount Tabor?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Six days after preaching in Caesarea Philippi Jesus ascended a mountain to be transfigured.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It took approximately six days from Caesarea Philippi to reach Mount Tabor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mount Tabor stands taller (at approximately 2,826 metres) than other mountains in the surrounding region</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:26:22', '2025-01-04 02:26:22'),
(489, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:4: &ldquo;And there appeared to them Elijah with Moses, who were talking with Jesus.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Elijah and Moses have in common?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Both Moses and Elijah encountered God on a mountain&mdash;Moses on Mount Sinai and Elijah on Mount Horeb (1 Kings 19).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They each fasted for 40 days and 40 nights (Exodus 24:18; 1 Kings 19:8) and were blessed enough to directly witness God&rsquo;s glory.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:26:54', '2025-01-04 02:26:54'),
(490, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:5: &ldquo;Then Peter said to Jesus, &lsquo;Rabbi, it is good for us to be here; let us make three dwellings, one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does the word &ldquo;Rabbi&rdquo; mean?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hebrew term rabbi translates to &ldquo;my great one&rdquo; (rab meaning &ldquo;great one&rdquo; and i -mine indicating possession).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Aramaic language Jesus spoke, it was also used as &ldquo;rabbuni.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish religious teachers are still known as rabbis</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:27:27', '2025-01-04 02:27:27'),
(491, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:17: &ldquo;Someone from the crowd answered him, &lsquo;Teacher, I brought you my son; he has a spirit that makes him unable to speak.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the spirit that possessed the child a &ldquo;dumb&rdquo; spirit?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, some demonic spirits were believed to cause speech impairments in humans and were referred to as &ldquo;dumb spirits.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Such spirits were thought to be more challenging to exorcise since they would not communicate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This belief explains why the disciples struggled to drive out this particular demon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, it&rsquo;s important to note that all demonic forces were ultimately defeated through Jesus&rsquo; sacrifice on the cross.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:27:56', '2025-01-04 02:27:56'),
(492, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:24: <sup class=\"versenum\">&nbsp;</sup>Immediately the father of the child cried out,&ldquo;I believe; help my unbelief!&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the father of the demon-possessed child plead with Jesus for healing?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Demon-possessed individuals often don&rsquo;t acknowledge or believe in Jesus&rsquo; power so others would intercede and pray for their healing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, the father of the possessed child in Matthew 9:23-24 and the Syrophoenician woman in Matthew 15:28 both pleaded for their children.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:29:39', '2025-01-04 02:29:39'),
(493, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:22: &ldquo;It has often cast him into the fire and into the water, to destroy him; but if you are able to do anything, have pity on us and help us.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was it possible for the demon-possessed to fall into the fire?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p>Yes it was possible. Traditional ovens used for cooking, especially baking bread, were often placed outside and left uncovered, creating a risk for the demon-possessed to fall in.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:30:20', '2025-01-04 02:30:20'),
(494, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:25: &ldquo;When Jesus saw that a crowd came running together, he rebuked the unclean spirit, saying to it, &lsquo;You spirit that keeps this boy from speaking and hearing, I command you, come out of him, and never enter him again!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews consider demonic possession a defilement?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Possessed individuals displayed behaviours distinctly different from others.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;As noted, &ldquo;Whenever it seizes him, it dashes him down; and he foams and grinds his teeth and becomes rigid. I asked your disciples to cast it out but they could not (Mark 9:18)&rdquo;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Such impure manifestations often led to impure actions; for instance, the demon-possessed man at Gadara was compelled to live among the graves (Matthew 8:28).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why the Jews regarded demonic figures as inherently unclean.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:31:03', '2025-01-04 02:31:03'),
(495, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:29: &ldquo;He said to them, &lsquo;This kind can come out only through prayer.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What types of demons are cast out only through prayer?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek term genos is used here to denote a specific class or type of demon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;This kind&rdquo; is thought to represent all demonic forces in general.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus reminds us that authority alone is insufficient; we must depend on prayer to engage in the ministry of casting out demons.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:33:23', '2025-01-04 02:33:23'),
(496, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:31: &ldquo;For he was teaching his disciples, saying to them, &lsquo;The Son of Man is to be betrayed into human hands, and they will kill him, and three days after being killed, he will rise again.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is it said that Jesus would be &ldquo;betrayed into human hands&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In that era, the &ldquo;hand&rdquo; symbolised the power to act.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As illustrated: &ldquo;It is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God&rdquo; (Hebrews 10:31).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, Jesus explained that He would be delivered into human hands to signify His submission to human power and authority.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:34:00', '2025-01-04 02:34:00'),
(497, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:33: &ldquo;Then they came to Capernaum; and when he was in the house he asked them, &lsquo;What were you arguing about on the way?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the disciples argue on the road?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The era was marked by significant social inequality; wealth, land and power were concentrated among a select few, leading to frequent disputes over societal status.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Such competition infiltrated the disciples&rsquo; discussions because they were influenced by these social pressures as well.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:34:37', '2025-01-04 02:34:37'),
(498, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:36: &ldquo;Then he took a little child and put it among them; and taking it in his arms, he said to them&hellip;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were children considered a symbol for innocence?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, children symbolises innocence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Moreover, in the Mediterranean world, they represented those without legal rights or status. Children could not claim inheritance rights until reaching maturity.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:35:13', '2025-01-04 02:35:13'),
(499, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:37: &ldquo;Whoever welcomes one such child in my name welcomes me, and whoever welcomes me welcomes not me but the one who sent me.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why adopt a child in Jesus&rsquo;s name?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Just as the disciples cast out demons in Jesus&rsquo;s name, we are called to welcome others, not based on their size or stature but because of Jesus&rsquo;s name.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is not the disciples\' smallness or humility that compels demons to leave but rather the power of Jesus\'s name.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:35:43', '2025-01-04 02:35:43'),
(500, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:38: &ldquo;John said to him, &lsquo;Teacher, we saw someone casting out demons in your name, and we tried to stop him because he was not following us.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was John jealous?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John&rsquo;s response reflects jealousy, as he sought to prevent someone from working miracles in Jesus&rsquo;s name.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This mirrors the Old Testament jealousy of Joshua, who asked Moses to stop Eldad and Medad from prophesying in the Tabernacle (Numbers 11:24-30).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Moses responded by advising Joshua to guard his heart against jealousy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus responded in a similar manner as He is the &lsquo;Moses&rsquo; of the New Testament.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:36:29', '2025-01-04 02:36:29'),
(501, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Have others cast out demons in Jesus&rsquo;s name?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In a short time, Jesus became widely known as an exorcist.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Jewish community some also claimed the ability to cast out demons, such as the sons of Sceva, who attempted exorcisms using Jesus\'s Name (Acts 19:11-22).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Acts describes these seven sons of Sceva, a Jewish high priest, using Jesus&rsquo;s name in an attempt to exorcise.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:36:55', '2025-01-04 02:36:55'),
(502, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:41: &ldquo;For truly I tell you, whoever gives you a cup of water to drink because you bear the name of Christ will by no means lose the reward.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Jesus acquire the name &ldquo;Christ&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, the awaited saviour was called the &ldquo;Messiah,&rdquo; which means &ldquo;the Anointed One&rdquo; in Hebrew (<img src=\"https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXeZbrvK5OQzhraRxa1CGE-IGnnmNIUkmvTGvatz1lQmkyfpI-eyHm8CqmJG1TuZSgOXahI2iLtiqsLNRXT3qZWgftk6Ca3N--EsmDp9W_iJk3VK9L4mvdYFe4inj9N3cf_5037cZaoAFLcG7Vk4Zgt3ydOQ?key=EGYgbpsCnlKmfZ1GTETMNQ\" width=\"42\" height=\"19\">mashiyach).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek equivalent is &ldquo;Christos&rdquo; (&Chi;&rho;&iota;&sigma;&tau;ό&sigmaf;).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, Jesus was known as the Christ because He fulfilled the Jewish expectation of the Messiah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:38:35', '2025-01-04 02:38:35'),
(503, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:43: &ldquo;If your hand causes you to stumble, cut it off.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is Jesus advocating the literal removal of limbs for sin?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews practised sin offerings where men in the temple would kill animals to atone for people&rsquo;s sins.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus taught a higher path, suggesting that atonement is not through animal sacrifice.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He took on the role of the atoning lamb sacrificed to bear humanity&rsquo;s sins. Therefore, His statement about &ldquo;cutting off the hand&rdquo; is a metaphor for removing sinful practices instead of sacrificing animals or harming oneself.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:39:03', '2025-01-04 02:39:03'),
(504, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:44: &ldquo;It is better for you to enter life maimed than to have two hands and go to hell, to the unquenchable fire.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the name Gehenna come about?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Gehenna, or the Valley of Hinnom, is a valley to the west of Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The temple stood at the city&rsquo;s highest point, while Hinnom lay at its lowest. In ancient times, human sacrifices were reportedly conducted here (2 Kings 16:3) earning it the name &ldquo;valley of murder&rdquo; (Jeremiah 7:33).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Later, it became associated with divine judgement believed to be the place where God would cast out His enemies in the last days.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:39:36', '2025-01-04 02:39:36'),
(505, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:46: \"It is better for you to enter life lame than to have two feet and to be thrown into hell.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is Gehenna called Hell?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Gehenna, known as the Valley of Hinnom, is a valley west of Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;The Canaanites, who occupied the land before the Israelites, practised child sacrifice there to the Canaanite god Molech (2 Kings 23:10; Jeremiah 7:31, 32:35).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This horrific act led the Jews to regard this place as the gateway to hell, associating it with evil and divine punishment.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:40:15', '2025-01-04 02:40:15'),
(506, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 9:49: &ldquo;For everyone will be salted with fire.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does Jesus mean by &ldquo;salted with fire&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish tradition held that the salt of Sodom and Gomorrah was created through fire.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;\"The Lord rained down fire and brimstone on Sodom and Gomorrah from heaven, destroying those cities, the entire valley, and all inhabitants, along with the vegetation\" (Genesis 19:24-26).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Lot\'s wife looked back, she was turned into a pillar of salt. This extremely hard salt is believed to be &ldquo;salt hardened by fire.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:40:49', '2025-01-04 02:40:49'),
(507, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What do we use salt ignited with fire for?</em></p>', 2, 40, '<ol>\r\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Before sacrifice, salt was sprinkled on the body of the sacrificial animal.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&ldquo;Salted with fire&rdquo; was a Hebrew expression, referring to the act of destroying a place by salting it.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In ancient times sprinkling salt over a ruined city symbolised its complete destruction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, \"Abimelech fought against the city all day, killed its inhabitants, and then razed it, scattering salt over it\" (Judges 9:45).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:41:23', '2025-01-04 02:41:23'),
(508, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What does it mean to be enveloped in fire?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 40, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Jerusalem temple, sacrificial animals were salted before being offered to ensure complete blood drainage and readiness for consumption.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As the Talmud notes, \"Salt must be rubbed on the sacrificial animal to make it fit for sacrifice.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This highlights the intense severity of Gehenna\'s fire in its purifying nature.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 02:41:51', '2025-01-04 02:41:51'),
(509, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:2: \"Some Pharisees came, and to test him they asked, \'Is it lawful for a man to divorce his wife?\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was Jesus\'s answer to the Pharisees about divorce?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus responded to the Pharisees with three key points regarding divorce:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Pharisees\' hearts were hardened, leading them to misuse the law (10:5).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Divorce is not permissible for arbitrary reasons (10:9).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">God instituted the law of marriage before the Jewish law (10:6).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:30:49', '2025-01-04 03:30:49'),
(510, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:9: &ldquo;Therefore what God has joined together, let no one separate.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say, &ldquo;God joined man in marriage&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Deuteronomy 24:1-4, Moses allowed for divorce but Jesus reminded the people of God\'s original intent.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Before the law in Deuteronomy, God united man and woman in the sacred bond of marriage (Genesis 2:18-25).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus underscored that God&rsquo;s law of marriage is higher than the provision for divorce given later by Moses.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:31:20', '2025-01-04 03:31:20'),
(511, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:13: \"People were bringing little children to him in order that he might touch them; and the disciples spoke sternly to them.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>At what age were children not regarded as adults?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Boys are permitted to begin Torah study in the synagogue at age of 13.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">At this age, a boy is considered a \'Bar Mitzvah\' (Son of the Commandment), signifying his responsibility to follow the law as an adult.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Children under 12 were not yet regarded as adults.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:31:53', '2025-01-04 03:31:53'),
(512, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why were children brought to Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish tradition holds that rabbis would bless children the day after <br>the Day of Atonement.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To this day, Jews bless boys with the phrase, \"May God make you like Ephraim and Manasseh,\" and girls with \"May God make you like Sarah, Rebecca, Rachel and Leah.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Parents brought their children to Jesus so that they could receive this blessing.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:32:25', '2025-01-04 03:32:25'),
(513, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:16: \"And he took them up in his arms, laid his hands on them, and blessed them.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Israelites see themselves as children?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, the Israelites referred to themselves as \'Bene Israel\' (Sons of Israel), which reflects a view of God as a Father in three key ways.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">God as the creator of the people of Israel.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">God as the protector who met all their needs.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">God as the father with the right to discipline and guide them.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:32:58', '2025-01-04 03:32:58'),
(514, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:19: \"You know the commandments: &lsquo;You shall not murder; You shall not commit adultery; You shall not steal; You shall not bear false witness; You shall not defraud; Honour your father and mother.&rsquo;&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was &ldquo;Do not defraud&rdquo; part of the precepts?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">While &ldquo;Do not defraud&rdquo; is not one of the Ten Commandments, it was an important moral principle during Jesus&rsquo;s time.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In fact, the prophet Malachi speaks of God\'s judgement against fraud saying, &ldquo;I will be quick to testify against those who defraud labourers of their wages, who oppress the widows and the fatherless, and deprive foreigners among you of justice, but do not fear me&rdquo; (Malachi 3:5).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:33:27', '2025-01-04 03:33:27'),
(515, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus tell the rich man not to defraud?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In addition to the Ten Commandments, Jesus instructed the wealthy man not to defraud others, possibly because at the time wealth was often amassed at the expense of the poor who were affected by heavy taxation and economic hardship. Jesus&rsquo; command could have been an appeal to resist unjust exploitation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:33:58', '2025-01-04 03:33:58'),
(516, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:22: \"When he heard this, he was shocked and went away grieving, for he had many possessions.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was it difficult for the rich man to give up his wealth?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">For both Jews and Romans wealth granted influence in society and politics.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many would even pay to attain such positions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, giving up wealth was not only a loss of material comfort but also a sacrifice of potential status and power.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:35:02', '2025-01-04 03:35:02'),
(517, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:25: &ldquo;It is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for someone who is rich to enter the kingdom of God.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus use the metaphor of the needle&rsquo;s eye?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jesus\' time, the needle&rsquo;s eye represented the smallest opening known to the Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus used this example as a vivid image, asking if a camel&mdash;the largest animal familiar to them&mdash;could possibly pass through it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This statement reflects how difficult it is for wealthy people to release their possessions, a challenge more difficult than acquiring them.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:35:38', '2025-01-04 03:35:38'),
(518, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:30: &ldquo;Who will not receive a hundredfold now in this age&mdash;houses, brothers and sisters, mothers and children, and fields, with persecutions&mdash;and in the age to come, eternal life.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus include \"fields\" among the rewards?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod Antipas who ruled Galilee during Jesus\' time, built two cities&mdash;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sepphoris&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Tiberias&mdash;to honour Caesar</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These elaborate constructions required substantial land and money.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;To acquire this, Herod forcibly took fields from the people, imposing hardship upon them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus Jesus includes \"fields\" in the promise of a hundredfold reward, symbolising restoration for what the faithful have lost in this life.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:37:07', '2025-01-04 03:37:07'),
(519, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:33: &ldquo;See, we are going up to Jerusalem, and the Son of Man will be handed over to the chief priests and the scribes.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say they were \"going up\" to Jerusalem?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">For Jews, pilgrimage to Jerusalem was a sacred tradition undertaken three times yearly.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As a city on a hill, standing 2,500 feet above sea level, those journeying from the plains of Galilee naturally referred to it as &ldquo;going up to Jerusalem&rdquo; (Matthew 5:14).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Every step toward Jerusalem symbolised a spiritual ascent and commitment to God.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:37:40', '2025-01-04 03:37:40'),
(520, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:37: &ldquo;They said to him, &lsquo;Grant us to sit, one at your right hand and one at your left, in your glory.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the sons of Zebedee request special positions?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Jewish Sanhedrin, the council members who sat to the left and right of the high priest held positions of influence.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Moreover, the sons of Zebedee came from a family with means, having boats, nets and servants: &ldquo;Immediately he called them; and they left their father Zebedee in the boat with the hired men, and followed him&rdquo; (Mark 1:20).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These factors gave them a natural devotion to Jesus and motivated their request for privileged positions in His kingdom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:38:23', '2025-01-04 03:38:23'),
(521, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:38: &ldquo;But Jesus said to them, &lsquo;You do not know what you are asking. Are you able to drink the cup that I drink, or be baptised with the baptism that I am baptised with?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Does the \"cup\" signify endurance?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, the &ldquo;cup&rdquo; symbolically denotes endurance and trial. In the Scriptures, the cup often represents divine judgement or destiny, as seen in Isaiah 51:22: &ldquo;See, I have taken from your hand the cup of staggering; you shall drink no more from the bowl of my wrath.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, Jeremiah 49:12 states: &ldquo;If those who do not deserve to drink the cup must drink it, will you go unpunished? You shall not go unpunished.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Thus, every &ldquo;cup&rdquo; given is with divine intention and purpose.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:39:03', '2025-01-04 03:39:03'),
(522, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did baptism become a symbol of endurance?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, rising water represented danger.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example: &ldquo;Deep calls too deep at the thunder of your cataracts; all your waves and your billows have gone over me&rdquo; (Psalm 42:7).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And, &ldquo;Or darkness so that you cannot see; a flood of water covers you&rdquo; (Job 22:11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The &ldquo;baptism&rdquo; might have symbolised endurance, signifying strength against such perilous waters.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:39:34', '2025-01-04 03:39:34'),
(523, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:39: &ldquo;They replied, &lsquo;We are able.&rsquo; Then Jesus said to them, &lsquo;The cup that I drink you will drink, and with the baptism with which I am baptised, you will be baptised.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the sons of Zebedee respond so quickly, &ldquo;We are able&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">They understood Jesus&rsquo; &ldquo;cup&rdquo; to symbolise a temple-related ritual or deed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even in the face of death the Jewish people maintained their religious traditions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An example is the Maccabean Revolt (167-160 B.C.), when thousands of Jews died resisting King Antiochus IV&rsquo;s ban on sacrifices in the Jerusalem temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thinking Jesus&rsquo; words related to a religious act, the sons of Zebedee quickly affirmed, &ldquo;We are able.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:40:08', '2025-01-04 03:40:08'),
(524, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:42: &ldquo;So Jesus called them and said to them, &lsquo;You know that among the Gentiles those whom they recognise as their rulers lord it over them, and their great ones are tyrants over them.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How was the role of a chieftain obtained?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In society, those with economic resources often rose to prominence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many secured high positions through financial influence, building infrastructure in their towns at personal expense to gain authority.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:40:40', '2025-01-04 03:40:40'),
(525, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:45: &ldquo;For the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life a ransom for many.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is &ldquo;ransom&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek term for ransom (&lambda;ύ&tau;&rho;&omicron;&nu; &ndash; &ldquo;ransom&rdquo;) refers to the price paid for someone&rsquo;s release.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In that era, there were three types of ransoms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The redemption of slaves.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The liberation of prisoners of war.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The rescue of captives.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Maccabean period, this concept also extended to refer to those who sacrificed their lives for their faith.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:41:13', '2025-01-04 03:41:13'),
(526, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Why did the Jews pay ransoms?</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish people were familiar with various forms of ransom or lutron.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Ransoms for the release of captives.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Ransoms to retrieve property during the Jubilee (Leviticus 25:21-52).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Compensation for harm caused by an ox (Exodus 21:30).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A ransom paid by a woman caught in adultery to her husband (Proverbs 6:35).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Ransoms for reclaiming belongings of deceased relatives.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:41:41', '2025-01-04 03:41:41'),
(527, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Should the ransom be offered to the temple?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites were instructed to redeem certain items and individuals by offering to the Lord.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This included redeeming men, animals and firstborn sons with a payment of five silver coins. &ldquo;They shall be redeemed when they are one month old; you shall pay five shekels of silver&rdquo; (Numbers 18:16).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Unclean animals could be redeemed if desired. For instance, &ldquo;If a donkey colt is to be redeemed, a lamb shall be given as a ransom&rdquo; (Exodus 13:13).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:42:09', '2025-01-04 03:42:09'),
(528, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:46: \"They came to Jericho. As he and his disciples and a large crowd were leaving Jericho, Bartimaeus son of Timaeus, a blind beggar, was sitting by the roadside\".</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Bartimaeus not Jewish?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The name Bartimaeus, derived from the Greek word &Beta;&alpha;&rho;&tau;&iota;&mu;&alpha;ῖ&omicron;&sigmaf; may appear Hellenistic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, &ldquo;Bartimaeus&rdquo; combines the Aramaic &ldquo;Bar&rdquo; (son of) and the Greek &ldquo;Timaios,&rdquo; indicating that his father\'s name was likely Timaeus &Tau;&iota;&mu;&alpha;ῖ&omicron;&sigmaf;, a Greek version of a Hebrew name.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus had other disciples with Greek names such as Andrew and Philip.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:42:41', '2025-01-04 03:42:41'),
(529, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Bartimaeus choose Jericho to beg?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jericho was a major city rebuilt by the Romans, with one of the main roads of Palestine passing through it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Roman tax collectors like Zacchaeus frequented the city., and pilgrims on their way to Jerusalem passed through Jericho.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bartimaeus likely chose this location to beg from the many pilgrims passing by.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:43:13', '2025-01-04 03:43:13'),
(530, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why does Jesus heal one blind man in Mark\'s Gospel but two in Matthew\'s Gospel?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark\'s account may be more concise, while Matthew wrote with a Jewish-Christian audience in mind, which required greater detail.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish law the testimony of two witnesses was needed to confirm an event (e.g., the conflicting testimonies during Jesus&rsquo; trial).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew may have included two witnesses for greater credibility to meet this requirement.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:43:41', '2025-01-04 03:43:41'),
(531, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:50: &ldquo;So throwing off his cloak, he sprang up and came to Jesus&rdquo; .</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Bartimaeus throw away his cloak?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Mark&rsquo;s Gospel, those who respond to Jesus&rsquo; call often leave behind their former livelihoods.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Examples include&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Peter who left his fishing nets.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Matthew who abandoned his tax booth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For Bartimaeus, a poor beggar, his cloak was likely his sole possession and a means of gathering alms as he would have spread it on the road to collect offerings.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Do not keep the clothes he has pledged for the night. And thou shalt take it back when the sun goeth down, that he may renew his garment\" (Deuteronomy 24:12-13)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Like those who followed Jesus, Bartimaeus left behind his sole possession, symbolising his commitment to a new life in Christ.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:44:31', '2025-01-04 03:44:31'),
(532, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 10:51: &ldquo;Then Jesus said to him, &lsquo;What do you want me to do for you?&rsquo; The blind man said to him, &lsquo;My teacher, let me see again.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the difference between &ldquo;Rabbi&rdquo; and &ldquo;Rabbuni&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 2, 41, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hebrew word Rabbi means &ldquo;My Teacher&rdquo; or &ldquo;My Lord.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In areas where Aramaic was spoken, however, an Aramaic suffix was added, giving the term &ldquo;Rabbuni&rdquo; (Rabb meaning &ldquo;Lord&rdquo; + oun as the Aramaic suffix + i for &ldquo;mine&rdquo;).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Both terms convey a deep sense of reverence, expressing &ldquo;my Teacher&rdquo; or &ldquo;my Lord.&rdquo;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:45:10', '2025-01-04 03:45:10'),
(533, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 11:1: &ldquo;When they were approaching Jerusalem, at Bethphage and Bethany, near the Mount of Olives, he sent two of his disciples.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were Bethphage and Bethany neighbouring areas?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Bethany was a village about two miles from Jerusalem on the Jericho road. Bethphage, on the other hand, was a smaller settlement on the slope leading from Bethany to Jerusalem on the Mount of Olives.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:46:15', '2025-01-04 03:46:15');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(534, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus begin his pilgrimage from Bethphage?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Bethphage, on the eastern slope of the Mount of Olives, was significant in rabbinical literature.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Texts such as the Babylonian Talmud considered it a sacred boundary to Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This may explain why Jesus began his triumphant procession from Bethphage.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:46:42', '2025-01-04 03:46:42'),
(535, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 11:2: &ldquo;...as you enter it, you will find tied there a colt that has never been ridden; untie it and bring it.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus ask for a colt that was never ridden?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Animals dedicated to sacred purposes, especially those related to the Jerusalem Temple, were reserved exclusively for holy use.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance the Ark of the Covenant was transported using a newly made cart with milch cows that had never been yoked (1 Samuel 6:7).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Unused animals were kept&nbsp; aside for sacred purposes, such as ritual purification.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:47:30', '2025-01-04 03:47:30'),
(536, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>From what age were donkeys used as vehicles?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Donkeys were given similar training to horses, starting from about six months of age.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, they were only used as riding animals after reaching about two years.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jerusalem, certain donkeys were even reserved exclusively for temple use.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:48:12', '2025-01-04 03:48:12'),
(537, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 11:13: &ldquo;Seeing in the distance a fig tree in leaf, he went to see whether he would find anything on it. When he came to it, he found nothing but leaves, for it was not the season for figs.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does the unfruitful fig tree symbolise?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">After cleansing the Jerusalem temple, Jesus saw the fig tree barren of fruit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This act may symbolise His judgment upon the corrupted temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The unfruitful fig tree serves as a symbol of the spiritually barren temple.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:49:02', '2025-01-04 03:49:02'),
(538, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 11:14: \"He said, &lsquo;May no one ever eat fruit from you again!&rsquo; And his disciples heard it.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where was the fig tree that Jesus cursed located?</em></p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus encountered the fig tree while journeying from Bethany to Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bethany was a village situated on the slope of the Mount of Olives.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The only geographical feature between Jerusalem and Bethany is the Mount of Olives.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the fig tree that Jesus cursed must have been located on the Mount of Olives.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:49:30', '2025-01-04 03:49:30'),
(539, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was Jesus cursing the fig tree a sign?</em></p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In the Old Testament, prophets provided signs before the impending destruction of Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, during the invasion of Judah by King Sargon II of Assyria in 711 B.C., God instructed Isaiah to walk naked for three years as a sign (Isaiah 20:3).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, the Babylonians defeated Egypt at Carchemish in 605 B.C., and Jeremiah was commanded to hide his belt by the Euphrates River as a sign of imminent destruction (Jeremiah 13:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus the cursing of the fig tree can also be interpreted as a sign foreshadowing the destruction of Jerusalem in A.D. 70.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:50:13', '2025-01-04 03:50:13'),
(540, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 11:16: \"And he would not allow anyone to carry anything through the temple.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who had the authority to make decisions regarding the Temple in Jerusalem?</em></p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The daily operations of the Jerusalem temple were overseen by the Sanhedrin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, any alterations to the temple\'s proceedings required their approval. In cleansing the temple, Jesus was asserting that His authority is superior to that of the Sanhedrin.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:50:35', '2025-01-04 03:50:35'),
(541, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 11:17: \"And he taught them, &lsquo;Is it not written, My house shall be called a house of prayer for all nations? But you have made it a den of robbers.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>In which part of the Jerusalem temple was trade conducted?</em></p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 30 Caiaphas, the high priest, relocated the trading activities from the Valley of Olives to the Temple in Jerusalem, a move that faced opposition from many in the Sanhedrin.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This trade took place in the Gentiles&rsquo; Court of the Temple of Jerusalem, which was a space for prayer, not commerce.<strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:51:48', '2025-01-04 03:51:48'),
(542, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 11:20: \"As they passed by in the morning, they saw the fig tree withered away to its roots.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were they familiar with the withered fig tree?</em></p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The prophet Ezekiel referred to Zedekiah, the king of Judah, as a dry vine: \"Thus says the Lord God: Shall it prosper? Shall he not pull up its roots and cut off its branches? Shall not its shoots be scorched? It will not take great power or many people to uproot it\" (Ezekiel 17:9).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In 597 B.C. King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon conquered Judea and enslaved King Zedekiah, who subsequently sought aid from Egypt to escape Babylonian captivity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Understanding this context, the prophet Ezekiel\'s metaphor of Zedekiah as a dry vine becomes evident.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:52:28', '2025-01-04 03:52:45'),
(543, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 11:21: \"Peter said to him, &lsquo;Rabbi, look! The fig tree that you cursed has withered.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus curse the fig tree?</em></p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"kateraso\" is used to describe Jesus\' act of cursing the fig tree.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, the word implies &lsquo;prayer with miraculous power&rsquo; rather than a conventional curse.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hence, the focus here is not on the nature of the curse itself but rather on Jesus\' miraculous authority.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mark 11:23: \"Truly I say to you, whoever says to this mountain, \'Be taken up and thrown into the sea,\' and does not doubt in his heart, but believes that what he says will come to pass, it will be done for him.\"</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Which mountain did Jesus say would fall into the sea?</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are two significant mountains on the road to Jerusalem:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Mount of Olives</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Temple Mount</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These two mountains were present before Jesus as he spoke of the immense power of faith.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:53:10', '2025-01-04 03:53:10'),
(544, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 11:28: \"And they asked him, \'By what authority are you doing these things? Who gave you this authority to do them?\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why do the Jews ask Jesus two questions about authority?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 42, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Hebrew, the word ras&uacute;t is used for authority, encompassing two dimensions:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Power within oneself</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Supernatural power</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>They posed two questions because ras&uacute;t embodies these two facets.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:53:59', '2025-01-04 03:53:59'),
(545, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:7: \"But the tenants said to one another, \'This is the heir; come, let us kill him, and the inheritance will be ours.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Does the land belong to the cultivators if the master is gone?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Neither Roman nor Jewish law granted ownership of farmland to farmers in the absence of the master.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even upon the master\'s death, the cultivators would not acquire ownership of the agricultural land.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This parable illustrates the folly of the tenants.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:55:21', '2025-01-04 03:55:21'),
(546, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:10: \"Have you not read this scripture? \'The stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were cornerstones important in the Old Testament?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Zerubbabel laid the final stone, known as the akrogonaisos (cornerstone), of the temple built after the Babylonian exile.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Zechariah 4:7 states, \"What are you, great mountain? Before Zerubbabel you shall become a plain; and he shall bring out the top stone amid shouts of \'Grace, grace to it!\'\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The cornerstone is also referred to as the Stone of Testing in Isaiah: \"Therefore, thus says the Lord God: Behold, I am laying in Zion a stone, a tested stone, a precious cornerstone, a sure foundation; whoever believes will not be in haste\" (Isaiah 28:16).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These references show that the cornerstone is foundational to the Law.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:56:19', '2025-01-04 03:56:19'),
(547, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:13: \"And they sent to him some of the Pharisees and some of the Herodians to trap him in his talk.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Herodians come to question Jesus about paying taxes?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">As their name indicates, the Herodians were supporters of King Herod, having accepted Herod Antipas\'s rule under Roman governance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, they had no qualms about paying taxes to Rome.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why they enlisted Herod\'s partisans to inquire about taxation.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:57:09', '2025-01-04 03:57:09'),
(548, '<p><em>Why did Herod\'s followers ask Jesus about paying taxes to Caesar?</em></p>', 2, 43, '<p>The Herodians were those who recognised the descendants of &lsquo;Herod the Great&rsquo; as the rightful kings of Israel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They regarded Herod Antipas as their saviour and accepted Roman rule; thus, they were prepared to pay taxes to Caesar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Herodians were adversaries of the Zealots because they accepted Rome\'s authority (Josephus, J.W. 4.139-41).</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:57:46', '2025-01-04 03:57:46'),
(549, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:14: \"And they came and said to him, \'Teacher, we know that you are true and teach the way of God in accordance with the truth, and show deference to no one; for you do not regard people with partiality. Is it lawful to pay taxes to the emperor, or not?\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What tax did the Jews inquire about regarding Caesar?</em></p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 6 Caesar imposed a head tax known as the Kenos in Judea, Samaria and Idumaea.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This tax was instituted to signify that these regions were under Roman control.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews contended that only God had the right to conduct a census of the people of Israel.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;A revolt against this tax, led by Judas of Galilee, was swiftly suppressed by Roman forces.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus they were inquiring specifically about this Kenos (Census) tax.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:58:35', '2025-01-04 03:58:35'),
(550, '<p><em><strong>&nbsp;</strong>What caused the dispute about paying taxes to Caesar?</em></p>', 2, 43, '<p>In A.D. 6 Caesar enacted the Kenos, or Census Tax, in Judea, Samaria and Idumaea.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees supported this tax as they were willing to pay it to maintain peace with the Roman authorities.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, the Zealots contended that only God was entitled to hold the Jews accountable for such taxation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This divergence of opinion led to disputes regarding the obligation to pay taxes to Caesar.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 03:59:26', '2025-01-04 03:59:26'),
(551, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did paying taxes become a problem?</em></p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Judea fell under Roman control in 63 B.C. and was elevated to provincial status in A.D. 6.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During this period Quirinius, the governor of Judea, conducted a census and revised the tax structure. This tax collection served as a reminder to the Jews of their subjugation to Rome.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A subsequent revolt led by Judas was suppressed by the Roman army (Acts 5:37).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since then, the issue of paying taxes has remained contentious in Judea.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:00:02', '2025-01-04 04:00:02'),
(552, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:18: \"Then the Sadducees, who say there is no resurrection, came to him and asked him a question.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is known about the Sadducees?</em></p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sadducees were the dominant priestly class during the Maccabean period, primarily associated with the Jerusalem Temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Following the destruction of the Temple in A.D. 70 they gradually diminished in prominence and influence.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:00:46', '2025-01-04 04:00:46'),
(553, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:18: &ldquo;Then the Sadducees, who say there is no resurrection, came to him and asked him a question.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Sadducees come to Jesus by themselves?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees and Herodians approached Jesus with the intent to test him (Mark 12:13).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, the Sadducees, who denied the existence of both resurrection and angels, approached Jesus to seek validation for their beliefs.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:01:20', '2025-01-04 04:01:20'),
(554, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:21: &ldquo;The second took her, and he died childless. Then the third did the same.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Should the dead brother\'s wife have been accepted?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Law of Moses, a deceased brother\'s wife should indeed be accepted (Genesis 38:8; Deuteronomy 25:5).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice was known as Levirate Marriage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, an individual could choose to waive their right to marry their brother\'s widow through a process called ḥalitzah (Deuteronomy 25:7-10). \"Boaz acquired Ruth by this law\" (Ruth 4).</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:02:07', '2025-01-04 04:02:07'),
(555, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:25: &ldquo;For when they rise from the dead, they neither marry nor are given in marriage, but are like angels in heaven.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were the Sadducees told that the dead will be like angels in heaven?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sadducees&rsquo; disbelief in both resurrection and angels necessitated Jesus&rsquo; assertion regarding the existence of angels.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By stating that the dead will be like angels in heaven, Jesus was addressing their misconceptions while affirming the reality of the resurrection.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:02:47', '2025-01-04 04:02:47'),
(556, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:29: &ldquo;Jesus answered, &lsquo;The first is, &ldquo;Hear, O Israel: The Lord our God, the Lord is one.&rdquo;&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus answer the lawyer by saying \'Hear, Israel\'?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There are three key declarations from God that the Jews were to remember: Deuteronomy 6:4-9, 11:13-21 and Numbers 15:37-41.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Each begins with \"Shema Yisrael\" (\"Hear, O Israel\"). Collectively these verses formed the Shema, a foundational creed recited twice daily by Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is the creed that Jesus was conveying to the lawyer.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:03:17', '2025-01-04 04:03:17'),
(557, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:31: &ldquo;The second is this: &lsquo;You shall love your neighbour as yourself.&rsquo; There is no other commandment greater than these.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was Israel\'s neighbour?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites adhered to a Holiness Code that dictated, \"Say to the congregation of Israel, &lsquo;You shall be holy, for I the Lord your God am holy&rsquo;\" (Leviticus 19:2).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This Holiness Code defined everyone, including strangers, as a neighbour. It instructs, &ldquo;Do not pick up the fruit that has fallen. Leave it for the poor and the stranger&rdquo; (Leviticus 19:10).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For the Israelites, the notion of neighbour often evoked the image of strangers lacking their own land, reflecting on their history as sojourners in Egypt.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:03:54', '2025-01-04 04:03:54'),
(558, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 12:40: &ldquo;They devour widows\' houses and for the sake of appearance say long prayers. They will receive the greater condemnation.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the scribes devour the widows\' houses?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 43, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, God places special emphasis on the care of widows (Exodus 22:22; Deuteronomy 10:18; Psalm 68:5; Isaiah 1:17).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although the exact means by which the jurists consumed the widows\' houses remains uncertain, some possible explanations include:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">High fees may have been charged for legal protection afforded to widows.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">They may have deceived widows into appointing them as stewards of their estates.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Certain taxes and debts may have resulted in the scribes acquiring ownership of the widows\' properties.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:04:25', '2025-01-04 04:04:25'),
(559, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 13:2: &ldquo;Jesus said to him, &lsquo;Do you see these great buildings? Not one stone will be left here upon another; all will be thrown down.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How does&nbsp; Mark remember that Jesus predicted the fall of the Jerusalem temple?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 44, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark composed his Gospel prior to the destruction of the Temple in Jerusalem in A.D. 70.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Flavius Josephus recounts that in A.D. 62 a man named Jesus, the son of Ananias, spoke against the Jerusalem Temple and was subsequently handed over to Albinus, the Roman procurator, and executed.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the prophesied downfall of the Jerusalem Temple must have been a pressing concern during Mark\'s time.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:07:24', '2025-01-04 04:07:24'),
(560, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 13:3: &ldquo;When he was sitting on the Mount of Olives opposite the temple, Peter, James, John, and Andrew asked him privately.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus teach about Jerusalem on the Mount of Olives?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 44, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Ezekiel\'s prophecy, God\'s glory departed from Jerusalem and stood on the Mount to the east.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in Ezekiel 11:23, &ldquo;And the glory of the Lord went up from the midst of the city and stood on the mountain on the east side of the city.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;The Mount of Olives, located east of Jerusalem, is where Jesus, as the embodiment of God&rsquo;s glory, chose to teach about the city.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:08:03', '2025-01-04 04:08:03'),
(561, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 13:14: &ldquo;But when you see the desolating sacrilege set up where it ought not to be, let the reader understand, then those in Judea must flee to the mountains.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the unholy desolating sacrilege?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 44, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus delivered this message from the Mount of Olives, facing the Temple in Jerusalem, making the prophecy specifically relevant to it. Historical references include:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Antiochus IV (Epiphanes), the governor of Syria, who in 168 B.C. set up a pagan idol within the Jerusalem Temple (1 Maccabees 1:54).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In A.D. 37-41, Emperor Caligula sought to erect a statue of himself in the Temple, demanding worship.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These events served as unholy signs of destruction for the Jewish people.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:08:44', '2025-01-04 04:08:44'),
(562, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>To which mountain should they flee?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 44, '<p dir=\"ltr\">By A.D. 40 tensions between the Israelites and the Romans had escalated to a breaking point.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The counsel given to Judeo-Christians was to vacate Jerusalem and seek refuge in the mountainous region of Perea should the Romans launch an attack.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Perea was the designated place of safety.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:09:14', '2025-01-04 04:09:14'),
(563, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 13:28: &ldquo;From the fig tree learn its lesson: as soon as its branch becomes tender and puts forth its leaves, you know that summer is near.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How could the fig tree know that summer was approaching?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 44, '<p dir=\"ltr\">People used the fig tree as a natural calendar in that era.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The fig tree sprouts new leaves in April and May and becomes lush and laden with fruit by June.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Farmers commonly relied on the fig tree\'s cycles to determine the optimal time for sowing seeds.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:09:53', '2025-01-04 04:09:53'),
(564, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 13:30: \"Truly I tell you, this generation will not pass away until all these things have taken place.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is referred to as &ldquo;this generation&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 44, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Commentary 1: The fall of the Jerusalem Temple in A.D. 70 is prophesied to occur within this generation.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Commentary 2: The term genos (generation) refers to the Jewish race. The Jewish race will endure until all these events transpire.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Commentary 3: This generation is understood to be the one that witnesses all the signs of the end times. Therefore the generation that observes all these signs will be the last.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:10:17', '2025-01-04 04:10:17'),
(565, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 14:1: \"It was two days before the Passover and the Feast of Unleavened Bread, and the chief priests and the scribes were looking for a way to put Jesus to death, for they said, \'Not during the festival, or there may be a riot among the people.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Are the day of&nbsp; Passover and the Feast of Unleavened Bread the same day?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 45, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Passover was celebrated on the fourteenth day of Nisan (Exodus 12:6-20).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Feast of Unleavened Bread commenced on the fifteenth day and continued until the twenty-first day of Nisan (Exodus 12:15-20; Deuteronomy 16:18).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These two feasts were often collectively referred to as days of&nbsp; Passover, encompassing a period known as Feast days.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:12:03', '2025-01-04 04:12:03'),
(566, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 14:8: \"She has done what she could; she has anointed my body beforehand for burial.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is Mark\'s account of the anointing by the sinful woman significant?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 45, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark\'s Gospel presents the anointing of the sinful woman in conjunction with the institution of the Holy Eucharist.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The practice among Jews involved anointing the body with perfumed oils after death, signifying honour and respect to the dead body.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this act, the sinful woman offered incense to the body of Jesus prior to His death, symbolising her recognition of His impending sacrifice.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:12:38', '2025-01-04 04:12:38'),
(567, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 14:22: \"While they were eating, he took a loaf of bread, and after blessing it, he broke it and gave it to them, saying, \'Take; this is my body.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus cut the bread with a knife?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 45, '<p dir=\"ltr\">For the Jews, eating was a religious act, and they typically broke bread by hand rather than cutting it with a knife.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was customary to break bread rather than slice it, which is why Jesus broke the bread in this manner.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:13:12', '2025-01-04 04:13:12'),
(568, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was bread important to the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 45, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews regarded bread as holy, transcending mere sustenance. They saw it as a profound gift from God and held it in great reverence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They would never lie down in front of bread, acknowledging its sacredness.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:13:45', '2025-01-04 04:13:45'),
(569, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 14:22: &ldquo;While they were eating, Jesus took bread, blessed it, broke it, and gave it to them, saying, &lsquo;Take; this is my body.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is unleavened bread used in the Qurbana?</em></p>', 2, 45, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Gospels record that Jesus took bread (artos).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Traditionally this is considered unleavened (azumos) bread. However, since the first century leavened bread has been used for Qurbana.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By the seventh century A.D., the Western Church began to adopt unleavened bread, while most Eastern churches continued using leavened bread.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Council of Florence in 1439 sanctioned the use of leavened bread by Eastern churches, whereas Western churches are not permitted to use leavened bread for the Eucharist (Catechism of the Catholic Church, 926).</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:14:22', '2025-01-04 04:14:22'),
(570, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 14:30: &ldquo;Jesus said to him, &lsquo;Truly I tell you, this day, this very night, before the rooster crows twice, you will deny me three times.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the rooster crow that day?</em></p>', 2, 45, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \'crowing\' refers to the early morning hours.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Before the priest went to prepare the altar, a trumpet sounded, which Josephus described as &lsquo;crowing Time&rsquo; (Josephus, War, 4.582). The word Alektor denotes a rooster and is typically male.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The expression &lsquo;cock crow&rsquo; likely refers to this trumpet.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Given that fowl were considered impure, they were unlikely to be found in the holy city (b. Baba Kamma 82b).</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:15:04', '2025-01-04 04:15:04'),
(571, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 14:34: &ldquo;He said to them, &lsquo;My soul is deeply grieved, even to death; remain here and keep watch.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus pray that His soul would be sorrowful unto death?</em></p>', 2, 45, '<p>This Psalm that Jesus prayed in Gethsemane echoes Psalm 55:4: &ldquo;My heart is in anguish; the terrors of death have fallen upon me.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This Psalm reflects the betrayal experienced by David from Ahithophel, his confidant, who conspired against him with David&rsquo;s son, Absalom (2 Samuel 15).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus, facing betrayal from one of His own disciples, echoed the same prayer.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:15:51', '2025-01-04 04:15:51'),
(572, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 14:36: &ldquo;He said, &lsquo;Abba, Father, all things are possible for you; remove this cup from me; yet, not what I will, but what you will.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus call his suffering a cup?</em></p>', 2, 45, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus&rsquo; reference to His suffering as a cup draws from Psalm 116, in which the Psalmist prays, &ldquo;I called on the name of the Lord; O Lord, I pray, save my life! I will lift up the cup of salvation and call on the name of the Lord&rdquo; (Psalms 116:4-13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hillel Psalms, known to be recited during the Jewish Passover, encompass Psalms 113 through 118.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By calling His suffering a cup, Jesus signifies that the Old Testament Passover is fulfilled in Him.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:16:43', '2025-01-04 04:18:15'),
(573, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 14:41: &ldquo;He came a third time and said to them, &lsquo;Are you still sleeping and resting? Enough! The hour has come; the Son of Man is betrayed into the hands of sinners.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>At what time was Jesus imprisoned?</em></p>', 2, 45, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greeks divided the night into four watches: 6-9, 9-12, 12-3 and 3-6.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Gospel of Mark, significant events of Jesus\' Passion transpire during each watch.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The first watch (6-9) covers the Last Supper.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The second watch (9-12) involves Jesus praying in Gethsemane and His subsequent arrest.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The third watch (12-3) details Peter&rsquo;s denial of Jesus.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The fourth watch (3-6) recounts Pilate&rsquo;s trial of Jesus.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:17:21', '2025-01-04 04:17:21'),
(574, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 14:64: &ldquo;You have heard his blasphemy! What is your decision?&rdquo; All of them condemned him as deserving death.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were the Jews allowed to carry out the death penalty for blasphemy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 45, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sanhedrin served as the supreme court of the Jews, possessing the authority to impose the death penalty through four methods: stoning, burning, beheading and strangulation (Mishnah, Sanhedrin 7:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Stoning was the prescribed penalty for serious blasphemy (Mishnah, Sanhedrin 7:4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in Judea the Roman Emperor had stripped the Jews of their right to carry out executions directly.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:17:51', '2025-01-04 04:17:51'),
(575, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 15:2: &ldquo;Pilate asked him, &lsquo;Are you the King of the Jews?&rsquo; He answered, &lsquo;You say so.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Jesus respond to Pilate\'s question regarding His kingship?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 46, '<p dir=\"ltr\">As the Roman prefect, Pilate was expected to understand the language of the territory he governed.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus language was a significant barrier for him. <br><br>Jesus\' response in Aramaic should be interpreted as \"at amarat,\" which translates to \"You are saying this\" or \"That is what you say.\"</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:20:51', '2025-01-04 04:20:51'),
(576, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 15:15: &ldquo;So Pilate, wishing to satisfy the crowd, released Barabbas for them; and after flogging Jesus, he handed him over to be crucified.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Jesus whipped?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 46, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Under Roman law (Pax Romana) a person condemned to crucifixion was to be beaten on the back with a whip prior to being nailed to the cross.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was to prevent the condemned from resting their back on the cross, which would relieve muscle tension in their arms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, the flogging aimed to ensure that the weight of the body hung entirely on the arms, resulting in shortness of breath.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:21:24', '2025-01-04 04:21:24'),
(577, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 15:16: &ldquo;The soldiers led him into the courtyard of the palace (that is, the praetorium); and they called together the whole cohort.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Pilate\'s praetorium considered a palace?</em></p>', 2, 46, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The praetorium was the official residence of the Roman governor during his stay in Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;It was located within the Antonia Fortress, a structure built by Herod.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The large room(&alpha;&upsilon;&lambda;&eta;), designed to accommodate a thousand seats, functioned as the official venue for the Roman governor\'s activities.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:22:03', '2025-01-04 04:22:03'),
(578, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 15:19: &ldquo;They struck his head with a reed, spat upon him, and knelt down in homage to him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is ironic about the soldiers kneeling before Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 46, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The soldiers kneeling before Jesus (proskuneo) is profoundly ironic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Roman emperors were regarded as deities, and subjects were expected to kneel and prostrate themselves, touching the ground with their hands or foreheads.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The soldiers\' act of prostration before Jesus was done to mock Him rather than pay true homage.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:22:33', '2025-01-04 04:22:33'),
(579, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 15:23: &ldquo;Then they offered him wine mixed with myrrh; but he did not take it.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the wine mixed with myrrh offered?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 46, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Wine mixed with myrrh was known to alleviate physical pain and induce a state of intoxication, facilitating a quicker recovery.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus, aware of the impending threat of death and the agony He was to endure on the cross, declined the mixture.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus did not wish to overcome his pain with the wine mixed with myrrh.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:23:14', '2025-01-04 04:23:14'),
(580, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 15:25: \"It was the third hour when they crucified him.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When was Jesus crucified?</em></p>', 2, 46, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark adhered to the Jewish chronology wherein the day commences at 6 a.m.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, John\'s account follows the Roman timeline, beginning at 12 a.m. Nonetheless both accounts converge on the same conclusion: Jesus was crucified at nine o\'clock in the morning.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:23:45', '2025-01-04 04:23:45'),
(581, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 15:35: \"And some of the bystanders heard it and said, &lsquo;Behold, he is calling Elijah.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When Jesus was on the cross and called out to God, why did those who witnessed it think he was calling Elijah?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 46, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus referred to God using the term Elohi.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The pronunciation of Elijah sounds akin to \'Eliah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in the Aramaic dialect prevalent in Galilee, the vowel /a/ was sometimes pronounced as /o/.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, when Jesus called out to God, those nearby erroneously assumed he was invoking Elijah.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:24:17', '2025-01-04 04:24:17'),
(582, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 16:2: \"Early on the first day of the week, when the sun had risen, they went to the tomb.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the women go to Jesus\' tomb with spices?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 47, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews regarded it as a pious duty to ensure the proper burial of the deceased (Deut. 21:22-23).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice is also documented in the Qumran Scrolls, highlighting its significance during that time (11 Q 1964.10-11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The women visited the tomb in the morning to address any deficiencies in Jesus\' burial.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:25:33', '2025-01-04 04:25:33'),
(583, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 16:7: &ldquo;But go, tell his disciples and Peter: &lsquo;He is going ahead of you to Galilee; there you will see him, just as he told you.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Mary come to the tomb?</em></p>', 2, 47, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mark indicates that the purpose was to anoint Jesus\' body.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, John does not mention anointing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Given that Jerusalem is 700 feet above sea level, the cool April weather allows a dead body to remain uncorrupted for a day. Therefore it is likely that Mary came to the tomb intending to anoint Jesus\' body.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:26:08', '2025-01-04 04:26:08'),
(584, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the disciples flee to Galilee?</em></p>', 2, 47, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It is reasonable to assume that the disciples did not flee to Galilee following Jesus\' death.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mary Magdalene could locate Peter and John because they remained in Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus indicated that He would go to Galilee before the disciples (Mark 16:7), suggesting that the disciples were likely still in Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:26:40', '2025-01-04 04:26:40'),
(585, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 16:14: &ldquo;Afterward, as the eleven were at the table, he appeared to them, and he rebuked them for their unbelief and hardness of heart because they had not believed those who saw him after he had risen.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why didn\'t Mark write about Jesus\' resurrection in detail?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 47, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Gospel of Mark was composed between A.D. 60 and 70, during which many of the disciples were still alive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently there was no pressing need for further evidence regarding Jesus\'s resurrection, as the testimonies of those who had witnessed it first hand were readily available.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This context explains why Mark&rsquo;s account does not delve deeply into the details of the resurrection.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:27:20', '2025-01-04 04:27:20'),
(586, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 16:17: &ldquo;And these signs will accompany those who believe: by using my name they will cast out demons; they will speak in new tongues.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who all saw the risen Christ?</em></p>', 2, 47, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary Magdalene (John 20:14-16).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary and Joanna, the mother of the sons of Zebedee (Matthew 28:9).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Peter (1 Corinthians 15:5).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The disciples who went to Emmaus (Luke 24:13 f).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The disciples, except Thomas (John 20:19).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">All the disciples (John 20:26 f).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">500 people (1 Corinthians 15:6).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">James the Younger (1 Corinthians 15:7).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:27:54', '2025-01-04 04:27:54'),
(587, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 16:16: &ldquo;The one who believes and is baptised will be saved; but the one who does not believe will be condemned.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the baptism of the early Christians like?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 47, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Early Christians practised baptism by immersion.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This immersion, known as Mamodisa, typically took place in rivers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Small ponds were constructed to facilitate baptisms in locations where rivers were scarce.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From the outset, baptisms were administered in the name of the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit.</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:28:40', '2025-01-04 04:28:40'),
(588, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Mark 16:17: &ldquo;And these signs will accompany those who believe: by using my name they will cast out demons; they will speak in new tongues.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is exorcism necessary for evangelism?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 47, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Gospel of Mark Jesus performs exorcisms and healings on four distinct occasions (1:21-28; 5:1-20; 7:24-30; 9:14-29).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The evangelist highlights that Jesus cast out demons numerous times as evidenced in various passages (1:32-34; 3:9; 3:11-12).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This frequent emphasis on exorcism suggests its significant role in the broader context of evangelism.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-04 04:29:08', '2025-01-04 04:29:08'),
(589, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:14: \"And the Word became flesh and lived among us, and we have seen his glory, the glory as of a father\'s only son, full of grace and truth.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the Israelites understand when John said, \"The Word became flesh and dwelt among us\"?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \'dwelt\' can be understood in the sense of \'tented.\'</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">God\'s glory (Shekinah) once tabernacled over the Israelites during their time in the wilderness, as reflected in Exodus 40:34-35: \"Then a cloud covered the tabernacle, and the glory of the Lord filled the tabernacle.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, when John proclaimed \"The Word became flesh and dwelt among us,\" the imagery that came to mind for his audience was the glory of God that filled the Jerusalem temple.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:16:43', '2025-01-06 01:16:43'),
(590, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:17: \"The law indeed was given through Moses; grace and truth came through Jesus Christ.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which of the laws did the Jews think Jesus broke?</em></p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Gospel of John, Jesus is accused by the Jews of being a lawbreaker. Their accusations are as follows:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He broke the Sabbath (John 5:16).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He called God His Father (John 10:31-36).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He misled the people (John 7:12).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He caused rebellion in the country (John 11:47-50).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He asked His followers to drink blood (John 6:53-56).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He proclaimed teachings without formal training in the law (John 7:14-15).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews detested Jesus because He appeared to be a lawbreaker, which was especially troubling for them as they held the laws of Moses in high regard.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:17:40', '2025-01-06 01:17:40'),
(591, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:18: \"No one has ever seen God. It is God the only Son, who is close to the Father\'s heart, who has made him known.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was it difficult to establish that Jesus was the Son of God?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In 44 B.C. the Roman Emperor Julius Caesar was assassinated, yet members of the Senate posthumously deified him, declaring him a god within the Roman Pantheon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many believed they witnessed his ascension to heaven (as noted by Suetonius in Deified Augustus 100:4; LCL 1:283-285).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Augustus Caesar, his successor, claimed to be the \'Son of God,\' and he became widely known as such.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, establishing Jesus as the Son of God was fraught with challenges, given the political and cultural context of the time.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:18:30', '2025-01-06 01:18:30'),
(592, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:28: \"This took place in Bethany across the Jordan, where John was baptising.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did John baptise in Bethany?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John is said to baptised in Bethany, but this place is situated near Jerusalem and not in Galilee.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is likely that the evangelist referred to a location of Batanea (Bashan)in the region&nbsp; of&nbsp; Galilee.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:19:18', '2025-01-06 01:19:18');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(593, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:29: \"The next day he saw Jesus coming toward him and declared, \'Here is the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world!\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the lamb symbolise in the Old Testament?</em></p>', 5, 6, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Daily Sacrificial Lamb: A lamb was offered as a burnt offering in the Temple of Jerusalem every morning and evening.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Lamb of Atonement: On the Day of Atonement, a lamb was sent into the wilderness to atone for&nbsp; the sins of the Israelites (Leviticus 16:3).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Abraham\'s Lamb: The lamb sacrificed in place of Isaac at Mount Moriah.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Passover Lamb: The lamb saved the houses of Israel from destruction on the eve of the Exodus from Egypt (Exodus 12:5).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Lamb of Isaiah 53: The lamb that symbolised the suffering servant of the Jews.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:20:08', '2025-01-06 01:20:08'),
(594, '<p><em>Why did John call Jesus the &ldquo;Lamb of God&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">When Abraham took Isaac to be sacrificed, Isaac asked, \"Where is the sacrificial lamb?\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Abraham replied, \"God will provide for himself the lamb\" (Genesis 22:14).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The location of the Jerusalem Temple, where this sacrifice was foreshadowed, was also known as \"Yahweh Yireh,\" which means \"God will provide.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, calling Jesus the \"Lamb of God\" indicates His role as the ultimate sacrifice.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:20:45', '2025-01-06 01:20:45'),
(595, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:32: \"John testified, \'I saw the Spirit descending from heaven like a dove, and it remained on him.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is the dove used as a metaphor for the Holy Spirit?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In many cultures the dove (yonah) symbolises the soul. Noah\'s dove, which returned with an olive leaf (Genesis 8:11) signified new hope.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Doves were also offered as sin offerings in the Temple of Jerusalem (Leviticus 12:7).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Doves were also considered a symbol of purity (Psalm 51:7), the dove thus became an accepted representation of the Holy Spirit.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:21:21', '2025-01-06 01:21:21'),
(596, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:33: &ldquo;I did not know him, but he who sent me to baptise with water said to me, &lsquo;He on whom you see the Spirit descending and remaining is the one who baptises with the Holy Spirit.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews receive baptism (Tevilah - immersion)?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews practised baptism with water for three primary reasons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">For purification: For instance, if an individual becomes impure by touching a dead body they could only enter the Temple of Jerusalem after undergoing Tevilah.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">For conversion: A person wishing to join Judaism was required to receive water baptism.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">As a sign of repentance: The Jews were baptised as an expression of repentance before weddings and significant feasts.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:21:59', '2025-01-06 01:21:59'),
(597, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:42: &ldquo;He brought him to Jesus. Jesus looked at him and said, &lsquo;You are Simon son of John; you are to be called Cephas&rsquo; (which is translated Peter).&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Peter get so many names?</em></p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Peter was originally known as Simeon (or Simon), a name commonly found among Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus assigned him the name \'Kepa,\' which means \'rock\' in Aramaic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This name was subsequently translated into Greek as \'Petros.\'</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:22:36', '2025-01-06 01:22:36'),
(598, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:46: &ldquo;Nathanael said to him, &lsquo;Can anything good come out of Nazareth?&rsquo; Philip said to him, &lsquo;Come and see!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Nathanael assert that \"no good thing comes out of Nazareth\"?</em></p>', 5, 6, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The town of Nazareth is not mentioned in the Old Testament, leading Nathanael to believe that nothing noteworthy could emerge from it.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A rivalry may have existed between Cana and Nazareth, suggesting that Nathanael&rsquo;s remark was a colloquial saying of people of Cana (Nathanael was from cana as noted in John 21:2) against those of Nazareth.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:23:13', '2025-01-06 01:23:13'),
(599, '<p><em><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Is Nathanael the same as Bartholomew, the disciple of Christ?</em></p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Traditionally, Nathanael is believed to be the same individual as the disciple Bartholomew. This is supported by:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Philip consistently appears alongside Nathanael or Bartholomew in the Gospels.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Nathanael appears in the Gospel of John, whereas Bartholomew is mentioned in the synoptic Gospels&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, some scholars argue they are distinct individuals for these reasons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Nathanael is not listed among the twelve disciples.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The two names are never mentioned together in the same context.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:23:48', '2025-01-06 01:23:48'),
(600, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:47: &ldquo;When Jesus saw Nathanael coming towards him, he said of him, &lsquo;Here is truly an Israelite in whom there is no deceit!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Jesus mean when He asked Matthew to follow Him?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term &lsquo;Akolutheo&rsquo; is the word Jesus used to invite Matthew to follow Him. This word encompasses several meanings:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To walk in the same direction.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To become a disciple.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To commit oneself to the same mission.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To retrace one\'s steps.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, when Jesus instructed Matthew to follow Him, He called him to embark on a journey of discipleship and shared purpose.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:24:23', '2025-01-06 01:24:23'),
(601, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 1:47: &ldquo;When Jesus saw Nathanael coming toward him, he said of him, &lsquo;Here is truly an Israelite in whom there is no deceit!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus describe Nathanael as one&nbsp; without deceit?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 6, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Nathanael\'s context, the term &ldquo;deceit&rdquo; (dolos)used indicates the absence of hypocrisy .&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The word dolos means \'bait used to catch fish,\' drawing a parallel to hypocrisy as a deceptive lure. Jacob, the forefather, demonstrated such hypocrisy (Genesis 27:35 LXX).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:24:56', '2025-01-06 01:24:56'),
(602, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 2:1: &ldquo;On the third day there was a wedding in Cana of Galilee, and the mother of Jesus was there.&rdquo;</strong><br><br><em>Was Cana an important village?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Cana was situated approximately two miles from Nazareth, alongside a stream known as Ain Kana (Spring of Cana).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The village likely derived its name from this stream. The stream travelled&nbsp; through Ebren, Rahob, Hammon and Cana leads to the significant city of Sidon.(Joshua 19:28)</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:34:33', '2025-01-06 01:34:33'),
(603, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 2:3: &ldquo;When the wine ran out, the mother of Jesus said to him, &lsquo;They have no wine.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong><br><em>How did Mary know that they ran out of&nbsp; wine?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish custom, the keys to the storehouse were typically kept by the women who managed the pantry.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is reasonable that the women of the house in Cana would be the first to notice the absence of wine.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:35:11', '2025-01-06 01:35:11'),
(604, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What disadvantages did the Jews suffer with the loss of the Temple in Jerusalem?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">With the destruction of the Temple, attendance at the temple for Passover and other significant holidays ceased.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The redemption of the firstborn was no longer possible, and the rites of the Day of Atonement, including expiation for sin, were rendered obsolete.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, certain impurities that could only be cleansed through sacrificial offerings remained unremedied.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:35:50', '2025-01-06 01:35:50'),
(605, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 2:6: &ldquo;Now there were six stone jars for the Jewish rites of purification, each holding twenty or thirty gallons.&rdquo;</strong><br><em>How much wine was produced in Cana that day?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A measure (metretes) is equivalent to approximately 30 litres. Consequently each stone jar would contain about 70 to 80 litres of water.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">That day, through the intercession of the Holy Mother, Jesus transformed 420 to 480 litres of water into wine for the guests.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:36:25', '2025-01-06 01:36:25'),
(606, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why does John mention the stone jars?</em></p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Gospel of John the number seven signifies perfection and completeness. Examples of this include:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Seven Wonders</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The seven &ldquo;I am&rdquo; statements</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The seven witnesses</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Father of Jesus, described as equal in seven respects.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The seventh stone jar, according to V. Jerome, represents the crucified body of Christ.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:36:56', '2025-01-06 01:36:56'),
(607, '<p><strong>&nbsp;John 2:6: &ldquo;There were six stone jars for the Jewish rites of purification, each holding twenty or thirty gallons.&rdquo;</strong><br><em>Was there a need for purification at the wedding venue?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus&rsquo; time, the Jews adhered to strict customs that prescribed washing hands before eating, known as netilat yadayim. <br><br>The accompanying prayer is as follows:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Baruch ata Adonai, Eloheinu Melech ha-olam, asher kidshanu b\'mitzvotav vitzivanu al n\'tilat yadayim&rdquo;.<br>(&ldquo;Blessed are You, Lord our God, King of the universe, who has sanctified us with Your commandments and commanded us concerning the washing of the hands.&rdquo;)</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:37:36', '2025-01-06 01:37:36'),
(608, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 2:9: &ldquo;When the steward tasted the water that had become wine and did not know where it came from (though the servants who had drawn the water knew), the steward called the bridegroom.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was the steward at the Jewish wedding?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word architrixlos is rendered as &ldquo;storekeeper&rdquo; in English, but its original meaning is closer to &ldquo;chief steward, master of the banquet or steward of the feast.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">One of the guests traditionally took on the role of the steward, often selected by lottery.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The steward was responsible for arranging food and managing hospitality for guests at the wedding venue.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:38:22', '2025-01-06 01:38:22'),
(609, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 2:15: &ldquo;Making a whip of cords, he drove all of them out of the temple, both the sheep and the cattle. He also poured out the coins of the money changers and overturned their tables.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why didn&rsquo;t the people oppose Jesus when He disrupted business in the temple?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The common people were largely opposed to the commercial activities within the temple, and there were understandable reasons for this sentiment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Currency exchange typically took place near the altar outside the temple, specifically for non-Jewish visitors who needed acceptable currency.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since temple practices required that no pagan currency enter the sanctuary, many supported Jesus in removing that trade from inside of the temple..</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:38:56', '2025-01-06 01:38:56'),
(610, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why was the currency exchanged in the temple?</em></p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish law, each Jew was obligated to pay half a shekel as temple tax (Exodus 30:11-16).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over time, Jewish currency evolved to include the drachma. A single shekel equated to four drachmas (tetradrachma) or four Roman pennies.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, the temple tax became two drachmas. Importantly, this tax had to be paid in Tyrian currency&mdash;a highly pure silver coin minted in the Phoenician city of Tyre.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Money changers in the temple were there to convert various coins into Tyrian currency.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:39:34', '2025-01-06 01:39:34'),
(611, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was the exchange of coins permitted in the temple?</em></p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;All men were obligated to pay the Temple Tax&rdquo; (Exodus 30:16), specifically in Tyrian shekels that were known for their purity and weight.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Tyrian shekel contained no graven images, making it suitable for religious use.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The money changers facilitated this conversion to ensure that offerings met the temple&rsquo;s purity standards.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:40:05', '2025-01-06 01:40:05'),
(612, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 2:20: &ldquo;The Jews then said, &lsquo;This temple has been under construction for forty-six years, and will you raise it up in three days?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why couldn&rsquo;t the Jews fathom the destruction of the Jerusalem temple?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 48, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The prophet Jeremiah foretold that, upon the Messiah&rsquo;s arrival, Jews from across the world would flock to the Jerusalem temple to offer sacrifices (Jeremiah 17:26, 33:11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;Those who bring thanksgiving sacrifices to the house of the Lord, saying, &lsquo;There is steadfast love,&rsquo; and the joy shall resound again&rdquo; (Jeremiah 33:11).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This prophecy anchored their hope in the temple&rsquo;s endurance for ever, which to them was inseparable from the Messiah&rsquo;s coming.So They struggled to envision the temple&rsquo;s disappearance.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 01:40:37', '2025-01-06 01:40:37'),
(613, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 3:2: &ldquo;He came to Jesus by night and said to him, &lsquo;Rabbi, we know that you are a teacher who has come from God.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Nicodemus come to Jesus by night?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 49, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Gospel of John, written after A.D. 85, reflects a period when some leading Jewish figures showed interest in Christianity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, they were hesitant to abandon their societal privileges within Judaism.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Nicodemus visits Jesus during the night so that he could seek Jesus discreetly without risking his status. There were many Jews like him.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 21:58:55', '2025-01-06 21:58:55'),
(614, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 3:3: &ldquo;Jesus answered him, &lsquo;Very truly, I tell you, no one can see the kingdom of God without being born from above.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Nicodemus lack faith?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 49, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Characters in John&rsquo;s Gospel often believed in Jesus after receiving blessings. For example:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The disciples believed after witnessing the miracle at Cana (John 2:11).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Samaritan woman believed after Jesus revealed her past (John 4:19).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Blind man believed after he received healing (John 9).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Nicodemus, however, believed in Jesus without witnessing any miracle. His faith deserves greater recognition for he believed without witnessing any tangible signs.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 21:59:33', '2025-01-06 21:59:33'),
(615, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 3:4: &ldquo;Nicodemus said to him, &lsquo;How can anyone be born after having grown old? Can one enter a second time into the mother&rsquo;s womb and be born?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who is an&nbsp; \"old man\" in jewish tradition?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 49, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Greco-Roman literature, there were two terms refering to people of advanced ages :</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Presbyter (Presbutes): Referring to men aged 50-60.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Elder (Geron): Referring to those older than 60.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Nicodemus suggests that an elder (person over 60) cannot experience a second birth. This verse emphasises that anyone in Christ is reborn as a &ldquo;new creation.&rdquo;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:00:10', '2025-01-06 22:00:10'),
(616, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 3:10: &ldquo;Jesus answered him, &lsquo;Are you a teacher of Israel, and yet you do not understand these things?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus refer to Nicodemus as a teacher?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 49, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Nicodemus was a Pharisee, a group that were entitled to give the interpretation to&nbsp; the Torah and to establish additional laws.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They composed the Mishnah (second law), which is w a part of the Talmud and were regarded as religious leaders or &lsquo;gurus&rsquo; in the society.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Challenging them was seen as blasphemy, which is why a servant struck Jesus when&nbsp; He was accused of dishonouring the high priest (John 18:22).</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:00:49', '2025-01-06 22:00:49'),
(617, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 3:14-15: &ldquo;And just as Moses lifted up the serpent in the wilderness, so must the Son of Man be lifted up, that whoever believes in him may have eternal life.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How does the brass serpent in the desert represent Christ?</em></p>', 5, 49, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jesus brings deliverance from death due to sin just like the brass serpent that saved Israelites from the serpent&rsquo;s bite.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The serpent also symbolised Pharaoh&rsquo;s authority, as he wore a serpent crown. Christ\'s triumph over sin iś prefigured in Moses&rsquo;&nbsp; victory over Pharaoh.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">This imagery reflects Christ&rsquo;s conquest over the serpent who first led humanity to sin in Eden.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Was Nehushtan the brass serpent that Moses made in the desert?</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Nehushtan was a serpent idol worshipped in Israel during the reigns of Ahaz and Hezekiah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was not the brass serpent Moses made but rather a superstitious adaptation from the Arameans (2 Kings 18:4).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is incorrect to equate Nehushtan with the serpent that Moses fashioned in the wilderness.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:01:38', '2025-01-06 22:01:38'),
(618, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 3:22: &ldquo;After this, Jesus and his disciples went into the Judean countryside, and he spent some time there with them and baptised.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus baptise with water like John?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 49, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The only biblical mention of Jesus baptising appears here in John 3:22, yet it is clarified later. &ldquo;&mdash;although it was not Jesus himself but his disciples who baptised&rdquo; (John 4:2).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John chapter 3 discusses the Holy Spirit, so it suggests Jesus focused on baptism with the Holy Spirit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore it must be assumed that Jesus might not baptise directly with water.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:02:16', '2025-01-06 22:02:16'),
(619, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 3:25: &ldquo;Now a discussion about purification arose between John\'s disciples and a Jew.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was the Jew who argued with John&rsquo;s disciples?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 49, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John baptised at Enon, near Samaria, so the term &ldquo;Jew&rdquo; may refer here to someone from Judah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word \"Ioudaios\" can also mean \"one from the land of Judea.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This Jew may have been one of those who came to worship at the Jerusalem temple.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:02:48', '2025-01-06 22:02:48'),
(620, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What were the requirements for water used for Jewish purification?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 49, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish purification involved ritual immersion in stepped pools called mikveh. The Mishnah specifies the following requirements for the water used:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">It must be rainwater or naturally flowing water.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The pool should be built below ground level.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">It must hold at least 350 litres of water.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The water\'s natural composition must remain unchanged (i.e., no other substances mixed in).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Impure water should not mix with the pool water.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:03:45', '2025-01-06 22:03:45'),
(621, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 3:29: &ldquo;The one who has the bride is the bridegroom. The friend of the bridegroom, who stands and hears him, rejoices greatly at the bridegroom\'s voice. For this reason, my joy has been fulfilled.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who is the bridegroom&rsquo;s friend?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 49, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish weddings, the bride and groom each chose close friends (called shoshbin) with specific duties:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">They supervised all wedding preparations.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">They served as witnesses to the marriage.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">They mediated to resolve conflicts in married life.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, Jesus is the bridegroom, the Jewish people are the bride and John the Baptist is the friend of the bridegroom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:04:12', '2025-01-06 22:04:12'),
(622, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 4:5: &ldquo;He came to a Samaritan city called Sychar, near the plot of ground that Jacob had given to his son Joseph.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where is the town of Sychar located?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This town likely refers to Askar, which was about a mile from Jacob&rsquo;s well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Church Father Jerome it corresponds to the Old Testament town of Shechem, which later became known as Sychar.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:11:47', '2025-01-06 22:11:47'),
(623, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 4:6: &ldquo;Jacob&rsquo;s well was there, and Jesus, tired out by his journey, was sitting by the well. It was about noon.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Jesus visited by the Samaritan woman at noon?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Jews, the sixth hour is around noon. According to the Romans, however, the sixth hour was 6:00 p.m.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is probable, given the context, that Jesus met the Samaritan woman around midday.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:12:37', '2025-01-06 22:12:37'),
(624, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 4:9: &ldquo;The Samaritan woman said to him, &lsquo;How is it that you, a Jew, ask a drink of me, a woman of Samaria?&rsquo; (Jews do not share things in common with Samaritans.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is it that Jews did not share things with Samaritans?</em></p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It is recorded that there was no &sigma;&upsilon;&gamma;&chi;&rho;&alpha;&omicron;&mu;&alpha;&iota;&nbsp; &ldquo; or &ldquo;contact,&rdquo; between Jews and Samaritans, meaning there was no &lsquo;common use&rsquo; of vessels or resources.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews and Samaritans avoided sharing soil and vessels as both groups upheld strict purity laws.<br><br></p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:13:32', '2025-01-06 22:13:32'),
(625, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the Israelites come to be known as &lsquo;Jews&rsquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Judah was the son of Jacob and Leah, as recorded in Genesis 29:35: &ldquo;And she conceived again and bore a son, and said, &lsquo;This time I will praise the Lord&rsquo;; therefore she named him Judah.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When the Israelites entered Canaan, the tribe of Judah received its inheritance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Those descending from this tribe came to be known as Yehudi, or &lsquo;Jew&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Later, during the Babylonian exile, all Israelites taken into captivity became collectively known as yehudim, meaning &lsquo;Jews&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:14:39', '2025-01-06 22:14:39'),
(626, '<p><em><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Why did the Samaritan woman hesitate to give water to Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Samaritans constructed a temple on Mount Gerizim, claiming to worship the true God, Jehovah. In 128 B.C. John Hyrcanus destroyed the Samaritan capital but in 30 B.C. King Herod rebuilt it, naming it Sebaste.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>This caused the Jews to view the Samaritans as blasphemers; an old saying (Talmud) even held that &ldquo;a piece of bread given by a Samaritan is more unclean than swine&rsquo;s flesh.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Because of such prejudice the Samaritan woman hesitated in giving Jesus water.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:15:10', '2025-01-06 22:15:10'),
(627, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 4:18: &ldquo;For you have had five husbands, and the one you have now is not your husband. What you have said is true!&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the Samaritan woman an adulteress?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">While the Samaritan woman&rsquo;s appearance at the well at noon suggests she may have been shunned, possibly for a scandalous past, this alone does not conclusively imply she was an adulteress. Additionally:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Samaritan woman demonstrated knowledge of religious matters.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">It would have been unlikely for an adulteress to have been legally married multiple times let alone five.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Divorce occurring five times was unusual.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jesus acknowledges her situation but does not label it as sin.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore evidence remains inconclusive in judging her as an adulteress.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:15:45', '2025-01-06 22:15:45'),
(628, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 4:20: &ldquo;Our ancestors worshipped on this mountain, but you say that the place where people must worship is in Jerusalem.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Samaritan woman argue with Jesus about the place of worship?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In 128 B.C. John Hyrcanus, a Jewish leader of the Maccabean period, destroyed the Samaritan temple on Mount Gerizim.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The justification for this destruction was the Samaritan practice of worshipping what were viewed as foreign gods, while Jewish worship was centred only on the temple in Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Samaritan woman&rsquo;s question to Jesus reflects her people&rsquo;s grief and discontent regarding the loss of their sacred place.</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:16:20', '2025-01-06 22:16:20'),
(629, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 4:25: &ldquo;The woman said to him, &lsquo;I know that Messiah is coming&rsquo; (who is called Christ). &lsquo;When he comes, he will proclaim all things to us.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Samaritans believe that the Messiah would come?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">While the Jews awaited a Messiah from the line of David to act as a kingly saviour, the Samaritans anticipated a prophet similar to Moses.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They referred to this figure as \"Taheb,\" meaning &ldquo;the One who turns&rdquo; or the Restorer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their expectation was not for a Davidic king but for a prophet to bring revelation and guidance.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:16:52', '2025-01-06 22:16:52'),
(630, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 4:35: &ldquo;Do you not say, &lsquo;Four months more, then comes the harvest&rsquo;? But I tell you, look around you, and see how the fields are ripe for harvesting.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the crop that Jesus is referring to?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The crop is barley, a staple food for the poor in ancient times.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some manuscripts mention that &ldquo;the field is white and ripe,&rdquo; alluding to barley, which ripens in April and May, the season during which this conversation took place according to John&rsquo;s account.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Barley was known as the &ldquo;poor man&rsquo;s food,&rdquo; referenced in 2 Kings 7:1:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Elisha said, &lsquo;Hear the word of the Lord: Thus says the Lord, Tomorrow about this time a measure of choice meal shall be sold for a shekel, and two measures of barley for a shekel, at the gate of Samaria.&rsquo;&rdquo;(2 Kings 7:1)</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:17:50', '2025-01-06 22:17:50'),
(631, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 4:40: &ldquo;So when the Samaritans came to him, they asked him to stay with them; and he stayed there two days.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was distinctive about Samaritan worship?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 50, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Samaritan worship was based on four key pillars:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Belief in Jehovah as the one true God.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sacrificial offerings on Mount Gerizim.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Adherence to the Levitical priesthood, which they believed continued through their lineage.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The use of the Samaritan Pentateuch, a Samaritan version of the first five books of the Bible.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These foundational elements distinguished their worship from that of the Jewish people.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:18:24', '2025-01-06 22:18:24'),
(632, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 5:1: &ldquo;After this there was a festival of the Jews, and Jesus went up to Jerusalem.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were the Israelites called Jews from the time of Abraham?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 51, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term &ldquo;Jews&rdquo; arose during the Babylonian exile in 586 B.C., originating from the name of the tribe of Judah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Before this, from the time of Abraham until the exile they were commonly referred to as \"Hebrews.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The term &ldquo;Jews&rdquo; gradually came to mean &ldquo;those from the land of Judah&rdquo; during and after the exile.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:28:38', '2025-01-06 22:28:38'),
(633, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 5:2: \"Now in Jerusalem by the Sheep Gate there is a pool, called in Hebrew Beth-zatha, which has five porticoes.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where was the Sheep Gate for the Jerusalem Temple?&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 51, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jerusalem\'s Temple included a northeast gate known as the Sheep Gate, which was used for bringing goats for sacrifice. The gate was also known as the Gate of Sacrifice for the same reason.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This gate held significance in the path to the temple as it symbolised the approach to sacrificial offerings.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:29:17', '2025-01-06 22:29:17'),
(634, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 5:10: \"So the Jews said to the man who had been cured, \'It is the sabbath; it is not lawful for you to carry your mat.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were Jews not allowed to carry anything on the Sabbath?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 51, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish law forbade carrying items on the Sabbath, even limiting it to objects under the weight of two figs.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sabbath was a day of rest and dedication to God. So that the Jewish people could spend time in His presence.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:29:51', '2025-01-06 22:29:51'),
(635, '<p><strong>&nbsp;John 5:19: \"Jesus said to them, \'Very truly, I tell you, the Son can do nothing on his own, but only what he sees the Father doing.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is sight and other senses given so much importance </em><em>in the Gospel of John?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 51, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Vision and the senses are deeply symbolic in John\'s Gospel:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sight - \"They will look on the one whom they have pierced\" (John 19:37).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Hearing - \"My sheep hear my voice\" (John 10:27).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Taste - \"The steward tasted the water that had become wine\" (John 2:9).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Touch - \"Then he poured water into a basin and began to wash the disciples&rsquo; feet and to wipe them with the towel\" (John 13:5).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Smell - \"The house was filled with the fragrance of the perfume\" (John 12:3).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-06 22:30:27', '2025-01-06 22:30:27'),
(636, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:9: \"There is a boy here who has five barley loaves and two fish. But what are they among so many people?\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does John emphasise that the boy had&nbsp; barley bread in his hands?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Passover feast falls on the fourteenth day of Nisan followed by the Feast of Unleavened Bread on the fifteenth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Barley harvest began on the sixteenth of Nisan, and the first fruits were offered in the temple that morning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus was resurrected on the sixteenth of Nisan, the very day the barley was offered as the first offering</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John&rsquo;s mention of the boy&rsquo;s barley bread signifies Jesus\'s ascension and connection to this offering.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:02:22', '2025-01-08 00:02:22'),
(637, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:19: \"When they had rowed about three or four miles, they saw Jesus walking on the sea and coming near the boat, and they were terrified.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where did the disciples reach on the sea when the storm arose?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sea of Galilee is approximately 40 miles wide and 140 miles long.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to John, they had rowed about 30 miles, roughly midway across the lake. This corresponds with Mark&rsquo;s account of them being \"in the middle of the sea\" (Mark 6:47).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is likely that the disciples were in the middle of the sea when the storm struck.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:03:03', '2025-01-08 00:03:03'),
(638, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:21: &ldquo;They wanted to put him in the boat, but suddenly the boat was at the land towards which they were going.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>In the Gospel of John, why is the account of Jesus walking on water placed before the account of the Holy Eucharist?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The sacred text that precedes the Jewish Passover meal is the Haggadah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this text, prior to recounting God\'s provision of manna to the Jews, the story of the crossing of the Red Sea is read.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This structure of the Haggadah is reflective of the Holy Eucharist. What transpired on the water serves as a precursor to the profound significance of the Eucharist.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:03:45', '2025-01-08 00:03:45'),
(639, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:23: &ldquo;Other boats from Tiberias came near the place where they had eaten the bread after the Lord had given thanks.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was special about the city of Tiberias?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Tiberias was a city constructed by Herod Antipas to appease Tiberius Caesar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was built atop a burial mound, which is why zealous Jews avoided residing in that area.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Despite this, the city played a crucial role in distributing bread among the common people.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:04:31', '2025-01-08 00:04:31'),
(640, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:31: &ldquo;Our ancestors ate the manna in the wilderness; as it is written, &lsquo;He gave them bread from heaven to eat.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews call the food that fell from heaven manna?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \'Manna\' (מָן, Ma Na) translates to &ldquo;What is this?&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When God bestowed heavenly sustenance upon the Jews in the desert, they were bewildered and questioned one another, asking, &ldquo;What is this?&rdquo; (Ma Na).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This inquiry ultimately gave rise to the name that they assigned to the divine provision.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:05:30', '2025-01-08 00:05:30'),
(641, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:41: &ldquo;Then the Jews began to complain about him because he said, &lsquo;I am the bread that came down from heaven.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say that He was the bread that came down from heaven?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews believed that manna was preserved in heaven (Targum Yer 1 on Exodus 16:4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They anticipated that the Messiah would restore the gift of manna and feed them with heavenly bread once again.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their expectation was rooted in the belief that the arrival of the Messiah would mark the beginning of a new era of heavenly sustenance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus Jesus\'s declaration of having come from heaven to be bread <br>was revolutionary.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:15:50', '2025-01-08 00:15:50'),
(642, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:49: &ldquo;Your ancestors ate the manna in the wilderness, and they died.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews end their relationship with manna?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews anticipated the establishment of a new kingdom with the coming of the Messiah.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed that the food in that kingdom would be manna, signifying that once the messianic kingdom was realised, labour would be unnecessary.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They envisioned receiving heavenly manna daily just as their ancestors did in the desert.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:17:17', '2025-01-08 00:17:17'),
(643, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:50: &ldquo;This is the bread that comes down from heaven, so that one may eat of it and not die.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does John give instructions about the Holy Eucharist in the middle of his Gospel?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The first twelve chapters of John\'s Gospel are often referred to as the Book of Signs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The greatest signs bestowed upon the Jews by God were experienced in the wilderness, with manna being one of the most significant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, John introduces the Holy Eucharist to illustrate that it is the biggest sign of the New Covenant.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:18:39', '2025-01-08 00:18:39'),
(644, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:56: \"Whoever eats my flesh and drinks my blood abides in me, and I in him.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What are the similarities between a Jewish family dinner and the incident of Jesus multiplying the loaves?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish dinner&nbsp; comprised of three essential components:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Libation Ceremony: Offering thanks to God.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Deipnon: The act of eating.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Symposium: Engaging in conversation and entertainment.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">All three elements were present when Jesus multiplied the loaves:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He took the bread and gave thanks.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He distributed it to the people to eat.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He spoke to them about the Holy Eucharist.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:20:23', '2025-01-08 00:20:23'),
(645, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:60: \"When many of his disciples heard this, they said, \'This teaching is difficult; who can accept it?\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>In what instances did the Jews restrain from celebrating the Passover?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Passover falls on Nisan 14.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are two reasons why Moses stayed away from celebrating the Passover (Numbers 9:6-12):</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">If someone becomes impure by touching a dead body.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">If one is on a long journey.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However they should observe Passover on the 14th of Iyyar the following month.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:22:45', '2025-01-08 00:22:45');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(646, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 6:61: \"But Jesus, being aware that his disciples were complaining about it, said to them, \'Does this offend you?\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How does this passage cause stumbling?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 52, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;The Jews classified two kinds of meat:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Krea &kappa;&rho;έ&alpha;&sigmaf;: Lifeless (bloodless) flesh, such as the meat of desert quail that they ate in the sinai desert</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sarx &sigma;ά&rho;&xi; (oup): Living flesh (Deuteronomy 12:20-28). They were forbidden to eat live meat.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-f1641390-7fff-672a-f72d-9434178e02c8\">Jesus referred to his body as Sarkz, which is why the idea of consuming Jesus\'s body (Sarks) posed a stumbling block for the Jews.</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:23:19', '2025-01-08 00:23:19'),
(647, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 7:2-3: &ldquo;Now the Jewish festival of Booths was near. His brothers said to him, \'Leave here and go to Judea, so that your disciples may see the works you are doing.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When did the Jews celebrate the festival of Booths?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 53, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Feast of Tabernacles was celebrated between the end of one Jewish agricultural year and the beginning of a new one.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By this time, the harvest of grapes, olives and other agricultural products would have concluded.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, it was a feast of joy, prosperity and thanksgiving.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was also a time to pray for the rains needed for the next year&rsquo;s crops because the Jews anticipated rain during the days associated with this feast.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:29:40', '2025-01-08 00:29:40'),
(648, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 7:8: \"You go to the festival. I am not going to this festival, for my time has not yet fully come.\"&nbsp;</strong><br><em>Why did the brothers invite Jesus to go to the feast?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 53, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Small groups from Galilee journeyed to Jerusalem for the feast and people typically travelled together during this pilgrimage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, it is likely that Jesus\'s brothers urged him to join them because they saw Him as a good friend.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:31:03', '2025-01-08 00:31:03'),
(649, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 7:12-32: &ldquo;There was considerable murmuring about him among the crowds. Some were saying, &lsquo;He is a good man,&rsquo; while others were saying, &lsquo;No, he is deceiving the crowd.&rsquo; Yet no one would speak openly about him for fear of the Jews. The Pharisees heard the murmurs of the crowd and sent temple guards to arrest him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Pharisees have the authority to arrest someone? Who were the chief priests responsible for the security of the temple premises?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 53, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The authority to arrest belonged to the temple guards who were appointed from the tribe of Levi to maintain security within the temple precincts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees did not possess the legal right to arrest individuals directly. They had to rely on temple authorities for such actions.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:32:03', '2025-01-08 00:32:03'),
(650, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 7:23: &ldquo;If a man receives circumcision on the Sabbath in order that the law of Moses may not be broken, are you angry with me because I healed a man on the Sabbath?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was circumcision performed on the Sabbath?</em></p>', 5, 53, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A Jewish male infant is required to be circumcised on the eighth day following his birth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This obligation holds even if the eighth day coincides with the Sabbath. Because circumcision is deemed a matter of greater significance than the Sabbath observance.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:32:59', '2025-01-08 00:32:59'),
(651, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 7:37: &ldquo;On the last day of the festival, the great day, while Jesus was standing there, he cried out, &lsquo;Let anyone who is thirsty come to me, and let the one who believes in me drink. As the scripture has said, &lsquo;Out of the believer&rsquo;s heart shall flow rivers of living water.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews do anything on Sukkot for rain?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 53, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Israel, willow trees that thrive in water-rich areas, were significant for the people.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If their branches were cut, they would quickly wither, indicating a direct relationship between their existence and water.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the final day of the Feast (Hosanna Rabba), the branches of these willows were cut and taken to the altar of the Temple in Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As the priests performed this ritual they sang Psalm 118:25, proclaiming that without God\'s protection, Israel would perish like the wilting plant.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:34:03', '2025-01-08 00:34:03'),
(652, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>On which feast day did Jesus speak of the living water?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 53, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus spoke of the living water at the conclusion of Sukkot, the Feast of Tabernacles.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This significant Jewish festival lasts for seven days, occurring from the 15th to the 21st of the seventh month (Tishri).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During this period, the Jewish people left their homes to dwell in tents as a commemoration of their 40 years in the desert.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was on the final day of this celebration that Jesus proclaimed the message of the living water.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:35:06', '2025-01-08 00:35:06'),
(653, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 7:38: &ldquo;Whoever believes in me, as the scripture has said, &lsquo;Out of the believer&rsquo;s heart shall flow rivers of living water.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>&nbsp;In what context of the tent-dweller does Jesus speak of living water?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 53, '<p dir=\"ltr\">On the last day of the Feast of Tabernacles, a special ritual called \'Hoshanna Rabba\' took place.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During this ceremony, all the priests brought a pitcher of water from the Pool of Siloam and poured it over the altar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The water from the altar flowed down to the area where their tents were situated, moistening the ground beneath them.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, Jesus\'s reference to living water takes on profound significance, linking the physical act of water pouring to the spiritual sustenance He offers.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:36:17', '2025-01-08 00:36:17'),
(654, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:4: &ldquo;They said to him, &lsquo;Teacher, this woman was caught in the very act of committing adultery.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Pharisees gather together to stone the adulteress?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Phinehas, a notable figure from the Old Testament, served as an inspiration for the Pharisees and other extremists.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He is remembered for his zealous act of killing an Israelite who brought a Midianite woman into his home (Numbers 25:6).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees gathered to stone the adulterous woman to demonstrate their own zeal for the law, mirroring the fervour of Phinehas.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:40:00', '2025-01-08 00:40:00'),
(655, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:4-5: &ldquo;They said to him, &lsquo;Teacher, this woman was caught in the very act of committing adultery. Now in the law, Moses commanded us to stone such women. What do you say?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How is Jesus caught in the trap of judging the woman caught in adultery?</em></p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish law, both parties involved in adultery were subject to punishment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in Deuteronomy 22:22, &ldquo;If a man is found lying with the wife of another man, both of them shall die, the man who lay with the woman, and the woman; so you shall purge the evil from Israel.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, if Jesus were to condemn only the woman, He would be seen as contradicting the law - aquiting the man and convicting only man.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This scenario highlights the necessity for all actions to be performed with love and compassion rather than strict adherence to the law alone.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:42:04', '2025-01-08 00:42:04'),
(656, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:5: &ldquo;Now in the law, Moses commanded us to stone such women. What do you say?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the trap in judging the adulterous woman?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Roman law, a woman caught in adultery could also face the death penalty.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yet, it is essential to note that under Roman law, a woman could only be sentenced to death if the male participant was also investigated.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore the matter becomes more complicated, illustrating the intricate legal and moral implications.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Ultimately, Jesus alone possesses the authority to forgive sins.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:43:18', '2025-01-08 00:43:18'),
(657, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:8: &ldquo;He bent down and wrote on the ground.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Jesus write on the ground?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The specific content of what Jesus wrote on the ground remains unknown.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is worth reflecting that God inscribed the Ten Commandments with His finger, as noted in Deuteronomy 9:10: &ldquo;The Lord gave me two stone tablets written with the finger of God.&rdquo; It is conceivable that what Jesus wrote symbolised a new commandment, one rooted in mercy&mdash;the very essence of His teachings.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:44:21', '2025-01-08 00:44:21'),
(658, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:12: &ldquo;Again Jesus spoke to them, saying, &lsquo;I am the light of the world. Whoever follows me will never walk in darkness but will have the light of life.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>In what context did Jesus declare that He is the light?</em></p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus made this declaration during the Festival of Lights, or Sukkot, when the doors of the temple remained open for seven days, only to be closed after the evening burnt offering.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Four large lamps, or menorahs, were lit to illuminate the temple grounds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This light was so bright that, as noted in Sukkah 53a, &ldquo;a woman can thresh wheat in this light.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus&rsquo;s proclamation as the world\'s light draws upon this rich imagery, indicating that He illuminates the path surrounded by life&rsquo;s darkness.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:45:06', '2025-01-08 00:45:06'),
(659, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Where was Jesus when He said that He is the light of the world?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">On the Jewish holiday of Sukkot, four 75-foot-high menorahs were lit in the Court of Women at the Temple of Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This spectacle reminded the Israelites of the pillar of fire, which represented the divine presence guiding them in the desert.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is from this profound context that Jesus proclaimed Himself as the light of the world, assuring us that with Him, we need not traverse the dark paths of life alone.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:45:56', '2025-01-08 00:45:56'),
(660, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:13: &ldquo;Then the Pharisees said to him, &lsquo;You are testifying on your own behalf; your testimony is not valid.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus speak of light and water on the occasion of the Tabernacle?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">On the first day of the Festival of Tabernacles (Sukkot), a reading known as the Haftarah is presented. This reading is taken from the prophetic books and includes Zechariah, specifically the fourteenth chapter. It prophesied the coming of the Messiah, detailing two significant events.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">There will be a continuous light. &ldquo;And there shall be a continuous day&mdash; it is known to the Lord alone&mdash; neither day nor night, for at evening time there shall be light&rdquo; (Zechariah 14:7).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Jews will experience ever-flowing water. &ldquo;On that day living waters shall flow out from Jerusalem, half of them to the eastern sea and half of them to the western sea; it shall continue in summer as in winter&rdquo; (Zechariah 14:8). Thus Jesus chose to speak about light and water on this occasion.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:47:07', '2025-01-08 00:47:07'),
(661, '<p><strong>John 8:31: &ldquo;Jesus said to the Jews who had believed in him, &lsquo;If you continue in my word, you are truly my disciples.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Do the Jewish scriptures have similar promises?</em></p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Indeed, the promises of the covenants (offer of Convents) are found in the Jewish scriptures, particularly in the Old Testament and Midrash texts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, consider the following covenant: &ldquo;Now therefore, if you obey my voice and keep my covenant, you shall be my treasured possession out of all the peoples. Indeed, the whole earth is mine&rdquo; (Exodus 19:5, NRSV).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Promises accompany these commands; they belong to the category of covenantal offers. If the people obey what is commanded, a reward follows.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Every command comes with a promise attached to it.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:48:03', '2025-01-08 00:48:03'),
(662, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:33: &ldquo;They answered him, &lsquo;We are descendants of Abraham, and we have never been enslaved to anyone. What do you mean by saying, &ldquo;You will be made free?&rdquo;&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews say they were never slaves?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews experienced political enslavement at various times&mdash; in Egypt, Babylon and under Roman rule.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However they maintained their religious freedom, never worshipping the gods of the lands where they were enslaved.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why they asserted that they had never been enslaved.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:48:53', '2025-01-08 00:48:53'),
(663, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:39: &ldquo;They answered him, &lsquo;Abraham is our father.&rsquo; Jesus said to them, &lsquo;If you were Abraham&rsquo;s children, you would be doing what Abraham did.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why didn&rsquo;t the Jews understand what Jesus said?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This misunderstanding reflects a literary technique employed by John known as Schematism, where one person&rsquo;s statement is interpreted differently by another.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Jesus referred to His Father, the Jews misinterpreted His words in light of Abraham.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:49:57', '2025-01-08 00:49:57'),
(664, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:44: &ldquo;You are from your father the devil, and you choose to do your father&rsquo;s desires. He was a murderer from the beginning and does not stand in the truth, because there is no truth in him. When he tells a lie, he speaks according to his own nature, for he is a liar and the father of lies.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus call the Devil the father of lies?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The first and most significant lie originated from the Devil\'s tongue, leading to Adam and Eve\'s expulsion from Paradise (Genesis 3:16).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The lie that condemned Jesus to death also stemmed from the Devil.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Devil\'s deceptions are dangerous as he misleads humanity by presenting falsehoods as truths.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:51:05', '2025-01-08 00:51:05'),
(665, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:48: \"The Jews answered him, &lsquo;Are we not right in saying that you are a Samaritan and have a demon?&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews call Jesus a Samaritan?</em></p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"Samaritan\" was a curse word among the Jews, particularly in the context of condemnation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, if someone committed blasphemy, the Jewish leaders would gather in the synagogue to pronounce a curse against him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Common phrases associated with such cursing included:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"He has a demon.\"</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"He is a Samaritan.\"</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The assertion that \"Jesus is a Samaritan\" was a derogatory epithet aimed at Him.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is possible that this curse marked the beginning of Jesus\'s suffering.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:51:56', '2025-01-08 00:51:56'),
(666, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 8:57-58: \"So the Jews said to him, &lsquo;You are not yet fifty years old, and have you seen Abraham?&rsquo; Jesus said to them, &lsquo;Very truly, I tell you, before Abraham was, I am.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John record short questions and answers in the Gospel?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 5, 54, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Gospel of John contains relatively few parables compared to the Synoptic Gospels. Instead, it features riddles as a distinct literary technique.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are approximately 38 riddles throughout John&rsquo;s Gospel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An example can be found in the exchange, &ldquo;Where is your father?&rdquo; to which Jesus replies, &ldquo;You know neither me nor my Father&rdquo; (John 8:19).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The questions and answers recorded in this Gospel often function as riddles, contributing to John&rsquo;s unique narrative style.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:52:44', '2025-01-08 00:52:44'),
(667, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 9:3: \"Jesus answered, &lsquo;Neither this man nor his parents sinned; he was born blind so that God&rsquo;s works might be revealed in him.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Jews treat a blind person?</em></p>', 5, 55, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The prevailing belief among the Jews was that blindness was a consequence of sin committed either by the individual or by their parents (Exodus 20:5).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Furthermore, a blind person was not permitted to enter the temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Levitical laws stated: \"No one with a blemish shall come near, including those with broken limbs, those who are hunchbacked or dwarfed, and anyone who is visually impaired\" (Leviticus 21:18-20).</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:56:45', '2025-01-08 00:56:45'),
(668, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 9:7: \"He said to him, &lsquo;Go, wash in the pool of Siloam&rsquo; (which means &lsquo;Sent&rsquo;). Then he went and washed and came back able to see.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What significance did the Pool of Siloam hold in the lives of the Israelites?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 55, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pool of Siloam played a crucial role during the siege of Jerusalem by the Assyrian king Sennacherib in 701 B.C. King Hezekiah of Judah undertook the construction of a canal to secure Jerusalem\'s access to fresh water.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This canal diverted water from the Gihon Spring in the Kedron Valley, leading to the Pool of Siloam within the city.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As noted in 2 Chronicles 32:30, \"Hezekiah stopped the upper spring of the Gihon and directed the water flow down westward to the city of David.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The water from this pool sustained the Israelites during a three-year siege, and it was at this pool that God&rsquo;s angel struck down 185,000 Assyrian soldiers (Isaiah 37:36).</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:57:28', '2025-01-08 00:57:28'),
(669, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>&nbsp;Why is this pool of Siloam called the &ldquo;Sent One&rdquo;?</em></p>', 5, 55, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \'Siloam\' is derived from the Hebrew root \'slh,\' which means \"to send\" (שָׁלַח, \"Shalah\").</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The same root is utilised in the word \"Shiloh\" (שִׁלֹה, \"Shalah\").&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the name Siloam is linked to the concept of the Sent One.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:58:06', '2025-01-08 00:58:06'),
(670, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 9:16 &ldquo;And some of the Pharisees said, &lsquo;This man is not from God, for he does not observe the Sabbath.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Pharisees assert that Jesus, who healed the blind man, did not observe the Sabbath?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 55, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees concocted two primary reasons to claim that Jesus violated the Sabbath observance:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He healed on the Sabbath.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He kneaded the soil on the Sabbath.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was forbidden for Jews to mold&nbsp; vessels from clay on the Sabbath.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees argued that these actions rendered Jesus\'s observance of the Sabbath unclean.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 00:59:28', '2025-01-08 00:59:28'),
(671, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 9:18: &ldquo;The Jews did not believe until they called the parents of the man who had received his sight and asked them whether he was blind and had received his sight.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Pharisees call the parents of the blind beggar to enquire about him?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 55, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A blind priest was on public trial for allegedly breaking the Sabbath.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Jewish system of justice, the testimony of witnesses held greater weight than physical evidence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, even without corroborative evidences, a person could be convicted based solely on witness&rsquo; testimony.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In a similar vein, the Pharisees summoned the blind beggar\'s parents to serve as witnesses against him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:00:14', '2025-01-08 01:00:14'),
(672, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 9:31: &ldquo;We know that God does not listen to sinners, but he does listen to the one who worships him and obeys his will.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Does God truly not hear the prayers of sinners?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 55, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The prevailing Jewish belief held that God would never perform miracles on behalf of sinners.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, John\'s account demonstrates that God indeed hears the prayers of sinners, as evidenced by the healing of the blind man.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John refutes the notion that such beliefs are inherently true.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:00:49', '2025-01-08 01:00:49'),
(673, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 10:9 &ldquo;I am the door; whoever enters by me will be saved and will come in and go out and find pasture.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the sheep gate like?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 56, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The sheep pens were constructed from stone with multiple shepherds often sharing a single enclosure.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This pen had only one entrance, and the night watchman would sleep across this threshold to protect the sheep and prevent them from straying.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:04:08', '2025-01-08 01:04:08'),
(674, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 10:11 &ldquo;I am the good shepherd. The good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the term \"good shepherd\" become familiar to the Israelites?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 56, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 14 Caesar imposed higher taxes on Palestine and referred to himself in his decrees as the \'good shepherd\'.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"To the governors who recommended burdensome taxes for his provinces, he wrote in answer that it was the part of a good shepherd to shear his flock, not to skin it.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, the term \'good shepherd\' became well-known among the people.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:05:22', '2025-01-08 01:05:22'),
(675, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 10:12: &ldquo;The hired hand, who is not the shepherd and does not own the sheep, sees the wolf coming and leaves the sheep and runs away. The wolf snatches them and scatters them.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What caused the mercenary to run away?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 56, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A herdsman possesses three primary weapons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A staff is used to keep the sheep together.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A rod crafted from wood for protection.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A sling</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However these tools prove insufficient when the wolves approach so the mercenary flees for his life.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:06:02', '2025-01-08 01:06:02'),
(676, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 10:22: &ldquo;At that time, the Festival of the Dedication took place in Jerusalem. It was winter.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the Festival of the Dedication celebrated in winter?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 56, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Feast of Dedication, known as Hanukkah, commences on the twenty-fifth day of the Hebrew month of Kislev.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This festival of lights is celebrated for eight days and falls during the winter months of November and December in Palestine.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:07:14', '2025-01-08 01:07:14'),
(677, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 10:30-31: &ldquo;I and the Father are one.&rdquo; Again the Jews picked up stones to throw at him.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews stone Jesus when He said that He and the Father are one?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 56, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Antiochus Epiphanes IV, the Seleucid king who ruled two centuries before Jesus, entered Jerusalem and proclaimed himself to be God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hanukkah celebrates the victory over the Seleucid kings and the restoration of the Temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On that very day, Jesus proclaimed His divinity, which incited the anger of the Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:07:41', '2025-01-08 01:07:41'),
(678, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 10:31: &ldquo;The Jews again picked up stones to throw at him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews pick up stones to throw at Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 56, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish pride lies in monotheism, which forms the foundation of their faith.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews\' creed is succinctly captured in the declaration, &ldquo;Hear, O Israel: The Lord our God, the Lord is one&rdquo; (Deuteronomy 6:4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To claim that God has a son is seen as egregious blasphemy, punishable by stoning. &ldquo;Anyone who blasphemes the name of the Lord shall be put to death; the whole congregation shall stone him&rdquo; (Leviticus 24:16).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They attempted to stone Jesus because He referred to Himself as the Son of God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:08:20', '2025-01-08 01:08:20'),
(679, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 11:1: &ldquo;Now a man named Lazarus was sick. He was from Bethany, the village of Mary and her sister Martha.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>On which festival did Jesus raise Lazarus?</em></p>', 5, 57, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus raised Lazarus during the Feast of Dedication&mdash;Hanukkah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This feast commemorates the rededication of the Temple in 164 B.C. during the time of Judas Maccabeus. Judas Maccabeus fought against the sacrilege of Antiochus Epiphanes IV who offered pork in the Temple and erected a statue of the god Jupiter.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In 164 B.C., Judas Maccabeus liberated Jerusalem from the Seleucid rule and restored the Temple.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hanukkah represents a time when the Jewish people longed for a saviour.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:10:23', '2025-01-08 01:10:23'),
(680, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was Bethany an important village?</em></p>', 5, 57, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The church father Eusebius referred to Bethany as \'Batanea\' (Eusebius, Onomasticon 44:9-11).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The \'sh\' in Hebrew changes to \'t\' in Aramaic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is believed that it refers to the \'Bashan\' of the Old Testament.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:11:19', '2025-01-08 01:11:19'),
(681, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 12:13: &ldquo;They took palm branches and went out to meet him. They shouted: &lsquo;Hosanna! Blessed is the one who comes in the name of the Lord! Blessed is the King of Israel!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What kind of branches did the Jews hold in their hands during Jesus\'s royal entry?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 57, '<p dir=\"ltr\">All four evangelists describe Jesus\' royal entry, yet only John specifies that the people held twigs in their hands, referring to them as palm branches.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, the other evangelists mention that branches of trees were laid on the road (Matthew 21:8; Mark 11:9).</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:12:06', '2025-01-08 01:12:06'),
(682, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 11:16: &ldquo;Thomas, who was called the Twin, said to his fellow disciples, &lsquo;Let us also go, that we may die with him.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is there evidence that St. Thomas came to India?</em></p>', 5, 57, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Didascalia Apostolorum (Teaching of the Apostles), written between A.D. 225-250 records that St. Thomas preached the gospel in Persia and India.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Marco Polo&rsquo;s travelogue documents his visit to the tomb of Thomas Shieha in India.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Panteneous, a sailor who travelled to India in A.D. 180, recounts seeing a Hebrew copy of the Gospel of Matthew off the coast of Kerala.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Ancient songs such as Maragam Kali Patt and Rampan Patt provide evidence of the presence of Thomas in Kerala since ancient times.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:12:49', '2025-01-08 01:12:49'),
(683, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why isn&rsquo;t the body of St Thomas located in India?</em></p>', 5, 57, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">An apocryphal book written in the first three centuries, The Acts of Judas Thomas, states that the bones of the king at the time of Thomas\'s death were taken from India to Edessa while he was still alive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Syriac version of this book notes, \"for one of the brethren had taken them away secretly and conveyed them to the West.\"</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:13:31', '2025-01-08 01:13:31'),
(684, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 11:34-35: &ldquo;Where have you laid him?&rdquo; They said to him, &ldquo;Lord, come and see.&rdquo; Jesus began to weep.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What made Jesus weeping noteworthy?</em></p>', 5, 57, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish culture, men typically refrained from weeping in public except in the presence of God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, &ldquo;Joseph looked for a place to weep when his heart was broken for his brother, and he went into his chamber and wept&rdquo; (Genesis 43:30).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus, as a rabbi, wept publicly, demonstrating the depth of His empathy and connection to humanity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His tears reflect how precious human sorrow is in the sight of God.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:14:13', '2025-01-08 01:14:13'),
(685, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 11:35-36: &ldquo;Jesus wept. So the Jews said, &lsquo;See how he loved him!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were they surprised that Jesus wept?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 57, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews understood certain organs to be the source of human emotions. For example:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Love is associated with the heart.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Anger is expressed through the nose.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Obedience is perceived through the ears.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Courage is linked to the kidneys (guts).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even in contemporary interpretations, the spine signifies courage, large ears suggest intelligence and the heart is associated with love. Thus, the Jews were surprised by Jesus\'s tears as they might not have expected Him to be&nbsp; emotional. Crying was likely regarded as an act associated only with women.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:14:59', '2025-01-08 01:14:59'),
(686, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 11:39: &ldquo;Jesus said, &lsquo;Take away the stone.&rsquo; Martha, the sister of the deceased, said to him, &lsquo;Lord, already there is a stench because he has been dead four days.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Lazarus in the tomb for 4 days?</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 5, 57, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews traditionally endeavoured to wrap&nbsp; the body on the day of death. The entire body was wrapped in a cloth, and special clothes were designated for the head and hands.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The process of transferring bones to a box would commence after one year. Since Jesus arrived in Bethany four days after Lazarus\' death, it suggests that&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Lazarus had indeed been entombed for four days.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:15:41', '2025-01-08 01:15:41'),
(687, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 11:48: &ldquo;If we let him go on like this, everyone will believe in him, and the Romans will come and destroy both our holy place and our nation.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Caiaphas fear a Roman attack?</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 5, 57, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman army systematically suppressed any rebellions that arose among the Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The rebellion of Theudas, mentioned in the Acts of the Apostles, serves as an example. &ldquo;Some time ago Theudas rose up, claiming to be somebody, and a number of men, about four hundred, joined him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">But he was killed, and all who followed him were dispersed and vanished.&rdquo; (Acts 5:36).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Caiaphas feared a similar Roman response if Jesus continued to gain followers.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:16:48', '2025-01-08 01:16:48'),
(688, '<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>John 11:49: &ldquo;But one of them, Caiaphas, who was high priest that year, said, &lsquo;You know nothing at all.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p><em><strong>&nbsp;</strong>What authority did Caiaphas have?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 57, '<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>As the high priest, Caiaphas wielded complete authority over the ordinances of the temple in Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His powers extended to maintaining the temple\'s treasures, ensuring its security, appointing priests and presiding over the Sanhedrin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, his position held significant weight in religious and political matters.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:17:20', '2025-01-08 01:17:20'),
(689, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 12:1: &ldquo;Six days before the Passover, Jesus came to Bethany, the home of Lazarus whom he had raised from the dead.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How significant was the number six to the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 58, '<ol>\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp;</strong>God created man on the sixth day thus the number 6 symbolises human frailty.</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Men were permitted to work for six days.</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">After six years of servitude, a Hebrew slave was granted freedom in the seventh year.</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The land could be cultivated for six years followed by a year of rest in the seventh year.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:21:45', '2025-01-20 05:48:31'),
(690, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 12:3: &ldquo;Mary took a pound of costly perfume made of pure nard, anointed Jesus&rsquo; feet, and wiped them with her hair. The house was filled with the fragrance of the perfume.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p><em><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Was Nardin a kind of ointment?</em></p>', 5, 58, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Nardin, also known as spikenard, is an aromatic oil derived from the Nardostachys jatamansi plant, found in the Himalayan regions of Nepal, China and India.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This ointment was produced commercially in these areas and was renowned for its fragrance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:22:30', '2025-01-08 01:22:30'),
(691, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 12:3: </strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How much oil did Mary use to anoint Jesus&rsquo; feet?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 58, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John recounts that Mary anointed Jesus&rsquo;s feet with a bottle of pure nard oil.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The &ldquo;bottle&rdquo; here refers to a Roman litre, which holds approximately one pound (327.25 grams) of fragrant oil.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This was a lavish, generous offering that exemplified the act of giving without measure to the Lord.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:23:50', '2025-01-08 01:23:50'),
(692, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 12:5: &ldquo;Why was this ointment not sold for three hundred denarii and given to the poor?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the ointment of the sinful woman valuable?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 58, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Judas remarked that the ointment the sinful woman poured on Jesus\'s feet was valued at 300 denarii.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since a daily wage at that time was 1 denarius, and only six days a week could be counted (no labour on the Sabbath).Thus a person could typically work about 300 days in a year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In such a scenario, the&nbsp; ointment of the sinful woman&nbsp; costs almost an entire year\'s wages.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:24:29', '2025-01-13 21:16:12'),
(693, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 12:7: &ldquo;Jesus said, &lsquo;Leave her alone. She bought it so that she might keep it for the day of my burial.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus connect the sinful woman&rsquo;s anointing with His death?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 58, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, a person&rsquo;s feet is annointed only for the burial .&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Anointing the feet of someone alive was seen as a way of foretelling death. That is the&nbsp; reason why Jesus directed her to reserve this gesture to prepare for His burial.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:25:06', '2025-01-13 21:17:10'),
(694, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 12:20: &ldquo;Now among those who went up to worship at the festival were some Greeks.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Greeks come to Jerusalem to worship?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 58, '<p dir=\"ltr\">These Greeks might have arrived in Jerusalem for the Passover feast.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Although Gentiles often visited Jerusalem to worship, the term &ldquo;Greeks&rdquo; (Hellenes) here could also refer to Greek-speaking Jews who lived in Hellenistic regions.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greeks who came to worship were likely Greek-speaking Jews.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:25:44', '2025-01-08 01:25:44'),
(695, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 12:24: &ldquo;Unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains just a single grain; but if it dies, it bears much fruit.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Does a grain of wheat bear fruit when it dies?</em></p>', 5, 58, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Gospel of John was written with an awareness of Greek philosophical ideas.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Greek philosophy considered all things to contain an inner life force which they called as the &lsquo;life principle.&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even if the outer shell of a seed decays, the &ldquo;life principle&rdquo; within it remains. This vital force within the seed gives rise to new life.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:26:17', '2025-01-13 21:18:11'),
(696, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 13:4: &ldquo;He got up from the table, took off his outer robe, and tied a towel around himself.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What Old Testament model did John use to present the Last Supper?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 59, '<p dir=\"ltr\">After the covenant was established on Mount Sinai, the Israelites shared a covenant meal, seeing God&rsquo;s footstool (Exodus 24:9-10).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, Jesus, at the Last Supper, washed His disciples&rsquo; feet as a symbol of service and offered a new commandment, paralleling the covenant&rsquo;s commandments.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John presents the Last Supper in this context, aligning it with the Old Testament covenant meal, marking the Holy Eucharist as the ultimate covenant.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:29:41', '2025-01-08 01:29:41'),
(697, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 13:5: &ldquo;Then he poured water into a basin and began to wash the disciples&rsquo; feet and to wipe them with the towel that was tied around him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews wash the feet of their guests?</em></p>', 5, 59, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It was customary in Jewish hospitality to welcome a guest by washing their feet. However, the role of the person performing this act held significance.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Normally Servants &nbsp; performed foot-washing of the guests to a house</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sometimes, a son might do so, if the guest is of very high reputation.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The head of the family washed only the feet of the chief guests among those of high reputation.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:30:33', '2025-01-13 22:03:14'),
(698, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 13:13: &ldquo;You call me Teacher and Lord&mdash;and you are right, for that is what I am.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus refer to Himself as &lsquo;teacher&rsquo; while washing the feet of his disciples?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 59, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish rabbis often taught their disciples during Passover (John 20:16).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Frequently, disciples studied at their teacher&rsquo;s feet (Acts 22:3) and it was common for disciples to untie the sandals of their teachers as a gesture of respect (Matthew 3:11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Here, Jesus&mdash;the Teacher&mdash;humbles Himself to perform the role of a disciple, an act of ultimate humility.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:31:16', '2025-01-08 01:31:16'),
(699, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 13:23: &ldquo;One of his disciples&mdash;the one whom Jesus loved&mdash;was reclining next to him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How was John able to lean on Jesus&rsquo;s chest?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 59, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish people did not traditionally eat while seated in chairs.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Middle East, people often recline on their left side during a meal, using the left hand for support and the right hand for eating.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sitting to the left of a person you respect and to the right of a loved one was customary.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, as John reclined at Jesus&rsquo; side, his head rested close to Jesus&rsquo; heart.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:31:54', '2025-01-08 01:31:54'),
(700, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 13:30: &ldquo;So, after receiving the piece of bread, he immediately went out. And it was night.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Judas leave after receiving the bread?</em></p>', 5, 59, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;The devil had already entered into Judas, who had received the bread&rdquo; (John 13:27).<br>A person influenced by the devil cannot remain in the company of the holy.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, Ananias and Sapphira, who were influenced by the devil, were removed from the church.<br>&ldquo;Peter said, &lsquo;Ananias, why has Satan filled your heart to lie to the Holy Spirit and to keep back part of the proceeds of the land?&rsquo;&rdquo; (Acts 5:3).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This illustrates the devil\'s work, which dispels the soul from the company of saints.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:32:34', '2025-01-13 22:04:59'),
(701, '<p><strong>&nbsp;John 12:32: &ldquo;And I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all people to myself.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus refer to the crucifixion as &lsquo;exaltation&rsquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 59, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Isaiah&rsquo;s prophecy about the servant begins with the phrase, &ldquo;He shall be exalted.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;My servant shall prosper; he shall be exalted and lifted up, and shall be very high. Just as there were many who were astonished at him&mdash;so marred was his appearance, beyond human semblance&rdquo; (Isaiah 52:13-14).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus refers to His death on the cross as exaltation to establish his identity as the suffering servant foretold by Isaiah.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:33:16', '2025-01-08 01:33:16');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(702, '<p><strong>John 12:37: &ldquo;Although he had performed so many signs in their presence, they did not believe in him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is special about the twelfth chapter of the Gospel of John?</em></p>', 5, 59, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The twelfth chapter of John marks the conclusion of Jesus&rsquo;s public ministry. After this chapter, Jesus speaks only to His disciples, preparing them for His glorification.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From This section is often referred to as the &ldquo;Book of Glory.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:33:53', '2025-01-08 01:33:53'),
(703, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 14:2: &ldquo;In my Father&rsquo;s house there are many dwelling-places.If it were not so, would I have told you that I go to prepare a place for you?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is special about the dwellings in the Father\'s house?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 60, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus uses the Greek term &ldquo;monē&rdquo; to describe these dwellings. The term does not refer to ordinary homes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish custom, when a groom was preparing for marriage , he would begin constructing a house on his father&rsquo;s land for his bride.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This house would usually be completed following the engagement and would be where the bride moved after the marriage.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;When Jesus spoke of the dwellings in the Father&rsquo;s house, the Jewish people would have thought of this (monē) house.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:36:16', '2025-01-08 01:36:16'),
(704, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What did the Jews understand when Jesus spoke of many dwellings?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 60, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkoth), the Jews lived in tents around Jerusalem. These tents symbolised God&rsquo;s provision for them during their days in wilderness to the promised land..</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed that when the Messiah arrives they would again dwell around Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Jesus mentioned the many dwellings in the Father&rsquo;s house, it is likely that they envisioned these tabernacled dwellings with the Messiah.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:36:57', '2025-01-13 22:28:54'),
(705, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 14:4-5: &ldquo;And you know the way to the place where I am going.&rdquo; Thomas said to him, &ldquo;Lord, we do not know where you are going. How can we know the way?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did Jesus mean by the way to the Father&rsquo;s house?</em></p>', 5, 60, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Most of Jesus&rsquo;s disciples were from Galilee, and the temple in Jerusalem was regarded as their Father&rsquo;s house. Three main routes could lead to Jerusalem:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Through Samaria (approximately 125 km), though rarely taken due to enmity with the Samaritans.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Along the Jordan River, a slower route with approximately 140 km.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Via Perea, on the east side of the Jordan, a route generally preferred by Jews and is about 170km.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Jesus spoke of the &ldquo;way&rdquo; to the Father&rsquo;s house, His disciples likely recalled these familiar routes to Jerusalem.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:37:44', '2025-01-13 22:30:33'),
(706, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the name &ldquo;Thomas&rdquo; come about?</em></p>', 5, 60, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name &ldquo;Thomas&rdquo; originates from the Aramaic word Toma, meaning &ldquo;twin.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When the Gospel was written in Greek, an &ldquo;<img src=\"https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXcl6VhcIrTl0uEmEwy5E3mAwTxrZAGMPawKvIqQ-DsgNIi7xs-BeQb5ZsjfXPoyT6lcmbqIf_bQkMW8YX2Fofqz1KqHY80uGcCMAJJp6ET7-ahppHSpoHQD9VL1XhVVf0H7mVfMJK3JvczUiQAY2IcqVqjo?key=EGYgbpsCnlKmfZ1GTETMNQ\" width=\"27\" height=\"21\">&rdquo; ending was added for Greek grammar, resulting in the name Thomas.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus the disciple Thomas is called &ldquo;the Twin<img src=\"https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXePSx2IhdSJJsN7zb-N4T2gZ1Ms_sAsJlHgLT3m82PGy16Fm8uFaaE_FYUlY1f7Z8W0iouKyAcZEJ9BflzA38Zl1oeqxC1BHcQWKCi5SnFUmmAapgJzyQvJL3g2fiDFxKFk4OFx8fgMVJNldw_2SPWUrJcc?key=EGYgbpsCnlKmfZ1GTETMNQ\" width=\"60\" height=\"28\">,&rdquo; symbolising his role in following Jesus, even to the point of readiness for martyrdom.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:38:23', '2025-01-08 01:38:23'),
(707, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 14:6: &ldquo;Jesus said to him, &lsquo;I am the way, and the truth, and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say seven \"I am\" verses?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 60, '<p dir=\"ltr\">If asked who God is, a Jewish person might respond with Exodus 3:14:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"And God said to Moses, &lsquo;I AM WHO I AM.&rsquo; He said further, &lsquo;Thus you shall say to the Israelites, &ldquo;I AM has sent me to you&rdquo;&rsquo;&rdquo; (Exodus 3:14).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For this reason, the Jews refrained from pronouncing the sacred name YHWH. Thus when Jesus used &ldquo;I am&rdquo; in His declarations, He was associating Himself with God, which the Jews understood as a proclamation of His divinity.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:38:59', '2025-01-08 01:38:59'),
(708, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 14:12: &ldquo;Very truly, I tell you, the one who believes in me will also do the works that I do and, in fact, will do greater works than these, because I am going to the Father.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is considered the greatest deed according to the Jews?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 60, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Two extraordinary events stand out in Jewish history.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Moses parting the Red Sea.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">David defeating Goliath.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These events were so significant that the Jews believed none could surpass them. However, they also held that when the Messiah arrived, even greater deeds than the above two, would be accomplished. Thus, Jesus encouraged belief through His works, which pointed to a greater reality in Him.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:39:41', '2025-01-13 22:31:01'),
(709, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 14:17: &ldquo;This is the Spirit of truth, whom the world cannot receive, because it neither sees him nor knows him. You know him because he abides with you, and he will be in you.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the gifts of the Holy Spirit manifest in people during the Old Testament?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 60, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, the gifts of the Holy Spirit are evident in the Old Testament.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, when Samuel was sent to anoint a new king for Israel after Saul,&nbsp; he initially thought Eliab, Jesse\'s son, was God&rsquo;s chosen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, it was through the Spirit&rsquo;s guidance that Samuel discerned that God had not chosen Eliab (1 Samuel 16:11-14).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:40:19', '2025-01-08 01:40:19'),
(710, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 14:18: &ldquo;I will not leave you orphaned; I am coming to you.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did orphanhood exist at that time?</em></p>', 5, 60, '<p dir=\"ltr\">If a husband died, a widow would often return to her father\'s house, remarry<br>or find work to support herself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Children without parental support were sometimes cared for by relatives but many lived as orphans performing menial work.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:41:01', '2025-01-08 01:41:01'),
(711, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 14:22: &ldquo;Judas (not Iscariot) said to him, &lsquo;Lord, how is it that you will reveal yourself to us, and not to the world?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was Judas (not Iscariot)?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 60, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This disciple is called &ldquo;Judas, son of James&rdquo; by Luke (Luke 6:16). Matthew and Mark refer to him as Thaddeus and some manuscripts also call him Lebbaeus (Textus Receptus).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to early Christian tradition, Judas preached the Gospel in Syria. Eusebius writes that Judas and Thomas shared the Gospel with Abgar, King of Edessa (Ecclesiastical History, 1.13). Judas is believed to have been martyred in Syria.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:41:31', '2025-01-08 01:41:31'),
(712, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 15:2: &ldquo;He removes every branch in me that bears no fruit. Every branch that bears fruit he prunes to make it bear more fruit.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were the vines prunned and prepared?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 61, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Even though it was harvest season, the grape vines that were left uncut yielded less fruit and ripened unevenly.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Careful pruning process is essential to avoid premature fruiting and to ensure the highest quality and quantity during harvest.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:47:40', '2025-01-13 22:31:30'),
(713, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 15:15: &ldquo;I do not call you servants any longer, because the servant does not know what the master is doing; but I have called you friends.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who are called God&rsquo;s friends in the Old Testament?</em></p>', 5, 61, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Abraham: &ldquo;Did you not, O our God, drive out the inhabitants of this land before your people Israel, and give it forever to the descendants of your friend Abraham?&rdquo; (2 Chronicles 20:7).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Moses: &ldquo;Thus the Lord used to speak to Moses face to face, as one speaks to a friend&rdquo; (Exodus 33:11).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Both Abraham and Moses are called &lsquo;friends of God&rsquo; in the Old Testament.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:48:26', '2025-01-08 01:48:26'),
(714, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 15:20: &ldquo;Remember the word that I said to you, &lsquo;Servants are not greater than their master.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who are these servants?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 61, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Slavery was common in the ancient world yet Jewish laws provided for fair treatment and even set slaves free in the sabbatical year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish law also ensured basic rights for slaves. This saying reflects the servant-master relationship known in that era.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:51:00', '2025-01-08 01:51:00'),
(715, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 16:2: &ldquo;They will put you out of the synagogues. Indeed, an hour is coming when those who kill you will think that by doing so they are offering worship to God.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were Christians expelled from synagogues?</em></p>', 5, 62, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the first century, synagogues often met in large homes with rooms arranged around a courtyard where people gathered.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">At the time John&rsquo;s Gospel was written, some Jews had converted to Christianity and were expelled from their homes, a situation which the Jews referred to as being &ldquo;put out of the synagogue.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:55:03', '2025-01-08 01:55:03'),
(716, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 16:7: &ldquo;Nevertheless I tell you the truth: it is to your advantage that I go away, for if I do not go away, the Advocate will not come to you; but if I go, I will send him to you.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the Jews understand when Jesus called the Holy Spirit the &ldquo;Paraclete&rdquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 62, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews offered sacrifices for atonement every morning and evening.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Speak to Aaron and his sons, saying: This is the law of the sin offering. The sin offering shall be slaughtered before the Lord in the place where the burnt offering is slaughtered; it is most holy&rdquo; (Leviticus 6:25).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They refer to this atoning sacrifice as a paraclete. They believe this atoning sacrifice acts as an advocate before God.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Jesus called the Holy Spirit Parakletos (Advocate), it would have reminded the Jews of this sacrificial advocacy.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:58:46', '2025-01-08 01:58:46'),
(717, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 16:8: \"And when he comes, he will prove the world wrong about sin and righteousness and judgement.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is the Holy Spirit said to convict the world of three things?</em></p>', 5, 62, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Roman court, those who committed a great wrong were required to be put under trial&nbsp; three times before giving the final verdit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilate judged Jesus three times for this reason (John 18:33, 19:1, 9). Similarly, the Holy Spirit, acting as our Advocate, convicts the world of three essential truths: sin, righteousness and judgement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 01:59:35', '2025-01-13 22:33:02'),
(718, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Does the Holy Spirit condemn humanity?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 62, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek root for &ldquo;convict the world of sin and judgement&rdquo; is Enengo meaning \'to correct for a specific purpose\'. This correction isn&rsquo;t condemnation but guidance toward divine purpose.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"God corrects Laban to treat Jacob well\" (Genesis 31:42).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"God corrects the nations and brings peace among them\" (Isaiah 2:4).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Holy Spirit&rsquo;s role is to guide humanity toward God&rsquo;s purposes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 02:00:26', '2025-01-08 02:00:26'),
(719, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 16:11: \"The ruler of this world has been condemned.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-03e10e91-7fff-28be-5caa-50c6e8b40d45\">Was the Messiah not to subjected for condemnation for the Jews ?</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 62, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews held that the Messiah would come to judge the world and raise Israel above other nations and he would remain for ever</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their judgement was that Israel would rise above all other lands and no other nation could resist them.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 02:01:08', '2025-01-13 22:35:06'),
(720, '<p><strong>John 16:13: \"When the Spirit of truth comes, he will guide you into all the truth.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How does the Holy Spirit lead to the fullness of truth?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 62, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Roman trials,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">the charge against the accused was read aloud,&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">It is followed by the reading of the Roman law thatis pertained to&nbsp; their offences</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Then the trial is conducted</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;&nbsp;and finally the punishment due is pronounced or declared acquitted.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Advocate, the Holy Spirit, acts similarly by bringing to our conscience the evidence of truth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This guidance is gradual, leading us to the fullness of understanding.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 02:01:45', '2025-01-13 22:36:06'),
(721, '<p><strong>John 16:20: \"Very truly, I tell you, you will weep and mourn, but the world will rejoice; you will have pain, but your pain will turn into joy.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is John&rsquo;s Gospel known as the \'Gospel of Joy\'?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 62, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Throughout John\'s Gospel, we encounter joy expressed in eight key moments:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"The joy of John the Baptist\" (John 3:29)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"The sower rejoicing with the reaper\" (John 4:36)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"The joy of Abraham\" (John 8:56)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"The joy of Jesus\" (John 11:15)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"The joy of the disciples\" (John 15:11)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"The joy in hearing Jesus&rsquo; teaching\" (John 15:11)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"The joy anticipated upon Jesus&rsquo; return\" (John 16:20-24)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\"The joy of seeing the risen Christ\" (John 20:20)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John\'s Gospel celebrates the enduring joy found in Christ, hence it is often called the \'Gospel of Joy\'.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 02:02:24', '2025-01-08 02:02:24'),
(722, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 16:21: &ldquo;When a woman is in labour, she has pain, because her hour has come. But when her child is born, she no longer remembers the anguish because of the joy of having brought a human being into the world.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How does the birth of a child bring happiness?</em></p>', 5, 62, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus&rsquo;s time, when a woman gives birth at home, neighbouring women often gather to assist her. Certain rituals are performed immediately following the birth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The umbilical cord is cut.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The baby is washed and cleaned.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Salt is applied to the baby&rsquo;s body.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The baby is wrapped in cloth.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;On the day you were born, your cord was not cut, nor were you washed with water to cleanse you, nor rubbed with salt, nor wrapped in cloths.&rdquo; (Ezekiel 16:4)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The birth of a child brings great joy to the community, reflecting a profound and shared celebration of life.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 02:02:58', '2025-01-08 02:02:58'),
(723, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Are there no parables in the Gospel of John?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 62, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Gospel of John, longer parables, or parabole, are replaced by shorter metaphors, known as paromiai.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Examples include:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&ldquo;The field is ripe for harvest&rdquo; (John 4:35)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&ldquo;The grain of wheat that falls and dies&rdquo; (John 12:24)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&ldquo;A woman in labour&rdquo; (John 16:21)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&ldquo;The good shepherd&rdquo; (John 10)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&ldquo;The vine&rdquo; (John 15)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Though John\'s Gospel lacks the extended parables found in other Gospels, these shorter metaphors (paromiai) provide significant spiritual insight.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 02:03:28', '2025-01-08 02:03:28'),
(724, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 17:1: &ldquo;After Jesus had spoken these words, he looked up to heaven and said, &lsquo;Father, the hour has come; glorify your Son so that the Son may glorify you.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is Jesus praying for in the seventeenth chapter of John?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 63, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Chapter 17 of John&rsquo;s Gospel records three prayers of Jesus:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jesus prays for Himself.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He prays for His disciples.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He prays for His future followers.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-08 02:11:17', '2025-01-08 02:11:17'),
(725, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 17:20: &ldquo;I ask not only on behalf of these, but also on behalf of those who will believe in me through their word.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is Jesus\'s Last Supper prayer called the Priestly Prayer?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 63, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At Mount Sinai, Aaron was appointed as high priest (Exodus 28:1). He had a priestly prayer to recite before the sacrificial act on the Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur), before the high priest entered the Holy of Holies and offered the sin offering, he prayed on behalf of all Israel, seeking forgiveness for the people&rsquo;s sins in preparation for sacrifice (Hebrews 9:7).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In John 17, Jesus prays to the Father just before offering Himself as the sacrifice for the sins of the world. This is why this prayer is called the Priestly Prayer.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 02:11:56', '2025-01-13 22:36:49'),
(726, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 17:21: &ldquo;That they may all be one. As you, Father, are in me and I am in you, may they also be in us, so that the world may believe that you have sent me.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John pray for unity?</em></p>', 5, 63, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By the late first century, various communities had begun to form:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Hermetic communities following Stoic philosophy</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mandean communities with Gnostic beliefs</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Qumran community or the Essenes</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Johannine community from which the Gospel of John emerged</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The evangelist&rsquo;s prayer for unity likely expresses a desire to bring these diverse communities together in Christ.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 02:12:24', '2025-01-08 02:12:24'),
(727, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 18:1: &ldquo;After Jesus had spoken these words, he went out with his disciples across the Kidron Valley to a place where there was a garden, which he and his disciples entered.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the garden called Gethsemane?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hebrew term \"gat shemanim\" could be translated as&nbsp; \'oil press\'.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name Gethsemane likely originated from this word due to the presence of numerous olive trees there used for oil production.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even today, ancient olive trees still stand as a testament to this historical significance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:34:40', '2025-01-13 22:38:04'),
(728, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 18:13: &ldquo;They took Jesus first to Annas, who was the father-in-law of Caiaphas, the high priest that year.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Caiaphas become the high priest?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The priestly line of Aaron&rsquo;s sons had served in the temple since the inception of priestly class .&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This succession was disrupted by the Babylonian Exile in 587 B.C. However, it was restored during the time of Ezra and Nehemiah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek invasion of Judea in 329 B.C. further interrupted this lineage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Later , Simeon, the leader of the Maccabees, assumed leadership and the high priesthood among the Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Judea fell under Roman control, the appointment of the high priest became a prerogative of Caesar. Thus, Ciaphas became the high priest by the appointment of Caesar.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:35:18', '2025-01-13 22:38:45'),
(729, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 18:19: &ldquo;Then the high priest questioned Jesus about his disciples and about his teaching.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the high priest skeptical of Jesus\'s teachings?</em></p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus and His disciples hailed from Galilee, a region adjacent to Gentile lands.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, the teachings emanating from Galilee were met with suspicion by those in Judea, who questioned their purity and adherence to Jewish orthodox&nbsp; tradition.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The high priest likely doubted whether Jesus&rsquo; teachings had been tainted by pagan influences.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:36:31', '2025-01-13 22:39:41'),
(730, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 18:24: &ldquo;Annas bound Jesus and sent him to Caiaphas.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the high priesthood handed down?</em></p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It was not until 174 B.C. that the high priesthood was formally conferred upon the tribe of Levi.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Following Onias III&rsquo;s tenure in 174 B.C., a man named Jason acquired the high priesthood by bribing King Antiochus Epiphanes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice continued with Menelaus, who also gained the position through similar means.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During the Maccabean period, the Hasmonean family held both the high priesthood and the kingship.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Antigonus, the high priest, was executed by King Herod in 37 B.C., leading to the Roman emperor assuming control over the appointment of the high priest.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:38:03', '2025-01-08 05:38:03'),
(731, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 18:28: &ldquo;Then they took Jesus from Caiaphas to Pilate\'s headquarters. It was early in the morning. They themselves did not enter the headquarters, so as to avoid ritual defilement and to be able to eat the Passover.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why didn\'t the Jews enter the praetorium?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews held a belief that Gentiles used to&nbsp; bury corpses within their homes, rendering such spaces ritually impure for the Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, they were generally reluctant to enter Gentile residences, as doing so could lead to a state of&nbsp; impurity that would prevent them from observing Passover.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:39:02', '2025-01-13 22:40:15'),
(732, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Caiaphas send Jesus to Pilate instead of Herod?</em></p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The high priest was historically appointed by the king of Judah until 6 B.C.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, when Caesar appointed the governor in 6 B.C., he granted Roman governors the authority to appoint the high priest.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, it was likely that Pilate appointed Caiaphas as the high priest. By sending Jesus to Pilate, Caiaphas aimed to assert his own authority over the situation.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:39:43', '2025-01-08 05:39:43'),
(733, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 18:28: &ldquo;Then they took Jesus from Caiaphas to Pilate\'s headquarters. It was early in the morning. They themselves did not enter the headquarters, so as to avoid ritual defilement and to be able to eat the Passover.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Jesus taken to Pilate at dawn?</em></p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">From 3:00 a.m. to 11:00 a.m., Pilate was present in the praetorium to engage with the people.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman governor could only meet the populace at other locations than his palace at Caesaria only on a few days each year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This scheduling is the reason why the trial of Jesus was concluded by the highpriest during the night, allowing for His immediate transfer to Pilate in the morning.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:40:19', '2025-01-13 22:41:06'),
(734, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 18:31: &ldquo;Pilate said to them, &lsquo;Take him yourselves and judge him according to your law.&rsquo; The Jews replied, &lsquo;We are not permitted to put anyone to death.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Pilate initially refuse to put Jesus on trial?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilate&rsquo;s initial reluctance stemmed from the types of crimes he typically addressed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There were two categories of trials in Judea at that time:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Religious crimes&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"3\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Political crimes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sanhedrin was responsible for adjudicating religious offences, while Pilate, as Procurator of Judea, primarily dealt with treason charges.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilate&rsquo;s refusal reflected the division of judicial authority, as he was not inclined to intervene in matters that fell within the purview of the Jewish authorities.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:41:19', '2025-01-13 22:42:08'),
(735, '<p><em>Did the law allow the Jews to carry out executions?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Following the elevation of Judea to a Roman province in A.D. 6, Coponius was appointed as the first Procurator (as noted by Josephus B.J 2.117).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">With Coponius&rsquo;s appointment, Rome has taken the authority for capital punishment from Jews and place the&nbsp; authority in the hands of the Roman Procurator.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, while the Sanhedrin held some jurisdiction, the ultimate power to impose the death sentence rested with the Roman authorities.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:42:03', '2025-01-13 22:43:10'),
(736, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 18:33: &ldquo;Then Pilate entered the headquarters again, summoned Jesus, and asked him, &lsquo;Are you the King of the Jews?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Pilate get to Jerusalem for Passover?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Following the replacement of Archelaus as king of&nbsp; of Judea, Pilate was appointed by the emperor as the governer. Thus, Pilate&rsquo;s official residence was in Caesarea.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During Passover, Jerusalem saw an influx of hundreds of thousands of Jews, often leading to civil unrest. Pilate\'s presence in Jerusalem during this festival was a strategic move to maintain order and quell potential riots.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:42:38', '2025-01-13 22:44:52'),
(737, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What was Pilate\'s praetorium?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Praetorium was a palace constructed by King Herod and it was there&nbsp; Roman authorities used to&nbsp; staywhen they visitJerusalem from Rome . That is why Pilate was also given Praetorium as his residence in Jerusalem as he was also a Roman delegate.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The governors used to&nbsp; sit on the judgment seat known as the Bema and pronounce verdicts.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some sources suggest that the praetorium was located within the Antonia Fortress, which is situated to the north of the Temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:43:35', '2025-01-13 22:45:46'),
(738, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What were Pilate\'s powers?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 64, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilate was the Head of the Roman army stationed at the Antonia Fortress.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He possessed the authority to confirm or reject sentences passed by the Sanhedrin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Rome retained the power to appoint the high priest, and it is said that Pilate even kept the garments of the high priest.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since he resided in Caesarea, he would come to Jerusalem during major festivals to maintain order.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:44:02', '2025-01-08 05:44:02'),
(739, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:1: &ldquo;Then Pilate took Jesus and had him flogged. And the soldiers wove a crown of thorns and put it on his head.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus wear the crown of thorns?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The crown of thorns was placed on Jesus&rsquo;s head as a mocking gesture by the soldiers. They crafted it from Acanthus spinosus, a thorny plant that was commonly found in Palestine.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This crown was meant to humiliate Jesus, and crowning with the thorns served as a method to augment the&nbsp; pain He endured on the cross, where He could not rest His head against it for comfort.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:46:03', '2025-01-13 22:47:08'),
(740, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:2-3: &ldquo;The soldiers wove a crown of thorns and put it on his head, and they dressed him in a purple robe. They kept coming up to him, saying, &lsquo;Hail, King of the Jews!&rsquo; and they struck him on the face.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What red robe did Jesus wear?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The robe Jesus was draped in was the Himation Prophuron, a royal garment in the Macedonian style(Paludamentum).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This style was worn by Persian kings and later adopted by Roman emperors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The garment was secured by a pin on the right shoulder and draped across the body, passing under the left arm.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Pliny, members of the senatorial class in the Roman Empire wore garments adorned with a broad purple stripe known as the latus clavus (Pliny, Natural History, 9.63n7087).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:46:54', '2025-01-13 22:47:44'),
(741, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:10: &ldquo;So Pilate said to him, &lsquo;You will not speak to me? Do you not know that I have power to release you, and power to crucify you?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Pilate have the authority to judge Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilate held two important positions:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Procurator (Epitropos) the title for the head of Roman auxiliary troops in Palestine.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Prefect (Eparchos), which granted him the authority to collect taxes and render judgments.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:47:42', '2025-01-13 22:48:10'),
(742, '<p><strong>John 19:12: &ldquo;From then on, Pilate tried to release him, but the Jews cried out, &lsquo;If you release this man, you are no friend of Caesar; everyone who claims to be a king sets himself against the emperor.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews try to intimidate Pilate by saying &ldquo;he was not Caesar\'s friend&rdquo;?</em></p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews was trying to bring to the memory of Pilate, the name of Sejanus, a general of Caesar who had been deposed in A.D. 31 due to his antagonism towards the Jewish people.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By referencing Sejanus, the Jews likely intended to convey to Pilate that a similar fate could befall him if he chose to oppose them.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:49:00', '2025-01-13 22:49:03'),
(743, '<p><strong>John 19:17: &ldquo;And carrying the cross by himself, he went out to what is called The Place of the Skull, which in Hebrew is called Golgotha.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How are Golgotha and Calvary connected?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Golgotha is the final elevation of the Gihon Hills, stretching from the site of the court gate in Jerusalem to the northern side of Zion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Calvary, a term often used interchangeably with Golgotha, refers to a specific area where stone was quarried from the mountain for the construction purposes..&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over time, Calvary evolved into a garden and a site of crucifixion.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:49:57', '2025-01-13 22:49:35'),
(744, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:18: &ldquo;There they crucified him, and with him two others, one on either side, with Jesus between them.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When did crucifixion get abolished?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The crucifixion of Jesus occurred after a series of events that culminated in His trial and condemnation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Notably, it was at the Battle of the Milvian Bridge in A.D. 312 that Emperor Constantine recognised the sign of the cross and achieved victory.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This victory of the emporer Constantine t led to his eventual recognition of the significance of the cross, and He abolished&nbsp; the punishment of death by crucifixion.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:50:46', '2025-01-13 22:50:46'),
(745, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:20: &ldquo;Many of the Jews read this inscription, because the place where Jesus was crucified was near the city; and it was written in Hebrew, in Latin, and in Greek.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Golgotha chosen as the location to crucify Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Roman law, crucifixion was to be conducted as&nbsp; public punishment intended to serve as a warning to others.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Golgotha, situated outside the city of Jerusalem and close to a major thoroughfare, was chosen to maximise visibility and public humiliation so that it might be a warning for others.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This location became notorious for the piles of bones from those who had been crucified there. So, it was also called the place of the skull.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:51:43', '2025-01-13 22:51:48'),
(746, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:21: &ldquo;Then the chief priests of the Jews said to Pilate, &lsquo;Do not write, &lsquo;The King of the Jews,&rsquo; but, &lsquo;This man said, I am the King of the Jews.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Pilate put the title \'King of the Jews\' on Jesus&rsquo;s cross?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews and the Gentiles of that time even beleived that the Messiah is to be originated from the Jews as stated in John 4:22, &ldquo;You worship what you do not know; we worship what we know, for salvation is from the Jews.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilate was unknowingly proclaiming&nbsp; a profound truth in this act of keeping a banner on the cross - : salvation originates from the Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilate unknowingly proclaimed&nbsp; through the INRI inscription on the cross (Iesus Nazarenus Rex Iudaeorum), that the Messiah originates from the Jews and thereby highlighting Jesus Christ as the Saviour for both Jews and Gentiles.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:52:32', '2025-01-13 22:54:08'),
(747, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:23: &ldquo;When the soldiers had crucified Jesus, they took his clothes and divided them into four parts, one for each soldier. They also took his tunic; now the tunic was seamless, woven in one piece from the top.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was Jesus\'s seamless robe?</em></p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The chiton was a garment traditionally worn by Jews close to the body, beneath the outer garment known as the himation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus&rsquo;s garment, referred to as the tunic in this passage, was woven from a single piece of cloth. It featured openings cut out for the head and arms, making it seamless&mdash;arraphos in Greek.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The high priest\'s robe is also seamless (see Josephus, Antiquities, III.VII.4; 161).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:53:19', '2025-01-08 05:53:19'),
(748, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:23: &ldquo;When the soldiers had crucified Jesus, they took his clothes and divided them into four parts, one for each soldier. They also took his tunic; now the tunic was seamless, woven in one piece from the top.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was special about His robe?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Although visually unremarkable, Jesus\'s robe was significant in its craftsmanship.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He wore the typical full-length robe worn by the poor Jews of His time.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:54:02', '2025-01-08 05:54:02'),
(749, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:24: &ldquo;So they said to one another, &lsquo;Let us not tear it, but cast lots for it to see who will get it.&rsquo; This was to fulfil what the scripture says, &lsquo;They divided my clothes among themselves, and for my clothing they cast lots.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why didn&rsquo;t the soldiers tear Jesus\'s robe?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, tearing the high priest\'s robe was considered a blasphemous act.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in Leviticus 21:10, &ldquo;The priest who is chief among his brothers, on whose head the anointing oil was poured, and who has been consecrated to wear the garments, shall not let the hair of his head hang loose or tear his garments.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since Jesus is the high priest of the new covenant, His robe should not be torn. This also emphasises His role as High priest of the New covenant.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:54:48', '2025-01-13 22:56:00'),
(750, '<p><strong>John 19:26: &ldquo;When Jesus saw his mother and the disciple whom he loved standing beside her, he said to his mother, &lsquo;Woman, here is your son.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus insult His mother by calling her &lsquo;woman&rsquo;?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus addressed His mother using the term gynai, a respectful title in the Ancient Near East.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This term can be challenging to translate accurately into many languages, including English. But in original culture the term it carries connotations of honour rather than disrespect.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Furthermore, the term &ldquo;behold&rdquo; (hinneh) is often employed in scripture to preface significant declarations (see Jeremiah 6:21; 9:6; 10:18). Jesus proclaims Mary as Mother using the same &ldquo;behold&rdquo; (hinneh)&nbsp; suggesting that this&nbsp; message to humanity is one of profound importance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, when Jesus says, &ldquo;Behold your mother,&rdquo; He imparts a message of utmost reverence and importance.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:55:48', '2025-01-13 22:56:41'),
(751, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:27: &ldquo;Then he said to the disciple, &lsquo;Here is your mother.&rsquo; And from that hour the disciple took her into his own home.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the first century Christians believe in the assumption of the Holy Mother?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Following Jesus&rsquo; death, His Holy Mother was entrusted to the care of John and it is believed she died in Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From the first century there was a prevailing belief that the souls of the righteous were taken to heaven with their bodies.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This belief is alluded to by Epiphanius in the fourth century (see Epiphanius Panarion 78.10-11, 23) and is clearly articulated in fifth-century Syriac manuscripts as well as the Gelasian Decree.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:56:40', '2025-01-08 05:56:40'),
(752, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:34: &ldquo;But one of the soldiers pierced his side with a spear, and at once blood and water came out.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What weapon was used to pierce Jesus&rsquo;s side?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The soldier pierced Jesus with a weapon known as the Longhe - lancea, a Latin term for a spear.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This weapon was typically a wooden staff about three and a half feet long, with an iron tip.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:57:19', '2025-01-08 05:57:19'),
(753, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Who is the person who pierced Jesus\'s side?</em></p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Gospel of John, one of the soldiers thrust a spear into Jesus\'s side. In the Acts of Pilate, believed to originate in the fourth century, this soldier is identified as Longinus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name Longinus is derived from the Latin word for \'spearman\'.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is said that Longinus, who was blind in one eye, regained his sight that day and later became a follower of Christ. He ultimately became a martyr in Caesarea around A.D. 58.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:57:57', '2025-01-08 05:57:57'),
(754, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:38: &ldquo;After these things, Joseph of Arimathea, who was a disciple of Jesus, though a secret one because of his fear of the Jews, asked Pilate to let him take away the body of Jesus. Pilate gave him permission; so he came and removed the body.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Joseph of Arimathea take the body of Jesus?</em></p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">It was possible&nbsp; to receive the body of a crucified person for burial, although normally&nbsp; no one would come forward to do so.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Romans soldiers generally hid the bodies of those executed. However, the Holy Mother and a few others were present to receive the body of Jesus. In that era, burying the dead was regarded as a pious act. Hence, Joseph of Arimathea requested permission from Pilate to procure the body of Jesus.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:58:31', '2025-01-13 22:57:38'),
(755, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was Jesus\'s tomb owned by Joseph of Arimathea?</em></p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">After Jesus\'s resurrection, the tomb became a place of worship for Christians.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 164, Emperor Hadrian transformed it into a temple dedicated to Jupiter in an effort to suppress Christianity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name of the owner likely remained associated with the grave as a memorial, affirming that the tomb of Jesus is indeed that of Joseph of Arimathea.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:59:06', '2025-01-08 05:59:06');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(756, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:39: &ldquo;Nicodemus, who had first come to Jesus by night, also came, bringing a mixture of myrrh and aloes, weighing about a hundred pounds.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How much did the hundred pounds of spices brought by Nicodemus weigh?</em></p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek term used for &lsquo;pounds&rsquo; is&nbsp;<img src=\"https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXcgVksKgJFLrw6tIV4MraGL0hnAAtUx-SHPM_2zFydHrYc1uR25XItyMdqsO0s48hjgEbJKmmbGCR8rrWyOKf3jwMMZvPlRJbJSPVxH34Wt7T9w6IQ3EQGL3_n-lA-AUEAH6RfhCMuscxBnGQvxr2KeCp9v?key=EGYgbpsCnlKmfZ1GTETMNQ\" width=\"55\" height=\"17\">.&rdquo; A hundred <img src=\"https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXflsFiScXiMNlzf0BEsHJtmMUjCADnvFmLr4RJWEemTFouOalgDAWNG_eWV2svgdg4KmvFYczp1Jof6W0TI4sPbxCbdWNeppxaDJGL--OjBq-v8VVLqT2U7HSabv1sOSjGxuezg78TrVUm_BVD3DlVSjSPx?key=EGYgbpsCnlKmfZ1GTETMNQ\" width=\"55\" height=\"17\"> amount to approximately 64.35 pounds or about 30 kilograms. Such a generous offering exemplifies the importance of honouring Jesus in death by giving Him a lavish burial.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 05:59:39', '2025-01-08 05:59:39'),
(757, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 19:41: &ldquo;Now there was a garden in the place where he was crucified, and in the garden there was a new tomb, in which no one had ever been buried.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the tomb come to be located in the garden?</em></p>', 5, 65, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The tomb was cut from a stone in what had been an abandoned quarry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over time, soil and seeds washed in by rainwater allowed vegetation to flourish, transforming the quarry into a garden filled with trees and plants.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Small burial niches, known as Kokhim tombs, were also carved into the stone walls.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:00:08', '2025-01-08 06:00:08'),
(758, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 20:7: &ldquo;He saw the linen wrappings lying there, and the handkerchief that had been on his head not lying with the linen wrappings but rolled up in a place by itself.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does the folded handkerchief symbolise?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The folded handkerchief offers two significant insights:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">It indicates that Jesus had risen and no one had taken His body away.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In Jewish custom, if a person leaves a folded napkin on the table, it signifies that the meal is not over and that they intend to return.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This implies that the risen Christ will return as the judge.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:01:34', '2025-01-08 06:01:34'),
(759, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 20:19: &ldquo;It was evening on that day, the first day of the week, and the doors of the house where the disciples had met were locked for fear of the Jews. Jesus came and stood among them and said, &lsquo;Peace be with you.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus say \"Peace be with you\" multiple times after His resurrection?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the waning days of Jesus&rsquo;s public ministry, tensions were rising in Palestine with the looming threat of armed revolt against Roman authority. Jewish factions, like the Zealots, believed that revolution could restore peace.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Inspired by the battles of the Maccabees, they were stirred by visions of triumph.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the resounding message of &ldquo;Peace be with you&rdquo; from Jesus post-resurrection signifies that true peace can only be attained through the cross.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:02:45', '2025-01-08 06:02:45'),
(760, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 20:22: \"When he had said this, he breathed on them and said to them, \'Receive the Holy Spirit.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How does receiving the Holy Spirit differ in the Old Testament and the New Testament?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament the Holy Spirit was imparted to individuals for specific purposes.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Balaam received the Spirit to prophesy (Numbers 23:7).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Samson received the Spirit to defeat the Philistines (Judges 15:14).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in the New Testament the Holy Spirit is gifted to individuals to remain with them for eternity. This is why Jesus instructed His disciples to receive the Holy Spirit at Pentecost.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:03:29', '2025-01-08 06:03:29'),
(761, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the Jews understand the concept of breathing?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At the time, respiration wasn&rsquo;t understood as it is today.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Alexandrian Medical School&rsquo;s studies, air (&pi;&nu;&omicron;ή) became breath (&pi;&nu;&epsilon;ῦ&mu;&alpha;) once it entered the heart.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When air is inhaled and moves from the lungs into the heart, it was thought to become the breath of life (&pi;&nu;&epsilon;ῦ&mu;&alpha;).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, breath from the heart was seen as the true breath.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:04:08', '2025-01-08 06:04:08'),
(762, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 20:26: \"A week later his disciples were again in the house, and Thomas was with them. Although the doors were shut, Jesus came and stood among them and said, \'Peace be with you.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does John mention Jesus reappeared after eight days?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">When John wrote his Gospel, the Sunday following the Sabbath was observed as the Lord&rsquo;s Day in the early Church. Jesus first appeared to His disciples on the first day of the week.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;That evening, on the first day of the week, the disciples, while they were afraid of the Jews, were gathered together, and Jesus came and stood among them, saying, &lsquo;Peace be with you&rsquo;&rdquo; (John 20:19).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The next Sunday, or the eighth day, Jesus reappeared, signifying the importance of the Lord&rsquo;s Day.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:04:44', '2025-01-08 06:04:44'),
(763, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 20:27: \"Then he said to Thomas, \'Put your finger here and see my hands. Reach out your hand and put it in my side.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus ask Thomas to touch Him?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman soldiers had checked Jesus&rsquo;s death by piercing His side with a spear.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"But one of the soldiers pierced his side with a spear\" (John 19:34).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To verify Jesus was alive, Thomas was invited to touch His wound to confirm Jesus&rsquo;s physical resurrection.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:05:18', '2025-01-08 06:05:18'),
(764, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why does John portray Thomas as an unbeliever?</em></p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At the close of the first century, the heresy of Docetism emerged, claiming that Jesus&rsquo;s body was not fully human but rather heavenly, unable to experience physical pain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to this view, His suffering on the cross was not truly bodily suffering.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In response, John highlights Thomas\'s unbelief as evidence against Docetism, showing that the wounds in Jesus&rsquo;s hands and side are real.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John confirms that Jesus\'s suffering on the cross was fully human and that He endured the same physical pain any human would have faced in His place.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:05:55', '2025-01-08 06:05:55'),
(765, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did John include Thomas&rsquo;s act of touching Jesus&rsquo;s wounds?</em></p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John included Thomas&rsquo;s act of touching Jesus&rsquo;s wounds as a profound witness to the resurrection:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Peter and the other disciple believed without seeing (John 20:3-10).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary Magdalene saw the risen Jesus.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Thomas touched the risen Jesus.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thomas&rsquo;s touch provided tangible evidence that Jesus resurrected from the dead.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:06:32', '2025-01-08 06:06:32'),
(766, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Thomas insist on touching Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At Calvary, the soldiers confirmed Jesus was dead by piercing Him with a spear (John 19:31-34).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John highlights Thomas&rsquo;s insistence on touching Jesus&rsquo;s wounds to show that true recognition of the living Jesus comes through personal experience.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:07:00', '2025-01-08 06:07:00'),
(767, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did John intentionally portray Thomas as an unbeliever?</em></p>', 5, 66, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In John&rsquo;s Gospel, each disciple recognises Jesus progressively. For instance:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Nathanael recognised Jesus when He mentioned seeing him under the fig tree.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary Magdalene recognised Jesus when He called her by name.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The disciples on the road to Emmaus recognised Him in the breaking of the bread.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The disciples by the Sea of Tiberius recognised Him when they caught 153 fish.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, Thomas recognises Jesus by His wounds, illustrating a unique and intentional progression in John\'s narrative style.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:07:29', '2025-01-08 06:07:29'),
(768, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 21:2: \"Simon Peter, Thomas called the Twin, Nathanael of Cana in Galilee, the sons of Zebedee, and two others of his disciples were together.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Thomas have a twin brother?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"Didymos\" means \"twin,\" but there is no indication that Thomas had a twin.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the Hebrew word \"Tomah\" (Tam) signifies not only \"twin\" but also \"unblemished\" or \"without defect.\" It translates as whole, innocent or sincere.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Tam translates as whole or unblemished. As a character description it means innocent, sincere or simple. In the Bible, the young Jacob is an &ldquo;ish tam&rdquo;, a simple man, who sat in tents (Genesis 25:27).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When translated into Greek, it is likely that the meaning \"twin\" was intended.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:08:55', '2025-01-08 06:08:55'),
(769, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What does Nathanael of Cana indicate?</em></p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In John&rsquo;s Gospel Jesus performs His first miracle in Cana (John 2), and Nathanael from Cana is mentioned again in chapter 21.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This suggests that the twenty-first chapter of the Gospel of John serves as the epilogue to the Gospel.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:10:05', '2025-01-08 06:10:05'),
(770, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was there anything special about the number 153?</em></p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time, 153 was believed to be the number of fish species in the sea.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Also, the sum of numbers from 1 to 17 is 153, symbolising completeness to the Jewish mind, as both 10 (representing the Commandments) and 7 (the number of creation days) were whole numbers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus 153 was considered a perfect number, symbolising Jesus&rsquo;s complete fulfilment.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:10:46', '2025-01-08 06:10:46'),
(771, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 21:4: \"Just after daybreak, Jesus stood on the beach; but the disciples did not know that it was Jesus.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews fish at night?</em></p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, fishing was done at night. Fish trading occurred early in the morning. To ensure freshness, fish like minnows were caught at night, as they lacked preservation methods to keep fish fresh for extended periods.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Night fishing also yielded a greater catch due to fish gathering near the surface because the sea gets cool and dark.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:11:26', '2025-01-08 06:11:26'),
(772, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 21:7: \"That disciple whom Jesus loved said to Peter, \'It is the Lord!\' When Simon Peter heard that it was the Lord, he put on some clothes, for he was naked, and jumped into the sea.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Peter go fishing unclothed?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish men of that period commonly wore two main types of clothing:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A sleeveless inner garment.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A long-sleeved outer coat.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was customary to remove the outer coat during work to prevent hindrance. So, it was likely that Peter was only wearing his inner garment while fishing, which would mean that he was &ldquo;naked&rdquo; by customary standards.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:12:06', '2025-01-08 06:12:06'),
(773, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 21:8: \"But the other disciples came in the boat, dragging the net full of fish, for they were not far from the land, only about a hundred yards off.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the disciples drag the net?</em></p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The net was filled with a school of 153 large fish, estimated to weigh around 125 kilograms (300 pounds). Such a heavy load would have been challenging to lift into the boat, so they opted to drag it through the water as they approached shore.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:12:45', '2025-01-08 06:12:45'),
(774, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 21:11: \"So Simon Peter went aboard and hauled the net ashore, full of large fish, a hundred and fifty-three of them; and though there were so many, the net was not torn.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the significance of the number of fish?</em></p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The number 153 has various symbolic meanings drawn from biblical traditions:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Some Jews believed there were 153 species of fish in the sea.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In Jewish tradition, the name of Jehovah was mentioned 153 times in the law.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mathematically, 153 is a \"Triangular Number\" (1+2+3+4+5...+17 = 153), similar to the triangular representation of the number 666 in Revelation 13:18.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Christian symbolism, the 153 fish in the net represent the universal Church, symbolising the gathering of all kinds.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:13:27', '2025-01-08 06:13:27'),
(775, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 21:15: \"When they had finished breakfast, Jesus said to Simon Peter, \'Simon son of John, do you love me more than these?\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus ask Peter the same question thrice?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, but there were subtle linguistic shifts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In His first two questions, Jesus used the term agape for love, signifying unconditional love.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the third question, however, He used phileo, which denotes brotherly affection.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Peter responded with \'phileo\' each time, signifying his affection. Jesus, in turn, lowered His expectations to meet Peter&rsquo;s response the third time.</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:14:08', '2025-01-08 06:14:08'),
(776, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 21:17: &ldquo;Lord, you know everything; you know that I love you.&rdquo; Jesus said to him, &ldquo;Feed my sheep.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does John highlight Peter&rsquo;s authority at the end of his gospel?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Unlike the Synoptic Gospels, John does not present Peter as the leading disciple in his early chapters. Notably:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Peter was not the first disciple called; it was Andrew who brought Peter to Jesus.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Peter initially resisted Jesus when He offered to wash Peter&rsquo;s feet.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Peter is not described as the disciple whom Jesus loved the most.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jesus rebukes Peter for drawing his sword during His arrest.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While Peter&rsquo;s role is prominent, his full authority is only established in the gospel&rsquo;s final passages.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:14:45', '2025-01-08 06:14:45'),
(777, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>John 21:20: &ldquo;Peter turned and saw the disciple whom Jesus loved following them.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was John the disciple whom Jesus loved?</em></p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Among the seven disciples who went fishing on the shores of Tiberias after the resurrection, one is referred to as &ldquo;the disciple whom Jesus loved.&rdquo; This figure, traditionally identified as John, appears to have been alive when the Fourth Gospel was written. These descriptions collectively point to John as this beloved disciple.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:15:24', '2025-01-08 06:15:24'),
(778, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How does Holy Communion serve as a memorial?</em></p>', 5, 67, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Every day, the Jews placed frankincense and salt in the Temple of Jerusalem as a perpetual memorial (Lehem Hapanim - the Bread of the Faces).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Leviticus:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;You shall take fine flour and bake twelve loaves of it; two-tenths of an ephah shall be in each loaf. They shall be set in two rows, six in a row, on the golden table before the Lord. Pure frankincense shall be placed with each row, as a token offering with the bread, a food offering to the Lord&rdquo; (Leviticus 24:5-7).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This bread reminded the Jews of God&rsquo;s covenant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, the Holy Communion represents a moment when God remembers us with boundless mercy and draws us into His eternal love.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-08 06:15:53', '2025-01-08 06:15:53'),
(779, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:3: &ldquo;I too decided, after investigating everything carefully from the very first, to write an orderly account for you, most excellent Theophilus.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was Theophilus, the person to whom the Gospel of Luke was addressed?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke dedicates his Gospel and his apostolic work to Theophilus (Luke 1:3; Acts 1:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Theophilus is a name of pagan origin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the customs of the time, it was common for an author to dedicate their work to someone who assisted in its publication.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is plausible that Theophilus played a significant role even financially&nbsp; in helping Luke to compile his Gospel.<strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-09db9265-7fff-7a4c-1320-6763cb707492\"><br></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:00:53', '2025-01-20 06:02:02'),
(780, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:5: &ldquo;In the days of King Herod of Judea, there was a priest named Zechariah, who belonged to the priestly order of Abijah. His wife was a descendant of Aaron, and her name was Elizabeth.&rdquo;</strong><br><br><em>During what period did Herod rule as king?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod\'s father, Antipater, was the first ruler of Judea appointed by Caesar. During the civil war between Caesar and Pompey, Antipater sided with Caesar. His loyalty paid off when Caesar won, leading to increased influence in Judea.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In 47 BCE, Antipater was appointed as the procurator of Judea by Julius Caesar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the same year., Rome appointed Herod to assist his father. Impressed by his governance, Mark Antony granted Herod the title of \'King of Judea\' in 40 B.C.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:01:59', '2025-01-20 06:02:31'),
(781, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Which number was assigned to the priestly division of Abijah?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to King David\'s division, the Jews had 24 priestly orders (1 Chronicles 24:1-19) to serve in the Jerusalem Temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">. Each group could serve for two weeks, which was common during Passover, Pentecost and the Feast of Tabernacles.Abijah\'s order was the eighth priestly order</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The cycle began with the first week of Nisan( the first month) and the first week of Tishri, (the seventh month).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to this cycle, it was probable&nbsp; that Abijah\'s priests might have ministered in the temple during the month of&nbsp; May and November.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:03:10', '2025-01-20 06:03:24'),
(782, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Were all the priests required to marry from the priestly line like Zechariah?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Priests were not mandated to marry women of priestly lineage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, they were prohibited from marrying a divorced woman or a woman engaged in prostitution.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in Leviticus 21:7, &ldquo;They shall not marry a harlot, or one who is defiled, or one who has been forsaken by her husband. For the priest must be holy before God.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:03:51', '2025-01-13 23:03:51'),
(783, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was Elizabeth\'s lineage significant?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Zacharias was a priest, and priests were only permitted to marry within the Jewish race.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the lineage of the priest\'s wife was significant, which is why Elizabeth is described as being from&nbsp; Aaron\'s lineage.<strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-1cb989c9-7fff-2587-e207-66a8a96ed6be\">&nbsp;<br></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:04:27', '2025-01-20 06:04:28'),
(784, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>When did Herod become known as \'King of the Jews\'?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod was officially given the title of \'King of the Jews\' in A.D. 40, although he had authority over parts of Palestine before then.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This title was conferred upon him by Mark Antony, the Roman emperor, as a reward for his assistance in stopping King Antigonus during Antony\'s war with the Parthians.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:05:00', '2025-01-13 23:05:00'),
(785, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:6: &ldquo;They were righteous in the sight of God, and kept the commandments and ordinances of the Lord without fault.&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong><br><br><em>Where did Elizabeth and Zechariah live?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Priests who did not hold significant&nbsp; positions in the Jerusalem temple&nbsp; typically resided outside the city.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Zechariah\'s residence was located in Ein Karem, approximately five miles west of Jerusalem, which is about 80 miles from Nazareth.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:05:34', '2025-01-20 22:28:08'),
(786, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:5: &ldquo;When Herod was king of Judah, there was a priest in the tribe of Abijah named Zacharias, whose wife was Elizabeth, one of the daughters of Aaron.&rdquo; </strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Which number was allotted to the priestly tribe of Abijah?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Levitical priests were organised&nbsp; into 24 divisions (1 Chronicles 24:4-6).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, following the Babylonian exile, only four of these groups returned to Israel (Ezra 2:36-39).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After the exile, those who were returned&nbsp; were re-divided into 24 groups once more. Abijah\'s group was designated as the eighthone in this grouping.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The temple service was scheduled for one year with each group receiving the opportunity to serve twice a year.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Therefore, it was during tribe Abijah\'s ministry that Zechariah&nbsp; was chosen by lot&nbsp; to offer incense.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:06:23', '2025-01-20 06:07:07'),
(787, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:8-9: &ldquo;Once when he was serving as priest before God and his section was on duty, he was chosen by lot, according to the custom of the priesthood, to enter the sanctuary of the Lord and offer incense.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the prescribed lot mentioned here?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time, there were two types of priests:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Chief Priests: Chief priests were members of the Sanhedrin who assisted the high priest in administrative matters and supported the Roman Emperor&rsquo;s appointment of the high priest. For example, &ldquo;the chief priests and the elders persuaded the crowds to ask for Barabbas and to have Jesus killed&rdquo; (Matthew 27:20).&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Priests: These were individuals typically residing outside Jerusalem, dedicated to the temple\'s cultic practices, with little involvement in its administration.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Zechariah belonged to this second class of priests, who could serve only when the lot fell in his name. .</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:07:51', '2025-01-20 06:06:03'),
(788, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How were the priests appointed to minister in the temple for the sacrifices?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Priests were divided into 24 groups. Each group was allotted two weeks of service per year.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this way, 48 weeks in a year were covered by alternating groups.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The remaining weeks were reserved for major festivals (e.g., Passover, Tabernacles and Pentecost), during which all priests would serve collectively.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:09:02', '2025-01-13 23:09:02'),
(789, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What role did Zechariah play in carrying out the temple\'s rituals?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><br>The daily temple ritual included the Tamid service (ref. m. Tamid 6.37.3), conducted both in the morning and the evening. It involved six parts.<br><br></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The priest offered incense after bowing in reverence.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He then entered the space where the congregation stood (Hekal), proceeding from the holy area.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">He gave the priestly blessing (Numbers 6:24-26).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The lamb was offered as a burnt sacrifice on the altar.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Trumpets sounded in harmony with the drink offering.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The people bowed as the Hallelujah Psalms and trumpets filled the air.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Zechariah was appointed to perform this ritual.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:09:45', '2025-01-13 23:09:45'),
(790, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Where did Zechariah offer incense?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Zechariah&rsquo;s duty led him to offer incense within the inner sanctuary, or Naos, just before the Holy of Holies. This sacred space held three key items.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A censer for incense</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Menorah</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A table for the showbread</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A curtain separated this area from the Holy of Holies.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:10:22', '2025-01-13 23:10:22'),
(791, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What materials were used for incense?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">God revealed to Moses the components of the holy incense.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;And the Lord said to Moses: &lsquo;Take sweet spices, stacte, and onycha, and galbanum, sweet spices with pure frankincense; of each there shall be an equal part&rsquo;&rdquo; (Exodus 30:34).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This incense also included a small portion of salt.&ldquo;And make an incense blended as by the perfumer, seasoned with salt, pure and holy&rdquo; (Exodus 30:35).</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:10:58', '2025-01-13 23:10:58'),
(792, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:9: \"He was chosen by lot, according to the custom of the priesthood, to enter the sanctuary of the Lord and offer incense.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where is the altar of incense located in the Jerusalem temple?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The altar used for incense offerings was built following God&rsquo;s instructions to Moses (Exodus 30).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Positioned near the Holy of Holies (Hekel) before the veil separating it from the Holy of Holies. (Exodus 40:5)&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The incense had to pass through the veil into the Holy of Holies, so that it is acceptable to the Lord. .</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:11:40', '2025-01-13 23:11:40'),
(793, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What did the offering in the temple consist of?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The incense (ketoret) offered in the temple contained thirteen distinct spices.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Four of these spices were specifically instructed by God to Moses through the Law (Exodus 30:34).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was believed that God communicated the remainder to Moses orally.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The thirteen ingredients were: (1) Stacte, (2) Onycha, (3) Galbanum, (4) Frankincense, (5) Myrrh, (6) Cassia, (7) Spikenard, (8) Saffron, (9) Costus, (10) Aromatic bark, (11) Cinnamon. The final two ingredients&mdash;(12) Vetch Lye and (13) Caper Wine&mdash;were used in the preparation of Onycha.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:12:19', '2025-01-13 23:12:19'),
(794, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:10: \"Now at the time of the incense offering, the whole assembly of the people was praying outside.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Zechariah alone during the incense offering?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The priest who offered incense ascended from the temple courtyard with other priests.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, only the appointed priest, in this case, Zechariah, entered the holy place where the golden altar was located; the others remained outside.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The incense offering was a sacred moment of solitude before God.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:12:56', '2025-01-13 23:12:56'),
(795, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:11: \"Then there appeared to him an angel of the Lord, standing at the right side of the altar of incense.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does Luke begin his gospel with the temple?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Old Testament concludes with Malachi&rsquo;s prophecy, which foretells God&rsquo;s return to His temple (Malachi 3).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This expectation sets the scene for Luke to start his Gospel in the temple, fulfilling the words:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;The Lord whom you seek will suddenly come to His temple&rdquo; (Malachi 3:1).</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:13:52', '2025-01-13 23:13:52'),
(796, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:15: \"For he will be great in the sight of the Lord. He must never drink wine or strong drink; even before his birth, he will be filled with the Holy Spirit.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was John a Nazirite who fasted?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Nazirites could abstain from wine, but they were permitted to eat freely,</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Wear regular clothes&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Marry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The tribe of Levi, to which John belonged, was typically exempt from the Nazarite vow (Numbers 6:13).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Therefore, it is likely that John was not a Nazirite in the traditional sense but rather a desert hermit, possibly similar to the Essenes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:14:31', '2025-01-13 23:14:31'),
(797, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:19: \"The angel replied, &lsquo;I am Gabriel. I stand in the presence of God, and I have been sent to speak to you and to bring you this good news.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the Jewish belief about the angel Gabriel?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish tradition holds Gabriel as one of the four archangels&mdash;alongside Michael, Sariel (or Uriel), and Raphael (1 Enoch 9:1; 1QM 9:15f).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, Gabriel is the angel who explains visions to Daniel (Daniel 8:16) and supports him in prophecy (Daniel 9:21).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Gabriel and the archangels praise God and intercede for humanity (Tobit 12:15; Jubilees 2:3).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:15:40', '2025-01-13 23:15:40'),
(798, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:21: &ldquo;Meanwhile, the people were waiting for Zechariah and wondered at his delay in the sanctuary.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the people wonder about Zechariah\'s delay in the temple?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews deeply believed in God&rsquo;s presence within the Holy of Holies in the Jerusalem Temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, they adhered strictly to the precise rituals of the temple, avoiding any mistakes that could offend God.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;The High Priest, who alone could enter the Holy of Holies once a year, never stayed longer than the prescribed time for prayer (Mishnah Yoma 5.1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, Zechariah\'s delay raised concern among the people, as they wondered if something divine might have taken place.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:17:21', '2025-01-13 23:17:21'),
(799, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:22: &ldquo;When he did come out, he could not speak to them, and they realised that he had seen a vision in the sanctuary; he kept motioning to them and remained unable to speak.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did they know that Zechariah had lost his voice?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish tradition held that after offering incense to the Lord, the priest would bless the people (Priestly Blessing), as outlined in Numbers 6:24-26.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Zechariah emerged, unable to speak or perform this customary blessing, the people immediately realised he had been struck mute, likely by a divine encounter.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:18:00', '2025-01-13 23:18:00'),
(800, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:26-27: &ldquo;In the sixth month the angel Gabriel was sent by God to a town in Galilee called Nazareth, to a virgin engaged to a man whose name was Joseph, of the house of David. The virgin&rsquo;s name was Mary.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the descent of&nbsp; the angel Gabriel to Nazareth prophesied?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Isaiah&rsquo;s prophecy, the king, or Saviour, of the Davidic line would emerge from the region of Zebulun and Naphtali:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;But there will be no gloom for those who were in anguish. In the former time he brought into contempt the land of Zebulun and the land of Naphtali&hellip; The people who walked in darkness have seen a great light&rdquo; (Isaiah 9:1-2).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Nazareth lies within the territory of these tribes, fulfilling this prophetic expectation.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:18:48', '2025-01-13 23:18:48'),
(801, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was Nazareth a Jewish village?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Galilee region, which includes Nazareth, was originally part of the Northern Kingdom of Israel.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, around 732&ndash;722 B.C., Assyria conquered Israel and settled people from various parts of its empire in the region (2 Kings 17).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During the Maccabean period, Galilee was re-annexed to Israel, and Alexander Jannaeus, a Maccabean leader, resettled many displaced Jews there.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, by this time, areas like Nazareth were once again Jewish villages.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:19:23', '2025-01-13 23:19:23'),
(802, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:27: &ldquo;Sent by God to a virgin engaged to a man whose name was Joseph, of the house of David. The virgin&rsquo;s name was Mary.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How was Saint Mary known in her time?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Jewish Old Testament (Masoretic Text), the name Miriam is written as &ldquo;Miri-am,&rdquo; as in the name of Moses\'s sister.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in Nazareth, where Mary lived, the spoken language was Aramaic, in which &ldquo;Miri-am&rdquo; is pronounced &ldquo;Mary-am.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, Mary was called Maryam in her time.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:20:15', '2025-01-13 23:20:15'),
(803, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>What do we understand when we say a betrothed virgin?</strong></p>', 4, 5, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A betrothed virgin refers to a young woman pledged in marriage, with a set time between engagement and the wedding itself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"padding-left: 40px;\">During this period, the girl would remain under her father&rsquo;s care.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"padding-left: 40px;\">Consequently, Mary would have likely been residing in Joachim&rsquo;s household.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">If a couple wished to dissolve the engagement after the betrothal, the marriage contract needed to be legally nullified with adultery regarded as valid grounds for such an annulment.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:21:15', '2025-01-13 23:21:15'),
(804, '<p><strong>Luke 1:28: &ldquo;And he came to her and said, &lsquo;Greetings, favoured one! The Lord is with you.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was this the first greeting Mary received?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Among the Jewish people, greetings often depended on age and social status.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example: &ldquo;Woe to you, Pharisees! For you love to have the seat of honour in the synagogues and to be greeted with respect in the marketplaces&rdquo; (Luke 11:43).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">No one would have customarily greeted a young girl before marriage with such a greeting as &ldquo;Hail!&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, it seems the angel Gabriel was indeed the first to offer Mary such an extraordinary greeting.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:21:57', '2025-01-13 23:21:57'),
(805, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:31: &ldquo;And now, you will conceive in your womb and bear a son, and you will name him Jesus.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How was Jesus named?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hebrew root for Jesus&rsquo; name is Yehoshua (Joshua).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When the Gospels were later recorded in Greek, His name became Jesus, meaning &ldquo;Yahweh saves.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is a name that signifies the power and salvation of God, standing above all names and powers.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:22:40', '2025-01-13 23:22:40'),
(806, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:32: &ldquo;He will be great and will be called the Son of the Most High, and the Lord God will give to him the throne of his ancestor David.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the angel say Jesus will be great?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish belief, Moses was considered the greatest prophet:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Never since has there arisen a prophet in Israel like Moses, whom the Lord knew face to face&rdquo; (Deuteronomy 34:10).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Messiah, however, was anticipated to surpass even Moses, fulfilling an even greater promise. Hence, the angel&rsquo;s proclamation that &ldquo;Jesus will be great&rdquo; points to His unique and divine glory.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:23:52', '2025-01-13 23:23:52'),
(807, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Luke include the birth of Jesus in his Gospel?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke&rsquo;s Gospel was written primarily for Gentile readers under Roman rule.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;At the time, many Gentiles revered the Roman Caesar as divine. This belief was reinforced by the Priene Inscription of 9 BC, in which Caesar declared himself &ldquo;Son of God&rdquo; and ordered that his birthday be celebrated as the beginning of the &ldquo;gospel.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke counters this by opening his Gospel with the true beginning of salvation: the birth of Jesus Christ, marking the advent of God&rsquo;s kingdom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:24:21', '2025-01-13 23:24:21'),
(808, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:35: \"The angel said to her, &lsquo;The Holy Spirit will come upon you, and the power of the Most High will overshadow you; therefore the child to be born will be holy; he will be called Son of God.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the virgin birth of Jesus understood as a living truth from the time the Bible was written?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This truth is affirmed in the Gospels of Matthew and Luke (Matthew 1:18-25; Luke 1:34).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Earlier, Paul&rsquo;s epistles allude to this mystery as well (Romans 1:3, Philippians 2:7).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Saint Ignatius of Antioch (A.D. 103) wrote, &ldquo;He was truly born of a Virgin&rdquo; (Letter to the Smyrnaeans).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Justin Martyr (c. A.D. 160) in Dialogue with Trypho and Clement of Alexandria&nbsp; (&ldquo;Jesus whom of the lightning flash of Divinity the Virgin bore&rdquo;- From his Peadagogus Book 195 AD)&rdquo; This doctrine was also acknowledged in early Church creeds in the 2nd century.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:25:45', '2025-01-13 23:25:45'),
(809, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:36: \"And now, your relative Elizabeth in her old age has also conceived a son; and this is the sixth month for her who was said to be barren.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How far did Mary travel to visit Elizabeth?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Elizabeth lived in Hebron, about 140 km from Nazareth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The journey was likely challenging, as Hebron stands approximately 1,138 feet above sea level.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:26:33', '2025-01-13 23:26:33'),
(810, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Is the lineage of Joseph and Mary important in the Gospels?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, Joseph belonged to the tribe of David, signifying Jesus\' kingship and fulfilment of Messianic prophecy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mary, being a relative of Elizabeth, a descendant of Aaron, links Jesus to the priestly heritage of Levi.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, Christ is presented as Lord, Saviour and King, embodying both royal and priestly lineages.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:27:30', '2025-01-13 23:27:30'),
(811, '<p><em><strong>&nbsp;</strong>What is the relationship between the Holy Mother and Elizabeth?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Bible describes Mary as of the tribe of Judah, while Elizabeth was from the tribe of Levi.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Elizabeth&rsquo;s mother might have been from Judah, and her father from Levi, making Mary and Elizabeth cousins by lineage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This familial connection might best be understood as being closer than cousins or as akin to a &ldquo;spiritual sisterhood.&rdquo;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:28:42', '2025-01-13 23:28:42'),
(812, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:38: \"Then Mary said, &lsquo;Here am I, the servant of the Lord; let it be with me according to your word.&rsquo; Then the angel departed from her.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How can it be said that the Holy Mother is sinless?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mary&rsquo;s complete consent to God&rsquo;s plan is seen in her willingness to bear Jesus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">God, who would never allow sin to taint such a holy calling, preserved Mary from all sin, including original sin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:29:25', '2025-01-13 23:29:25'),
(813, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Does a servant have any standing?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Greco-Roman culture, a servant&rsquo;s value was often tied to their master&rsquo;s societal status.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, a palace servant was highly esteemed. In this sense, the &ldquo;servant of the Lord&rdquo;&mdash;the God of all creation&mdash;is surpassing dignity and honour among humankind.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:29:59', '2025-01-13 23:29:59'),
(814, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:39: \"In those days Mary set out and went with haste to a Judean town in the hill country.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What town in Judea did Mary visit?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Zechariah, Elizabeth&rsquo;s husband, was a priest from the line of Aaron, who was of the tribe of Levi.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Old Testament, the descendants of Aaron were given specific towns as part of their inheritance. One such town was Hebron, located in the hill country of Judea:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;The first lot fell to the descendants of Aaron of the tribe of Levi. They were given Kiryat Arba (that is, Hebron) in the hill country of Judah, with its surrounding pasturelands&rdquo; (Joshua 21:10-11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, Mary travelled to Hebron to visit Elizabeth.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:31:20', '2025-01-13 23:31:20');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(815, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Is there anything special about Mary&rsquo;s hasty departure?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Luke\'s Gospel, the verb eporeumai is used to describe Mary&rsquo;s departure in haste.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke uses this term often to describe individuals filled with the Holy Spirit (Acts 8:27, 12:17).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He implies that Mary, led by the Holy Spirit, was eager to leave quickly.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:32:04', '2025-01-13 23:32:04'),
(816, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Which route did Mary take for her journey?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There were three main routes from Galilee to Judea:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The route through Samaria (around 100 km): Jews generally avoided this path due to tensions with the Samaritans.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Way of the Sea (approximately 125 km) was a slow path that followed the coast.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Way of the Shur (around 140 km) passes through the Shur desert. This route was most commonly taken by Jews and likely by Mary as well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Travellers often went in large groups to protect themselves from bandits, as highlighted in the Parable of the Good Samaritan.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:32:47', '2025-01-13 23:32:47'),
(817, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How far did Mary travel to visit Elizabeth?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Elizabeth lived in Hebron, Judea, approximately 140 kilometres (100 miles) from Nazareth, at an elevation of 1,138 feet above sea level.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:33:33', '2025-01-13 23:33:33'),
(818, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:40 &ldquo;She entered the house of Zechariah and greeted Elizabeth.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is the route that Mary took to visit Elizabeth significant?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish tribal lands, Mary, residing in Nazareth of the tribe of Zebulun, would travel south to Judea, passing through territories of the tribes of Issachar, Manasseh, Ephraim and Benjamin&mdash;right through the heart of Israel.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mary&rsquo;s journey through these sacred lands foreshadows Jesus\'s own journey to Jerusalem, where He would later fulfil His mission.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:36:14', '2025-01-13 23:36:14'),
(819, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:42 &ldquo;She exclaimed with a loud cry, &lsquo;Blessed are you among women, and blessed is the fruit of your womb.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Elizabeth call Mary blessed?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Bible, only three women are specifically called \"blessed\":</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jael: &ldquo;Most blessed of women be Jael, the wife of Heber the Kenite, of tent-dwelling women most blessed&rdquo; (Judges 5:24). Jael was a courageous woman who saved Israel by killing Sisera, the commander of the Canaanite army.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Judith: &ldquo;Uzziah said to her, &lsquo;O daughter, you are blessed by the Most High God above all other women on earth&rsquo;&rdquo; (Judith 13:18). Judith saved Israel by beheading the Assyrian commander Holofernes.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary: &ldquo;Blessed are you among women, and blessed is the fruit of your womb&rdquo; (Luke 1:42). Mary saved humanity from the bondage of sin through her acceptance of God\'s plan. For this reason, she is venerated as blessed among women.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:37:00', '2025-01-13 23:37:00'),
(820, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:43 &ldquo;And why has this happened to me, that the mother of my Lord comes to me?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How is Mary the ark of the covenant in the New Testament?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Elizabeth&rsquo;s question echoes King David\'s words when the ark of the covenant was brought to him.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;David was afraid of the Lord that day; he said, &lsquo;How can the ark of the Lord come into my care?&rsquo;&rdquo; (2 Samuel 6:9).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Just as Mary stayed in Elizabeth\'s home for three months, the ark of the covenant remained in the house of Obed-Edom for three months, during which time the Lord blessed his household:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;The ark of the Lord remained in the house of Obed-Edom the Gittite for three months, and the Lord blessed Obed-Edom and all his household&rdquo; (2 Samuel 6:11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:37:39', '2025-01-13 23:37:39'),
(821, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:46: &ldquo;And Mary said, &lsquo;My soul magnifies the Lord.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>In which language did Mother Mary sing her hymn?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mary&rsquo;s hymn, often known as the Magnificat, was likely sung in Aramaic or Hebrew.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The phrase &ldquo;from generation to generation&rdquo; (Luke 1:50) appears in both languages, suggesting she would have expressed herself in either Aramaic, the common spoken language, or Hebrew, often used for sacred expressions.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:38:15', '2025-01-13 23:38:15'),
(822, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:48: &ldquo;For he has looked with favour on the lowliness of his servant. Surely, from now on all generations will call me blessed.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Mary refer to herself as a &ldquo;servant&rdquo;?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mary&rsquo;s use of &ldquo;servant&rdquo; aligns with the humility she expressed in her hymn.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many early Christians, particularly under Roman rule, were slaves.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Roman Governor Pliny even referred to Christians as &ldquo;a band of slaves&rdquo; in his report to Caesar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Identifying herself as God&rsquo;s &ldquo;servant&rdquo; connected Mary to this group\'s humility. The Lord understands our helplessness better than we do.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:38:53', '2025-01-13 23:38:53'),
(823, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:57: &ldquo;Now the time came for Elizabeth to give birth, and she bore a son.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the first son have a special place?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The firstborn son, or bekor, held a significant role, often inheriting over half of the family estate and serving as the head of the family.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If twins were born, special attention was given to determine which emerged first, marking him as the firstborn.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:39:29', '2025-01-13 23:39:29'),
(824, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:58: &ldquo;Her neighbours and relatives heard that the Lord had shown his great mercy to her, and they rejoiced with her.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Elizabeth say that God showed great mercy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Elizabeth&rsquo;s barrenness brought two kinds of humiliation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">First, barrenness was considered a curse, casting her as accursed in the eyes of her community.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Second, since both she and Zechariah came from a priestly line, their lack of descendants was seen as a deep loss.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Her joy reflects God&rsquo;s mercy in relieving both of these hardships.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:40:07', '2025-01-13 23:40:07'),
(825, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:59: &ldquo;On the eighth day they came to circumcise the child, and they were going to name him Zechariah after his father.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jews name babies at birth?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, a male child becomes a part of the community upon circumcision, not at birth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, names were often given on the eighth day. This is why the day is also associated with circumcision and naming.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:40:42', '2025-01-13 23:40:42'),
(826, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did Jews traditionally name children after their fathers?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish custom often followed papponymy, where names were derived from the paternal lineage, generally skipping one generation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An example is in Chronicles 5:36.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, by that time, naming after the father was also practised. (Tobit&nbsp; 1:1 Mur 29:10 [Yeh&ucirc;dah bar Yeh&ucirc;dah]; 42:12 [Yeh&ocirc;sep bar Yeh&ocirc;sep])</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:41:17', '2025-01-13 23:41:17'),
(827, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:60: \"But the child\'s mother said to them, \'No, he must be called John.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Jews name their children?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, surnames were not commonly used.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Instead, individuals were often referred to by their father\'s name, a practice known as patronymics.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, one might hear \"John Ben Zacharias\" or \"Jonathan ben Hannan.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Occasionally, individuals were also given nicknames that reflected positive attributes or natural elements, such as Yohanan, meaning \"Wished by God\"; Yona, meaning \"a Dove\"; or Elon, meaning \"an Oak.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Names for baby girls often drew inspiration from nature as well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Examples include Rachel, meaning \"An Ewe,\" Deborah, meaning \"A Bee,\" and Tamar, meaning \"A Palm.\" These names reflect the parents\' desire for their children to be associated with beauty and strength in the natural world.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:41:52', '2025-01-13 23:41:52'),
(828, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:63: &ldquo;He brought a tablet and wrote on it: &lsquo;His name is John.&rsquo; Everyone was amazed.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is a blackboard?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, Luke uses the term \'pinakidion\' to refer to a writing tablet.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These tablets were typically crafted from a small wooden plank coated with wax. Writing was done using a stylus or chisel made from iron.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Judges would inscribe verdicts on these boards, and since Zechariah was a priest, he also held the role of a judge.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:42:46', '2025-01-13 23:42:46'),
(829, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:79: \"To give light to those who sit in darkness and the shadow of death, to guide our feet into the way of peace.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does Luke speak of peace?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In 13 B.C., Emperor Augustus Caesar commissioned the construction of a temple known as \'Ara Pacis Augustae,\' translating to \"Caesar\'s Temple of Peace.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Alongside this temple, a proclamation was made offering rewards to those who contributed to the establishment of peace within the Roman Empire.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Those eager to promote peace were regarded as esteemed members of society.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke highlights the theme of peace to illustrate that Jesus is the true peacemaker.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:44:43', '2025-01-13 23:44:43'),
(830, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 1:69: \"He has raised up a mighty saviour for us in the house of his servant David.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What kind of saviour was raised up in the house of David?</em></p>', 4, 5, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The passage indicates that a \"horn of salvation\"<strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-6103986f-7fff-60ff-aff6-c4ec2a691c82\">k&eacute;ras sōtērias</strong><img src=\"https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXfvF6Rc2XTEj5huV4ppXepJ0iRW-oMso9vQGX0r_2-25oBYuqH3RfaqCG55Za-Y-XEnBOWx8BEj4mGa_fLpIVtvQg13ZvImNK_dH7JAWdhpPBZDBRCbwWlIoQPrkeC2b7NF2pOLC5qy2Fv-mVybfopJGoc?key=cC4rLbw_ctkHNqWVjyOUaVBy\" width=\"82\" height=\"22\"> was lifted up in the house of David.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In biblical symbolism, a horn often represents strength and power, akin to the horns of bulls and goats that were used as instruments of victory.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When a king triumphed in battle, he would sound a victory horn. By calling Jesus the \"Horn of Salvation,\" the text signifies the victory accomplished through Christ.</p>', 1, '2025-01-13 23:49:35', '2025-01-13 23:49:35'),
(831, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 24:2: \"They saw that the stone had been rolled away from the tomb.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was the stone that covered the tomb rolled away?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Tombs (Kokhim) in Jesus\'s time were constructed by carving out spaces in the rock.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was customary to cut and then roll large stones in front of the tombs. These heavy stones served as a protective barrier, preventing thieves from entering. No matter how large the stone, it is inevitable that one day it will be rolled away.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:48:55', '2025-01-14 18:48:55'),
(832, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 24:4: \"While they were perplexed about this, suddenly two men in dazzling clothes stood beside them.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What leads to the belief that the two men mentioned here are angels?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The angels who appeared at Jesus\'s tomb were described as wearing shining, dazzling clothes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Bible, thunder and lightning often accompany the appearance of angels (Exodus 19:16; Ezekiel 1:13; Revelation 4:5).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Ezekiel, for instance, described angels as having an appearance like burning coals of fire with lightning flashing from them (Ezekiel 1:13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This imagery is likely why the angels at the tomb were described as having such radiant attire.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:50:03', '2025-01-14 18:50:03'),
(833, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 24:12: \"But Peter got up and ran to the tomb; stooping and looking in, he saw the linen cloths by themselves; then he went home, amazed at what had happened.\"</strong><br><em>What kind of clothes were used to wrap Jesus&rsquo;s body?</em></p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish funerals typically involved three types of cloth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The first was the sindon (a large cloth used to wrap the body).&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The second was a cloth for wrapping the hands and feet, called keiria.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The third was the soudarion, a cloth used to cover the face, which was the one that had been around Jesus\'s head (John 20:7).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The discarded linen cloths at the tomb signified that Jesus had risen.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:50:54', '2025-01-14 18:50:54'),
(834, '<p><strong>Luke 24:13: \"That same day two of them were going to a village called Emmaus, about seven miles from Jerusalem.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>What is the length of a stadion?</em></p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The stadion (plural: stadia) was the unit of measurement for the length of a racecourse in ancient times.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It equated to roughly 625 feet, or about 185 metres.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the distance from Jerusalem to Emmaus, given as 60 stadia, translates to about seven miles (11 kilometres).</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:51:53', '2025-01-14 18:51:53'),
(835, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Where is the village of Emmaus located?</em></p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The village of Emmaus-Nicopolis is traditionally identified as the site of the biblical Emmaus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This place is mentioned in the Book of Maccabees (1 Maccabees 3:40).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name Nicopolis was later given to the village during the Byzantine period.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Several locations, including Abu Ghosh and Qubeibah, are traditionally associated with the village of Emmaus.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The world is filled with the Spirit of the Lord (Wisdom 17).</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:52:38', '2025-01-14 18:52:38'),
(836, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Where is the village of Emmaus located today?</em></p>', 4, 70, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">\'Imwas or Nicopolis:<br>Emmaus is traditionally thought to be at Imwas (also called Amwas) or Nicopolis. However, Nicopolis is located about 20 miles from Jerusalem, which contradicts the distance mentioned in Luke\'s Gospel (which places Emmaus only 60 stadia, or seven miles, from Jerusalem).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">El-Qubeibeh:<br>El-Qubeibeh, a town southwest of Jerusalem, is commonly believed to be the modern-day location of Emmaus. It is situated precisely seven miles from Jerusalem, making it a strong candidate for the biblical Emmaus.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:53:30', '2025-01-14 18:53:30'),
(837, '<p><strong>Luke 24:18: \"One of them, whose name was Cleopas, asked him, \'Are you the only stranger in Jerusalem who does not know the things that have taken place there in these days?\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is the Cleopas who went to Emmaus and the Clopas of John (John 19:25) the same person?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke names the disciple who went to Emmaus as Cleopas, a Greek name. The Hebrew version of this name is Cleopatra (&Kappa;&lambda;&epsilon;ό&pi;&alpha;&tau;&rho;&omicron;&sigmaf;).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, it is unlikely that this Cleopas is the same person as Clopas, who was the husband of Mary, the mother of James. The connection is not explicitly made in the text and the names differ in their forms and cultural backgrounds.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:54:13', '2025-01-14 18:54:13'),
(838, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 24:21: \"But we had hoped that he was the one to redeem Israel. Yes, and besides all this, it is now the third day since these things took place.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Israelites wait for a king who was to deliver them?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites longed for a Messiah who would restore the kingdom to its former glory, akin to the days of King David.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their expectations were shaped by prayers such as the &Scaron;em&ocirc;neh \'Esreh (the 18 Benedictions) and the Qaddi&scaron; (the Kaddish). These prayers expressed their yearning for redemption.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The victories of the Maccabees had reignited their hopes for a kingly figure who would not only bring victory but also provide the strength to endure hardship and failure.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:55:00', '2025-01-14 18:55:00'),
(839, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 24:42-43: \"They gave him a piece of broiled fish, and he took it and ate in their presence.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What prompted the resurrected Jesus to eat?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish tradition holds that angels, being spiritual beings, cannot consume human food.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By eating, Jesus demonstrated that He was truly human and that He physically rose from the dead.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His act of eating also allowed Him to share in the humanity of His disciples, affirming that His resurrection was not a mere illusion but a tangible reality.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This gesture affirmed the fullness of His incarnation, eradicating any misconceptions about Him being a ghost.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:55:48', '2025-01-14 18:55:48'),
(840, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 24:50: \"Then he led them out as far as Bethany, and, lifting up his hands, he blessed them.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where was Jesus when He ascended to heaven?</em></p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Luke\'s Gospel, Jesus ascended to heaven from Bethany. However, in the Acts of the Apostles, the ascension took place on the Mount of Olives (Acts 1:12).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There is no contradiction between these accounts. Bethany was a village on the eastern slope of the Mount of Olives, so both locations are effectively the same.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:56:34', '2025-01-14 18:56:34'),
(841, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 24:51: \"While he was blessing them, he withdrew from them and was carried up into heaven.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the connection between Jesus\'s ascension and the priesthood?</em></p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The ascension of Jesus can be seen as a parallel to the actions of the high priest on the Day of Atonement (Yom Kippur), when the priest would enter the Holy of Holies to offer a sin offering for the people of Israel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Just as the high priest\'s sacrifice absolved the sins of Israel, Jesus\'s ascension marks the moment when He, as the High Priest, offered Himself as the ultimate atonement for the sins of the world.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This act of ascending to heaven signifies the completion of His redemptive work, offering forgiveness for all humanity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">With the destruction of the Jerusalem Temple in A.D. 70, the office of the High Priest was abolished, but Jesus\'s eternal priesthood remains unbroken.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:57:23', '2025-01-14 18:57:23'),
(842, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the Ascension take place 40 days after the Resurrection?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Luke\'s Gospel, the Ascension occurs on the same day as the Resurrection. However, in the Acts of the Apostles, which is also written by Luke, it is stated that the Ascension took place 40 days after the Resurrection (Acts 1:3).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Tertullian, Cyprian and Chrysostom also stated that the Ascension occurred 40 days after the Resurrection.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"For He ascended into heaven, as God, with the same flesh wherein He was born; and carried up with Him the affections of His faithful, leaving His mortal part to be laid in the grave, that it might become the way whereby we might ascend to Him.\" &mdash; St. Augustine, Sermon 213.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:57:59', '2025-01-14 18:57:59'),
(843, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why does Luke give the benediction at the end of his Gospel?</em></p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the first chapter of Luke\'s Gospel, Zechariah could not give the priestly blessing after offering incense.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Usually, after the offering of incense, the priest blesses the people\" (Talmud 7.2).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Zechariah could not bless the people because he was speechless due to his unbelief (unfinished Leitourgia). Jesus fulfilled this unfinished blessing on the Mount of Olives, situated on the opposite side of the temple, when He gave His final blessing to the disciples.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:58:47', '2025-01-14 18:58:47'),
(844, '<p><em>What is the meaning of &ldquo;blessing&rdquo; in the New Testament?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 4, 70, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the New Testament, to bless means \"to greet/gift the presence of God.\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, in Luke 1:42, Gabriel&rsquo;s greeting, \"The Lord be with you,\" is a blessing.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Likewise, in Luke 24:51, the final blessing that Jesus gives to His disciples is the promise of the Holy Spirit.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A blessing in the New Testament means that God is with you. It&rsquo;s not a promise of material prosperity.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 18:59:27', '2025-01-14 18:59:27'),
(845, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 23:1: \"Then the whole company of them arose and brought him before Pilate.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews entrust Pilate with judging Jesus?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 71, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sanhedrin was the Jewish court, which could sentence a person to death; however, the most severe punishment they could impose was stoning, as seen in the cases of Stephen and the woman caught in adultery.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Crucifixion, a Roman form of execution, was beyond their jurisdiction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, Jesus was brought before Pilate, the Roman governor, to be condemned to the most brutal form of execution: crucifixion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Had the Sanhedrin condemned Jesus, He would have been stoned, but it was God\'s will that He face the crucifixion.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:03:15', '2025-01-14 19:03:15'),
(846, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 23:12: \"And that day Herod and Pilate became friends with each other; before this they had been enemies with each other.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Herod and Pilate reconcile?</em></p>', 4, 71, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod Antipas, being half-Jewish, and Pilate, a Gentile, had previously been at odds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their reconciliation, however, symbolised the transformative unity in Jesus Christ, which tore down the walls between Jews and Gentiles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As Ephesians 2:14 states, \"For he is our peace; in his flesh he has made both groups into one and has broken down the dividing wall, that is, the hostility between us.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:04:10', '2025-01-14 19:04:10'),
(847, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 23:26: \"As they led him away, they seized a man, Simon of Cyrene, who was coming from the country, and they laid the cross on him, and made him carry it behind Jesus.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Simeon of Cyrene a Jew?</em></p>', 4, 71, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In 332 B.C., Ptolemy, the king of Egypt, conquered the African kingdom of Cyrene, and in 31 B.C., Augustus Caesar made it a Roman province.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During this period, many Jews settled there. Therefore, it is likely that Simeon of Cyrene was a Jew who had come to Jerusalem for the Passover feast.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His role in carrying Jesus\'s cross was part of God\'s plan, demonstrating that even the most unexpected individuals have a role in fulfilling God\'s purpose.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:04:54', '2025-01-14 19:04:54'),
(848, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 23:43: \"Jesus said to him, \'Truly I tell you, today you will be with me in Paradise.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the good thief immediately ascend to heaven?</em></p>', 4, 71, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The question of time is secondary; it concerns disposition. The good thief was assured of salvation through his Baptism of Desire (Catechism of the Catholic Church 1258).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is not specified whether he ascended immediately but we know that the dead were welcomed into heaven upon Christ\'s ascension.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Romans 8:29 affirms, \"For those whom he foreknew he also predestined to be conformed to the image of his Son.\" Therefore, The good thief underwent natural purification and entered eternal life with Christ.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:05:36', '2025-01-14 19:05:36'),
(849, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 23:44: \"It was now about the sixth hour, and there was darkness over the whole land until the ninth hour.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does the scripture say that there was darkness over the whole land?</em></p>', 4, 71, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Crucifixion was a Roman form of punishment, symbolising the absolute power of the Roman emperor over life and death.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The spectacle of execution was often performed in public to demonstrate the emperor&rsquo;s authority.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Such punishments could last for days, and the crucified person&rsquo;s agony served as an example to the people.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The darkness that enveloped the earth as Jesus was crucified, signified God\'s profound sorrow and love displayed through His Son&rsquo;s suffering.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:06:20', '2025-01-14 19:06:20'),
(850, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:2: &ldquo;The chief priests and the scribes were looking for a way to put him to death, but they feared the people.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How was the Jewish priesthood passed down?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The priests among the Jews were from the tribe of Levi, specifically from the descendants of Aaron.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During King David&rsquo;s reign, the line of the priest Zadok became particularly prominent, and his descendants later formed the priestly clan known as the Sadducees.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Since the time of David, there have been 24 priestly divisions in Israel, each responsible for service in the Temple.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:19:37', '2025-01-14 19:19:37'),
(851, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:7: &ldquo;Then came the day of Unleavened Bread, on which the Passover lamb had to be sacrificed.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the difference between the Passover in Egypt and the Passover in Jesus&rsquo;s time?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the first Passover, a lamb or goat was sacrificed and eaten in each household, as instructed in Exodus 12:46, with no special sacrificial method.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, by the first century, the Passover lamb was sacrificed at the Temple in Jerusalem and consumed in the city.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The sacrifice in Jesus\'s time was performed by weaving and cutting two cords, a more formal method than the earlier, more direct practice.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:20:24', '2025-01-14 19:20:24'),
(852, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:15: &ldquo;And he said to them, &lsquo;I have eagerly desired to eat this Passover with you before I suffer.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why aren&rsquo;t lambs sacrificed for Passover today?</em></p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the first Passover, the lamb had to be killed and eaten by each family within their home (Exodus 12:46).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, after the destruction of the Temple, Jews could no longer offer Passover lambs there. In place of the lamb, a lamb\'s thigh bone (often referred to as the \'Shank Bone\') became a key element of the meal, symbolising the sacrifice.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This bone, known as the \'Zeroa,\' is mentioned in Isaiah 53:1.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The inclusion of the Zeroa and other elements in the Passover meal later became symbolic, remembering the sacrifice made for the Israelites\' deliverance and foreshadowing the ultimate sacrifice Jesus would make.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:22:13', '2025-01-14 19:22:13'),
(853, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:18: &ldquo;For I tell you that from now on I will not drink of the fruit of the vine until the kingdom of God comes.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How does Holy Communion become a memory?</em></p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Temple of Jerusalem, the \"Lehem Hapanim\" or the \"Bread of the Faces\" was presented daily, made with fine flour and seasoned with salt and cumin.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"You shall make twelve loaves of fine flour, using two-tenths of an ephah of flour for each loaf. They should be placed on the gold table in two rows of six. Pure frankincense should be placed on each loaf as a memorial offering, made by fire to the Lord\" (Leviticus 24:5-7).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The people believed that as long as this bread remained in the temple, God would remember them.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:22:59', '2025-01-14 19:22:59'),
(854, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:24: &ldquo;A dispute also arose among them as to which one of them was to be regarded as the greatest.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the disciples argue about their status?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At Jewish feasts, the seating arrangement was of great importance. The table was often arranged as a half circle with the most important person seated in the centre and others arranged by priority.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This custom, which was also evident in synagogue settings, likely prompted the disciples&rsquo; dispute about who would be the greatest.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As Jesus observed in Matthew 23:6-7, some people desired the place of honour at feasts and the most esteemed seats in synagogues, desiring recognition as \"Rabbi.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The disciples&rsquo; quarrel likely stemmed from this desire for status and priority, even in their shared journey with Christ.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:23:50', '2025-01-14 19:23:50'),
(855, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:30: \"That you may eat and drink at my table in my kingdom, and sit on thrones judging the twelve tribes of Israel.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus promise His 12 disciples that they would eat and drink in the kingdom of heaven?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, Moses selected twelve men to lead the tribes of Israel (Numbers 1:11-19, 44).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These leaders were privileged to eat and drink with God and Moses. As it is written, \"He did not lay his hand on the nobles of the Israelites; they saw God, and they ate and drank\" (Exodus 24:11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, Jesus promises His disciples that they, too, will eat and drink in the kingdom of heaven.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:24:35', '2025-01-14 19:24:35'),
(856, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:38: \"They said, &lsquo;Lord, here are two swords.&rsquo; But he replied, &lsquo;It is enough.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus ask His disciples to carry a sword?</em></p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word makaira used here refers to a \"small knife\" rather than a large weapon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus does not advocate for the use of swords for combat, as He Himself declares, \"Put your sword back into its place; for all who take the sword will perish by the sword\" (Matthew 26:52).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The disciples were to keep the swords as a symbol of preparation for the upcoming persecution, employing figurative language to highlight the difficult times ahead.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:25:21', '2025-01-14 19:25:21'),
(857, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:40: \"When he arrived there, he said to them, &lsquo;Pray that you may not come into the time of trial.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the Jews do after the Passover meal?</em></p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">After the Passover meal, Jews would typically remain awake throughout the night in prayer, seeking deliverance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They often recounted the story of God&rsquo;s salvation from Egypt. It was a night of watchfulness, awaiting the arrival of the promised Saviour.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As Jesus prayed fervently, sweating blood, the crowds were also engaged in prayer for a Saviour they had not yet recognised.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:25:59', '2025-01-14 19:25:59'),
(858, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:55: \"When they had kindled a fire in the middle of the courtyard and sat down together, Peter sat among them.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were there so many people in the high priest\'s house?</em></p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The night of Passover, known as Leil Shimurim&mdash;the Night of Vigil&mdash;was a sacred occasion.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It commemorates the night when the Lord kept vigil to bring the Israelites out of Egypt, as described in Exodus 12:42: \'It is a night of vigil for the Lord to bring them out of the land of Egypt.\'</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For generations, the Israelites have followed the tradition of staying awake, keeping watch in honour of the Lord.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This explains why so many were gathered at the high priest\'s house.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:26:40', '2025-01-14 19:26:40'),
(859, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why was there so much confusion when Peter denied Jesus?</em></p>', 4, 72, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The night of Passover, called Leil Shimurim, held significant meaning for the Jewish people, as it marked the night of the Lord&rsquo;s vigil.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;\"It is the night in which the Lord kept vigil to bring them out of Egypt. Therefore, generations after generations, the Israelites should keep awake and observe that night in honour of the Lord\" (Exodus 12:42).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Passover night in Egypt was when the Lord kept vigil, marking it as a night for His people to remain watchful.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;As a result, the Passover became a night of vigilance, a time to stay awake in anticipation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why there were many gathered in the high priest&rsquo;s house.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:27:20', '2025-01-14 19:27:20'),
(860, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 21:1: &ldquo;He looked up and saw rich people putting their gifts into the treasury.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was known as the temple treasury?</em></p>', 4, 73, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jerusalem temple had twelve large receptacles where offerings were made, each designated for different types of offerings, such as New Shekels, Old Shekels, Bird Offerings, Wood, Frankincense, Gold, and more.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The priest would announce what each person had deposited, except for the twelfth box, which was for Free Will Offerings.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These offerings were not publicly announced.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The widow&rsquo;s offering could be viewed as one of these voluntary gifts, signifying her silent contribution.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:36:39', '2025-01-14 19:36:39'),
(861, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 21:15: &ldquo;For I will give you words and a wisdom that none of your opponents will be able to withstand or contradict.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does Jesus mean by \'words and wisdom\'?</em></p>', 4, 73, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The phrase \"eloquence and wisdom\" can be understood through the concept of hendiadys, a figure of speech commonly found in Hebrew.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In hendiadys, two words with nearly identical meanings are used together to convey a deeper or fuller sense.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, &ldquo;day and night&rdquo; often means the entirety of the day, not two separate concepts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, &ldquo;eloquence and wisdom&rdquo; (or, \"mouth and wisdom\") can be interpreted as a unified idea, signifying &ldquo;an answer that no one can refute.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus promises His followers that, through His guidance, they will receive an answer so compelling that their adversaries will have no power to resist or oppose it.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:37:29', '2025-01-14 19:37:29'),
(862, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 21:20: &ldquo;When you see Jerusalem surrounded by armies, then you know that its desolation has come near.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Roman army surround Jerusalem?</em></p>', 4, 73, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 67, the Roman general Vespasian besieged Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In A.D. 70, the siege was handed over to his son, Titus, who led his army into the city and destroyed the temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus warned that the sight of the encircling armies was a sign of the coming devastation, urging people not to waste time in internal conflict but to prepare for what is to come.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:38:09', '2025-01-14 19:38:09'),
(863, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 21:20:</strong> <em>Were armies stationed around Jerusalem later?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 73, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The word stratopedon is used to describe the army here, specifically a legion of about 6,000 soldiers encamped at one location.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is a direct reference to the siege of Jerusalem in A.D. 70, led by Titus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:38:46', '2025-01-14 19:38:46'),
(864, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 20:17: &ldquo;But he looked at them and said, &lsquo;What then does this text mean: &lsquo;The stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the cornerstone of the house?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 74, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Some Roman-style houses were designed with arched roofs. In these houses, the cornerstone was placed at the top.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This stone, known as the Rosh Fana (headstone), was critical as it supported all the other stones in the structure</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:41:17', '2025-01-14 19:41:17'),
(865, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 19:2: &ldquo;A man was there named Zacchaeus; he was a chief tax collector and was rich.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews despise tax collectors?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 75, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Tax collectors worked for the Roman authorities.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Many obtained their positions by bribing Rome and paying money upfront to secure the role.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Then, these Tax collectors would collect customs and taxes to recoup their payment. For this reason, Jews held a deep resentment toward tax collectors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:50:09', '2025-01-14 19:50:09'),
(866, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 19:3: &ldquo;He was trying to see who Jesus was, but on account of the crowd he could not, because he was short in stature.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does the scripture describe Zacchaeus as a short man?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 75, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Since ancient times, Israel upheld the concept of physiognomy, the belief that outward appearance reflected inner character.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, the Israelites made Saul king partly because he was tall (1 Samuel 9:2).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Describing Zacchaeus as short may reflect a perception among some Jews that he was cursed by God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:51:20', '2025-01-14 19:51:20'),
(867, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 19:4: &ldquo;So he ran ahead and climbed a sycamore tree to see him, because he was going to pass that way.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is a sycamore tree?</em></p>', 4, 75, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The sycamore is an Egyptian fig tree with dark red or purple fruit. It symbolises prosperity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:52:19', '2025-01-14 19:52:19'),
(868, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 19:12: &ldquo;So he said, &lsquo;A nobleman went to a distant country to get royal power for himself and then return.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Could kingship be attained during Jesus&rsquo;s time?</em></p>', 4, 75, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Under the great empires, many rulers held titles such as kings and princes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Emperors allowed these regional leaders to govern smaller territories, such as when Herod ruled under Roman authority.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They honoured kings who administered well with additional titles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Josephus even records that Archelaus, Herod&rsquo;s son, journeyed to Rome to seek kingship.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:53:16', '2025-01-14 19:53:16'),
(869, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 19:37: &ldquo;As he was now approaching the path down from the Mount of Olives, the whole multitude of the disciples began to praise God joyfully with a loud voice for all the deeds of power that they had seen.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were royal processions a common sight in Jerusalem?</em></p>', 4, 75, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The people were well acquainted with displays of power in Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman army frequently demonstrated its might by parading through Jerusalem with weapons and Caesar&rsquo;s emblems, asserting Roman dominance over the city.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus&rsquo;s entrance into Jerusalem also symbolises His authority.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:54:55', '2025-01-14 19:54:55'),
(870, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 19:38: &ldquo;Blessed is the king who comes in the name of the Lord! Peace in heaven, and glory in the highest heaven!&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is Jesus&rsquo;s entry into Jerusalem (Hosanna Sunday) called the royal entry?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 4, 75, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus&rsquo;s entry into Jerusalem on what is known as Hosanna Sunday or Palm Sunday is often called the \"royal entry\" because it mirrors the traditional processions of kings, particularly those of the time, though with notable differences.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When a king, such as Caesar, entered a city, the following typically occurred:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A military escort would accompany the king, symbolising power and authority.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Shouts of victory from the people, often calling out praise or victory chants, such as \"Hosanna\" (meaning \"save us\" or \"deliver us\").</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Branches and leaves would be used to decorate the streets. The people often waved palm branches, which were symbols of peace and victory.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sacrifices were offered in the temple as part of the royal celebrations.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Jesus entered Jerusalem on Hosanna Sunday, all the above occurred.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:55:58', '2025-01-14 19:55:58'),
(871, '<p><strong>Luke 19:44: &ldquo;They will crush you to the ground, you and your children within you, and they will not leave within you one stone upon another, because you did not recognise the time of your visitation from God.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the Jerusalem temple destroyed without leaving one stone upon another?</em></p>', 4, 75, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jerusalem Temple was completely destroyed during the Bar Kokhba Revolt in A.D. 135.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Roman General Julius Severus executed the destruction on the orders of Emperor Hadrian, concluding the second major Jewish revolt against Roman rule.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Following this, the Jews were prohibited from entering Jerusalem. This destruction underscores that all human creations eventually meet an end.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:57:07', '2025-01-14 19:57:07');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(872, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 19:45: &ldquo;Then he entered the temple and began to drive out those who were selling things there.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus cleanse the temple to fulfil a prophecy?</em></p>', 4, 75, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, Jesus&rsquo;s cleansing of the temple fulfilled the prophecy in the book of Zechariah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Zechariah foretold that with the arrival of the Saviour, there would no longer be merchants in the Jerusalem temple:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"Every pot in Jerusalem and Judah shall be sacred to the Lord of hosts, so that all who sacrifice may come and use them... And there shall no longer be traders in the house of the Lord of hosts on that day&rdquo; (Zechariah 14:21).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This prophecy came to fulfilment when Jesus cleansed the temple, a symbolic act that prefigures His ultimate cleansing of the Church by His own blood.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:57:55', '2025-01-14 19:57:55'),
(873, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 19:46: &ldquo;He said to them, &lsquo;It is written, My house shall be a house of prayer; but you have made it a den of robbers.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does Jesus mean by calling the temple a &lsquo;den of robbers&rsquo;?</em></p>', 4, 75, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, the prophet Jeremiah used this expression to condemn the state of God&rsquo;s temple at Shiloh. He warned:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Has this house, which is called by my name, become a den of robbers in your sight? You know, I too am watching, says the Lord. Go now to my place that was in Shiloh... and see what I did to it because of the wickedness of my people Israel&rdquo; (Jeremiah 7:11-12).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The priests Hophni and Phinehas, sons of Eli, served unfaithfully at Shiloh, turning the temple into a place of dishonour.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Israel&rsquo;s subsequent defeat at the hands of the Philistines and the death of Eli&rsquo;s sons (1 Samuel 4:1-22) followed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:58:41', '2025-01-14 19:58:41'),
(874, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did all the evangelists write about Jesus&rsquo;s cleansing of the temple?</em></p>', 4, 75, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The last prophets of Israel foresaw that the Messiah would purify and restore the temple. Zechariah prophesied that no merchants would remain in the Lord&rsquo;s house:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;No trader shall again be in the house of the Lord of hosts on that day&rdquo; (Zechariah 14:21).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Likewise, Malachi foretold, &ldquo;He will purify the descendants of Levi and refine them like gold and silver, until they present offerings to the Lord in righteousness&rdquo; (Malachi 3:3).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This shared prophetic vision explains why all the evangelists emphasise Jesus&rsquo;s act of cleansing the temple.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 19:59:16', '2025-01-14 19:59:16'),
(875, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:2: &ldquo;In a certain city there was a judge who neither feared God nor had respect for people.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did stories of unrighteous judges exist in Jesus&rsquo;s time?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, a similar tale existed about King Philip, the father of Alexander the Great.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A woman once pleaded with him to hear her case and do her justice. However, busy with his affairs, the king dismissed her, stating he had no time. In response, she boldly declared, &ldquo;If you don&rsquo;t have time to do justice, you have no right to rule the kingdom.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This type of story was well-known in those days, illustrating the expectation that leaders should always seek justice.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:27:43', '2025-01-14 21:27:43'),
(876, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the widow bother the judge?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jesus\'s time, judges were known as Dayyan. Jewish courts handled two types of cases:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Criminal cases</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Civil cases</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Criminal cases were ruled on by a Sanhedrin&mdash;a group of 72 members&mdash;while civil cases, especially disputes related to money or property, were settled by a three-judge court.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The widow likely brought her case before one of these judges.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:28:26', '2025-01-14 21:28:26'),
(877, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:3: &ldquo;In that city, there was a widow who kept coming to him and saying, &lsquo;Grant me justice against my opponent.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus specifically talk about a widow and not just any woman?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The decree Lex Papia Poppaea, issued by Augustus Caesar, mandated that all widows aged 20 to 50 remarry due to the high widowhood rate caused by frequent wars, which often forced large families to relocate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Augustus, appointing himself as the protector of widows, set this law in place.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yet, even in Old Testament times, Jehovah had been considered the ultimate protector of widows (Exodus 22:22-24; Deuteronomy 10:18; 24:17, 24:17-21; Joshua 22:9 22:9; 24:3; Jeremiah 5:28; Lamentations 5:3; Zechariah 7:10; Malachi 3:5).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This social and religious context granted widows a special place in the Gospels.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:29:40', '2025-01-14 21:29:40'),
(878, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why does Jesus include a widow as a character in the parable of the unjust judge?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish society at that time, women did not usually bring cases to court; this responsibility was typically assumed by a husband, father or brother.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Only a widow was permitted to participate in court proceedings because she has no male relatives to represent her.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hence, Jesus introduces a widow in the parable, emphasising her vulnerability and resilience.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:30:22', '2025-01-14 21:30:22'),
(879, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:5: &ldquo;Yet because this widow keeps bothering me, I will grant her justice, so that she may not wear me out by continually coming.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were Jewish widows permitted to marry their husband&rsquo;s brothers?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Under Jewish law, known as Levirate Marriage, if a woman became a widow, her husband&rsquo;s brother was required to marry her to preserve the family lineage (Deuteronomy 25:5-10).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;If brothers live together, and one of them dies without a son, her husband&rsquo;s brother shall take her as his wife and fulfill the duty of a brother-in-law to her&rdquo; (Deuteronomy 25:5).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, by Jesus\'s time, adherence to this law had waned. Through the Ketubah (Marriage Contract), a widow was entitled to her deceased husband&rsquo;s property.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke\'s parable reflects a period when Levirate Marriage was not widely practised.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:31:08', '2025-01-14 21:31:08'),
(880, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the widow&rsquo;s persistence make the judge uncomfortable?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek term kopto is used to describe discomfort.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It means &ldquo;to strike on the face,&rdquo; a phrase that also appears in 1 Corinthians 9:27:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;I punish my body and enslave it, so that after proclaiming to others I should not be disqualified&rdquo; (1 Corinthians 9:27).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This language underscores the widow&rsquo;s relentless pursuit of justice, likening it to the discipline and perseverance of prayer.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:32:11', '2025-01-14 21:32:11'),
(881, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:7: &ldquo;And will not God grant justice to his chosen ones who cry to him day and night? Will he delay long in helping them?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus conclude His parable with a question?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus concludes the parable of the unjust judge and the persistent widow with a rhetorical question.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This approach, known in Hebrew as a minori ad maiorem, illustrates that one thing is far superior to another.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus implies that if an unjust judge can deliver justice, then certainly the heavenly Father will respond swiftly and justly to those who consistently pray to Him.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:33:03', '2025-01-14 21:33:03'),
(882, '<p><strong>Luke 18:11-12: &ldquo;The Pharisee, standing by himself, was praying thus, &lsquo;God, I thank you that I am not like other people: thieves, rogues, adulterers, or even like this tax collector. I fast twice a week; I give a tenth of all my income.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What are the two fasts of the Pharisees?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites practised two types of fasting:<br><strong>Communal Fasting</strong><br>a. Preparation for the Day of Atonement (Numbers 29:7).<br>b. During times of enemy attacks or severe crises.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Individual Fasting</strong><br>The Pharisees traditionally fasted on the second and fifth days of the week, recalling Moses&rsquo;s forty-day fast on Mount Sinai.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Tradition held that Moses ascended Mount Sinai on the second day and descended on the fifth. Fasting on the second and fifth days of the week honours this memory.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:34:11', '2025-01-14 21:34:11'),
(883, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:12: &ldquo;I fast twice a week; I give a tenth of all my income.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were the different kinds of Jewish tithe?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Pentateuch, the Jewish people observed three types of tithes:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">First Tithe: One-tenth of crops and livestock were offered at the temple and consumed there in a sacred meal with the Levites (Deuteronomy 14:22-27).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Second Tithe: Another tenth given to the Levites for their sustenance (Genesis 28:22).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Third Tithe: Every third year, a portion was given to the poor and the Levites (Deuteronomy 14:28-29; 26:12-13).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These tithes embodied the principle of &ldquo;freely received, freely given,&rdquo; fostering generosity toward God and the community.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:34:57', '2025-01-14 21:34:57'),
(884, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:25: &ldquo;Indeed, it is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for someone who is rich to enter the kingdom of God.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Can a camel go through the eye of a needle?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jerusalem, there was a narrow gate called the &ldquo;Eye of the Needle&rdquo; through which people exited the city at night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A camel could pass through only if it&rsquo;s stripped of all its baggage. This act symbolises humility and the willingness to abandon material possessions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The &ldquo;Eye of the Needle&rdquo; gate thus prevented thieves from bringing large goods into the city at night. Jesus could be likened to a camel passing through this small gate, emphasising the virtue of humility.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:35:43', '2025-01-14 21:35:43'),
(885, '<p><em>Did the camel hold any specific significance to the Israelites?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Though the elephant was known as the largest animal in the world, the camel was the largest animal familiar to the people of Israel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, Jesus referred to the camel to represent how difficult it is for the wealthy to enter the kingdom of God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This image also appears in the Babylonian Talmud, which refers to the camel as the largest animal known in the region (Berakot 55b, Bava Metzia 38b).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This parable reflects the principle that abandonment of worldly riches leads to spiritual gain.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:36:29', '2025-01-14 21:36:29'),
(886, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:28: \"Then Peter said, &lsquo;Look, we have left our homes and followed you.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did you need three people to pray?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, according to Halachah, at least ten people (a minyan) are needed to form a community (hadah) for prayer.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, &ldquo;Boaz went to the city gate. Then the aforementioned relative arrived, and Boaz said to him, &lsquo;Come over, my friend, and sit here.&rsquo; So he came and sat down. Then Boaz took ten men of the elders of the city, and said, &lsquo;Sit down here&rsquo;; so they sat down&rdquo; (Ruth 4:1-2).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, it is believed that God does not require a large crowd to hear prayers. God is present with even a small gathering, and even our sighs are prayers heard by the Lord.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:37:13', '2025-01-14 21:37:13'),
(887, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:35: \"As he approached Jericho, a blind man was sitting by the roadside begging.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How many beggars did Jesus heal in Jericho?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Luke&rsquo;s and Mark&rsquo;s accounts, it is recorded that Jesus healed just one blind beggar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in Matthew&rsquo;s Gospel, it is recorded that Jesus healed two blind beggars: &ldquo;When they heard that Jesus was passing by, two blind men sitting by the roadside shouted, &lsquo;Lord, have mercy on us, Son of David!&rsquo;&rdquo; (Matthew 20:30).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew likely mentioned two beggars intentionally, as he wrote from a Jewish perspective.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish law often requires the testimony of two people as valid confirmation:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;In your law it is written that the testimony of two witnesses is true&rdquo; (John 8:17).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, Matthew may have included two blind men to fulfil the requirement of two witnesses.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:38:02', '2025-01-14 21:38:02'),
(888, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:35-36: &ldquo;As he approached Jericho, a blind man was sitting by the roadside begging. When he heard a crowd going by, he asked what was happening.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where was Jesus located when He healed the blind man?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke and Matthew offer slightly different details regarding the location of the healing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Luke, it happened as Jesus approached Jericho, while Matthew places it as Jesus was leaving Jericho: &ldquo;As they were leaving Jericho, a large crowd followed him&rdquo; (Matthew 20:29).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During Jesus&rsquo; time, there were actually two Jerichos:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Old Jericho, the ancient city referenced in the Old Testament where Elisha&rsquo;s spring was located.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">New Jericho, built by King Herod.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The distance between the two Jerichos was about a half-hour&rsquo;s walk. Both are located near Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew likely describes the healing as occurring while Jesus was departing from Old Jericho, whereas Luke suggests that it occurred while Jesus approached New Jericho.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, both accounts could refer to the same event.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:38:42', '2025-01-14 21:38:42'),
(889, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 18:38: &ldquo;Then he shouted, &lsquo;Jesus, Son of David, have mercy on me!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the blind beggar call Jesus &lsquo;Son of David&rsquo;?</em></p>', 4, 76, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, King Solomon, the son of David, was revered as both a wise man and a skilled healer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The blind beggar likely recognised Jesus as a descendant of David and a powerful healer, much like Solomon, and called Him &lsquo;Son of David&rsquo; as an acknowledgment of this heritage and belief in His healing power.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:39:11', '2025-01-14 21:39:11'),
(890, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 17:11: \"On the way to Jerusalem, Jesus was going through the region between Samaria and Galilee.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Luke mention that Jesus passed through Samaria on His way to Jerusalem?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Samaritans believed that Mount Gerizim was the true place of worship, in contrast to the Jewish belief that worship should take place in Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, they looked upon those who made pilgrimages to Jerusalem with pity.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During this journey, Jesus healed ten lepers, including a Samaritan.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:42:14', '2025-01-14 21:42:14'),
(891, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 17:12: \"As he entered a village, ten lepers approached him. Keeping their distance, they called out...\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the significance of the number 10 here?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish tradition, a prayer is considered a community prayer only when a minimum of ten people, known as a minyan, participate. This formal group of at least ten individuals was regarded as an official Jewish community.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The presence of ten lepers thus symbolises a community, and their collective cry for mercy reflects the belief that communal prayers are answered</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:42:57', '2025-01-14 21:42:57'),
(892, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the Jews interpret leprosy?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews saw leprosy as a visible manifestation of deep internal impurity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The skin, believed to be a permeable substance, was thought to allow impurities from within to surface.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Leprosy was regarded as the outward reflection of the soul&rsquo;s profound impurity.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:43:32', '2025-01-14 21:43:32'),
(893, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 17:12: \"As he entered a village, ten lepers standing at a distance saw him.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were lepers excluded from the Jewish community?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Leprosy was believed to be a divine punishment for sin (2 Chronicles 26:16-21; Numbers 12:10-15).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">There was no known cure for leprosy.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Touching a leper was believed to render someone unclean.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Lepers were required to live outside the city and were forbidden from leaving their designated area (Leviticus 13:46).&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These beliefs contributed to the exclusion of lepers from the community.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:44:13', '2025-01-14 21:44:13'),
(894, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 17:14: \"When he saw them, he said, \'Go and show yourselves to the priests.\' And as they went, they were made clean.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were the criteria to be labelled as a leper in the Bible?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">If people noticed white spots on their skin, they were instructed to inform the priest.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">If the white spots spread to body hair, it was confirmed as leprosy. <br><br></p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">When the white patches became thick and spread between the hair, it was identified as acute leprosy, and the person was removed from the community.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:45:14', '2025-01-14 21:45:14'),
(895, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 17:18: \"Was none of them found to return and praise God except this foreigner?\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus call the Samaritan leper a Gentile?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus referred to the healed Samaritan leper as a Gentile (Allogenes) because, as a Samaritan, he was not part of the Jewish community and did not have access to the Jerusalem temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The historian Josephus describes a physical barrier in the temple that separated the Court of the Gentiles from the inner sanctuary: \"a partition made of stone all around, which was as tall as three cubits\" (Josephus, Jewish War, 5.2 &sect;&sect;193).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus&rsquo;s words highlighted that salvation was now open to all people, as the prophets had promised (Isaiah 56:1-8), and that the barriers separating Jews and Gentiles were being removed.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:46:01', '2025-01-14 21:46:01'),
(896, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 17:18: &ldquo;Was none of them found to return and give praise to God except this foreigner?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is it mentioned that a Samaritan alone returned to give thanks?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Gospel of Luke is often called the &ldquo;Gospel of the Gentiles&rdquo; because it was specifically written for Gentile Christians.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke emphasises that Jesus is the Saviour of both Jews and Gentiles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This emphasis on inclusivity explains why only the Samaritan, a Gentile, returned to give thanks to Jesus. It underscores the message that God\'s grace extends to all, including those outside Jewish circles.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:46:41', '2025-01-14 21:46:41'),
(897, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 17:34: &ldquo;I tell you, on that night there will be two in one bed; one will be taken and the other left.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus prophesy that only one would be taken?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During the Jewish Revolt of A.D. 66-70, many lives were lost, and many people were either enslaved or deported.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A small remnant stayed in Israel, fulfilling what Jesus must have foreseen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:47:27', '2025-01-14 21:47:27'),
(898, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 17:37: &ldquo;Then they asked him, &lsquo;Where, Lord?&rsquo; He said to them, &lsquo;Where the corpse is, there the vultures will gather.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What type of bird does \"vulture\" refer to here?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In this context, Jesus used the word aetos, which traditionally translates as &ldquo;vultures.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word gups means &ldquo;eagle,&rdquo; so the &ldquo;eagle&rdquo; in this passage likely refers to vultures gathering around a corpse, symbolising divine judgement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Wherever evil resides, destructive forces&mdash;here represented by the vultures&mdash;are sure to follow.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:48:04', '2025-01-14 21:48:04'),
(899, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What does the &ldquo;corpse&rdquo; symbolise here?</em></p>', 4, 77, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Hebrew term chahal, meaning &ldquo;the one pierced to death,&rdquo; symbolises Christ, who was crucified. The &ldquo;corpse&rdquo; here may thus refer to Christ, who died for humanity&rsquo;s sins.</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The &ldquo;eagle&rdquo; is also a metaphor for God\'s people, as in, &ldquo;Those who wait for the Lord shall renew their strength; they shall mount up with wings like eagles&rdquo; (Isaiah 40:31). At the end of the age, God&rsquo;s faithful are compared to eagles surrounding Christ, who was &ldquo;pierced&rdquo; and &ldquo;redeemed humanity&rdquo; by His blood (Revelation 5:9).</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;Another interpretation sees the corpse as a symbol of sin, attracting the presence of evil forces.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 21:49:09', '2025-01-14 21:49:09'),
(900, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 16:6: &ldquo;&lsquo;And he asked, &ldquo;How much do you owe my master?&rdquo; He answered, &ldquo;A hundred jugs of olive oil.&rdquo; He said to him, &ldquo;Take your bill, sit down quickly, and make it fifty&rdquo;&rsquo;&rdquo;.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How much did the master lose when 100 baths of oil became 50?</em></p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish unit bath measured liquids, equivalent to about 9 gallons (1 gallon = 3.78 litres).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So, 100 baths of oil amounts to 900 gallons, or roughly 3,400 litres, which requires about 150 olive trees and is valued at around 1,000 denarii.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By reducing the debt to 50 baths, the debtor effectively cuts the amount owed to 500 denarii.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The master willingly accepted this immense loss, symbolising God&rsquo;s willingness to forgo judgment for those who seek mercy.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:01:36', '2025-01-14 22:01:36'),
(901, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 16:7: &ldquo;Then he asked another, &lsquo;And how much do you owe?&rsquo; He replied, &lsquo;A hundred measures of wheat.&rsquo; He said to him, &lsquo;Take your bill and make it eighty.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How much is a hundred measures of wheat?</em></p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">One kor (measure) equals about 400 litres, which is approximately 11 bushels.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">One bushel of wheat is roughly 40 kg.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, 100 kor amounts to about 4,000 kg of wheat.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:02:34', '2025-01-14 22:02:34'),
(902, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 16:8: &ldquo;And his master commended the dishonest manager because he had acted shrewdly; for the children of this age are more shrewd in dealing with their own generation than are the children of light.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who were called the children of light?</em></p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The \"children of light\" likely refers to the Essenes, a Jewish sect during Jesus\'s time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They lived communally in Qumran, a desert location, and called themselves the \"Sons of Light.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This reference might point to them as the children of light in the parable, symbolising their devout lifestyle.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:03:29', '2025-01-14 22:03:29'),
(903, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the master praise the steward for reducing the tenants&rsquo; debt?</em></p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John Cage notes that the master praised the steward because he had acted shrewdly in reducing the tenants\' debts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Large landowners often leased their lands, and in years of adverse weather, tenants could not always produce sufficient crops to cover their rent.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Under Roman law, in such situations, a master had several options:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Seize other property owned by the debtor.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Enforce imprisonment for the outstanding debt.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Offer a \"Voluntary Debt Remission,\" allowing for a portion of the tenant&rsquo;s debt to be forgiven.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Through Voluntary Debt Remission, masters could waive part of a tenant&rsquo;s rent, particularly when crop yields were low.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The steward likely used this provision, reducing the debts as a way to ensure his own security by winning the tenants\' favour. This may explain why the steward cut the debts to 50 bushels of oil and 50 measures of wheat.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:04:14', '2025-01-14 22:04:14'),
(904, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 16:19: &ldquo;There was a rich man who was dressed in purple and fine linen and who feasted sumptuously every day.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the red (purple) robe expensive?</em></p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, robes dyed in red or purple were traditionally reserved for royalty and the elite.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;For instance, Solomon&rsquo;s palanquin was adorned with fine linen (Song of Solomon 3:10), and the Midianite kings wore red (Judges 8:26).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, the kings of Babylon wore such garments (Daniel 5:7, 16, 29).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The red robe symbolises wealth.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:05:07', '2025-01-14 22:05:07'),
(905, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the rich man live comfortably?</em></p>', 4, 78, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Red Silk: The rich man adorned himself in purple and red silk. These colours are associated with royalty and wealth.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Fine Linen: He used fine linen as undergarments, another mark of affluence.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Bread Napkins: He would use pieces of bread like napkins to wipe his hands, a custom indicating great indulgence and disregard for resources.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:06:02', '2025-01-14 22:06:02'),
(906, '<p><strong>Luke 16:20: &ldquo;And at his gate lay a poor man named Lazarus, covered with sores.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is only Lazarus named in the parable of the rich man and Lazarus?</em></p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The name Lazarus is derived from the Hebrew name Eleazar, meaning &ldquo;God helps.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This name emphasises God&rsquo;s compassion and assistance in the parable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, Lazarus is carried by angels to Abraham&rsquo;s side, and Abraham speaks on his behalf.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By naming Lazarus, the parable underscores that God will always support those in need, even if others overlook them.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:06:46', '2025-01-14 22:06:46'),
(907, '<p><em>Why did Luke write the parable of the rich man and Lazarus?</em></p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Between A.D. 41 and 52, Judah experienced severe famine, as referenced in Acts 11:28:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;One of them named Agabus stood up and, by the Spirit, predicted that there would be a severe famine over all the world; and this took place during the reign of Claudius.&rdquo;<br>In addition to famine, Rome levied heavy taxes, forcing many to sell their properties.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke uses this parable to convey that during times of great hardship, God calls for wealth to be shared, not hoarded.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:07:25', '2025-01-14 22:07:25'),
(908, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What does the word Lazarus mean?</em></p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The name Lazarus carries two meanings:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">(1) &ldquo;Whom no one can help&rdquo;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">(2) &ldquo;God is of help.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Together, these meanings imply that even when all human assistance is absent, God is present to support.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name can be interpreted as a combination of lo-ezer (no help) and El-ezer (God helps).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the name Lazarus signifies that God stays close to those who have no one else to turn to.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:08:55', '2025-01-14 22:08:55'),
(909, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 16:23: &ldquo;In Hades, where he was being tormented, he looked up and saw Abraham far away with Lazarus by his side.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How is the torment of Hades described?&nbsp;</em></p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word basanos (&beta;ά&sigma;&alpha;&nu;&omicron;&sigmaf;), translated as \'torment,\' originally referred to a test for authenticity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Historically, gold was rubbed against a basanos (touchstone) to verify its purity. If the gold was genuine, the stone would leave a stain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, the torment in Hades is seen as a process that reveals the true value of one\'s actions.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:09:39', '2025-01-14 22:09:39'),
(910, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How could the rich man speak to Abraham?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish tradition, the rich man&rsquo;s soul went to Hades, a place where mortal sinners await judgment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In another belief, the soul remained close to the body for three days after death, which is why Jesus waited four days to raise Lazarus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During this three-day period, communication between realms was thought possible, permitting the rich man to speak to Abraham.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:10:19', '2025-01-14 22:10:19'),
(911, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What does it mean that Lazarus reclined in Abraham&rsquo;s lap?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 78, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish custom, the most honoured position at a meal was closest to the host. The chief guest was able to recline near the host.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To say that Lazarus was in Abraham&rsquo;s lap symbolises closeness and favour in a heavenly banquet.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While reclining, the beloved person&rsquo;s head would naturally rest near the other&rsquo;s chest, evoking a sense of comfort and peace.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:10:47', '2025-01-14 22:10:47'),
(912, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 15:8: &ldquo;Or what woman having ten silver coins, if she loses one of them, does not light a lamp, sweep the house, and search carefully until she finds it?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the woman&rsquo;s lost coin worth searching for?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The woman lost a silver coin known as a drachma, valued at around four shekels&mdash;roughly the equivalent of four days&rsquo; wages.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the drachma&rsquo;s value has varied over time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:13:07', '2025-01-14 22:13:07'),
(913, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Which coin did the woman lose?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The coin was a drachma, a type of silver currency.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During Herod\'s and his sons\' reign, such coins were not minted in Israel. Instead, coins from Tyre (such as the Tyrian Tetradrachma or Shekel) and the Roman denarius were used.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:13:46', '2025-01-14 22:13:46'),
(914, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 15:8: &ldquo;Or what woman having ten silver coins, if she loses one of them, does not light a lamp, sweep the house, and search carefully until she finds it?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the woman need a lamp to find the coin?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Houses of that era typically opened to an inner courtyard, with windows and doors facing inward.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This design left interior rooms quite dim, making a lamp necessary to search for a lost coin.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:14:27', '2025-01-14 22:14:27'),
(915, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 15:9: &ldquo;When she has found it, she calls together her friends and neighbours, saying, &lsquo;Rejoice with me, for I have found the coin that I had lost.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the woman&rsquo;s celebration excessive?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word used for the woman&rsquo;s joy is Xairow, which describes an ordinary sense of happiness in life. In Galilee, it was customary for neighbouring women to share food and leaven.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The woman&rsquo;s joy over finding her coin reflects this communal spirit. She celebrates her happiness with her friends.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:15:26', '2025-01-14 22:15:26'),
(916, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 15:12: &ldquo;The younger of them said to his father, &lsquo;Father, give me the share of the property that will belong to me.&rsquo; So he divided his property between them.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the younger son have a right to his inheritance?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time, sons typically received their inheritance only after their father&rsquo;s death.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To ask for it while the father was alive was akin to wishing for his death.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The younger son&rsquo;s wealth thus symbolised the father&rsquo;s life itself.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:16:05', '2025-01-14 22:16:05'),
(917, '<p><em>How did the Jews divide their inheritance?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Mosaic Law, the eldest son received double the inheritance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;He must acknowledge as firstborn the son of the unloved, giving him a double portion of all he has; that son is the first issue of his virility and has the birthright&rdquo; (Deuteronomy 21:17).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The other heirs received equal shares, but this inheritance only occurred after the father&rsquo;s death.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:16:51', '2025-01-14 22:16:51'),
(918, '<p><em>What is the share given by the father to the son?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Jewish Mishnah, a father can give two kinds of o hari (inheritance) to his children.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Shekiv Mera: This is the portion given by the father to his children on his deathbed.<br>Example: &ldquo;Abraham gave all he had to Isaac. But to the sons of his concubines Abraham gave gifts while he was still living&rdquo; (Genesis 25:5-6).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Matanat Bari: This is the share given by the father to his children while he is alive. However, the children only acquire full rights to this inheritance after the father&rsquo;s death.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why, when the prodigal son returns, the father orders the fatted calf to be killed; the father remains the owner, even though he has given his sons a share.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the parable, the divided o hari given by the father is a Matanat Bari, as it was granted while the father was alive.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:17:30', '2025-01-14 22:17:30'),
(919, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 15:13: &ldquo;A few days later the younger son gathered all he had and travelled to a distant country, and there he squandered his property in dissolute living&rdquo;.</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was it problematic for the prodigal son to go to a foreign land?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The younger son likely went to a Gentile region, as suggested later by his involvement with pigs&mdash;a taboo animal among Jews.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Selling Jewish property, particularly land, to Gentiles was a serious offence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the Ketsatsah tradition, anyone who did so was ostracised from the community.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This cultural condemnation is at the root of the prodigal son&rsquo;s greatest sin.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:18:12', '2025-01-14 22:18:12'),
(920, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 15:15: &ldquo;So he went and hired himself out to one of the citizens of that country, who sent him to his fields to feed the pigs&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the prodigal son agree to take care of pigs?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Paramone Contract was a form of employment contract among the Greeks of that era, binding a person to a master for assigned tasks with minimal pay or benefits.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The prodigal son, by taking on this type of lowly work, symbolically reaches the lowest rungs of society.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His employment in taking care of pigs emphasises his fall from honour to destitution.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:18:48', '2025-01-14 22:18:48'),
(921, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 15:27: &ldquo;The servant said, &lsquo;Your brother has come, and your father has killed the fatted calf, because he has got him back safe and sound&rsquo;&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was so special about the calf that was killed?</em></p>', 4, 79, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The calf mentioned here is a &ldquo;fatted calf&rdquo; (siteutos in Greek).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, a calf would be fattened specifically for major celebrations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This calf was reserved to be slaughtered and eaten only on extraordinary occasions and was served only to the most distinguished guests.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The father&rsquo;s choice to kill the fatted calf shows his unreserved joy, symbolising the joy with which God welcomes and receives a repentant soul.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:19:26', '2025-01-14 22:19:26'),
(922, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 14:1-2: &ldquo;On one occasion when Jesus was going to the house of a leader of the Pharisees to eat a meal on the Sabbath, they were watching Him closely. Just then, in front of Him, there was a man who had dropsy.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was known as dropsy disease?</em></p>', 4, 80, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Dropsy is a condition in which water accumulates in the body, causing swelling. In the cultural context of the time, any excess material in the body was seen as a sign of impurity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the dropsy condition is considered impurity.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:27:10', '2025-01-14 22:27:10'),
(923, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 14:7: &ldquo;When He noticed how the guests picked the places of honour, He told them a parable.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the prominent place at a wedding?</em></p>', 4, 80, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At Jewish feasts, the seating arrangement was designed in a shape that resembles a half circle.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;The most important person sat in the centre of this arrangement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As one moved further away from the centre, their status diminished. The prominent places were at the top, signifying the most honoured positions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:28:45', '2025-01-14 22:28:45'),
(924, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What are the formalities and customs practised during a Jewish meal?</em></p>', 4, 80, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish meals, particularly those associated with sacred observances, followed specific formalities.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;Meals were served at fixed times, such as the Passover meal on the 14th of Nisan.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A person was always designated to preside over the meal. For example, the head of the household at the Passover meal.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">As seen in the Pharisees\' Haburah meals, each participant had a specific place to sit and a task to perform.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:29:32', '2025-01-14 22:29:32'),
(925, '<p><strong>Luke 14:8: &ldquo;When you are invited by someone to a wedding banquet, do not sit down at the place of honour, in case someone more distinguished than you has been invited by your host.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the master of a banquet have any specific responsibilities?</em></p>', 4, 80, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The master of the feast plays a pivotal role in the banquet, particularly in initiating the meal. He begins the feast by taking the bread, dipping it and handing it to another guest.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John 13:26 illustrates this: \"Jesus answered, \'It is the one to whom I give this piece of bread when I have dipped it.\' So when he had dipped the piece of bread, he gave it to Judas son of Simon Iscariot.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish culture, it was considered a profound honour to be given bread in this way.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:30:21', '2025-01-14 22:30:21'),
(926, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 14:12: \"He said also to the one who had invited him, \'When you give a luncheon or a dinner, do not invite your friends or your brothers or your relatives or rich neighbours, in case they may invite you in return, and you would be repaid.\'\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Jews send invitations to a feast?</em></p>', 4, 80, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, the invitation to a feast was a formal affair.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two invitations were typically sent: the first would announce the timing and the guest list, while the second would confirm the guests&rsquo; attendance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The poor, publicans, or outcasts, who were often excluded from such feasts, were invited only if the others declined the invitation.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This structured approach ensured that no one could decline without offering a valid reason.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:30:54', '2025-01-14 22:32:29'),
(927, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 14:17: &ldquo;When the time came for the banquet, he sent his servant to say to those who had been invited, &lsquo;Come, for everything is ready now.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who did the master call to the banquet?</em></p>', 4, 80, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish society, the elite were often the first to be invited to a feast.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Inviting those considered lower in status would be seen as diminishing the honour of the event.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Mark 2:16 gives us insight into this: \"When some of the scribes of the Pharisees saw that he was eating with sinners and tax collectors, they said to his disciples, \'Why does he eat with tax collectors and sinners?\'\"</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the master initially called upon those of higher social standing to attend the feast.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:33:08', '2025-01-14 22:33:08'),
(928, '<p><strong>Luke 14:21: &ldquo;So the servant returned and reported this to his master. Then the owner of the house became angry and said to his servant, &lsquo;Go out quickly into the streets and alleys of the town and bring in the poor, the crippled, the blind and the lame.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the poor live outside the city?</em></p>', 4, 80, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the social and religious context of the time, the poor and disabled were often viewed as cursed by God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was believed that their condition made them unworthy of association with the holy, and thus they were often relegated to live outside the city, such as in the outskirts of Jerusalem, in places considered unclean.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:33:41', '2025-01-14 22:33:41');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(929, '<p><strong>Luke 14:27: &ldquo;Whoever does not carry the cross and follow me cannot be my disciple.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the cross a common symbol of suffering?</em></p>', 4, 80, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The practice of crucifixion, originating with the Phoenicians, Persians and Carthaginians, was later adopted and perfected by the Romans.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For Jews, the cross was associated with the most shameful and painful form of punishment, often reserved for the worst criminals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When Jesus calls His followers to carry their cross, He invites them to take on the immense suffering that comes with following Him. This includes the possibility of physical death.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 22:34:14', '2025-01-14 22:34:14'),
(930, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:1: &ldquo;At that very time there were some present who told him about the Galileans whose blood Pilate had mingled with their sacrifices.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did their blood mix with the sacrifices?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The temple in Jerusalem had a stream used to wash blood-stained sacrificial vessels (Aristeas c285 B.C).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The water, mixed with sacrificial blood, drained through a channel (called \"Arain\") onto nearby fallow land, forming a pool of blood and water that could not be touched until it settled in the ground, as it was considered part of the sacrificial rite.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The blood of Galileans killed by Pilate likely mingled with this sacrificial blood pool.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:15:15', '2025-01-14 23:15:15'),
(931, '<p><em>Was it a crime to mix blood with the sacrifice?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">For Jews, mixing one\'s blood with another&rsquo;s was unthinkable, as they believed that this fate befell only the worst of sinners.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hence, the idea arose that those subjected to such treatment must have been sinners.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:16:02', '2025-01-14 23:16:02'),
(932, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:2: &ldquo;He asked them, &lsquo;Do you think that because these Galileans suffered in this way they were worse sinners than all other Galileans?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who were these Galileans whom Pilate sacrificed?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Historically, there have been several assumptions about the identity of these Galileans.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Followers of the revolutionary Judas, the Galilean.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A revolutionary militant group.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Galilean bystanders were caught in the crossfire of a clash between the Roman imperial troops and local demonstrations.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:16:47', '2025-01-14 23:16:47'),
(933, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:3: &ldquo;No, I tell you; but unless you repent, you will all perish as they did.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What made Pilate&rsquo;s murder acceptable to the Jews?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish law, no homicide was permitted in the synagogue.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Exodus 21:14 states, &ldquo;Anyone who kills a person by treachery shall be taken from my altar to be put to death.&rdquo; Pilate\'s actions, including the killing of these Galileans, took place within the temple precincts, making it even more offensive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This act, occurring in a sacred space, caused the Jews to stumble in their understanding, as it violated the sanctity of the temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:17:29', '2025-01-14 23:17:29'),
(934, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:4: &ldquo;Or those eighteen who were killed when the tower of Siloam fell on them, do you think that they were worse offenders than all the others living in Jerusalem?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was there a tower at Siloah?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The water from the Gihon Spring, Jerusalem\'s only source of water, flows into the Pool of Siloah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While parts of the pool have been uncovered, there is no evidence of a tower. Historians have not found any collapsed towers at the site.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in 1913, French archaeologist Raymond Weil discovered the foundation stones of a tower about a hundred meters from the Pool of Siloah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It is thought that this structure might have been a columbarium, a place for keeping pigeons that are to be used in temple sacrifices.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:18:08', '2025-01-14 23:18:08'),
(935, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:6: &ldquo;Then he told this parable: A man had a fig tree planted in his vineyard; and he came looking for fruit on it and found none.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the fig tree planted in the vineyard?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The soil of a vineyard is ideal for growing both grapes and figs, which is why it was common to plant fig trees on the sides of vineyards.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Additionally, the practice of trellising, where vines grow around trees, was used to cultivate grapes, and fig trees were often included in this method. This practice was particularly effective for growing early varieties of wine grapes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, fig trees were planted in vineyards as part of an agricultural technique that combined the two crops for better productivity.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:18:46', '2025-01-14 23:18:46'),
(936, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:7: &ldquo;So he said to the gardener, &lsquo;See here! For three years I have come looking for fruit on this fig tree, and still I find none. Cut it down! Why should it be wasting the soil?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the fig tree planted in the vineyard?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Trellising, a method of planting fig trees in vineyards, was a common practice.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;The Roman historian Pliny noted that fig trees were particularly well-suited for this cultivation method (Pliny, Natural History, 17:35 199-200). &lsquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This agricultural technique allowed the fig tree to thrive alongside the grapevines, benefiting from the same soil and enhancing the overall yield.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, planting fig trees in vineyards was a practical and effective farming method.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:19:30', '2025-01-14 23:19:30'),
(937, '<p><strong>Luke 13:7: <strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-24f1fea8-7fff-7372-de1c-63c93707bb3f\">&nbsp;&ldquo;So he said to the gardener, &lsquo;See here! For three years I have come looking for fruit on this fig tree, and still I find none. Cut it down! Why should it be wasting the soil?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Does a fig tree bear fruit in three years?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The fig tree generally bears fruit four to five years after sprouting. However, under Jewish law, the fruits of the first three years of a fig tree&rsquo;s life were forbidden to eat.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The fourth-year fruits were to be presented to the Lord, as stated in Leviticus 19:23: &ldquo;When you come into the land and plant any kind of tree for food, you shall regard its fruit as forbidden. Three years it shall be forbidden to you; it must not be eaten.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the farmer may have waited three years, during which he could not consume the fruit, and then awaited the fruits for another four years.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:21:34', '2025-01-14 23:21:34'),
(938, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:8: &ldquo;And the vinedresser said to him, &lsquo;Sir, let it alone this year also, until I dig around it and put manure on it.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Does the fig tree need special care?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Fig trees require well-drained soil to thrive. In traditional farming practices, cultivating around the tree to encourage rooting and applying manure were common methods.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, fig trees need plenty of water before they can bear fruit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Once the tree begins to bear fruit, the water requirement decreases.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:22:12', '2025-01-14 23:22:12'),
(939, '<p><strong>Luke 13:9: &ldquo;If it bears fruit next year, well and good; but if not, you can cut it down.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were the unfruitful fig trees cut down?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Unfruitful trees were typically cut down for several reasons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Unfruitful trees were often seen as a curse upon the land (Amos 2:13).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A barren fig tree was frequently interpreted as a bad sign, a lack of divine blessing.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A fig tree that does not bear fruit can prevent other trees from bearing fruit.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, trees that failed to bear fruit were usually removed. This also serves as a reminder for us to bear fruits for the Kingdom of God.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:22:56', '2025-01-14 23:22:56'),
(940, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:11: &ldquo;And there was a woman who had been bent over for eighteen years and was quite unable to stand up straight.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What happened to the woman&rsquo;s affliction that Jesus healed?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus recognised the woman&rsquo;s condition as a work of the devil.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The evangelist describes her affliction as a \"spirit of weakness\" (Pneuma Exousa Astheneias, 13:11).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Jesus asks, &ldquo;And ought not this woman, a daughter of Abraham whom Satan bound for eighteen long years, be set free from this bondage on the Sabbath day?&rdquo; (Luke 13:16).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus cast out the spirit of weakness, restoring her health and strength.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:23:35', '2025-01-14 23:23:35'),
(941, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:14: &ldquo;But the leader of the synagogue, indignant because Jesus had cured on the Sabbath, kept saying to the crowd, &lsquo;There are six days on which work ought to be done; come on those days and be cured, and not on the Sabbath day.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Jesus work by healing the woman?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus performed the healing of the woman by laying His hands on her, as written:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;When he laid his hands on her, immediately she stood up straight and began praising God&rdquo; (Luke 13:13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This act of healing, done on the Sabbath, was viewed by the synagogue leader as work.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:24:10', '2025-01-14 23:24:10'),
(942, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 14:13-14: &ldquo;But when you make a feast, invite the poor, the maimed, the lame, and the blind. Then you will be blessed; because they cannot repay you. You will be repaid at the resurrection of the righteous.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What would you give in return if you were invited to a feast?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Mediterranean world, it was customary for those invited to a feast to invite those who had hosted them in return.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice also extended to that of exchanging gifts; the quantity of the gift would typically reflect what had been received.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus, however, instructs us to invite those who cannot repay us, stating that when we invite the poor, we should expect nothing in return.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:24:47', '2025-01-14 23:24:47'),
(943, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:19: &ldquo;It is like a mustard seed that someone took and sowed in the garden; it grew and became a tree, and the birds of the air made nests in its branches.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is the mustard plant a tree?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Only Luke refers to the mustard seed growing into a tree.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Typically, the mustard plant in Palestine reaches a height of around six feet, which is more akin to a shrub or large herb than a tree.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Rabbi Shimon ben Halafta mentions the \"mustard tree\" in ancient rabbinic literature.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, although the mustard is commonly recognised as a plant today, its growth was viewed differently historically.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:25:45', '2025-01-14 23:25:45'),
(944, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:24: &ldquo;Strive to enter through the narrow door. For many, I tell you, will try to enter and will not be able.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the narrow gate for the Jews?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, two types of doors to heaven were recognised.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The first was the wide gate, intended for law-abiding Jews, the descendants of Abraham. This gate symbolised ease of entry for those who followed the law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The second, the narrow gate, was seen as the more difficult path, meant for those who struggled to obey the Mosaic law.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;When Jesus urged His followers to enter through the narrow gate, He highlighted that the wider path was not open to them as a guarantee of heaven. The Jews would have understood that the narrow gate was the true way, requiring earnest effort and adherence to God\'s commandments.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:26:18', '2025-01-14 23:26:18'),
(945, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:31: &ldquo;At that very hour, some Pharisees came and said to him, &lsquo;Get away from here, for Herod wants to kill you.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where did the Pharisees ask Jesus to go because Herod was about to kill him?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod Antipas ruled over Galilee, so Jesus must have been preaching in that region when the Pharisees delivered this warning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Pharisees may have suggested that Jesus leave Galilee and go to Perea, an area beyond Herod\'s jurisdiction, as they sought to protect Him from Herod&rsquo;s plans.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:26:50', '2025-01-14 23:26:50'),
(946, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:32: &ldquo;And He said to them, &lsquo;Go and tell that fox, &lsquo;Behold, I cast out demons and perform cures today and tomorrow, and the third day I finish my course.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the fox symbolise?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Hebrew, the word for fox is shual-שׁוּעָל, which was considered a symbol of deceitfulness.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish Midrash often describes the fox as a \"beast of prey\" (Song of Songs Rabbah 2:15).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Rabbinic traditions also associated foxes with lesser, immoral figures in society, while lions were viewed as symbols of strength and nobility (Jerusalem Talmud Shevit 39a).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The saying, &ldquo;It is better to be the tail of lions than the head of foxes,&rdquo; exemplifies this view.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By calling Herod a fox, Jesus was labeling him as insignificant and deceitful, contrasting Herod\'s power and cunning with God\'s integrity and authority.\"</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:27:24', '2025-01-14 23:27:24'),
(947, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus tell Herod that he would be there today and tomorrow?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus&rsquo;s ministry in Galilee concludes with the thirteenth chapter of the Gospel of Luke. From this point onward, His journey leads to Jerusalem, where He is to die on the cross.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hence, all His activities from this moment on fall under Pilate\'s jurisdiction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is why Jesus told Herod that He would be there today and tomorrow.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:27:55', '2025-01-14 23:27:55'),
(948, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:34: &ldquo;Jerusalem, Jerusalem, you who kill the prophets and stone those who are sent to you, how often have I longed to gather your children together as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings! But you were not willing!&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did King David choose Jerusalem to build the temple?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Hebron was initially David&rsquo;s capital from the tribe of Judah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">However, Jerusalem, a city that the Israelites had been unable to conquer when they entered the Promised Land (Judges 1:21), became his chosen city.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Furthermore, it was believed that Mount Moriah, where Abraham had nearly sacrificed Isaac (Genesis 22), was located in Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Additionally, the Gihon spring provided a reliable water source.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;These factors contributed to David&rsquo;s decision to establish Jerusalem as the location for the temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:28:32', '2025-01-14 23:28:32'),
(949, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 13:34: &ldquo;How often have I desired to gather your children together, as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, and you were not willing to come to me!&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is it recorded that Jesus pronounced a curse on Jerusalem in the Gospel of Luke?</em></p>', 4, 81, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Luke&rsquo;s Gospel, there&rsquo;s no record of Jesus cursing Jerusalem, as He is depicted as one who remains composed and does not express anger.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke&rsquo;s Gospel, written for a Gentile audience, portrays Jesus as a model of self-control, aligning with the philosophical ideals of the Gentile world, where a true man is one who governs his emotions.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;This could explain why Jesus is not depicted as an angry man in Luke&rsquo;s Gospel.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:29:00', '2025-01-14 23:29:00'),
(950, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 12:6-7: &ldquo;Are not five sparrows sold for two pennies? Yet not one of them is forgotten in God&rsquo;s sight.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How are five sparrows sold for two coins?</em></p>', 4, 82, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Sparrows were commonly sold for food, and Jewish law required that a mother sparrow with young be freely given if captured.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, &ldquo;When a bull, sheep, or goat is born, it shall remain seven days with its mother&rdquo; (Leviticus 22:27).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">One would receive a fifth for free, possibly a young one when buying four sparrows.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The fifth sparrow, free yet priceless, symbolises God&rsquo;s attention to the least valued.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:39:59', '2025-01-14 23:39:59'),
(951, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 12:13: &ldquo;Someone in the crowd said to him, &lsquo;Teacher, tell my brother to divide the family inheritance with me.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is the reason for disputes between brothers over property?</em></p>', 4, 82, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to tradition, the eldest son inherited two-thirds of the father&rsquo;s property, yet disputes could arise over the quality or productivity of each brother\'s share.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Brothers often worked the land together, which sometimes led to disagreements.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:40:34', '2025-01-14 23:40:34'),
(952, '<p><strong>Luke 12:27: &ldquo;Consider the lilies, how they grow: they neither toil nor spin; yet I tell you, even Solomon in all his glory was not clothed like one of these.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was weaving like in Jesus&rsquo;s time?</em></p>', 4, 82, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Clothing was woven in the home, predominantly by women, although some were employed for temple and palace textiles. Skilled artisans also created elaborate garments, which were valued in the markets.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus illustrates that lilies, without human labour, surpass even the most beautifully crafted garments.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:41:16', '2025-01-14 23:41:16'),
(953, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 12:33: &ldquo;Sell your possessions, and give alms. Make purses for yourselves that do not wear out, an unfailing treasure in heaven, where no thief comes near and no moth destroys.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the Jewish view on wealth?</em></p>', 4, 82, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish sects held various views on wealth:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Pharisees: Saw wealth as a blessing for obeying God&rsquo;s laws.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Essenes: Believed in communal sharing of wealth.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sadducees: Emphasised wealth as a means to enjoy worldly pleasures.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Others saw wealth as potentially idolatrous.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The diversity of these views highlights the contrasting beliefs regarding the purpose and significance of material possessions.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:42:58', '2025-01-14 23:42:58'),
(954, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 12:35: &ldquo;Be dressed for action and have your lamps lit.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What does it mean to gird up your loins?</em></p>', 4, 82, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In ancient Jewish custom, people often wore long tunics, which hindered physical activity or travel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To prepare for strenuous tasks, they would tuck their robes into a loincloth or girdle, allowing more freedom of movement. This practice was referred to as &ldquo;girding up one&rsquo;s loins.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;And he said to Gehazi, &lsquo;Gird up your loins, and take my staff in your hand and go&rsquo;&rdquo; (2 Kings 4:29).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They worked with their long robes tucked into their belts, which is why \'tighten your waist\' became a saying.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:50:02', '2025-01-14 23:50:02'),
(955, '<p><strong>Luke 12:51 Do you think that I have come to bring peace to the earth? No, I tell you, but rather division!</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why pay the last penny?</em></p>', 4, 82, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke contextualises this statement within the Roman judicial system.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Under Roman law, debtors who couldn&rsquo;t repay were sent to debtors&rsquo; prison. The judge, known as the \"Archontes,\" would place the debtor under the \"Praktor,\" or warden&rsquo;s, authority, where they remained until repaying their debt through hard labour.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The judge will place the debtor under the jailer&rsquo;s watch. The only way to be freed is by repaying the debt through hard labour.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:51:46', '2025-01-14 23:51:46'),
(956, '<p><strong>Luke 12:58: &ldquo;Thus, when you go with your accuser before a magistrate, on the way make an effort to settle the case, or you may be dragged before the judge, and the judge hand you over to the officer, and the officer throw you in prison.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does the judge hand over the accused to the officer?</em></p>', 4, 82, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke writes for a Gentile audience, referencing the Greek court system and not the Roman judicial system.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Greek practice, one could approach a judge to resolve a dispute or enforce a debt. If the borrower was unable to pay, the judge could order repayment, even by seizing property if necessary. When assets could not cover the debt, the defendant faced imprisonment.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The officer was responsible for confiscating the accused\'s property and collecting the debt, so the phrase states that the accused would be handed over to this officer.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:52:23', '2025-01-14 23:52:23'),
(957, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 12:59: &ldquo;I tell you, you will never get out until you have paid the very last penny.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Could one get out of jail if they pay?</em></p>', 4, 82, '<p dir=\"ltr\">If a debtor refuses to repay, the lender can approach the court. Once the debt is confirmed, the court can demand repayment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If the debtor&rsquo;s assets were insufficient, their property could be seized and sold to cover the debt.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The debtor was imprisoned if neither assets nor property could cover the amount.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:52:50', '2025-01-14 23:52:50'),
(958, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 11:1: &ldquo;Now a certain man was ill, Lazarus of Bethany, the village of Mary and her sister Martha.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were women allowed to manage wealth?</em></p>', 4, 83, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish society, a married woman could not transfer property without her husband&rsquo;s consent (M. Ketubah 4:4, 8:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, widowed women had the right to manage property in their own name.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An unmarried woman would inherit her father&rsquo;s property if there were no brothers, and she could use it as she saw fit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This indicates that women, particularly those who were widowed or unmarried, had a degree of autonomy in managing wealth, as reflected in the story of Mary and Martha, where they are portrayed as independent in their own right.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:54:11', '2025-01-14 23:54:11'),
(959, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 11:15: &ldquo;But some of them said, &lsquo;He casts out demons by Beelzebul, the ruler of the demons.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was Beelzebul?</em></p>', 4, 83, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"Beelzebul\" originates from two words: \"Baal,\" meaning \"chief,\" and \"Zebul,\" meaning \"sky\" or \"heaven,\" thus translating to \"Chief of Heaven.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In early centuries, it was thought that demons inhabited another realm or even another planet, with Beelzebul as their leader. Beelzebul, therefore, symbolised the head of a demonic kingdom somewhere in the skies.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:54:46', '2025-01-14 23:54:46'),
(960, '<p><strong>Luke 11:20: &ldquo;But if it is by the finger of God that I cast out the demons, then the kingdom of God has come to you.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is it the hand of God that casts out demons?</em></p>', 4, 83, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Numerous manuscripts say demons are expelled by the &ldquo;Finger of God.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish belief, God\'s fingers, or Etzba Elohim, have divine power equal to that of God&rsquo;s own words.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This connection explains why &ldquo;God wrote the Ten Commandments with His finger&rdquo; (Exodus 31:18).</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:56:20', '2025-01-14 23:56:20'),
(961, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why does Luke write that Jesus casts out demons by divine power rather than the Holy Spirit?</em></p>', 4, 83, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Gospel of Matthew, Jesus casts out demons by the Holy Spirit, as in, &ldquo;But if it is by the Spirit of God that I cast out demons, then the kingdom of God has come to you&rdquo; (Matthew 12:28).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in Luke&rsquo;s Gospel, the emphasis is on the &ldquo;Finger of God,&rdquo; as understood by the Jewish audience familiar with God&rsquo;s power symbolised as &ldquo;the Finger of God&rdquo; (Exodus 8:19).</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:56:55', '2025-01-14 23:56:55'),
(962, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why were they astonished when Jesus cast out demons with words?</em></p>', 4, 83, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Among the Jews, some attempted exorcisms using various rituals and objects, such as burning parts of animals (Tobit 6:6-8), wearing specific rings (Josephus, A.J. 8.8.5 &sect;&sect;45348), or burning plant roots (Josephus, B.J. 7.6.3 &sect;178384).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The people were amazed because Jesus needed only words to cast out demons, revealing a divine authority unique to Him.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:57:30', '2025-01-14 23:57:30'),
(963, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 11:24: &ldquo;When the unclean spirit has gone out of a person, it wanders through waterless regions looking for a resting place. When it finds none, it says, &lsquo;I will return to my house from which I came.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is it possible for an unclean spirit to return?</em></p>', 4, 83, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Demons can indeed be cast out in Jesus\'s name, leaving the person&rsquo;s heart like a house that has been cleaned and furnished.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, if that heart is not filled with prayer, good works for God&rsquo;s kingdom, and God&rsquo;s Word, the unclean spirit may find an opportunity to return.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:58:03', '2025-01-14 23:58:03'),
(964, '<p><strong>Luke 11:30: &ldquo;For just as Jonah became a sign to the people of Nineveh, so the Son of Man will be to this generation.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What sign did Jonah give to the Ninevites?</em></p>', 4, 83, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Nineveh, an ancient Assyrian city, was known as &ldquo;Fish Town&rdquo; (from the word \"Ninua\") because the people worshipped Nanshe, a fish deity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jonah, who was swallowed and then released by a great fish, served as a sign to the Ninevites, indicating that Jehovah is greater than their fish god.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This foreshadowed Jesus&rsquo;s death and resurrection as God&rsquo;s ultimate sign to the world.</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:58:38', '2025-01-14 23:58:38'),
(965, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 11:50: &ldquo;so that the blood of all the prophets, shed from the foundation of the world, may be charged against this generation, from the blood of Abel to the blood of Zechariah, who perished between the altar and the sanctuary.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus speak of Abel and Zechariah?</em></p>', 4, 83, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Abel is mentioned in the first book of the Hebrew Canon, while Zechariah appears in the last.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This context likely influenced Jesus to refer to both Abel and Zechariah, spanning the history of prophetic sacrifice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-14 23:59:05', '2025-01-14 23:59:05'),
(966, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:1: \"After this, the Lord appointed seventy-two others and sent them on ahead of him in pairs to every town and place where he himself intended to go.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How many people did Jesus send?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Manuscripts vary, with some noting Jesus sent seventy and others seventy-two. This figure recalls Moses, who selected seventy men from Israel&rsquo;s tribes to support him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;So Moses went out and told the people the words of the Lord; and he gathered seventy elders of the people and placed them all around the tent&rdquo; (Numbers 11:24).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two additional men, Eldad and Medad, remained in the camp but still received the spirit, accounting for both numbers (Numbers 11:26).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, either seventy or seventy-two may be correct, inspired by this Old Testament event.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:12:28', '2025-01-15 00:15:29'),
(967, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus send seventy-two disciples?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, seventy-two represented the Gentile nations of the world. Luke uses this symbolism to imply that the disciples were sent to extend God&rsquo;s kingdom universally.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:13:27', '2025-01-15 00:15:42'),
(968, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What was the significance of the number 70 in the Old Testament?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Moses appointed seventy elders from the Israelites to assist him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;Then the Lord said to Moses, &lsquo;Gather for me seventy of the elders of Israel, whom you know to be the elders of the people and officers over them; bring them to the tent of meeting, and have them take their place there with you&rdquo; (Numbers 11:16).</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jacob&rsquo;s seventy descendants entered Egypt during the famine. They represented God&rsquo;s covenantal family (Genesis 46:27).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;All the offspring of Jacob were seventy persons; Joseph was already in Egypt&rdquo; (Exodus 1:5).</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:14:10', '2025-01-15 00:15:53'),
(969, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:3: &ldquo;Go on your way; see, I am sending you like lambs into the midst of wolves.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus send His disciples to the wolves?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Indeed, Jesus sent his disciples into a hostile environment, which is symbolised by wolves.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The world, as represented by the 70 nations that emerged from the sons of Noah (Genesis 10), is fraught with danger. Israel, in particular, often found itself at odds with these hostile nations, which were sometimes characterised as devouring wolves, as seen in texts like 1 Enoch 89:14.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The wolf also symbolised hostile individuals.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, Jesus&rsquo;s directive to send His disciples among the wolves underscores the imperative need to preach the Gospel, regardless of whether the circumstances are favourable or adverse.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:16:45', '2025-01-15 00:16:45'),
(970, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:7: &ldquo;Eat and drink what they provide, for the labourer deserves to be paid. Do not move about from house to house.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were the disciples advised against going from house to house?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, to stay in another&rsquo;s home and neglecting one&rsquo;s own was seen as a slight against the latter.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was a matter of pride for a host to provide for an important guest. Therefore, Jesus instructed His disciples not to go from house to house in order to honour the first host and maintain the integrity of their hospitality.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:17:24', '2025-01-15 00:17:24'),
(971, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Do disciples have a right to stipend?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, the disciple is entitled to his sustenance. This principle is reiterated in a parallel verse found in Matthew 10:10 (Source Q):&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Take no bag, nor two tunics, nor sandals, nor a staff; for labourers deserve their food.&rdquo; (Matthew 10:10)</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This verse affirms that those who serve God are entitled to their provisions.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:20:17', '2025-01-15 00:20:17'),
(972, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:8: &ldquo;Whenever you enter a town and they welcome you, eat what is set before you.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews receive visitors from another land?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, Jewish hospitality was renowned and deeply ingrained in their culture, as it was a divine commandment (Leviticus 19:34; Isaiah 58:7).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Torah instructs, &ldquo;You shall treat the stranger who resides with you as the native among you; you shall love the stranger as yourself, for you were strangers in the land of Egypt: I am the Lord your God&rdquo; (Leviticus 19:34).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some families even displayed signs on their doors to indicate their readiness to welcome the needy and those arriving from afar (Tosefta, Berakot 4:8).</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:20:59', '2025-01-15 00:32:09'),
(973, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:11: &ldquo;Even the dust of your town that clings to our feet, we wipe off in protest against you. Yet know this: the kingdom of God has come near.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews shake the dust off their feet?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">There are two significant reasons for this practice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"padding-left: 40px;\">First, the Jews typically welcomed guests by washing their feet. If a visitor had to shake off the dust from their feet, it indicated they had not been properly welcomed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"padding-left: 40px;\">This act of dusting off one\'s feet symbolises a rejection of the hospitality that should have been extended.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Secondly, washing a guest&rsquo;s feet was a hallmark of Jewish hospitality; thus, leaving dust on one\'s feet suggested a failure in this duty.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"padding-left: 40px;\">Dusting off one&rsquo;s feet as one departs from a city serves as a sign that they were not accepted by the people there.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:22:03', '2025-01-15 00:22:03'),
(974, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:17: &ldquo;The seventy-two returned with joy, saying, &lsquo;Lord, even the demons submit to us in your name!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus send His disciples only to cast out the Devil?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The expulsion of the Devil was a fundamental aspect of the gospel preached by Jesus.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;As recorded in Mark 1:39, &ldquo;He went throughout Galilee, proclaiming the good news in their synagogues and casting out demons.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The power to cast out demons serves as a sign affirming the gospel\'s truth. In Mark 3:14-15, we read, &ldquo;He appointed twelve, whom he also named apostles, to be with him, and to be sent out to proclaim the word and to have authority to cast out demons.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, Jesus commissioned His disciples not solely to expel demons but primarily to preach the gospel. This gospel stands as the present sign that empowers them to cast out demons. In preaching the gospel, the kingdom of the Devil is dismantled.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:22:48', '2025-01-15 00:22:48'),
(975, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:18: &ldquo;He said to them, &lsquo;I watched Satan fall from heaven like lightning.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Jesus see the Devil fall like lightning?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The most significant downfall of the Devil occurred on the cross. As Jesus commenced his public ministry, he triumphed over the Devil\'s temptations in the wilderness.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Many were liberated and healed, and the disciples were bestowed with the authority to cast out demons.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Ultimately, Satan faced eternal defeat through Jesus&rsquo;s death on the cross.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From the perspective of his faith in the cross, Jesus perceives the Devil&rsquo;s fall.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:23:26', '2025-01-15 00:23:26'),
(976, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:20: &ldquo;Nevertheless, do not rejoice at this, that the spirits submit to you, but rejoice that your names are written in heaven.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews have faith in the Book of Life?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, the year begins with Rosh Hashanah, a time marked by ten days of repentance culminating in Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to this belief, God opens the Book of Life on the first day of repentance when the trumpet sounds, determining who will be granted life in the coming year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These ten days are a time of reflection and repentance; God decides who will live each year.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:24:05', '2025-01-15 00:24:05'),
(977, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Jesus say that we should not be overjoyed at the \'subduing of demons\'?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The dominion over demons that the disciples experienced was derived from the power of Jesus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hence, their relationship with Him is paramount in their authority over the Devil.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A connection with Jesus, characterised by holiness, faith, faithfulness, evangelism and a longing for heaven, fosters true joy in exercising authority over demons.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:24:42', '2025-01-15 00:24:42'),
(978, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:30: &ldquo;Jesus replied, &lsquo;A man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho, and fell into the hands of robbers, who stripped him, beat him, and went away, leaving him half dead.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the road from Jerusalem to Jericho important?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The road from Jerusalem to Jericho has been significant in Israel since ancient times.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Notably, it was the route David took to escape from Absalom (2 Samuel 15:23),&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;the path King Zedekiah used to flee from the Chaldeans in 587 B.C. (2 Kings 25).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">This road was also traversed by Jesus on his way to Jerusalem (Mark 10:46)&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Roman army approached to besiege Jerusalem through this route.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Thus, the route from Jerusalem to Jericho has historically been a crucial thoroughfare for the Israelites.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:25:22', '2025-01-15 00:25:22'),
(979, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was there a road from Jerusalem to Jericho?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;By this way King David escaped from Absalom&rdquo; (2 Samuel 15:23).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This route was also likely the one King Zedekiah took when he attempted to flee Jerusalem during the Babylonian siege in 578 B.C. (2 Kings 25:4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman army also followed the same path when it attacked Jerusalem in A.D. 69 (Josephus, History of the Jewish War, 5.42, 69f.).</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:26:01', '2025-01-15 00:26:01'),
(980, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How far was the road from Jerusalem to Jericho?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">This route lies approximately 1,200 feet above sea level.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It stretches about 24 kilometres in length and passes through the rugged Judean desert.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Because the land was unsuitable for agriculture only goat herders resided in this area.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:27:18', '2025-01-15 00:27:18'),
(981, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:33-34: &ldquo;But a Samaritan while travelling came near him; and when he saw him, he was moved with pity. He went to him and bandaged his wounds, having poured oil and wine on them. Then he put him on his own animal, brought him to an inn, and took care of him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What solidified the separation between Jews and Samaritans?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Instead of adhering to the Torah of the Israelites, the Samaritans followed the Samaritan Pentateuch.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">In 112 B.C., the Maccabean king John Hyrcanus destroyed the Samaritan temple on Mount Gerizim.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The Samaritans also altered their language, making linguistic changes that marked their identity.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the separation between the Jews and Samaritans was solidified.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:27:59', '2025-01-15 00:27:59'),
(982, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the Jews choose the Jerusalem-Jericho route?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The easiest route for the Jews to reach Jerusalem was through Samaria.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, due to their hostility with the Samaritans, Jews avoided this path.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Instead, they preferred the longer route, travelling from Galilee to Jerusalem through Perea and Jericho. The road from Jerusalem to Jericho was particularly treacherous with many curves and ravines.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:28:31', '2025-01-15 00:28:31'),
(983, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:35: &ldquo;The next day he took out two denarii, gave them to the innkeeper, and said, &lsquo;Take care of him; and when I come back, I will repay you whatever more you spend.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Good Samaritan need to pay the innkeeper?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There were two types of inns in Israel:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Commercial inns, known as Pandocheia.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Non-commercial inns, called Katalumata.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Samaritan took the wounded man to a commercial inn, where he paid for the care.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hence, the Good Samaritan was indeed required to pay the innkeeper for the services rendered.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:29:07', '2025-01-15 00:29:07'),
(984, '<p><strong>Luke 10:35-36: &ldquo;The next day he took out two denarii and gave them to the innkeeper, saying, &lsquo;Take care of him; and when I come back, I will repay you whatever more you spend.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Good Samaritan help the man lying in his path, knowing that he was a Jew?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish and Samaritan dress codes were distinct, but since the robbers had taken the man&rsquo;s clothes, it was impossible to identify him by his attire.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, the road from Jerusalem to Jericho was longer and predominantly used by Jews, while the Samaritans had an easier route to Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the man lying on the road was likely a Jew. It&rsquo;s apparent that the Samaritan helped the man knowingly.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:29:41', '2025-01-15 00:29:41');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(985, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:38: &ldquo;As they went on their way, he entered a village, and a woman named Martha welcomed him into her home.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What do Martha and Mary symbolise?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">By A.D. 70, Jewish Christians had been barred from entering the synagogue, a place where old legal rites were practised&mdash;symbolised by Martha&rsquo;s actions, which are marked by a more legalistic and carnal approach.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Saint John Chrysostom (John Chrysostom on Martha, Mary, and Lazarus, PG 61:171) suggests that Mary symbolises the Church, who chose the \"better part\"&mdash;spiritual rather than legalistic.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The contrast between Martha and Mary reflects the Church&rsquo;s spiritual glory as it stands apart from the synagogue&rsquo;s outdated practices.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:30:13', '2025-01-15 00:30:13'),
(986, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:39: &ldquo;She had a sister called Mary, who sat at the Lord\'s feet and listened to His teaching.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is special about Mary who sat at the feet of Jesus?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish culture, women were not permitted to study the law at the feet of a rabbi.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, a rabbi would sit with his disciples, teaching them to become future rabbis.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;While it was customary for women to hear the Torah in the synagogues, sitting at a rabbi&rsquo;s feet was reserved for men.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke specifically highlights Mary\'s position as a disciple, underscoring the Kingdom of Heaven\'s inversion of societal roles. Mary\'s choice to sit at Jesus&rsquo; feet is remarkable because it signifies her deliberate choice to engage with Jesus\'s teachings in a way that broke traditional gender boundaries.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:30:42', '2025-01-15 00:30:42'),
(987, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 10:40: &ldquo;But Martha was distracted with much serving, and she went up to him and said, &lsquo;Lord, do you not care that my sister has left me to serve alone? Tell her then to help me.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Martha do something wrong?</em></p>', 4, 84, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish families, there were usually more than one woman, and when guests arrived, the house\'s matron typically oversaw the preparation of meals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Martha, who likely played this role, was focused on the hospitality and service required to make her guests feel comfortable. However, Jesus pointed out that Martha&rsquo;s worry about serving others was less important than her opportunity to sit and listen to Him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:31:12', '2025-01-15 00:31:12'),
(988, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:3: &ldquo;He said to them, &lsquo;Take nothing for your journey, no staff, nor bag, nor bread, nor money&mdash;not even an extra tunic.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What type of money was Jesus referring to?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke&rsquo;s text refers to argyrios-ά&rho;&gamma;&upsilon;&rho;&omicron;&sigmaf;, or silver coins. Greek coins were generally copper, while Roman coins were often silver.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Jesus may have been referring to the Roman silver coins circulating in Palestine, such as the Tyrian silver shekels (tetradrachms) and half-shekels commonly used by Jews.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:41:41', '2025-01-15 00:41:41'),
(989, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:12: &ldquo;The day was drawing to a close, and the twelve came to him and said, &lsquo;Send the crowd away, so that they may go into the surrounding villages and countryside, to lodge and get provisions; for we are here in a deserted place.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where was the desolate area where Jesus multiplied the loaves?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke identifies this location near Capernaum. The area is not a desert but an area known as Madbera dabet Sayeda in Aramaic.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Likely a pastureland, people often grazed goats here amid patches of grass.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:42:27', '2025-01-15 00:42:27'),
(990, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:25: \"What does it profit them if they gain the whole world, but lose or forfeit themselves?\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who is the Old Testament character who saved his life by losing his property?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Lot, an Old Testament figure, saved his life by relinquishing his possessions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Before God destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah, Lot was initially reluctant to leave behind his belongings.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yet, God&rsquo;s angel compassionately took him by the hand and led him to safety.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">\"But he lingered; so the men seized him and his wife and his two daughters by the hand, the Lord being merciful to him, and they brought him out and left him outside the city\" (Genesis 19:16).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:43:08', '2025-01-15 00:43:08'),
(991, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:28: \"Now about eight days after these sayings Jesus took with him Peter and John and James, and went up on the mountain to pray.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What caused the authorities to treat Jesus\'s royal accession with suspicion?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman authorities had witnessed several uprisings against their rule prior to A.D. 32-33, including:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Judas, son of Hezekiah (A.D. 4)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Simeon the slave</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Judas of Galilee</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These revolts were forcibly suppressed by the Romans, and all the leaders of the revolts were ultimately killed. Against this backdrop, Jesus&rsquo;s royal ascension was seen as a potential threat to Roman authority.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:43:50', '2025-01-15 00:51:02'),
(992, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why is it said that after eight days Jesus went up to the mountain to be transfigured?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The number eight holds symbolism of new beginnings and a new order. For instance, Noah was the eighth person preserved in the flood (along with his family, totalling eight people on the ark).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, circumcision, a sign of God&rsquo;s covenant, was performed on the eighth day.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the \"eighth day\" signified a new era.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:44:28', '2025-01-15 00:44:28'),
(993, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:35: \"They brought it to Jesus; and after throwing their cloaks on the colt, they set Jesus on it.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Jesus\'s royal entry an important event?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the AD&nbsp; 300., a wall inscription was discovered depicting a crucified figure with the body of a man and the head of a donkey.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Created in the first century to mock Christians, this illustration shows that Jesus\'s royal entry was perceived as a an important event in the life of Jesus and later in the life of Christians&nbsp; that even provoked ridicule among the public.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-cb6c223e-7fff-7b8e-89fb-128105d882ff\"></strong>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:45:02', '2025-01-20 05:59:44'),
(994, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:42: \"While he was coming, the demon dashed him to the ground in convulsions. But Jesus rebuked the unclean spirit, healed the boy, and gave him back to his father.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is rebuking the devil the same as commanding?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \"rebuke\" here comes from the Greek word epimao, which implies a direct strike, as in \"hitting a target.\" Unlike a general command, this rebuke conveys precision and authority.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name of Jesus itself is a powerful blow to the devil, casting out darkness with divine authority.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:45:40', '2025-01-15 00:45:40'),
(995, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:47: &ldquo;Every day he was teaching in the temple. The chief priests, the scribes, and the leaders of the people kept looking for a way to kill him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jesus have the right to teach in the temple?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Rabbis among the Jews often taught their disciples in the synagogue precincts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As an established rabbi of his time, Jesus held the privilege to teach within the temple premises, as did other rabbis.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, there was something extraordinary about his words, setting him apart.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:46:21', '2025-01-15 00:46:21'),
(996, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:51: &ldquo;When the days drew near for him to be taken up, he set his face to go to Jerusalem.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does Jesus decide to go to Jerusalem in Luke\'s Gospel?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Gospel of Luke is divided into two main sections:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">1:1&ndash;9:50, detailing Jesus\'s life and ministry in Galilee.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">9:51&ndash;24:53, describing Jesus\'s journey to Jerusalem, culminating in his death and resurrection.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Luke, Jesus sets out for Jerusalem, aware that he is going there to fulfill his mission through his death and resurrection. Thus, Luke&rsquo;s Gospel uniquely highlights this transition point, where Jesus resolutely chooses the path leading to Jerusalem and ultimately, to the Cross.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:47:07', '2025-01-15 00:47:07'),
(997, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:52-53: &ldquo;And he sent messengers ahead of him. On their way, they entered a village of the Samaritans to make ready for him; but they did not receive him, because his face was set toward Jerusalem.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why couldn&rsquo;t the Samaritans accept Jesus\'s disciples?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Samaritans worshipped on Mount Gerizim and despised those travelling to Jerusalem for worship.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Historical tensions were deepened under Roman Governor Cumanus (A.D. 48-52) when Samaritans attacked Jews travelling to Jerusalem (Josephus, Antiquities 20.118).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This division over sacred places led the Samaritans to reject Jesus&rsquo;s disciples.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:47:41', '2025-01-15 00:47:41'),
(998, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:54: &ldquo;When his disciples James and John saw it, they said, &lsquo;Lord, do you want us to command fire to come down from heaven and consume them?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>To which event in the Old Testament is the prayer for fire to come down from heaven related?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Some manuscripts add the phrase &ldquo;like Elijah&rdquo; here, linking this passage to 2 Kings 1:1-10.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In Samaria, after King Ahaziah fell ill, he sent messengers to Baalzebub, the god of Ekron, to inquire about his recovery.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Through Elijah&rsquo;s prayer, God sent fire from heaven, consuming a hundred men sent by the king. In a similar spirit, John asks for divine fire to destroy those who reject Jesus.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:48:23', '2025-01-15 00:48:23'),
(999, '<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Luke 9:59: &ldquo;To another he said, &lsquo;Follow me.&rsquo; But he said, &lsquo;Lord, first let me go and bury my father.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Jews delay burying the dead?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Touching a dead body was ritually defiling under Jewish law, though allowances were made for close relatives.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;They shall not defile themselves by touching a dead body; but for father, mother, son, daughter, brother, or unmarried sister, they may be defiled&rdquo; (Ezekiel 44:25).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Burying the dead quickly was considered an act of reverence, so they were typically buried without delay.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:48:57', '2025-01-15 00:48:57'),
(1000, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:59: \"To another he said, &lsquo;Follow me.&rsquo; But he said, &lsquo;Lord, first let me go and bury my father.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Didn&rsquo;t Jesus permit His own Father to be buried?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Here, we are not speaking of immediate burial following death, but rather a secondary burial, known as ossilegium, practised among Jews in the early centuries.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This process involved placing the bones of the deceased into stone caskets roughly a year after the initial burial.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After death, the body would decompose on a stone slab, after which the bones were gathered into ossuaries and stored in small wall cavities (kokhim).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was typically the son&rsquo;s duty to transfer the bones to these stone caskets.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus likely meant not to wait for this secondary burial ritual.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:49:29', '2025-01-15 00:49:29'),
(1001, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 9:60: \"But Jesus said to him, &lsquo;Let the dead bury their own dead; but as for you, go and proclaim the kingdom of God.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were the burial customs following someone\'s death?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The deceased\'s body was wrapped in straw and placed in grave niches (kokhim).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mourning formally began after the burial with the seven-day period known as Shiva, during which earthen vessels in the house were broken as a symbol of grief.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Close relatives would continue mourning in a period called Shoshim that lasted for thirty days.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After a year, the bones were transferred to the ossuary. Families would continue to remember the departed in prayer.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:50:00', '2025-01-15 00:50:00'),
(1002, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was everyone allowed to bury their deceased?</em></p>', 4, 69, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Burying one\'s parents was traditionally the duty of the son.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Priests were permitted to handle the remains of their parents, siblings or children (Leviticus 21:3; Ezekiel 44:25), but high priests and Nazirites were restricted from any contact with corpses, including family (Leviticus 21:11; Numbers 6:6).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus&rsquo;s call to proclaim the kingdom of God transcended even these sacred duties, urging followers to prioritise God&rsquo;s mission above all else.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 00:50:29', '2025-01-15 00:50:29'),
(1003, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 8:2: &ldquo;And also some women who had been cured of evil spirits and infirmities; Mary, called Magdalene, from whom seven demons had gone out.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Mary called Mary Magdalene?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Mary likely hailed from Magdala, a town situated near the Sea of Galilee, which had a port that facilitated fish trade.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Adjacent to this was an area known for fish drying, called Tarichae.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the designation of Mary Magdalene would have stemmed from her association with Magdala.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:13:08', '2025-01-15 01:13:08'),
(1004, '<p><strong>Luke 8:3: &ldquo;And Joanna, the wife of Herod&rsquo;s steward Chuza, and Susanna, and many others, who provided for them out of their resources.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who was Joanna?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Joanna likely resided in Tiberias, where Herod\'s palace was located.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A woman whose husband was alive typically did not manage property herself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Likewise, in rabbinical tradition, it was considered improper for a husband to study the law while being responsible for the family\'s honour.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, it is plausible that Joanna was a widow.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:15:12', '2025-01-15 01:15:12'),
(1005, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 8:4: &ldquo;And when a great crowd gathered and people from town after town came to him, he said in a parable:&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Luke omit the phrase &lsquo;Talitha cumi&rsquo; in his account?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke crafted his Gospel for an audience heavily influenced by Greek culture, where magicians frequently recited peculiar phrases before performing their tricks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">To avoid any association with such magical incantations, Luke chose to omit the phrase &ldquo;Talitha cumi&rdquo; in his account.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:15:50', '2025-01-15 01:15:50'),
(1006, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 8:7: &ldquo;And some seed fell among thorns; and the thorns grew with it and choked it.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How do thorns crush seeds?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Thorns and their seeds emerge when the first rains fall.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, the size of the leaves produced by such thorny plants varies. The lack of sunlight caused by these large leaves makes it challenging for the seeds to germinate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:16:26', '2025-01-15 01:16:26'),
(1007, '<p><strong>Luke 8:11: &ldquo;The Pharisee, standing by himself, was praying thus, &lsquo;God, I thank you that I am not like other people: thieves, rogues, adulterers, or even like this tax collector.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were the two fasts of the week that this Pharisee observed?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites practised two types of fasting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Community fasting was observed, for example, one day in preparation for the Day of Atonement (Numbers 29:7) or when facing attacks from enemies; during such times, the entire community would fast.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Individual fasting: Some Pharisees practised individual fasting on the second and fifth days after the Sabbath. The Pharisee in this passage was observing such a two-day weekly fast.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:17:22', '2025-01-15 01:17:22'),
(1008, '<p><strong>Luke 8:15: &ldquo;But as for that in the good soil, these are the ones who, when they hear the word, hold it fast in an honest and good heart, and bear fruit with patient endurance.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the hundredfold fruit common in Palestine?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In certain parts of Syria, crops yielding up to a hundredfold were recorded. However, such bountiful harvests were rare, and four&mdash;or five fold yields were generally considered a good return.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In times of particular abundance in Palestine, yields occasionally reached thirtyfold.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:18:01', '2025-01-15 01:18:01'),
(1009, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 8:31: &ldquo;They begged him not to order them to go back into the abyss.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews believe that demons existed on earth?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">During the Yom Kippur festival, the scapegoat&mdash;carrying the sins of the people&mdash;was driven into the desert.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There, it was believed that the demonic power Azazel would take possession of it, symbolically removing Israel&rsquo;s sins (Leviticus 16:10, 21&ndash;22).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice indicates that many Jews believed demonic forces resided on earth. The holiness needed to stand firm against such powers was considered crucial.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:18:39', '2025-01-15 01:18:39'),
(1010, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 8:33: &ldquo;Then the demons came out of the man and entered the swine, and the herd rushed down the steep bank into the lake and was drowned.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is it mentioned that the demons entered the pigs?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites were under Roman occupation, enforced by the 10th Legion of the Roman army. This legion&rsquo;s symbol was a wild boar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Israelites held a messianic hope that the Messiah would come to liberate them from Roman oppression.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, the demons entering the pigs could be seen as an affirmation to the people that Jesus was the Saviour they awaited.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:19:17', '2025-01-15 01:19:17'),
(1011, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 8:41: &ldquo;Just then, there came a man named Jairus, a synagogue leader. He fell at Jesus&rsquo; feet and begged him to come to his house.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the name Jairus mean?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jairus is the Greek form of the Hebrew name Ya&rsquo;ir, which appears in multiple places in the Old Testament (Numbers 32:41; Deuteronomy 3:14; Joshua 13:30).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hebrew meaning of Ya&rsquo;ir is &ldquo;May He (Yahweh) enlighten.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:20:01', '2025-01-15 01:20:01'),
(1012, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Who was the synagogue ruler?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Israelites appointed an overseer for each synagogue.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His responsibilities included:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Preparing the synagogue&rsquo;s surroundings for prayer.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Safeguarding the scrolls of the holy Scriptures.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Overseeing the School of Legal Studies.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Performing charitable works.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Maintaining the synagogue building.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:20:33', '2025-01-15 01:20:33'),
(1013, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 8:43-44: &ldquo;Now there was a woman who had been suffering from haemorrhages for twelve years; and though she had spent all she had on physicians, no one could cure her. She came up behind him and touched the fringe of his clothes, and immediately her haemorrhage stopped.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was bleeding regarded as an impurity?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish law recognised two types of bleeding:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Niddah: Blood from a woman&rsquo;s menstruation.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Zavah: An abnormal discharge of uterine blood.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;If a woman has a discharge of blood for many days, not at the time of her impurity, or if she has a discharge beyond the time of her impurity, all the days of the discharge she shall continue in uncleanness&rdquo; (Leviticus 15:25).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yet, in her faith, she believed touching Jesus would not render Him impure.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:21:05', '2025-01-15 01:21:05'),
(1014, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 8:44: &ldquo;She came up behind him and touched the fringe of his clothes, and immediately her haemorrhage stopped.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the bleeding woman approach Jesus from behind?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Israelite law, a bleeding woman was forbidden from physical contact, as anyone she touched would be unclean until evening.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Everything upon which she lies during her impurity shall be unclean; everything also upon which she sits shall be unclean. Whoever touches these things shall be unclean, and shall wash his clothes and bathe himself in water and be unclean until the evening&rdquo; (Leviticus 15:26-28).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, she approached from behind, hoping Jesus would remain unaware of her touch.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:21:47', '2025-01-15 01:21:47'),
(1015, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 8:48: &ldquo;He said to her, &lsquo;Daughter, your faith has made you well; go in peace.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus call the woman &lsquo;daughter&rsquo;?</em></p>', 4, 85, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish rabbis often addressed young women as &ldquo;daughter.&rdquo; For instance, &ldquo;Sing aloud, O daughter Zion; shout, O Israel! Rejoice and exult with all your heart, O daughter Jerusalem!&rdquo; (Zephaniah 3:14), and, &ldquo;Hear, O daughter, consider and incline your ear; forget your people and your father&rsquo;s house&rdquo; (Psalm 45:10).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By calling her \"daughter,\" Jesus may have referred to a term of address commonly employed by the rabbis and the people of Israel.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:22:17', '2025-01-15 01:22:17'),
(1016, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:2: &ldquo;A centurion there had a slave whom he valued highly, and who was ill and close to death.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Roman centurion arrive in Capernaum?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A Roman army was stationed to assist Herod Antipas, King of Galilee, in Capernaum.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Their primary role was to maintain order and collect taxes.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The centurion mentioned in the passage was the commander of the Roman forces encamped in Capernaum.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:25:00', '2025-01-15 01:25:00'),
(1017, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:5: &ldquo;For he loves our people, and it is he who built our synagogue for us.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Could Jews accept money for synagogues from non-Jews?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Under Halachic law, temples and synagogues could accept donations from Gentiles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Historical accounts show that Jews received funds from non-Jews, such as King Cyrus and King Artaxerxes of Persia, to construct the Temple (Ezra 6:4; Nehemiah 2:8).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, it was not customary for Jews to accept the annual Temple Tax from Gentiles.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:25:50', '2025-01-15 01:25:50'),
(1018, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why was the Roman centurion in Capernaum?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Roman centurions who held significant positions often received property upon retirement (Josephus, War 7:216-217).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Lands captured during military campaigns were frequently allocated to these officials.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This particular centurion had likely received agricultural land in Galilee from the Roman government.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:26:37', '2025-01-15 01:26:37'),
(1019, '<p><strong>Luke 7:8: &ldquo;For I also am a man set under authority, with soldiers under me; and I say to one, &lsquo;Go,&rsquo; and he goes, and to another, &lsquo;Come,&rsquo; and he comes, and to my slave, &lsquo;Do this,&rsquo; and the slave does it.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did John have disciples?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Many individuals drawn to a strict interpretation of Jewish life joined John\'s disciples, who emphasised fasting and prayer more than the general Jewish population.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even after John\'s death, some continued to be recognised as his disciples (Acts 19:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:27:32', '2025-01-15 01:27:32'),
(1020, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:12: &ldquo;As he approached the gate of the city, a man who had died was being carried out, the only son of his mother; and she was a widow.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the dead person taken outside the city gate?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The deceased was carried outside the city for burial because Jewish law&nbsp;<br>stated that contact with a dead body rendered a person impure.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the body was removed from the city to maintain ritual purity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice serves as a reminder of our need to remove the conditions of sin <br>from our surroundings.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:28:27', '2025-01-15 01:28:27'),
(1021, '<p><strong>Luke 7:14: &ldquo;He came forward and touched the bier, and the bearers stood still. He said, &lsquo;Young man, I say to you, rise!&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Wasn\'t Jesus unclean when he touched the bier?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the teachings of the Hillel School, the law permitted a measure of impurity in certain circumstances.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, preserving life, engaging in warfare, procreation, and performing cremations were situations where defilement was acceptable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Hillel Pharisaic School regarded the act of saving a life as one of significant priority.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:29:13', '2025-01-15 01:29:13'),
(1022, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:20: &ldquo;When the men had come to him, they said, &lsquo;John the Baptist has sent us to you to ask, &ldquo;Are you the one who is to come, or are we to wait for another?&rdquo;&rsquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John not refer to Jesus as the \"One who is to come\" and not the \'Messiah\'?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The term \'Remes\' refers to a hermeneutical method used by the Jews, which allows a term to point to specific portions of their scriptures.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For example, the phrase \"coming one\" alludes to Malachi 3:1.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John\'s choice of the Remes method in referring to Jesus as the \"Coming One\" rather than the \"Messiah\" draws on Isaiah 29:18 and 35:5-6.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:29:56', '2025-01-15 01:29:56'),
(1023, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:29: &ldquo;(All the people who heard this, including the tax collectors, acknowledged the justice of God, because they had been baptised with the baptism of John.)&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What did the scribes teach?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The scribes typically taught the teachings of the rabbis who preceded them, often lacking original insights.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, many rabbis tended to repeat the same ideas, leading to a lack of novelty.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:30:40', '2025-01-15 01:30:40'),
(1024, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:38: &ldquo;She stood behind him at his feet, weeping, and began to bathe his feet with her tears and to dry them with her hair. Then she continued kissing his feet and anointing them with the ointment.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the sinful woman wipe Jesus\'s feet with her hair?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Israelite culture, women were typically not permitted to unveil their hair in public, as it was deemed inappropriate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The sinful woman demonstrated profound love and humility by wiping Jesus\'s feet with her hair.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:31:35', '2025-01-15 01:31:35'),
(1025, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:39: &ldquo;When the Pharisee who had invited him saw it, he said to himself, &lsquo;If this man were a prophet, he would have known who and what kind of woman this is who is touching him&mdash;that she is a sinner.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Simon, the host, upset when the sinful woman anointed Jesus?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Simon and others like him often disdained money earned through certain occupations, viewing such earnings as impure.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Profits derived from prostitution and tax collection were particularly frowned upon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, Simon\'s disquiet stemmed from the fact that the money this sinful woman had earned through prostitution was considered unacceptable in the eyes of God.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:32:16', '2025-01-15 01:32:16'),
(1026, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:42: &ldquo;When they could not pay, he cancelled the debt for both of them. Now which of them will love him more?&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What is debt consolidation?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A denarius represents a day&rsquo;s wage. In a scenario where one borrows 50 denarii, the obligations are clear:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The debt must be repaid.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">If one fails to repay, they must work for 50 days without compensation or face imprisonment for up to seven years.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">However, as stated in Deuteronomy 15, in the seventh year, all debts are to be forgiven.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In this parable, the master forgives the debt before the seventh year.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:32:59', '2025-01-15 01:32:59'),
(1027, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:44: &ldquo;Then turning to the woman, he said to Simon, &lsquo;Do you see this woman? I entered your house; you gave me no water for my feet, but she has bathed my feet with her tears and wiped them with her hair.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was washing a guest\'s feet a form of hospitality?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Palestine, streets were often sandy, making feet washing not only a courteous gesture but also essential for maintaining cleanliness in the home.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Washing a guest\'s feet was a customary act of hospitality, demonstrating care and respect for the individual.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:33:42', '2025-01-15 01:33:42'),
(1028, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Should Simon have washed and anointed Jesus\'s feet?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Indeed, when hosting a feast, it was customary for a servant to provide water for guests to wash their hands and feet, along with fragrant ointments for anointing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This practice served to cleanse the dust from their feet and alleviate fatigue from their travels.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Simon\'s failure to extend this courtesy to Jesus reflects a significant oversight in his hospitality.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:34:21', '2025-01-15 01:34:21'),
(1029, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Weren\'t women allowed to bare their hair in public?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the time of Jesus, women seldom wore their hair down in public. There were primarily three occasions when women might have kept their hair loose in public settings:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To perform lamentations</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Widows were permitted to shave their heads in public</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">As a means of seduction</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There were weeping women with loose hair at places of mourning. <br><br>The Jews perceived the sinful woman weeping with her hair down as an expression of her grief.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:34:57', '2025-01-15 01:34:57'),
(1030, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:46: &ldquo;You did not anoint my head; she has anointed my feet.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the host usually anoint the head of the guest?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Oil was traditionally smeared on the head in several contexts:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">When appointing a king.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">For grooming purposes.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To express mourning.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To signify abundance (Psalm 23:5).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Records do not indicate that the host applied oil on the guest&rsquo;s body. However, when guests arrived, oil was generally made available in the household.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Women were permitted to sit down and apply oil to their bodies. A phrase known as \"Anoint Yourself \" suggested that this self-anointing was not to be done lightly.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:35:39', '2025-01-15 01:35:39'),
(1031, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 7:47: &ldquo;Therefore I tell you, her sins, which were many, have been forgiven; hence she has shown great love. But the one to whom little is forgiven loves little.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Is there a connection between the anointing of Simeon&rsquo;s house and the Holy Eucharist?</em></p>', 4, 86, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the early Christian community, the Holy Mass was often celebrated in homes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There, the forgiveness of sins was integral to the service of breaking bread. <br><br>The anointing of Simeon&rsquo;s house, as recorded by Luke, must be understood within the context of the Holy Eucharist, where both the service of breaking bread and the service of forgiveness were part of the Mass in domestic settings.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:36:25', '2025-01-15 01:36:25'),
(1032, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 6:1: &ldquo;One Sabbath while Jesus was going through the grainfields, his disciples plucked some heads of grain, rubbed them in their hands, and ate them.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What grain did the disciples pick and eat?</em></p>', 4, 87, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In some manuscripts, this event occurs during the &ldquo;second-first&rdquo; Sabbath, a term associated with the period from Passover to Shavuot.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Barley, which ripens during this season, may have been the grain they picked and ate.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:38:24', '2025-01-15 01:38:24'),
(1033, '<p><strong>Luke 6:4: &ldquo;He entered the house of God, and took and ate the bread of the Presence, which it is not lawful for any but the priests to eat, and gave some to his companions.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>From which temple did David eat the showbread?</em></p>', 4, 87, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jerusalem Temple had not yet been built during David\'s time. Instead, David went to the region of Nob, where he visited the Lord\'s Tabernacle.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As recorded in 1 Samuel 21:1: &ldquo;David came to Nob to Ahimelech, the priest; Ahimelech came trembling to meet David and said to him, &lsquo;Why are you alone, and no one with you?&rsquo;&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time, Ahimelech was serving as the priest there.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:39:05', '2025-01-15 01:39:05'),
(1034, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 6:13: &ldquo;And when day came, he called his disciples and chose twelve of them, whom he also named apostles.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the significance of the number 12 to the Jews?</em></p>', 4, 87, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When the Israelites first settled in Canaan, there were twelve tribes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, following the Assyrian exile, only ten tribes remained in Babylonian captivity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By Jesus\'s time, the Jews consisted of just two and a half tribes: Judah, Benjamin and half of Levi.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish people hoped that the Messiah would restore all twelve tribes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Why did Jesus choose twelve disciples?</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Moses originally selected twelve men to lead Israel (Numbers 1:17), which later symbolised the twelve tribes.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During the Babylonian exile, ten tribes of Israel remained captive (2 Kings 17:6).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Only two and a half tribes (Judah, Benjamin, and half of Levi) were present at Jesus\'s time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews anticipated that the Messiah would restore all twelve tribes of Israel, choosing twelve disciples as significant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Luke 6:15: &ldquo;And Matthew, and Thomas, and James son of Alphaeus, and Simon, who was called the Zealot.&rdquo;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Why was Simon, the disciple of Christ, called a \"Zealot\" or \"terrorist\"?</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">There are two main perspectives on this:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Simon may have been part of the Zealots, a group dedicated to armed resistance against Roman rule.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Nine different people named Simon appear in the Bible. The term \"Zealot\" may have been used as a nickname to distinguish this disciple because of his intense passion for studying and spreading the gospel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This title highlights Simon&rsquo;s strong zeal for Christ\'s teachings, inspiring us to be equally fervent in our faith.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:40:06', '2025-01-15 01:40:06'),
(1035, '<p><strong>Luke 6:16: &ldquo;And Judas son of James, and Judas Iscariot, who became a traitor.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Judas called \"Iscariot\"?</em></p>', 4, 87, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The name &ldquo;Iscariot&rdquo; is believed to derive from two Hebrew words: Ish,meaning &ldquo;man,&rdquo; and Qiriyah, referring to a place called Kerioth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, &ldquo;Iscariot&rdquo; translates to &ldquo;man of Kerioth.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This name reflects his origins rather than his character.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:41:11', '2025-01-15 01:41:11'),
(1036, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 6:27: &ldquo;But I say to you that listen, love your enemies, do good to those who hate you.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who were the enemies of the Jews?</em></p>', 4, 87, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The enemies of the Jews can be categorised into five groups:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Gentiles</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Opponents of the State of Israel</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Those who did not follow Jewish laws</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Enemies of Jehovah</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Personal enemies</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The term polemius was typically used for the first four categories.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in this verse, Jesus used the term exthros, specifically referring to personal enemies. His teaching emphasises love for personal adversaries rather than political or religious opponents.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:42:02', '2025-01-15 01:42:02'),
(1037, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 6:35: &ldquo;But love your enemies, do good, and lend, expecting nothing in return. Your reward will be great, and you will be children of the Most High; for he is kind to the ungrateful and the wicked.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the Jews charge interest on loans?</em></p>', 4, 87, '<p dir=\"ltr\">There was no legal restriction preventing Jews from lending money at interest; however, usury from the poor members of society, such as orphans and widows, was strictly prohibited.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As stated in Exodus 22:25, &ldquo;If you lend money to my people, to the poor among you, you shall not deal with them as a creditor; you shall not exact interest from them.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:42:44', '2025-01-15 01:42:44'),
(1038, '<p><strong>Luke 6:38: &ldquo;Give, and it will be given to you: a good measure, pressed down, shaken together, running over, will be put into your lap; for the measure you give will be the measure you get back.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why is it said that it&rsquo;s measured and put into the lap?</em></p>', 4, 87, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Some garments had pleats stitched near the waist, functioning as pockets for carrying small items.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;This design is referred to as \"kolpon.\"</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:43:16', '2025-01-15 01:43:16'),
(1039, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 5:1: \"Once while Jesus was standing beside the lake of Gennesaret, and the crowd was pressing in on him to hear the word of God.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Are the Sea of Galilee, the Sea of Gennesaret and the Sea of Tiberias the same body of water?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, these are various names for the same lake.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Sea of Galilee, the Sea of Gennesaret, the Sea of Tiberias and Lake Kinneret all refer to one body of water into which the Jordan River flows.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Historically known as Lake Kinneret, it was also called Lake Gennesaret in Greek.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name &lsquo;Sea of Galilee&rsquo; arises from the region on its shores, while Herod Antipas named it Lake Tiberias in honour of Caesar Tiberius.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:45:23', '2025-01-15 01:45:23'),
(1040, '<p><strong>Luke 5:2: &ldquo;He saw two boats at the shore of the lake; the fishermen had gone out of them and were washing their nets.&rdquo;</strong><br><em>What rituals were required when a leper was cured?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The nets used were likely Trammel Nets, which were designed to catch fish and it consisted of multiple layers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Remains of similar linen nets were found at Ein Gedi in 1964.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Because of their layered structure, these nets needed to be washed after each fishing session to remove debris and maintain their durability.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:46:24', '2025-01-15 01:46:24'),
(1041, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 5:5: &ldquo;Simon answered, &lsquo;Master, we have worked all night long but have caught nothing. Yet if you say so, I will let down the nets.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>In what sense did Peter call Jesus \'Master\'?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Peter used the term \"Epistata\" (Master), a title meaning \"One with the right to command.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This title was commonly used for a ship\'s captain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By addressing Jesus this way, Peter symbolically handed over the authority of his boat to Jesus, acknowledging Him as captain.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:47:07', '2025-01-15 01:47:07');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1042, '<p><strong>Luke 5:14: &ldquo;And he ordered him to tell no one. &lsquo;Go,&rsquo; he said, &lsquo;and show yourself to the priest, and, as Moses commanded, make an offering for your cleansing, as a testimony to them.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What rituals were required when a leper was cured?</em></p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Levitical law, a specific purification ritual was required upon a leper\'s healing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two clean birds, cedarwood, scarlet thread and hyssop, were to be brought. The priest would take clean spring water in an earthen vessel, sacrifice one of the birds over it, and dip cedarwood, scarlet thread, and hyssop&mdash;along with the live bird&mdash;into the blood. He would then sprinkle this seven times upon the person to be cleansed, declare them clean and release the live bird into the open.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Afterwards, the individual was to wash their clothes, shave their hair and bathe in water to be fully cleansed (Leviticus 14:4&ndash;8).&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:49:48', '2025-01-15 01:49:48'),
(1043, '<p><strong>Luke 5:16: &ldquo;But he would withdraw to deserted places and pray.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the wilderness significant to the Jewish people?</em></p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The wilderness held deep meaning for the Israelites, as it was the place where they formed a nation during the exodus from Egypt.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">God desired to lead Israel to another wilderness experience, as expressed in Jeremiah:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;They did not say, &lsquo;Where is the Lord who brought us up from the land of Egypt, who led us in the wilderness, in a land of deserts and pits, in a land of drought and deep darkness&rsquo;&rdquo; (Jeremiah 2:6).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Israel encountered God&rsquo;s love most intimately in the wilderness.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:50:49', '2025-01-15 01:50:49'),
(1044, '<p><strong>Luke 5:17: &ldquo;One day, while he was teaching, Pharisees and teachers of the law were sitting nearby (they had come from every village of Galilee and from Judea and Jerusalem); and the power of the Lord was with him to heal.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who were the teachers of the law who came to Jesus?</em></p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The teachers of the law, known as \"Nomodidaskalos&rdquo;. They were a specific group of Pharisees who acted as legal experts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They interpreted and taught the law, functioning like modern jurists, and served within the court.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:51:27', '2025-01-15 01:51:27'),
(1045, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 5:21: &ldquo;Then the scribes and the Pharisees began to question, &lsquo;Who is this who is speaking blasphemies? Who can forgive sins but God alone?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews view it as blasphemy for Jesus to forgive sins?</em></p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish belief, all sin is ultimately against God, meaning only God has the authority to forgive sins.&nbsp;<br><br>Therefore, when Jesus forgave sins, the Jewish leaders viewed this as blasphemy, as He was taking on a divine role.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:52:13', '2025-01-15 01:52:13'),
(1046, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 5:27: &ldquo;After this he went out and saw a tax collector named Levi, sitting at the tax booth; and he said to him, &lsquo;Follow me.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Matthew also called Levi?</em></p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Matthew was likely also called Levi, a name linked to his heritage as one of the forefathers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, he may have been known by the Greek name \"Matthew\" (Maththaion) while serving in a Roman-administered role.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The name \"Mattayah,\" meaning \"Gift of Yahweh,\" eventually evolved into \"Matthew.\"</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:52:55', '2025-01-15 01:52:55'),
(1047, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 5:30: &ldquo;The Pharisees and their scribes were complaining to his disciples, saying, &lsquo;Why do you eat and drink with tax collectors and sinners?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What food impurities did the Jews strive to avoid?</em></p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews sought to avoid impurities related to food, including:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Utensils that weren&rsquo;t ritually cleaned</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Food that was not cooked in a ritually pure manner</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Items deemed impure</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Food that had been offered to idols</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Meals shared with individuals considered unclean.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jewish people diligently avoided defiling dining practices.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:53:32', '2025-01-15 01:53:32'),
(1048, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why didn&rsquo;t the Pharisees eat with tax collectors and prostitutes?</em></p>', 4, 88, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In their view, eating with tax collectors and harlots was to accept and even condone their professions.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Associating with them in this way was seen as a dishonour that could diminish their standing in society.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For this reason, the Pharisees avoided such associations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 01:54:09', '2025-01-15 01:54:09'),
(1049, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:2: &ldquo;where for forty days he was tempted by the devil. He ate nothing at all during those days, and when they were over, he was famished.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were forty days significant to the Jews?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The number forty symbolised a period of preparation and trial in Jewish tradition. For instance:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Moses spent forty days on the mountain before receiving the law (Exodus 24:18).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">After Israel&rsquo;s sin of the golden calf, Moses spent another forty days on Mount Sinai interceding for Israel (Deuteronomy 9:18, 25).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Elijah journeyed for forty days to Mount Horeb (1 Kings 19:8).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Jonah preached repentance to Nineveh for forty days (Jonah 3:4).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These forty days were seen as a time of probation through which God prepares people for significant spiritual purposes.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:10:16', '2025-01-15 02:10:16'),
(1050, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:6: &ldquo;And the devil said to him, &lsquo;To you I will give their glory and all this authority; for it has been given over to me, and I give it to anyone I please.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Has all power and glory over the nations been given to the Devil?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Devil has no such true authority.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Here, the tempter attempts to deceive Jesus by lying,&nbsp;hoping to lure Him into sin.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;For the devil is a liar and the father of lies&rdquo; (John 8:44).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Devil&rsquo;s claim to power and glory over the nations is a mere fabrication.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:11:14', '2025-01-15 02:11:14'),
(1051, '<p><strong>Luke 4:9: &ldquo;Then the devil took him to Jerusalem and placed him on the pinnacle of the temple, saying to him, &lsquo;If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down from here.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which tower did the Devil take Jesus to?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Traditionally, this tower is considered the Antonia Fortress, built by Herod, and considered the highest point on the Temple Mount.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During major Jewish festivals, Roman soldiers were stationed at the tower to ensure security.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:11:59', '2025-01-15 02:11:59'),
(1052, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did the Devil ask Jesus to jump from the top of the temple tower?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish belief, the Jerusalem Temple on Mount Zion represented the meeting point of heaven and earth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some Jews believed that descending from the temple tower could symbolize coming down from heaven, signifying divine approval or authority. <br>This illuminates why the devil tempted Jesus to jump from the temple\'s pinnacle, attempting to provoke a display that would seemingly validate His divine mission through a miraculous sign.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:12:53', '2025-01-15 02:12:53'),
(1053, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:16: &ldquo;When he came to Nazareth, where he had been brought up, he went to the synagogue on the sabbath day, as was his custom. He stood up to read.&rdquo;</strong><br><br><em>What rituals were observed in the synagogue on the Sabbath?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Singing of Psalms</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Recitation of Torah passages, beginning with the Shema Israel (Deut 6:4-9; 11:13-21; Num 15:37-41)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Singing of the 18 Hymns known as Tefillah</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Reading from the Torah</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Reading from the Prophetic Books (Haftarah)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A sermon or lesson on the Scripture</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Concluding with the synagogue official&rsquo;s blessing over the people (the Priestly Blessing of Num 6:24-26)</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:13:47', '2025-01-15 02:13:47'),
(1054, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What languages did Jesus speak?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus likely spoke three languages: Aramaic, Hebrew and Greek.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Aramaic: This was Jesus&rsquo;s spoken language, reflected in phrases like &ldquo;Talitha koum&rdquo; and &ldquo;Eloi, Eloi, lama sabachthani&rdquo;.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Hebrew: Jesus was able to read Scripture, demonstrating His knowledge of Hebrew (Luke 4:16).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Greek: Due to Hellenistic influence, many people in Galilee knew Greek. In John 12:20-21, Greek-speaking worshippers approached Philip to meet Jesus.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:14:26', '2025-01-15 02:14:26'),
(1055, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What were the origins of synagogues?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">1. The Jerusalem Temple was originally the only worship centre for Israelites. However, when the Babylonians destroyed the Temple in 586 B.C., Israelites established synagogues as places of prayer and Torah study.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">2. Israelites were expected to visit the Temple three times annually. Still, their devotion was not limited to these few occasions, so they initially gathered for prayer in homes (e.g., Bet-Hamikdash). Over time, these small groups became centres for Torah study known as Bamot.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Synagogues thus evolved from Bamot.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:15:07', '2025-01-15 02:15:07'),
(1056, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the Jews read scriptures in the synagogue on the Sabbath?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, the Sabbath morning prayers included three main elements:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Reading from the Torah</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Reading from the prophetic books</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A proclamation or sermon</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The readings were arranged so the entire Scripture could be read in a year. The prophet Isaiah&rsquo;s book is traditionally read in July and August.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:16:37', '2025-01-15 02:16:37'),
(1057, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:17: &ldquo;The scroll of the prophet Isaiah was given to him. He unrolled the scroll and found the place where it was written.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Israelites believe they received their language?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Book of Jubilees, written in Hebrew in the first century B.C., describes how Hebrew was God\'s language during creation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed that God taught Hebrew to Abraham after the confusion of languages at Babel, making it the language of divine knowledge (Jubilees 12:19-27).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:17:20', '2025-01-15 02:17:20'),
(1058, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:18: &ldquo;The Spirit of the Lord is upon me, because he has anointed me to bring good news to the poor. He has sent me to proclaim release to the captives and recovery of sight to the blind, to let the oppressed go free.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who are the poor?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke wrote his gospel during a time of persecution, specifically under Emperor Titus Flavius Domitian.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During this period, confiscation of Christian property was common, resulting in many Christians becoming impoverished. <br><br>These Christians, who had lost their possessions, are the \"poor\" <br>referred to in Luke&rsquo;s Gospel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke shows that Christ comforts those who have lost everything.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:18:09', '2025-01-15 02:18:09'),
(1059, '<p><em>Why did Jesus say that he was anointed with the Spirit of God?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Old Testament, three groups were customarily anointed by God:&nbsp;<br>Kings, Priests, and Prophets with particular emphasis on the king as the one anointed by God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus, claiming to be anointed by the Spirit of God, declares Himself as the King (Messiah) in the line of David.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If God calls someone, He anoints and consecrates them for His purpose.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:18:47', '2025-01-15 02:18:47'),
(1060, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:20: &ldquo;And he rolled up the scroll, gave it back to the attendant, and sat down. The eyes of all in the synagogue were fixed on him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was there something special about opening and closing the scroll in the synagogue?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Scrolls used in synagogues were stored in rolled form, wound around wooden poles called the Tree of Life (Etz Hayyim), much like scrolls are kept today.&nbsp;<br><br>Readers would hold the scroll with one hand and unroll it with the other to read it upright. <br><br>To prevent direct contact, clothes were often rolled with the scroll, as touching the inner surface was prohibited.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:19:29', '2025-01-15 02:19:29'),
(1061, '<p><strong>&nbsp;Luke 4:23: &ldquo;He said to them, &lsquo;Doubtless you will quote to me this proverb, &lsquo;Doctor, cure yourself!&rsquo; And you will say, &lsquo;Do here also in your hometown the things that we have heard you did at Capernaum.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did the proverb &ldquo;physician, heal thyself&rdquo; exist in those days?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, it appears that this proverb was familiar in Jesus\'s time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Plutarch referred to it when he wrote, &ldquo;the merchant who sold cough medicine coughed all day&rdquo; (Apology 7).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cicero also noted doctors who couldn&rsquo;t cure their own ailments (Cicero Ep.ad fam IV v. 5).</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:20:12', '2025-01-15 02:20:12'),
(1062, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:25: &ldquo;But the truth is, there were many widows in Israel in the time of Elijah, when the heaven was shut up three years and six months, and there was a severe famine over all the land.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What lesson did the famine in Elijah&rsquo;s time teach the Jews?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Baal was regarded as the god of rain, but God withheld rain, bringing famine to the land to demonstrate His power.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Despite the drought, God miraculously provided Elijah with water and bread (1 Kings 17) and sustained Zarephath\'s widow.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The famine of Elijah&rsquo;s time thus illustrated God&rsquo;s miraculous provision and grace.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:20:53', '2025-01-15 02:20:53'),
(1063, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:26: &ldquo;Yet Elijah was sent to none of them except to a widow at Zarephath in Sidon.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where was Zarephath, where Elijah encountered the widow?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to 1 Kings 17:9, God sent Elijah to the widow in Zarephath, a Phoenician village situated between Tyre and Sidon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The historian Josephus Flavius mentions a village called Zarephath (Antiquities 8.13.2).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:21:52', '2025-01-15 02:21:52'),
(1064, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:28: &ldquo;When they heard this, all in the synagogue were filled with rage.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did they become angry when Jesus mentioned the events from the times of Elijah and Elisha?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews traditionally looked down on Gentiles, believing they were destined for condemnation.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">By highlighting accounts from Elijah and Elisha in which God&rsquo;s grace extended to Gentiles, Jesus praised those whom the Jews often despised.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His listeners were enraged that a carpenter&rsquo;s son, one of their own, spoke favourably of the Gentiles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:22:42', '2025-01-15 02:22:42'),
(1065, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:29: \"They got up, drove him out of the town, and led him to the brow of the hill on which their town was built so that they might hurl him off the cliff.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did the Jews attempt to throw Jesus off the mountain?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">At that time, Jews occasionally enacted the death penalty (similar to &lsquo;Lynch Law&rsquo;) without formal court proceedings.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Such punishment was administered to those who were perceived to reject God or established traditions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Seeing an opportunity, they attempted to throw Jesus from the mountaintop.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This cliff is known today as \'The Cliff of Precipitation,\' in Nazareth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:23:42', '2025-01-15 02:23:42'),
(1066, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:33: \"In the synagogue there was a man who had the spirit of an unclean demon, and he cried out with a loud voice.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did the Jews know when an unclean spirit afflicted them?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews held that unclean spirits dwelled in the air and could enter people through food and drink, potentially influencing 32 human organs.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Ancient Egyptians also held similar beliefs in spiritual possession.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:24:26', '2025-01-15 02:24:26'),
(1067, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:35: \"But Jesus rebuked him, saying, &lsquo;Be silent, and come out of him!&rsquo; When the demon had thrown him down before them, he came out of him without having done him any harm.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus command the demon to be silent?</em></p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Saint Cyril of Alexandria suggests three reasons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The demon&rsquo;s praise aimed to disrupt the gospel\'s message.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The demon proclaimed Jesus&rsquo;s identity with an unclean tongue.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Darkness cannot reveal light.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For these reasons, Jesus instructed the demon to remain silent.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Christ must be proclaimed with a sanctified voice.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:25:08', '2025-01-15 02:25:08'),
(1068, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 4:41: \"And they were filled with great awe and said to one another, &lsquo;Who then is this, that he commands even the winds and the water, and they obey him?&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why are there numerous signs performed by Jesus in the Gospel of Mark?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 89, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews believed that God displayed four types of miracles during the exodus from Egypt, as referenced in Psalm 107:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Deliverance from hunger</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Deliverance from imprisonment</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Healing from sickness</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Rescue from peril at sea</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These categories of miracles are evident in the Gospel of Mark:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Hunger: Jesus multiplies bread.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Imprisonment: He frees the demon-possessed.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Sickness: He heals the deaf.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Peril at sea: He calms the storm.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:25:52', '2025-01-15 02:25:52'),
(1069, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:1: &ldquo;In the fifteenth year of the reign of Emperor Tiberius, when Pontius Pilate was governor of Judea, and Herod was ruler of Galilee, and his brother Philip ruler of the region of Ituraea and Trachonitis, and Lysanias ruler of Abilene.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When did the Jewish year begin?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman calendar began on January 1st, but the Jews followed a lunar calendar, with the first month being Nisan (Rosh Hashanah), which falls around March.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Passover was observed on the 14th of Nisan, marking the beginning of the Jewish religious year.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:28:16', '2025-01-15 02:28:16'),
(1070, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Who was the ruler of Galilee when Jesus began his public ministry?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod Antipas, who was given power by Caesar, ruled over Galilee and Perea when Jesus began His public ministry.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Herod Antipas was eventually deposed by the Roman Emperor Caligula in A.D. 39 after he declared himself king.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:32:43', '2025-01-15 02:32:43'),
(1071, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why is it said that Jesus&rsquo;s public ministry lasted three years?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus was baptised in the fifteenth year of Tiberius Caesar, estimated to be around A.D. 29-30 according to the Roman calendar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Gospel of John, Jesus is depicted as visiting Jerusalem three times for the Passover (John 2:13, 23; 6:4; 11:55; 12:1; 13:1; 18:39; 19:14), suggesting His public ministry spanned approximately three years.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:33:50', '2025-01-15 02:33:50'),
(1072, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What was Tiberius Caesar&rsquo;s fifteenth regnal year?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Tiberius Caesar became the Emperor of Rome after the death of Augustus Caesar in A.D. 14-15.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, the fifteenth regnal year of Tiberius Caesar corresponds to A.D. 29-30.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:37:13', '2025-01-15 02:37:13'),
(1073, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:2 : &ldquo;...during the high priesthood of Annas and Caiaphas, the word of God came to John son of Zechariah in the wilderness.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the political situation in Judea when Jesus began His public ministry?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The territories of Judea were under Roman rule, governed by Pontius Pilate during the reign of Emperor Tiberius Caesar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman Emperor appointed the high priest, and at that time, Caiaphas held this position. Herod Antipas governed Galilee under Roman authority.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:38:07', '2025-01-15 02:38:07'),
(1074, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Were there two high priests, Annas and Caiaphas, at that time?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Annas, son of Sethi, became high priest in 6 A.D., but in 15 A.D., he was removed by Valerius Gratus, the Roman prefect.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Nevertheless, Annas retained influence by having his son-in-law Caiaphas appointed as high priest, effectively wielding control from behind the scenes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This enduring influence among the Jews led many to consider that there were two high priests.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:38:51', '2025-01-15 02:38:51'),
(1075, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Who was the high priest during Jesus&rsquo;s time?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Caiaphas served as high priest from 18 to 36 A.D., appointed by the Roman prefect Valerius Gratus.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He was a Sadducee and played a significant role in initiating the plot to crucify Jesus.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:41:15', '2025-01-15 02:41:15'),
(1076, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:1-2: &ldquo;In the fifteenth year of the reign of Emperor Tiberius, when Pontius Pilate was governor of Judea, and Herod was ruler of Galilee...during the high priesthood of Annas and Caiaphas, the word of God came to John son of Zechariah in the wilderness.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>When did John receive God&rsquo;s message?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Luke&rsquo;s Gospel, God&rsquo;s word came to John the Baptist in the fifteenth year of Tiberius Caesar&rsquo;s reign, or around A.D. 28-29.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:41:59', '2025-01-15 02:41:59'),
(1077, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Who was Lysanias during the time of John the Baptist?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Lysanias was the tetrarch of Abilene, a region north of Galilee near Mount Lebanon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Records confirm that an official named Lysanias governed the area in the 1st century A.D.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:42:35', '2025-01-15 02:42:35'),
(1078, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Who was Tiberius Caesar?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Tiberius Julius Caesar Augustus was the emperor who ruled the Roman Empire from AD 14 to 37.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Born to Tiberius Claudius Nero and Livia Drusilla, he was later adopted by Augustus Caesar (formerly known as Octavian), the first Roman emperor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In 4 AD, Augustus declared Tiberius as his successor, preparing him to take the throne.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:43:08', '2025-01-15 02:43:08'),
(1079, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:4: \"As it is written in the book of the words of the prophet Isaiah, \'The voice of one crying out in the wilderness: &ldquo;Prepare the way of the Lord, make his paths straight.&rsquo;\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John the Baptist refer to Isaiah\'s prophecy, \"Make the paths straight\" (Isaiah 40:4)?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The prophecy refers to God bringing the Jews back from Babylonian exile in 539 B.C., during which He promised to prepare a way back to Israel, symbolised through the phrase \"making the paths straight.\" This passage from Isaiah (40:1-11) was regularly read and revered on the Sabbath.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">John the Baptist cited Isaiah&rsquo;s words to emphasise that, just as God&rsquo;s deliverance brought the Jews back from exile, a new deliverance&mdash;this time from sin&mdash;was at hand.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:43:54', '2025-01-15 02:43:54'),
(1080, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:7: \"John said to the crowds that came out to be baptised by him, \'You brood of vipers! Who warned you to flee from the wrath to come?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did John the Baptist call them a brood of vipers?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">When the land was cleared for farming, burning off the field waste was common. During the clearing process, vipers, abundant in the area, would flee their burrows to escape the flames. John drew a parallel, suggesting that just as these vipers tried to escape danger, these people also attempted to avoid God&rsquo;s coming wrath without true repentance.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Vipers do not lay eggs but give birth to their young. <br>The young tear their mothers&rsquo; bodies, hurting them from within. John suggested that the people, like the young vipers, had turned against God, who had given them life and salvation, betraying Him in their actions.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:45:01', '2025-01-15 02:45:01'),
(1081, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:11: \"In reply he said to them, &lsquo;Whoever has two coats must share with anyone who has none; and whoever has food must do likewise.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What garment did John instruct them to give?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">John was referring to a garment known as the chiton, an inner tunic worn directly against the skin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over this, one would wear an outer garment, the himation. As a person would wear only one chiton at a time, John urged those with more than one to give to those who lacked.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:45:42', '2025-01-15 02:45:42'),
(1082, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:12: \"Even tax collectors came to be baptised, and they asked him, &lsquo;Teacher, what should we do?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who are the tax collectors John addresses?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Tax collectors from Galilee, which was ruled by Herod Antipas, were likely present.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Goods transported through Galilee required toll payments, and John&rsquo;s audience may have included these tax collectors, who collected tolls along the region\'s trade routes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:46:16', '2025-01-15 02:46:16'),
(1083, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:14: \"Soldiers also asked him, &lsquo;And we, what should we do?&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Who were the soldiers who came to John?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod the Great established a Jewish military colony in Bathyra, which later came under the jurisdiction of Philip the Tetrarch.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The soldiers who approached John likely belonged to this military community-based in Trachonitis.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:46:53', '2025-01-15 02:46:53'),
(1084, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:19: &ldquo;But Herod the ruler, who had been rebuked by him because of Herodias, his brother&rsquo;s wife, and because of all the evil things that Herod had done.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What were Herod Antipas\'s wrongdoings?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod Antipas was initially married to Phasaelis, the daughter of King Aretas IV of Nabataea.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, he divorced Phasaelis and married Herodias, his brother Philip&rsquo;s wife, an act forbidden under Jewish law since Philip and Herodias had a daughter, Salome.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish law forbids marrying a brother&rsquo;s wife if there are children involved.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:47:28', '2025-01-15 02:47:28'),
(1085, '<p><strong>Luke 3:23: \"Jesus was about thirty years old when he began his work.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus wait till thirty to begin his public ministry?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish tradition, a man could assume priestly duties at the age of thirty: &ldquo;From thirty years old up to fifty years old, everyone who can enter to perform service in the tent of meeting&rdquo; (Numbers 4:3).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, David began his kingship at thirty: &ldquo;David was thirty years old when he began to reign&rdquo; (2 Samuel 5:4).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, Jesus, as both King and High Priest from David\'s lineage, began His ministry at thirty.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:48:03', '2025-01-15 02:48:03'),
(1086, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:23: \"Jesus was about thirty years old when he began his work. He was the son (as was thought) of Joseph, son of Heli.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What are the differences between the genealogies of Jesus in the Gospels of Matthew and Luke?</em></p>', 4, 90, '<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Matthew:&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Traces 42 generations</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Abraham to Jesus&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Legal genealogy</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Presented in three sets of 14 generations each</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">This genealogy emphasises Jesus as the successor to King David.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Luke:&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Traces 77 generations</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">&nbsp;From Jesus back to Adam&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">A physical genealogy&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Presented as a continuous list,&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"2\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Emphasis the role of Jesus as the Saviour of all humanity, fulfilling Israel&rsquo;s long-awaited hope.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:49:35', '2025-01-15 02:49:35'),
(1087, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 3:38: &ldquo;son of Enos, son of Seth, son of Adam, son of God.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why does Luke begin the genealogy of Jesus with Adam?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke begins with Adam to contrast Jesus, the universal Saviour, with Caesar, who was then considered divine.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Augustus Caesar was believed to be descended from the gods Aeneas and Jupiter and claimed to have been adopted by a deity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, Luke emphasises that all humanity is adopted into Christ, presenting Jesus as the Redeemer of all, from Adam onward.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:49:59', '2025-01-15 02:49:59'),
(1088, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Why does Luke end the genealogy of Jesus with Adam?</strong></p>', 4, 90, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The promise of a Saviour began with Adam:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;I will put enmity between you and the woman, and between your offspring and hers; he will strike your head, and you will strike his heel&rdquo; (Genesis 3:15).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Luke concludes with Adam to highlight that Jesus is the promised descendant who would redeem humanity.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:50:24', '2025-01-15 02:50:24'),
(1089, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:1: \"In those days a decree went out from Emperor Augustus that all the world should be registered.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Caesar issue the decree asking the Israelites to register?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The decree for a census was a strategic move by Caesar Augustus, who recognised the potential for unrest in Judea, particularly following the death of Herod.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Having ruled Judea for 38 long years, Herod\'s passing raised concerns about possible rebellions for independence.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The census aimed to consolidate Roman authority and prevent any potential insurrections by ensuring that the population was accounted for and under control.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:51:25', '2025-01-15 02:51:25'),
(1090, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:1: \"In those days a decree went out from Emperor Augustus that all the world should be registered.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was the Roman Empire under a census when Jesus was born?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Roman Empire conducted a census every fourteen years. Historical records, including Gamaliel&rsquo;s speech (Acts 5:37), suggest that a census took place in AD 6, but this likely involved a specific census for the Jewish people.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Herod, who had ruled for nearly 38 years, was approaching the end of his life, and Caesar Augustus anticipated potential rebellion against Rome upon Herod&rsquo;s death.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, some Jews resisted paying Roman taxes (Luke 20:22).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, strict tax collection was enforced as a preventive measure against riots, indicating that Caesar likely ordered a special census for Judaea.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:52:01', '2025-01-15 02:52:01'),
(1091, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:3: &ldquo;All went to their own towns to be registered.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Joseph learn about Augustus Caesar&rsquo;s order?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Caesar&rsquo;s royal edict was proclaimed in various parts of the country and displayed in public spaces, such as bathhouses, temples and marketplaces, as documented by Josephus (Antiquities 19.291).</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:52:35', '2025-01-15 02:52:35'),
(1092, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Caesar order a census of the Jews?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<ol>\r\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To identify eligible taxpayers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"4\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">To recruit people for military service.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, he ordered a census of the Jewish population, demonstrating how God orchestrates events for His purposes.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:53:56', '2025-01-15 02:53:56'),
(1093, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:2: &ldquo;This was the first registration and was taken while Quirinius was governor of Syria.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was a census necessary for the Jewish people?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jews were dispersed from Palestine to various regions, yet they still paid a tax to the Jewish authorities.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Those outside Palestine were required to pay only half of what the local Jews paid.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Only those aged between 15 and 60 paid this tax. This demanded the recording of birth dates.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:54:30', '2025-01-15 02:54:30'),
(1094, '<p><em>Was Jesus born when Quirinius was the governor of Syria?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The historical record indicates that Quirinius became the governor of Syria only in the 6th century A.D. At the time of Jesus\'s birth, traditionally dated around 5 B.C., Quinctilius Varus was the governor of Syria.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Luke may have confused these two figures.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Another census did occur in A.D. 6, during Quirinius&rsquo;s governorship in Syria. This census led to a rebellion against Roman rule led by Judas the Galilean, marking the beginning of tensions that would culminate in the First Jewish War (A.D. 67-70), which resulted in the destruction of the Temple in Jerusalem.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke may have unintentionally conflated the events surrounding Jesus\'s birth with the later census under Quirinius.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:55:13', '2025-01-15 02:55:13'),
(1095, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Who was Quirinius?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 68, '<p>Quirinius (also known as Quirinaios in historical accounts) was an advisor appointed by Emperor Augustus to assist Caesar&rsquo;s young son, Gaius, who was in charge of Roman Syria around 2 B.C. (Tacitus provides this historical context).</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:55:38', '2025-01-15 02:55:38'),
(1096, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the census hold significance in Jewish life?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Two censuses significantly impacted Jewish life, both bringing unforeseen calamities.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">David&rsquo;s census in 2 Samuel 24 resulted in a plague among the people.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Later, in AD 67, a census incited resistance from Judas the Galilean against Roman demands, culminating in Jerusalem&rsquo;s destruction in AD 70.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:57:49', '2025-01-15 02:57:49'),
(1097, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did everyone obey the command to register their names?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;&ldquo;This was the first registration and was taken while Quirinius was governor of Syria.&rdquo; Luke 2:2</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A group of Jews revolted against this census registration because they opposed they didn&rsquo;t want&nbsp; their names to be recorded.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Judas of Galilee led this movement of resistance against the registration.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Joseph&rsquo;s family from Galilee cooperated with the registration process.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:58:27', '2025-01-15 02:58:27'),
(1098, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:4-5: &ldquo;Joseph also went from the town of Nazareth in Galilee to Judea, to the city of David called Bethlehem, because he was descended from the house and family of David. He went to be registered with Mary, to whom he was engaged and who was expecting a child.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did Joseph know he was descended from David?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Jews held strong connections to their ancestral heritage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For instance, Paul knew he was from the tribe of Benjamin:<br>&ldquo;For I was circumcised on the eighth day, a member of the people of Israel, of the tribe of Benjamin, a Hebrew born of Hebrews; as to the law, a Pharisee&rdquo; (Philippians 3:5).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Benjamin, Paul&rsquo;s ancestor, lived about 1,500 years before him.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Similarly, Joseph would have been well aware of his Davidic lineage, passed down through oral tradition and family memory, even though David lived approximately 1,000 years prior.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:59:08', '2025-01-15 02:59:08'),
(1099, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did Bethlehem get named as the City of David?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Salma, a descendant of Caleb, is considered the founding father of Bethlehem (1 Chronicles 2:51).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">David&rsquo;s family line also had deep roots in Bethlehem, where his ancestors&mdash;Elimelech, Naomi, Boaz and Ruth&mdash;dwelt (Ruth 1:6).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Boaz, the great-grandfather of David&rsquo;s father, Jesse, was integral to this lineage. Bethlehem also holds significance as the place where Samuel anointed David as king (1 Samuel 16:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This rich heritage established Bethlehem as the City of David.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 02:59:43', '2025-01-15 02:59:43'),
(1100, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:7: &ldquo;And she gave birth to her firstborn son and wrapped him in bands of cloth, and laid him in a manger, because there was no place for them in the inn.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Where did Mary lay the infant Jesus?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Scripture indicates that Mary laid the infant Jesus in a manger &phi;ά&tau;&nu;&eta;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek word for manger, phatnē-&phi;ά&tau;&nu;&eta;, signifies a feeding trough for domesticated animals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was here, in a humble manger &phi;ά&tau;&nu;&eta;, that Mary placed Jesus.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:00:28', '2025-01-15 03:00:28'),
(1101, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What were the typical facilities that were available at inns?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Inns of that time were usually simple, single-room dwellings, offering limited space for rest and sleep.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They served primarily as protection from night-time dangers, including thieves.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Most inns employed a keeper for security reasons.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:00:58', '2025-01-15 03:00:58'),
(1102, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:8: &ldquo;In that region, there were shepherds living in the fields, keeping watch over their flock by night.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was it necessary to watch the goats at night?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish tradition divided the day and night into several watches.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The night was kept from 6 p.m. to 6 a.m., during which the nocturnal watch (night watch) was observed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Goat herders, often working in shifts, kept vigil in turns, watching over the flock throughout both day and night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Those assigned to guard sheep in the daytime could rest at night, but they remained vigilant in protecting the goats through the night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:01:36', '2025-01-15 03:01:36'),
(1103, '<p><em><strong>&nbsp;</strong>Where did the shepherds live?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Near Bethlehem, there stood a tower known as the Tower of Eder.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was near this site that Jacob buried Rachel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The shepherds present at the time of Jesus&rsquo;s birth were living near this very tower.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:02:02', '2025-01-15 03:02:02');
INSERT INTO `got_questions` (`id`, `question`, `category_id`, `sub_category_id`, `answer`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1104, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why were there shepherds near Bethlehem?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The region around Bethlehem was arid, and goats were the primary source of livelihood for those living there.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Additionally, because of Bethlehem\'s proximity to Jerusalem and the temple, pilgrims often sold goats to support their worship offerings.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As a result, shepherds were commonly found near Bethlehem.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:02:42', '2025-01-15 03:02:42'),
(1105, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:10: &ldquo;But the angel said to them, &lsquo;Do not be afraid; for see&mdash;I am bringing you good news of great joy for all the people.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was known as the significant &lsquo;good news&rsquo; before Jesus&rsquo;s time?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The word \"gospel\" comes from the Greek term evangelion, which was strongly associated with the Roman army.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Evangelion was also the title given to a messenger dispatched to deliver news of victory or significant events to the emperor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over time, this term came to represent the greatest news to humanity&mdash;the birth of the Messiah.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:03:11', '2025-01-15 03:03:11'),
(1106, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:11: &ldquo;To you is born this day in the city of David a Saviour, who is the Messiah, the Lord.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Bethlehem called the City of David?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Bethlehem was known as David&rsquo;s city because David&rsquo;s father, Jesse, was identified as &ldquo;Jesse of Bethlehem&rdquo; (1 Sam 17:58).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">David&rsquo;s family roots in Bethlehem granted the city its title, the City of David.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:04:56', '2025-01-15 03:04:56'),
(1107, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was it significant to the Jews that Jesus was born in the City of David?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, the Jewish people held many beliefs concerning David and the anticipated Messiah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">They believed that God would bring forth another David (b. Sanh. 98b) and entrust the kingdom to this new David (Midr. Ps. 5.4, 18.27).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some even believed this new Davidic reign would be eternal (b. Hag. 14a, b. Sanh. 38b).</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:05:35', '2025-01-15 03:05:35'),
(1108, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Was David&rsquo;s lineage seen as flawed?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">David&rsquo;s great-grandmother, Ruth, was a Moabite woman.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">While this was an unusual lineage, the Jews did not regard it as a flaw.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Instead, they believed that God compensated for any perceived shortcomings in that ancestry (b. Yebam. 77a; Midr. Ps. 116.9, 1.2).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish tradition even held that the Law forbade marriage to a Moabite man, but not a Moabite woman (b. Yebam. 76b), thus honouring Ruth&rsquo;s place in David&rsquo;s line.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:06:18', '2025-01-15 03:06:18'),
(1109, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did Jesus instruct the demons to be silent?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, Jesus used the term phioupheti, meaning &ldquo;Incantational Restriction.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus directed the Devil to &ldquo;cease all movements through this command.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:06:53', '2025-01-15 03:06:53'),
(1110, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:14: &ldquo;Glory to God in the highest, and on earth peace among those whom he favours!&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the significance of the \'peace\' sung by the angels then?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Augustus Caesar\'s proclamation of PAX ROMANA (Peace and Prosperity) (B.C. 27 - A.D. 14) was widely known.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Augustus claimed to promise eternal peace to all lands under his rule.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, in the years that followed, there were numerous riots and disturbances along Rome\'s borders, particularly in Judea and Galilee.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In contrast, God became man to offer the peace that Caesar could not provide. This is the true significance of the peace heralded by the angels: only Christ can grant genuine peace.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:07:31', '2025-01-15 03:07:31'),
(1111, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:16: &ldquo;So they went with haste and found Mary and Joseph, and the child lying in the manger.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Was Christ\'s birth in a manger a fulfillment of prophecy?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Isaiah begins his prophecy with a lamentation, stating, &ldquo;The ox knows its owner, and the donkey its master&rsquo;s crib; but Israel does not know, my people do not understand&rdquo; (Isaiah 1:3).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The birth of Christ in a manger serves as a poignant reminder to those who fail to recognise the true Master.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:08:18', '2025-01-15 03:08:18'),
(1112, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 22:19: &ldquo;Then he took a loaf of bread, and when he had given thanks, he broke it and gave it to them, saying, &lsquo;This is my body, which is given for you. Do this in remembrance of me.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Did God say, &ldquo;Do this in remembrance of me&rdquo; in the Old Testament?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Indeed, God required that frankincense be placed with the bread of the Presence in the Tabernacle (Leviticus 24:7). He instructed that this offering be kept in memory of Him.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Furthermore, God promised to remember humanity when the priests sounded their trumpets (Numbers 10:10).&nbsp;</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">God desires to be remembered (Anamnesis).&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:08:59', '2025-01-15 03:08:59'),
(1113, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:21: &ldquo;After eight days had passed, it was time to circumcise the child; and he was called Jesus, the name given by the angel before he was conceived.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How did Yeshua come to be known as Jesus?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Hebrew, He was known as Yeshua. However, since the Gospel was written in Greek, the name was rendered using \'s\', as there is no \'sh\' sound in Greek.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Consequently, His name appears as \"Iesous\" in Greek. When Latin became the official language of the Church, \'Iesous\' was adapted, as the \'y\' is pronounced like \'i\' in Latin.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Thus, Yeshua came to be known as Jesus in the English language.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:09:39', '2025-01-15 03:09:39'),
(1114, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:22: &ldquo;When the time came for their purification according to the law of Moses, they brought him up to Jerusalem to present him to the Lord.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was Jesus taken to the temple?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to the law of Moses, both men and beasts were required to undergo certain rituals. The firstborn belonged to God (Exodus 13), and a clean animal\'s firstborn was to be sacrificed.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Additionally, the firstborn son had to be redeemed for five shekels.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus was presented at the temple for this redemption.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:10:21', '2025-01-15 03:10:21'),
(1115, '<p><em>How many days after the birth of Jesus was the purification of Mary?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">A woman who has given birth is considered impure due to the blood associated with childbirth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The Scripture states, &ldquo;Tell the people of Israel that a woman who conceives and gives birth to a male child shall wait seven days; she shall be impure. On the eighth day, the child is to be circumcised. Then she must wait thirty-three days for purification from the blood. She shall not touch any holy thing or enter the holy place until the days of her purification are completed&rdquo; (Leviticus 12:2-4).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus was circumcised on the eighth day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Following this, Mary waited thirty-three days for her purification(Leviticus 12:2-4).</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:11:10', '2025-01-15 03:11:10'),
(1116, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Should Jesus have been offered in the temple?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The tribe of Levi was designated to serve in the temple, as stated, &ldquo;The priests, the sons of Levi, shall stand and declare to all the people of Israel: &lsquo;Give heed, O Israel! Today you have become the people of the Lord your God&rsquo;&rdquo; (Deuteronomy 10:8).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, Jesus belonged to the tribe of Judah.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">His consecration in the temple signifies His eternal priesthood.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:11:43', '2025-01-15 03:11:43'),
(1117, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did the name Jerusalem come about?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Since the time of Abraham, the location was known as Salem (Genesis 14:18; Psalm 76:2).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">During the Greek period, it became associated with the temple (Heiron) of Salem, which eventually evolved into Jerusalem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Later, David added the name \"YHWH Yireh,\" further transforming it into Jerusalem.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:12:18', '2025-01-15 03:12:18'),
(1118, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How many days after childbirth were allotted for purification according to Jewish law?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The twelfth chapter of Leviticus provides the laws regarding purification.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A woman was considered impure for seven days following the birth of a male child and fourteen days after the birth of a female child.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">After this initial period, there was an additional purification period: thirty-three days for a male child and sixty-six days for a female child.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Following these periods, a woman was expected to go to the temple to offer a sacrifice.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:13:01', '2025-01-15 03:13:01'),
(1119, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:23-24&ldquo;And they did so according to the law of the Lord, that all the firstborn should be called holy to the Lord, and that a pair of turtledoves or two young pigeons should be sacrificed&rdquo;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why were the firstborn sons brought to the temple?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish tradition, the firstborn sons were to be redeemed.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This act was known as Pidyon Haben.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">All firstborn sons belonged to God, and parents could reclaim them through a ritual of redemption.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For this purpose, Mary&nbsp; sacrificed a pair of young pigeons or two turtledoves in the temple.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:14:09', '2025-01-15 03:14:09'),
(1120, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:24: \"And they offered a sacrifice according to what is stated in the law of the Lord, &lsquo;a pair of turtle-doves or two young pigeons.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Which bird is called turtle dove?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The turtle dove, Streptopelia turtur, is a smaller pigeon known for its distinctive \'tur... tur... tur\' sound, not due to any resemblance to an actual turtle.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the eighth day, there are three significant rituals:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Circumcision</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Purification</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Dedication</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two doves were offered as a purification sacrifice for Mary. This was considered a poor person&rsquo;s offering:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;If she cannot afford a sheep, she shall take two turtle-doves or two pigeons, one for a burnt offering and the other for a sin offering. The priest shall make atonement on her behalf, and she shall be clean&rdquo; (Leviticus 12:8).&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:14:52', '2025-01-15 03:14:52'),
(1121, '<p><strong>Luke 2:25: &ldquo;Now there was a man in Jerusalem whose name was Simeon; this man was righteous and devout, looking forward to the consolation of Israel, and the Holy Spirit rested on him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What consolation did the Israelites hope for?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">They anticipated the Paraklēsis (Consolation) promised by God to Israel, as expressed in the prophecy:<br>&ldquo;They shall come with weeping, and with consolations I will lead them back. I will let them walk by brooks of water. For I have become a father to Israel, and Ephraim is my firstborn&rdquo; (Jeremiah 31:9).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This comfort promised to Israel involved the gathering of its scattered children, fulfilling Jeremiah&rsquo;s vision.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:15:30', '2025-01-15 03:15:30'),
(1122, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Did the Jews expect consolation from God?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, the prophet Isaiah foretold Israel&rsquo;s coming comfort: &ldquo;Comfort, O comfort my people, says your God&rdquo; (Isaiah 40:1).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Further, Isaiah says, &ldquo;As a mother comforts her child, so I will comfort you; you shall be comforted in Jerusalem&rdquo; (Isaiah 66:13).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Israel awaited the promised comfort as prophesied by Isaiah.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:15:59', '2025-01-15 03:15:59'),
(1123, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Who was considered godly according to the Jews?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The Greek term eusebes &nbsp;&epsilon;ὐ&sigma;&epsilon;&beta;ή&sigmaf;(meaning devout or pious) is translated here as godly.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This word describes a person with devoted piety toward God&rsquo;s law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A truly godly individual exhibits deep zeal for God&rsquo;s commandments.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:16:36', '2025-01-15 03:16:36'),
(1124, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:34: &ldquo;Then Simeon blessed them and said to his mother Mary, &lsquo;This child is destined for the falling and the rising of many in Israel, and to be a sign that will be opposed.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Simeon tell Mary that Jesus would be a controversial figure?</em></p>', 4, 7, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In the Gospel of Luke, Mary embodies the Chosen Israel (Anawim YHWH), and the Holy Family of Nazareth represents a redeemed Israel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, this chosen Israel excludes certain groups, making them a potentially controversial figure for some.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:17:17', '2025-01-15 03:17:17'),
(1125, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:35: &ldquo;so that the inner thoughts of many will be revealed&mdash;and a sword will pierce your own soul too.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What sword pierced Mary&rsquo;s heart?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<ol>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary\'s grief at Jesus&rsquo; suffering &ndash; often symbolised by the Piet&agrave;.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">Mary&rsquo;s inner doubts (according to St. Basil).</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\">The accusations Mary had to endure concerning Jesus.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These elements are traditionally viewed as the &lsquo;sword&rsquo; that pierced Mary&rsquo;s heart.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:17:54', '2025-01-15 03:17:54'),
(1126, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:34-35: &ldquo;Simeon blessed them and said to his mother Mary, &lsquo;This child is destined for the falling and the rising of many in Israel and to be a sign that will be opposed so that the inner thoughts of many will be revealed&mdash;and a sword will pierce your own soul too.&rsquo;&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What was the sword that pierced Mary&rsquo;s heart?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">The early Church Fathers interpreted this \"sword\" as the sorrow in Mary\'s heart upon comprehending the profound mysteries of salvation made possible through Jesus\'s death on the cross.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Saint Ambrose describes this sword as &ldquo;the pain of her heart in understanding the mysteries of salvation that Jesus makes possible through the death on the cross.&rdquo;<br>Saint John Damascene adds that &ldquo;in God\'s plan for the salvation of humankind, this sword represents the pain of realizing the significance of her son&rsquo;s (Christ&rsquo;s) death</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:19:34', '2025-01-15 03:19:34'),
(1127, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:36: &ldquo;There was also a prophet, Anna, the daughter of Phanuel, of the tribe of Asher. She was of a great age, having lived with her husband seven years after her marriage.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Were there female prophets in the Jerusalem Temple?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, it is likely that prophets, leading ascetic lives, were associated with the Jerusalem temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">One example is Huldah, a prophetess who lived during King Josiah&rsquo;s reign.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As recorded in 2 Kings 22:14, &ldquo;Hilkiah the priest, Ahikam, Achbor, Shaphan, and Asaiah went to Huldah the prophetess, the wife of Shallum, son of Tikvah, son of Harhas, keeper of the wardrobe, who resided in Jerusalem&rsquo;s new quarter.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Let us imitate Anna in three ways: (1) &lsquo;Prayer as a Guard against Satanic Temptation,&rsquo; (2) &lsquo;Watchfulness in Preparation for the Coming of the Son of Man,&rsquo; and (3) &lsquo;Self-Denial to Ward Off Greed and Arrogance.&rsquo;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:20:18', '2025-01-15 03:20:18'),
(1128, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:37: &ldquo;She never left the temple but worshipped there with fasting and prayer night and day.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>How old was the Prophet Anna?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Since Anna was a widow for 84 years, she was likely over 100 years old when she met Jesus.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;Additionally, according to the Jews, the number 84 (7 x 12) symbolises a complete or fulfilled life.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Luke may have been thinking of Judith, who lived to be 105 years old (Judith 16:23).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:21:08', '2025-01-15 03:21:08'),
(1129, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How many days did the Jews fast?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish law, fasting was only required on the Day of Atonement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As Leviticus 16:30-31 states, &ldquo;It is a day of atonement for you to cleanse you from all your sins; it is a Sabbath of complete rest, and you shall fast.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">However, monastic groups like the Essenes fasted for extended periods.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:21:40', '2025-01-15 03:21:40'),
(1130, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:42: &ldquo;And when he was twelve years old, they went up as usual for the festival.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did twelve-year-old Jesus become a wonder for his audience?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">In Jewish tradition, a boy officially starts the study of the interpretations of Thorah and becomes a Bar Mitzvah or &ldquo;Son of the Commandment&rdquo; at the age of 12. From this age onwards he is accountable for each commandment and its interpretation of the Law.,&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From the age of twelve, a Jewish boy starts to attends the synagogue prayers and listens to the interpretations of the law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Therefore, twelve-year-old Jesus, who has not become a Bar Mitzvah, has shown profound knowledge in Law and its interpretations.&nbsp; That is the reason why his words were taken with wonder in the temple.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:22:20', '2025-01-20 05:55:25'),
(1131, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>Why did Luke mention that Jesus was twelve years old when He went to the festival?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">From the age of 12, a Jewish boy was expected to fulfil all duties to God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attending the temple and worshipping during Passover was required for all Jewish males from this age.&nbsp;</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:22:50', '2025-01-15 03:22:50'),
(1132, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What should have a 12-year-old Jewish boy do in relation to the study of the Law?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\"><img src=\"source - https:/www.myjewishlearning.com/article/kippah-tallit-and-tefilin-the-clothing-of-jewish-prayer/\" alt=\"\">At the age of twelve, a Jewish boy is recognised as a \"Bar Mitzvah,\" or \"Son of the Law.\" From this point on, he is obligated to observe religious laws and major festivals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">He also begins the practice of wearing Tefillin (phylacteries) on his forehead and hands during prayer, symbolising devotion.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong id=\"docs-internal-guid-7d3f20da-7fff-0901-a130-10681cefc939\"><img src=\"https://lh7-rt.googleusercontent.com/docsz/AD_4nXffEXxcMO8sMC64eJyarYeI_CQ3W5yfOTp8y8WI22hxYY3xJwEgSeLucCSOnUPrFnb17gYKxMjAxKql5g_c88gyLektkUyH1J5ndiGtIDnxJjE1p4y4P3abeNCmwUZfqoE2x62BJA?key=cC4rLbw_ctkHNqWVjyOUaVBy\" width=\"1598\" height=\"900\"></strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:23:21', '2025-01-20 05:57:58'),
(1133, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:43 \"After the festival was over, they started to return, but the boy Jesus stayed behind in Jerusalem, and his parents did not know it.\"</strong><br><em>Can those who come for Passover go back?</em></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Yes, those who came to Jerusalem for Passover could leave after the first day. According to tradition, they were required to stay in Jerusalem on the first day and could return the following morning:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><br>&ldquo;Boil and eat it at the place that the Lord your God will choose; and in the morning you may start back to your tents&rdquo;(Deuteronomy 16:7).<br>There was to be no journey back on the first day of Passover.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:23:58', '2025-01-15 03:23:58'),
(1134, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:44 \"They assumed that he was in the group of travellers, and went a day\'s journey. Then they started to look for him among their relatives and friends.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why did Jesus&rsquo;s parents lose track of him?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Typically, groups on pilgrimage to Jerusalem travelled in large caravans, called \"synodia,\" including people, camels and donkeys.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The men generally walked behind, women at the front, and children ran and played in between.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Families would regroup at night for rest, and it was then that Jesus&rsquo;s parents realised he was not with them.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:24:29', '2025-01-15 03:24:29'),
(1135, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:44-45 &ldquo;They assumed that he was in the group of travellers, and went on a day\'s journey. Then they started to look for him among their relatives and friends; when they did not find him, they returned to Jerusalem to search for him.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>What led to Jesus being separated from his parents on the journey?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Pilgrims often travelled in large groups from their village to Jerusalem, joined by others along the way.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">These groups worshipped and celebrated together, creating a sense of shared community.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Jesus\'s parents likely assumed He was with friends or relatives, as children often mingled freely within the group.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:25:14', '2025-01-15 03:25:14'),
(1136, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:46 \"After three days they found him in the temple, sitting among the teachers, listening to them and asking them questions.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the 12-year-old Jesus permitted to speak among the teachers?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish tradition encouraged open dialogue and questioning among learners and teachers.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was common for the rabbis to listen to the youngest members of the group and give them the opportunity to ask questions, with some even answering the youngest first.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This allowed Jesus the chance to engage with the teachers in the temple.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:26:08', '2025-01-15 03:26:08'),
(1137, '<p><em>How was it remarkable that the 12-year-old Jesus taught among the teachers?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Jewish belief held that when the Messiah came, He would sit on \"Moses\'s seat\"&mdash;a special seat in the synagogue reserved for the awaited Saviour.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was astonishing, then, for the 12-year-old Jesus to be seated among the teachers, foreshadowing His role as a divine teacher.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:26:45', '2025-01-15 03:26:45'),
(1138, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><strong>Luke 2:47 : \"And all who heard him were amazed at his understanding and his answers.\"</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Why was the 12-year-old Jesus considered a miracle in the temple?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Jewish tradition, a boy was required to obey the laws at the age of 13, (He is Bar Mtizvah which means \"Son of Commandment\").</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">From that age, a Jewish boy would go to the rabbis to study the interpretation of the law in the synagogue. However, 12-year-old Jesus, not yet obligated to this study, displayed remarkable understanding of the law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This astonished those in the temple, as Jesus&rsquo;s formal education in interpreting the law had not yet begun.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:27:25', '2025-01-15 03:27:25'),
(1139, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>What was the education of a Jewish boy like?</em></p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Primary Education (Ages 6-10): Boys learned Hebrew letters by writing them on a writing board and practised reading the Torah aloud.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Secondary Education (Ages 10-13): During this period, students learned both the Torah and its commentaries (Midrash) through recitation.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:27:54', '2025-01-15 03:27:54'),
(1140, '<p dir=\"ltr\" role=\"presentation\"><em>How did Jewish children memorise the laws?</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 4, 68, '<p dir=\"ltr\">Since scrolls were precious and inaccessible to children, they memorised passages through repeated recitation, as instructed by their rabbis.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Often, rabbis would require children to recite passages aloud many times to ensure retention.</p>', 1, '2025-01-15 03:28:17', '2025-01-15 03:28:17');
